  <graph edgedefault="directed">
    <node id="ICU">
      <data key="d0">ICU</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Intensive care unit room used as the primary clinical environment for studying aerosol propagation, persistence, escape, and zonal behavior under different pressure configurations. | Critical-care hospital zone where CFD simulations have been used to study airflow patterns and contaminant-control behavior, including multi-patient ICU configurations.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_22,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_23,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_25,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_31,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_32,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_34,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_35,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_36,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_37,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_39,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_49</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
      <data key="d6">INTENSIVE CARE UNIT</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POSITIVE-PRESSURE ICU">
      <data key="d0">POSITIVE-PRESSURE ICU</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">ICU room operated in a positive-pressure configuration with the door closed. The study reported that up to 6% of generated particulate matter escaped from this condition through the door boundary. | An ICU operating under positive pressure conditions. Its pressure-specific data were used as the basis for the fixed zonal map used in subsequent ICU-specific analysis, and PM concentrations returned to background at about 800 seconds.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
      <data key="d6">POSITIVE PRESSURE ICU</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEUTRAL-PRESSURE ICU">
      <data key="d0">NEUTRAL-PRESSURE ICU</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">ICU room operated in a neutral-pressure configuration with the door open. This condition showed greater aerosol escape than the positive-pressure closed-door condition, with up to 19% of generated particulate matter escaping. | An ICU operating under neutral pressure conditions. Its zone assignments were nearly the same as those under positive pressure, and PM concentrations returned to background at about 800 seconds.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
      <data key="d6">NEUTRAL PRESSURE ICU</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEGATIVE-PRESSURE ICU">
      <data key="d0">NEGATIVE-PRESSURE ICU</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">ICU room operated under negative pressure relative to adjacent spaces. Outside sensors did not register an aerosol spike for this configuration, indicating stronger containment of room-generated aerosols. | ICU operated under negative pressure. In this condition, aerosol was effectively mixed inside the room, returned to baseline faster, and did not produce concentration spikes outside the room, supporting infectious-aerosol containment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.97</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
      <data key="d6">NEGATIVE PRESSURE ICU</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ADJACENT ENVIRONMENTS">
      <data key="d0">ADJACENT ENVIRONMENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Spaces next to the ICU that were monitored to determine whether aerosols generated inside the ICU propagated beyond the room boundary.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEAR THE AEROSOL SOURCE">
      <data key="d0">NEAR THE AEROSOL SOURCE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">One of the three ICU zones identified by K-means clustering of temporospatial aerosol concentration data, representing the area closest to the simulated patient aerosol source.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM PERIPHERY">
      <data key="d0">ROOM PERIPHERY</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">One of the three ICU zones identified by clustering, representing peripheral room areas that receive aerosol after dispersion from the source-proximal zone.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_1,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OUTSIDE THE ROOM">
      <data key="d0">OUTSIDE THE ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The monitored zone outside the ICU room, used to detect whether aerosols escaped from the ICU through door gaps, an open doorway, or other boundary leakage paths.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DOOR GAPS">
      <data key="d0">DOOR GAPS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Leakage paths at the ICU door boundary through which particulate matter escaped from the ICU, especially noted for the positive-pressure closed-door condition.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPEN DOORWAY">
      <data key="d0">OPEN DOORWAY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Air-transfer path created by the open door in the neutral-pressure ICU condition, allowing stronger exchange between the ICU and outside-room area.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POSITIVE PRESSURE WITH CLOSED DOOR">
      <data key="d0">POSITIVE PRESSURE WITH CLOSED DOOR</data>
      <data key="d1">PRESSURE_RELATIONSHIP</data>
      <data key="d2">Pressure condition in which the ICU is maintained at positive pressure while the door is closed. Despite the closed door, up to 6% of generated particulate matter escaped.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEUTRAL PRESSURE WITH OPEN DOOR">
      <data key="d0">NEUTRAL PRESSURE WITH OPEN DOOR</data>
      <data key="d1">PRESSURE_RELATIONSHIP</data>
      <data key="d2">Pressure and door-state condition in which the ICU is approximately neutral relative to adjacent spaces and the door is open. This condition allowed up to 19% of particulate matter to escape.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEGATIVE PRESSURE">
      <data key="d0">NEGATIVE PRESSURE</data>
      <data key="d1">PRESSURE_RELATIONSHIP</data>
      <data key="d2">Pressure relationship in which the ICU is maintained at lower pressure than adjacent areas. In the study, this condition was associated with no aerosol spike detected outside the ICU. | The pressure condition applied to the circular hole in the downwards-blowing fan simulation. It drives the modeled downward airflow that strongly affects particle deposition and dispersion. | A pressure relationship in which the isolation ward is maintained at lower pressure than adjacent spaces, supporting containment of potentially infectious aerosols within the ward.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.98</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_5,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_6,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_18,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_24,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_30,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_31,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_35,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_39,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_40,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
      <data key="d6">NEGATIVE PRESSURE</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACE NACL AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">TRACE NACL AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">Generated sodium chloride tracer aerosol used to mimic patient aerosol generation and to track aerosol propagation in the ICU and adjacent environments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POTENTIALLY INFECTIOUS RESPIRATORY AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">POTENTIALLY INFECTIOUS RESPIRATORY AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory aerosol particles that may carry infectious agents, motivating the study of aerosol persistence and transport in ICUs during the COVID-19 pandemic context.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SIMULATED PATIENT AEROSOL SOURCE">
      <data key="d0">SIMULATED PATIENT AEROSOL SOURCE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Experimental representation of a patient emitting aerosols; the study generated trace NaCl aerosols to mimic aerosol production by a patient in an ICU.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL PROPAGATION">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL PROPAGATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Observed movement and spread of generated aerosol particles within the ICU and into adjacent spaces, mapped through temporospatial particulate matter concentration data. | The movement and spread of an aerosol plume through a room. In the text, plume propagation may be affected by the onset of local turbulence and is relevant to infectious aerosol transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
      <data key="d6">AEROSOL PLUME PROPAGATION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THREE-ZONE ICU REPRESENTATION">
      <data key="d0">THREE-ZONE ICU REPRESENTATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Data-driven zonal representation suggested by K-means clustering, dividing the ICU aerosol behavior into three zones: near the aerosol source, room periphery, and outside the room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO-PHASE PLUME BEHAVIOR">
      <data key="d0">TWO-PHASE PLUME BEHAVIOR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Observed aerosol plume behavior consisting of an initial dispersion of the original aerosol spike throughout the room followed by an evacuation phase.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISPERSION OF THE ORIGINAL AEROSOL SPIKE">
      <data key="d0">DISPERSION OF THE ORIGINAL AEROSOL SPIKE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">First phase of the observed plume behavior, in which the generated aerosol spike spreads from the source area into the broader ICU room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.79</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EVACUATION PHASE">
      <data key="d0">EVACUATION PHASE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Second phase of the observed plume behavior, in which dispersed aerosol concentration decreases as particles are removed, diluted, or transported from the room air volume.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_0,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGLE-OCCUPANCY ICU ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">SINGLE-OCCUPANCY ICU ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The primary hospital zone studied for aerosol monitoring. The excerpt specifies that the study was limited to single-occupancy ICU rooms where aerosol dispersion, evacuation, pressure operation, and air-exchange-driven decay were evaluated.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL SOURCE LOCATION">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL SOURCE LOCATION</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A within-room sampling or reference location near the original aerosol release point. It is one of the locations used to characterize how the aerosol plume dispersed from its initial spike.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEGATIVE-PRESSURE OPERATION">
      <data key="d0">NEGATIVE-PRESSURE OPERATION</data>
      <data key="d1">PRESSURE_RELATIONSHIP</data>
      <data key="d2">A room pressure operating condition evaluated in the study. The excerpt states that rooms under negative-pressure operation cleared aerosol nearly twice as fast as other pressure conditions. | Pressure state in which the ICU is maintained below the pressure of the adjacent environment, causing air from Zone 3 to infiltrate into the ICU through Zone 2 following the pressure differential.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
      <data key="d6">NEGATIVE PRESSURE OPERATION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEUTRAL-PRESSURE OPERATION">
      <data key="d0">NEUTRAL-PRESSURE OPERATION</data>
      <data key="d1">PRESSURE_RELATIONSHIP</data>
      <data key="d2">A room pressure operating condition with no intentional positive or negative pressure bias, included in the comparison of aerosol decay rates. | A pressure operating condition applied during ICU aerosol decay experiments. The text states that neutral and positive pressure operations had similar decay rates and clear-out times for a given ICU.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
      <data key="d6">NEUTRAL PRESSURE OPERATION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR EXCHANGE RATES">
      <data key="d0">AIR EXCHANGE RATES</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation-related air replacement metric that closely tracked aerosol decay trends in the ICU rooms, indicating that clearance was strongly governed by room air exchange. | A ventilation-rate concept referenced in the cited study on CO2 and aerosol behavior. No numeric air-change value is given, but the term indicates the rate at which indoor air is replaced, influencing dilution and removal of airborne contaminants. | Ventilation-rate metric referenced in the survey of commuter trains. No numeric ACH value is provided in the excerpt, but air exchange rates describe how quickly cabin air is replaced or diluted, affecting airborne contaminant removal. | A qualitative ventilation condition of the tested room. The high air exchange rate was cited as the reason that a measurable change in ozone concentration would not be expected.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">AIR EXCHANGE RATES,HIGH AIR EXCHANGE RATE</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INITIAL AEROSOL DISPERSION PHASE">
      <data key="d0">INITIAL AEROSOL DISPERSION PHASE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The first phase of plume behavior, during which the original aerosol spike spread from the aerosol source location through the room. | Room-wide aerosol distribution established after approximately 10 minutes of fan operation before UV-C exposure begins. The particle positions after this mixing period are used as starting points for later trajectory and inactivation calculations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
      <data key="d6">INITIAL AEROSOL DISPERSION PATTERN</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WELL-MIXED EVACUATION PHASE">
      <data key="d0">WELL-MIXED EVACUATION PHASE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The second phase of plume behavior, during which the aerosol concentration behaved as well mixed and decayed uniformly as room air was cleared.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL DECAY TRENDS">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL DECAY TRENDS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
