      <data key="d0">AIRFLOW OUTLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation outlet paths in the ICU rooms where airflow velocities were measured. These outlets contributed to characterization of room airflow and air exchange behavior.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTS">
      <data key="d0">VENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation openings whose dimensions were measured and combined with airflow velocity data to calculate airflow rates and the fraction of air escaping from the ICU rooms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL SPATIAL AND TEMPORAL DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL SPATIAL AND TEMPORAL DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The measured distribution of aerosols over space and time in the ICU rooms and their immediate vicinity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL DISPERSION AND EXFILTRATION">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL DISPERSION AND EXFILTRATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The analyzed and modeled movement of aerosols within the ICU rooms and from the rooms to surrounding areas. This pattern was used to understand potential exposure inside and outside the rooms under real-world conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRFLOW ESCAPING FROM THE ROOM">
      <data key="d0">AIRFLOW ESCAPING FROM THE ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The fraction of room airflow escaping through measured paths such as vents and the door gap. This pattern is directly relevant to aerosol exfiltration from ICU rooms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OTHER INFECTIOUS AGENTS">
      <data key="d0">OTHER INFECTIOUS AGENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The text generically refers to other infectious agents that may be contained in long-lived aerosols, in addition to SARS-CoV-2. No specific organism, pathogen class, or transmission setting is further defined.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.58</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ICU AEROSOL SPATIAL DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">ICU AEROSOL SPATIAL DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The room-scale spatial pattern of aerosol or particle concentrations observed across different grid locations in the ICU. The distribution was characterized using a distributed low-cost sensor network and spot checks with a movable reference PMS sensor.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BACTERIAL AND FUNGAL BIOAEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">BACTERIAL AND FUNGAL BIOAEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne biological aerosols referenced from prior indoor-environment literature. They represent microbial aerosol contaminants that may be relevant to indoor air quality, although the excerpt does not identify specific bacterial or fungal species.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.38</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMMON AREAS OUTSIDE THE ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">COMMON AREAS OUTSIDE THE ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Hospital areas outside the ICU rooms where aerosol monitors were deployed to detect whether generated particles moved beyond the patient room boundary.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HALLWAY">
      <data key="d0">HALLWAY</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Adjacent circulation area outside the ICU rooms. Two to three aerosol sensors were placed near the ICU door gap, and another hallway sensor was positioned about 10–20 feet from the door to monitor particle movement outside the room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_24,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_33,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_35,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ANTECHAMBER">
      <data key="d0">ANTECHAMBER</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Intermediate space associated with the negative pressure ICUs. At least one aerosol monitor was placed in this area, making it an important buffer zone for assessing aerosol transfer between the ICU and surrounding hospital spaces.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_24,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DOOR GAP">
      <data key="d0">DOOR GAP</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Opening or leakage pathway at the ICU doorway near which hallway sensors were positioned. It represents a potential route for airflow and aerosol particle transfer between the ICU and adjacent hallway.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HEAD OF BED PARTICLE SOURCE LOCATION">
      <data key="d0">HEAD OF BED PARTICLE SOURCE LOCATION</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Location at the patient's head or head of the bed where NaCl aerosol particles were generated. This placement was used to mimic aerosol release during patient coughing, sneezing, or talking.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NACL AEROSOL SURROGATE PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">NACL AEROSOL SURROGATE PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Non-biological NaCl aerosol particles generated by nebulizing 1% NaCl solution for 60 seconds. They served as a surrogate for patient-generated airborne particles released during respiratory activities, with measured particle sizes spanning approximately 10 nm to 3 µm.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL SPATIAL DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL SPATIAL DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Measured distribution of aerosol particle concentrations across ICUs and surrounding areas. The pattern was characterized using 16–18 aerosol monitors placed in a predetermined grid at multiple heights, including approximately 0.2 m, 1.0 m, and 2 m.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOW-OCCUPANCY EXPERIMENTAL CONDITION">
      <data key="d0">LOW-OCCUPANCY EXPERIMENTAL CONDITION</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Experimental condition in which the ICUs were unoccupied except for researchers operating the nebulizer and monitoring peripheral sensor readings. This reduced occupancy-related airflow disturbance and uncontrolled aerosol sources.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPERIMENTAL HOSPITAL ROOM">
      <data key="d0">EXPERIMENTAL HOSPITAL ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Hospital room used for aerosol plume-tracking experiments. After a 60-second aerosolization, particle concentration initially spiked and then decayed toward background as room air was exchanged or leaked through available air paths.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR OUTLETS">
      <data key="d0">AIR OUTLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Engineered ventilation outlets associated with the HVAC system. They served as a primary route for air exchange and aerosol evacuation from the experimental room. | Air-exhaust or discharge openings whose positions were documented for the studied rooms and which contribute to airflow removal from the venues. | Extraction airflow boundaries where air exits the simulation domain. The thermal boundary condition at these outlets is zero flux, meaning the extracted-air temperature is not prescribed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">AIR OUTLETS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GAPS UNDER THE DOORWAY">
      <data key="d0">GAPS UNDER THE DOORWAY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Uncontrolled leakage pathway beneath the doorway. Aerosol-laden air could escape through these gaps, contributing to particle concentration decay independently of the HVAC system.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPEN DOOR">
      <data key="d0">OPEN DOOR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Open doorway pathway allowing aerosol particles to escape from the room. This non-HVAC route affected plume movement and the decay of measured aerosol concentration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.77</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ADJACENT SPACE OUTSIDE ROOM">
      <data key="d0">ADJACENT SPACE OUTSIDE ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Area outside the experimental room that could receive aerosol-laden air escaping through doorway gaps or an open door. The text does not specify the exact adjacent area, but it functions as the receiving space for leakage.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.61</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL PLUME DECAY PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL PLUME DECAY PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Observed air-distribution behavior after short aerosolization: an initial particle concentration spike followed by decay as particles were removed through HVAC exchange or escaped through doorway-related air paths.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BACK HALLWAY">
      <data key="d0">BACK HALLWAY</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The adjacent hallway outside ICU 1 where particle sensors were positioned approximately 10–20 feet from the ICU door to assess whether aerosols moved from the room into nearby circulation space.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ICU 1 DOORWAY">
      <data key="d0">ICU 1 DOORWAY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The doorway connecting ICU 1 with the back hallway. Its open or closed configuration was part of the experimental setup, with the door closed during the positive-pressure condition and open during the neutral-pressure condition.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEUTRAL PRESSURE CONDITION">
      <data key="d0">NEUTRAL PRESSURE CONDITION</data>
      <data key="d1">PRESSURE_RELATIONSHIP</data>
      <data key="d2">The ICU 1 pressure state evaluated with the door open. This condition represented a reduced or absent pressure differential between ICU 1 and adjacent space, allowing direct exchange through the doorway.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEGATIVE PRESSURE CONDITION">
      <data key="d0">NEGATIVE PRESSURE CONDITION</data>
      <data key="d1">PRESSURE_RELATIONSHIP</data>
      <data key="d2">The ICU 1 pressure state evaluated as a separate experimental condition to characterize how negative pressure affected aerosol distribution relative to the room and surrounding spaces.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NACL PARTICLE TRACER">
      <data key="d0">NACL PARTICLE TRACER</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">The airborne tracer material used in the experiment: nebulized sodium chloride particles released for 60 seconds at the patient-head location to make aerosol movement measurable.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TIME-RESOLVED 3D AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">TIME-RESOLVED 3D AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The spatial and temporal aerosol concentration pattern generated from particle sensor readings aligned to the start of nebulization and averaged in 10-second epochs. This pattern was visualized as 3D maps for the different ICU 1 pressure conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="K-MEANS AEROSOL ZONES">
      <data key="d0">K-MEANS AEROSOL ZONES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Clustered spatial zones derived from spatiotemporal sensor data using K-means clustering. These zones represent grouped aerosol-distribution behavior across the sensor network.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HEAD OF BED">
      <data key="d0">HEAD OF BED</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The localized area in ICU 1 where aerosolization occurred. The text identifies this area as the location of the initial aerosol concentration spike.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POSITIVE PRESSURE OPERATIONS">
      <data key="d0">POSITIVE PRESSURE OPERATIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">PRESSURE_RELATIONSHIP</data>
      <data key="d2">One of the pressure operating conditions tested in ICU 1 during aerosol distribution experiments. The text reports that positive pressure showed trends similar to neutral pressure after the initial aerosol spike.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEUTRAL PRESSURE CONDITIONS">
      <data key="d0">NEUTRAL PRESSURE CONDITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">PRESSURE_RELATIONSHIP</data>
      <data key="d2">One of the pressure operating conditions tested in ICU 1. The text states that neutral pressure conditions showed aerosol dispersion trends similar to those observed under positive pressure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_27,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INITIAL AEROSOL CONCENTRATION SPIKE">
      <data key="d0">INITIAL AEROSOL CONCENTRATION SPIKE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">An observed aerosol distribution pattern occurring during aerosolization, with the initial concentration spike located at the head of the bed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNIFORM SPREADING DURING DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">UNIFORM SPREADING DURING DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">An observed aerosol distribution pattern in which aerosol spread throughout ICU 1 during the dispersion phase after the initial aerosolization event.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WELL-MIXED AEROSOL STATE">
      <data key="d0">WELL-MIXED AEROSOL STATE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">An observed distribution state reached approximately 90–120 seconds after the initial particulate matter spike, when sensors near the aerosolization source and sensors at the room periphery recorded similar aerosol concentrations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMMON AREA OUTSIDE ICU 1">
      <data key="d0">COMMON AREA OUTSIDE ICU 1</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The hospital area outside the outer door of ICU 1. The particle plume entered this area after reaching the ICU door, became diluted, and was not detected by monitors located 10–20 feet from the door.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LARGER OPERATING ROOMS FROM HECKER ET AL.">
      <data key="d0">LARGER OPERATING ROOMS FROM HECKER ET AL.</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Operating rooms referenced as a comparison case from a similar experimental design. Unlike ICU 1, these larger operating rooms did not exhibit well-mixed aerosol conditions and showed more spatially distinct aerosol distributions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HVAC SYSTEM SERVING ICU 1">
      <data key="d0">HVAC SYSTEM SERVING ICU 1</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The heating, ventilation, and air-conditioning system serving ICU 1. It supplied filtered air and generated room air currents that mixed aerosolized trace particles and contributed to dilution before evacuation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM VENT IN ICU 1">
      <data key="d0">ROOM VENT IN ICU 1</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The exhaust or return air pathway in ICU 1 through which aerosol-laden air was removed from the room. It contributed to the decay of aerosol concentration after the room became well mixed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OUTER DOOR OF ICU 1">
      <data key="d0">OUTER DOOR OF ICU 1</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The air-transfer pathway between ICU 1 and the adjacent common area. At approximately the same time the room became well mixed, the aerosol plume reached this door, began escaping the ICU, and produced the maximum measured particle concentration immediately outside the door.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WELL-MIXED AEROSOL STATE IN ICU 1">
      <data key="d0">WELL-MIXED AEROSOL STATE IN ICU 1</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The observed air distribution condition in ICU 1 at approximately 90–120 seconds, when sensors near the aerosolization source and peripheral sensors showed similar aerosol readings. This indicates effective room-scale mixing by HVAC-driven air currents.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DILUTED PLUME IN COMMON AREA">
      <data key="d0">DILUTED PLUME IN COMMON AREA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The aerosol distribution pattern observed after the particle plume escaped through the ICU door into the common area. The plume diluted rapidly and was not detected by monitors 10–20 feet from the ICU door.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NON-WELL-MIXED AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION IN LARGER OPERATING ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">NON-WELL-MIXED AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION IN LARGER OPERATING ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The aerosol distribution pattern reported in larger operating rooms from the comparison study, where the aerosol field did not become uniform and could be spatially distinguished between different room regions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LARGER ORS">
      <data key="d0">LARGER ORS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Larger operating-room hospital zones where aerosol behavior was not well mixed. Aerosol distribution could be distinguished between separate OR zones, indicating spatial heterogeneity rather than uniform room-wide mixing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIFFERENT OR ZONES">
      <data key="d0">DIFFERENT OR ZONES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Spatial sub-zones within larger operating rooms that showed distinguishable aerosol concentration patterns. These zones demonstrate that aerosol behavior varied by location within the OR.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OUTSIDE ICU AREA">
      <data key="d0">OUTSIDE ICU AREA</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Area outside the ICU where monitoring indicated whether aerosol particles escaped the room. Under negative pressure, no aerosol concentration spikes were registered in this outside area.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ZONE 1">
      <data key="d0">ZONE 1</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Data-driven aerosol zone in ICU 1 whose sensors showed the largest and earliest particulate-matter concentration spike, indicating rapid and strong aerosol arrival.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_30,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_31,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_32,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ZONE 2">
      <data key="d0">ZONE 2</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Data-driven aerosol zone in ICU 1 whose sensors showed later spikes with consistent particulate-matter levels, indicating delayed but coherent aerosol transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_30,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_31,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_32,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ZONE 3">
      <data key="d0">ZONE 3</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Data-driven aerosol zone in ICU 1 whose sensors showed lower and delayed particulate-matter spikes or, in the negative pressure ICU, no rise above background levels.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_30,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_31,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_32,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_33,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH ACR">
      <data key="d0">HIGH ACR</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">High air-change-rate condition associated with greater room air velocities, increased turbulence, enhanced aerosol mixing, and faster return of aerosol concentration to baseline.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NON-WELL-MIXED OR CONDITIONS">
      <data key="d0">NON-WELL-MIXED OR CONDITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Air-distribution pattern observed in larger ORs where aerosol concentrations were not spatially uniform, allowing distributions to be distinguished between zones. | Assumed air-distribution condition used for the ICU aerosol accounting analysis. Under this assumption, sensor particle concentrations could be corrected by coverage volume and integrated over time by zone.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
      <data key="d6">WELL-MIXED CONDITIONS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ZONALLY DISTINCT AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">ZONALLY DISTINCT AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Spatial aerosol distribution pattern in which different room zones have clearly distinguishable aerosol concentrations or trends.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EFFECTIVE IN-ROOM MIXING">
      <data key="d0">EFFECTIVE IN-ROOM MIXING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Aerosol mixing pattern observed under negative pressure, likely driven by high ACR, greater air velocities, and turbulence. This mixing reduced the concentration spike near the aerosolization source.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOW SOURCE-NEAR CONCENTRATION SPIKE">
      <data key="d0">LOW SOURCE-NEAR CONCENTRATION SPIKE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Observed pattern in which the concentration spike near the aerosolization source was lowest under negative pressure, consistent with stronger room mixing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAST RETURN TO BASELINE">
      <data key="d0">FAST RETURN TO BASELINE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Aerosol decay pattern under negative pressure and high ACR where concentration returned to the baseline level in approximately 500 seconds, faster than the approximately 800 seconds observed in positive and neutral pressure cases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NO OUTSIDE AEROSOL SPIKE">
      <data key="d0">NO OUTSIDE AEROSOL SPIKE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Containment-related distribution pattern where monitoring outside negative pressure rooms did not register aerosol concentration spikes, indicating particles remained inside the ICU.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ZONE 1 EARLY HIGH PM SPIKE">
      <data key="d0">ZONE 1 EARLY HIGH PM SPIKE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Zonal particulate-matter pattern in which Zone 1 sensors showed the largest and earliest PM concentration spike.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ZONE 2 DELAYED CONSISTENT PM LEVELS">
      <data key="d0">ZONE 2 DELAYED CONSISTENT PM LEVELS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Zonal particulate-matter pattern in which Zone 2 sensors spiked later than Zone 1 and showed consistent PM levels.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ZONE 3 LOWER DELAYED OR BACKGROUND PM">
      <data key="d0">ZONE 3 LOWER DELAYED OR BACKGROUND PM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Zonal particulate-matter pattern in which Zone 3 sensors showed lower and delayed PM spikes or did not rise above background levels under negative pressure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOLIZED PARTICLES GENERATED IN ICU">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOLIZED PARTICLES GENERATED IN ICU</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Aerosolized particulate matter generated in the ICU and used as a surrogate for infectious airborne particles. Its movement and containment were used to assess pressure and ventilation performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HEAD OF BED AREA">
      <data key="d0">HEAD OF BED AREA</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The area near the head of the bed in the ICU. In negative pressure cases, sensors located in this area were assigned to Zone 2, likely due to the effect of a nearby suction vent.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STRONG SUCTION VENT NEAR THE HEAD OF THE BED">
      <data key="d0">STRONG SUCTION VENT NEAR THE HEAD OF THE BED</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">A localized suction or exhaust vent near the head of the ICU bed. It likely influenced airflow and sensor clustering, causing both head-of-bed sensors to be assigned to Zone 2 in negative pressure cases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOWER AND DELAYED PM SPIKE">
      <data key="d0">LOWER AND DELAYED PM SPIKE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A particulate-matter distribution pattern in which PM concentration increased later and to a lower magnitude than elsewhere, or stayed near background. This was observed for Zone 3 sensors under negative pressure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ZONE 1 IMMEDIATE PM SPIKE AND 30-60 S EQUILIBRATION">
      <data key="d0">ZONE 1 IMMEDIATE PM SPIKE AND 30-60 S EQUILIBRATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A Zone 1 PM behavior pattern in which concentration spiked immediately with particle generation and then equilibrated to the average room concentration within approximately 30–60 seconds.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEGATIVE-PRESSURE PM DECAY TO BACKGROUND AT ~500 S">
      <data key="d0">NEGATIVE-PRESSURE PM DECAY TO BACKGROUND AT ~500 S</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A particle decay pattern observed in the negative pressure ICU, where aerosol concentration returned to the background level of approximately 1 #/cm3 at about 500 seconds.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POSITIVE-AND-NEUTRAL PM DECAY TO BACKGROUND AT ~800 S">
      <data key="d0">POSITIVE-AND-NEUTRAL PM DECAY TO BACKGROUND AT ~800 S</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A particle decay pattern observed in positive and neutral pressure ICU conditions, where aerosol concentration returned to the background level of approximately 1 #/cm3 at about 800 seconds.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BACKGROUND PM LEVEL (~1 #/CM3)">
      <data key="d0">BACKGROUND PM LEVEL (~1 #/CM3)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The background particulate matter concentration level, reported as approximately 1 particle per cm3, to which aerosol concentrations returned after initial PM loading.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NORMALIZED ZONAL PM CONCENTRATION TIME SERIES">
      <data key="d0">NORMALIZED ZONAL PM CONCENTRATION TIME SERIES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The zonal PM concentration time series normalized by dividing each value by the peak value of that experiment, enabling comparison across rooms and pressure conditions despite differences in initial aerosol concentration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THRESHOLD-DEPENDENT ZONE ASSIGNMENT">
      <data key="d0">THRESHOLD-DEPENDENT ZONE ASSIGNMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A zonal assignment behavior in which the algorithm's assignment of sensors to Zone 1, Zone 2, or Zone 3 can vary depending on the user-set threshold level based on variance between sensors.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRFLOW-DEPENDENT ZONAL ASSIGNMENT">
      <data key="d0">AIRFLOW-DEPENDENT ZONAL ASSIGNMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A zonal assignment behavior showing that airflow or pressure setting affects how ICU sensors are grouped into zones.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SIMILAR POSITIVE AND NEUTRAL ZONE ASSIGNMENTS">
      <data key="d0">SIMILAR POSITIVE AND NEUTRAL ZONE ASSIGNMENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A zonal assignment pattern in which the positive and neutral pressure cases produced nearly the same zone assignments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SIGNIFICANTLY DIFFERENT NEGATIVE-PRESSURE ZONE ASSIGNMENTS">
      <data key="d0">SIGNIFICANTLY DIFFERENT NEGATIVE-PRESSURE ZONE ASSIGNMENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A zonal assignment pattern in which the negative pressure cases differed significantly from the positive and neutral pressure cases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HEAD-OF-BED SENSORS ASSIGNED TO ZONE 2">
      <data key="d0">HEAD-OF-BED SENSORS ASSIGNED TO ZONE 2</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A negative-pressure zonal assignment outcome in which both head-of-bed sensor locations were assigned to Zone 2, likely due to the nearby strong suction vent.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.81</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HVAC-FILTERED AIR">
      <data key="d0">HVAC-FILTERED AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Filtered supply airflow introduced by the HVAC system into the ICU. It dilutes aerosol after the initial room-scale dispersion phase and contributes to aerosol evacuation from the well-mixed room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DOORS, DOOR GAPS, OR OTHER OPENINGS">
      <data key="d0">DOORS, DOOR GAPS, OR OTHER OPENINGS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Leakage or opening pathways between the ICU and adjacent surroundings. These pathways allow aerosol exfiltration from the ICU under positive or neutral pressure and allow inflow into the ICU under negative pressure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR EXCHANGE RATE">
      <data key="d0">AIR EXCHANGE RATE</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Room air-exchange parameter governing how quickly the ICU returns to background PM concentration during the evacuation phase. The text does not provide a numeric ACH value but identifies air exchange rate as a key determinant of removal time. | A ventilation-rate metric discussed as a potential indicator of an air distribution system's effectiveness. The cited case study specifically examines whether ACH alone adequately predicts mitigation of cough-generated airborne infectious aerosols. | Ventilation parameter characterizing the two supply ventilation conditions in the CFD study. A higher air exchange rate reduced both maximum aerosol particle volume concentration and particle travel time through the station. | The ventilation metric explicitly identified as being measured by the CO2 tracer gas concentration decay method. It represents the rate at which indoor air is replaced or diluted, commonly expressed as air changes per hour.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">AIR CHANGE RATE,AIR EXCHANGE RATE</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WELL-MIXED CONDITION">
      <data key="d0">WELL-MIXED CONDITION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Room-scale air distribution state reached after generated aerosol disperses from the point-source region into the rest of the ICU. It is indicated by Zone 1 concentration falling to the room average and Zone 2 concentration rising after the initial Zone 1 peak decreases. | The room air distribution state after aerosol became sufficiently mixed for the empirical decay-rate expression to estimate relative aerosol concentration over time. | An idealized room air distribution condition in which air and contaminants are assumed to be uniformly mixed under steady-state conditions. The derivation of the referenced equation assumes this condition, although the passage notes it is rarely met in real-life ventilation scenarios.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_31,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">WELL-MIXED ROOM CONDITION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISPERSION PHASE">
      <data key="d0">DISPERSION PHASE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Early aerosol redistribution pattern lasting about 30–60 seconds, during which the initial PM spike moves from Zone 1 toward the room periphery and Zone 2 before the room becomes well mixed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PRESSURE DIFFERENTIAL BETWEEN THE ROOM AND THE OUTSIDE">
      <data key="d0">PRESSURE DIFFERENTIAL BETWEEN THE ROOM AND THE OUTSIDE</data>
      <data key="d1">PRESSURE_RELATIONSHIP</data>
      <data key="d2">Pressure relationship between the ICU room and the adjacent outside environment. Along with room condition such as door state, it governs airflow direction and affects how quickly the room returns to background particulate matter concentration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM-TO-ADJACENT DOORWAY AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">ROOM-TO-ADJACENT DOORWAY AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Air communication pathway between the ICU and adjacent environment whose condition, such as door open or closed, influences aerosol exchange and the rate at which the room returns to background particulate matter concentration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FROM ZONE 2 TO ZONE 3">
      <data key="d0">FROM ZONE 2 TO ZONE 3</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Exfiltration pathway describing aerosol movement from the ICU-side Zone 2 into the adjacent environment Zone 3 under positive or neutral pressure conditions. | Infiltration pathway describing air movement from the adjacent environment Zone 3 into ICU Zone 2 during negative pressure operation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
      <data key="d6">FROM ZONE 3 TO ZONE 2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNIFORM AEROSOL DECAY PHASE">
      <data key="d0">UNIFORM AEROSOL DECAY PHASE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Post-mixing evacuation or decay phase in which particle concentration decreases uniformly across the ICU. This uniformity allows the room aerosol decay rate to be characterized using the average particle concentration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STUDIED ICU ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">STUDIED ICU ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The set of intensive care unit rooms evaluated in Table 2 for aerosol decay-rate expressions, time to 90% reduction, and return-to-background concentration under different pressure scenarios.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HVAC">
      <data key="d0">HVAC</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation system involved in controlling airflow and pressure behavior during the ICU aerosol decay experiments. In the negative-pressure scenario, it aspirated particle-laden air into the ICU.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_33,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DOOR OPENING">
      <data key="d0">DOOR OPENING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The opening through which aerosol was mixed during the neutral and positive pressure experiments, functioning as an air and aerosol transfer pathway into or out of the ICU room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACR">
      <data key="d0">ACR</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The air change rate reported in Table 1. The text states that ACR correlated well with ICU aerosol decay rates, indicating that ventilation exchange rate influenced aerosol clearance behavior.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ICU1/ICU3 ACR RATIO OF 1.83">
      <data key="d0">ICU1/ICU3 ACR RATIO OF 1.83</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">A derived comparative air-change-rate metric for ICU 1 relative to ICU 3 in negative-pressure mode. The reported value of 1.83 indicates that ICU 1 had a higher ACR than ICU 3 under that mode.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEGATIVE PRESSURE SCENARIO">
      <data key="d0">NEGATIVE PRESSURE SCENARIO</data>
      <data key="d1">PRESSURE_RELATIONSHIP</data>
      <data key="d2">A pressure operating condition in which particle-laden air was aspirated into the ICU by the HVAC system, indicating inward airflow behavior during the aerosol decay experiment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMERGENCY ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">EMERGENCY ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Hospital environments mentioned as potentially having aerosol concentrations that vary across space and time, requiring more detailed measurements than simple well-mixed room comparisons.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMMON AREAS">
      <data key="d0">COMMON AREAS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Shared hospital areas outside the ICU room that may receive aerosolized microparticles exfiltrated from the ICU rather than removed by the HVAC system.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NURSING STATION">
      <data key="d0">NURSING STATION</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Measured location outside or near the ICU room where dispersed aerosols were quantified after aerosolization, as listed in the table caption.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_34,62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INSIDE ROOM ZONES">
      <data key="d0">INSIDE ROOM ZONES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Interior ICU measurement region represented by Zones 1 and 2. Particle concentrations from these zones were used to estimate the fraction of aerosolized particles that remained in the room and were evacuated by HVAC.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNDER THE DOORWAY">
      <data key="d0">UNDER THE DOORWAY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Doorway leakage or transfer path where dispersed aerosols were measured after aerosolization. It represents a route for particle movement from the ICU room toward outside areas.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ICU1/ICU3 ACR RATIO">
      <data key="d0">ICU1/ICU3 ACR RATIO</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Relative air-change-rate comparison between ICU1 and ICU3. In negative mode, the reported ICU1/ICU3 ACR ratio was 1.83.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ICU1/ICU3 DECAY-RATE EXPONENT RATIO">
      <data key="d0">ICU1/ICU3 DECAY-RATE EXPONENT RATIO</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Relative aerosol decay metric comparing ICU1 with ICU3. In negative mode, the reported decay-rate exponent ratio was 1.6 and was compared with the ACR ratio to assess consistency between ventilation rate and aerosol removal.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEGATIVE MODE">
      <data key="d0">NEGATIVE MODE</data>
      <data key="d1">PRESSURE_RELATIONSHIP</data>
      <data key="d2">Pressure operating condition under which ICU1 and ICU3 were directly compared. In this mode, the ICU1/ICU3 ACR ratio was 1.83 and the decay-rate exponent ratio was 1.6.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POSITIVE MODE">
      <data key="d0">POSITIVE MODE</data>
      <data key="d1">PRESSURE_RELATIONSHIP</data>
      <data key="d2">Pressure operating condition for which similar geometry ICUs showed trends consistent with those observed in negative mode.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NONUNIFORM SPATIOTEMPORAL AEROSOL CONCENTRATIONS">
      <data key="d0">NONUNIFORM SPATIOTEMPORAL AEROSOL CONCENTRATIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Air-distribution behavior in which aerosol concentrations vary by location and time. The text notes that operating rooms and emergency rooms may exhibit this pattern and therefore require more detailed measurements.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ZONE IMMEDIATELY OUTSIDE THE ICU">
      <data key="d0">ZONE IMMEDIATELY OUTSIDE THE ICU</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The area directly outside the ICU where fugitive aerosols were observed in neutral and positive pressure scenarios. It represents the first adjacent receiving zone for aerosols leaving the ICU.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SHARED AREA">
      <data key="d0">SHARED AREA</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A surrounding common clinical area outside the ICU that could receive aerosols escaping from the room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNDER-DOOR GAP">
      <data key="d0">UNDER-DOOR GAP</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The pathway under the ICU doorway through which aerosol transport out of the room was assessed. Aerosol fraction through this pathway was calculated using averaged measurements from two sensors positioned at the door gap and outlet flow fractions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM OUTLETS">
      <data key="d0">ROOM OUTLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The outlet pathways used in the calculation of volumetric flow rates and flow fractions. For each outlet, flow rate was calculated from outlet area and average velocity, then used to estimate aerosol fraction leaving the room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOLIZED PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOLIZED PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The airborne particles released during aerosolization and tracked as a proxy for potentially infectious aerosol movement between the ICU and surrounding areas. | Modeled airborne particles released by the source occupant and dispersed according to ventilation strategy and emitter position. Their spatial distribution was linked to numerically derived individual infection risk. | Airborne aerosol particles released directly in front of the mannequin face and dispersed for 14 minutes before being used as initial positions for later tracking. The model uses a single baseline particle diameter of 0.8 µm, while the experimental geometric mean aerosol diameter is reported as 1.6 ± 1.2 µm. | Airborne particle phase released by the infected passenger in the simulations. The study tracked their volume concentration and travel time as proxies for epidemic-risk-relevant airborne exposure. | Airborne aerosol particles modeled in the arena; the text discusses aerosol behavior rather than naming a specific pathogen.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">AEROSOL PARTICLES</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL DISPERSION FRACTIONS">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL DISPERSION FRACTIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The calculated distribution of aerosolized particles among monitored locations, including inside the ICU, under the doorway, and at the nursing station. Fractions were derived from time-integrated aerosol concentration near outlets multiplied by outlet flow fractions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FUGITIVE AEROSOL PRESENCE OUTSIDE ICU">
      <data key="d0">FUGITIVE AEROSOL PRESENCE OUTSIDE ICU</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The observed pattern of aerosol escape from the ICU into surrounding zones. Fugitive aerosols were detected outside the ICU in neutral and positive pressure scenarios, were highest in open-door cases, and were not detected in closed-door negative-pressure experiments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NURSING STATIONS OUTSIDE THE ICU">
      <data key="d0">NURSING STATIONS OUTSIDE THE ICU</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Clinical work areas located outside the ICU, approximately 10–20 ft from the ICU door. These areas did not show a particulate-matter spike, likely because the trace aerosol was diluted and background particle levels were high.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ICU DOOR">
      <data key="d0">ICU DOOR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The doorway associated with the ICU and near the nursing stations. It represents a potential air and aerosol transfer pathway between the ICU and surrounding hospital areas such as the hallway and nearby nursing stations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACER AEROSOL PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">TRACER AEROSOL PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">Tracer material used experimentally for aerosol plume tracking. Although the text describes particles rather than a gas, this entity is typed as TRACER_GAS under the available ontology because it served the tracer function for measuring aerosol movement.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL PLUME TRACKING">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL PLUME TRACKING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The observed movement pattern of tracer aerosol used to characterize how aerosols propagate through the ICU and nearby hospital zones. The study used tracer particles for plume tracking, but particle size distribution was not used in the analysis.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DILUTED TRACE AEROSOL NEAR NURSING STATIONS">
      <data key="d0">DILUTED TRACE AEROSOL NEAR NURSING STATIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A distribution pattern inferred from the lack of a particulate-matter spike at nursing stations outside the ICU. The trace aerosol signal was likely diluted before reaching these stations and was difficult to distinguish from high background particle levels.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.77</data>
      <data key="d4">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">62e55c5d-3b2a-4772-a671-df2065fce8b1</data>
