      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Pathogens carried in exhaled droplets during direct respiratory transmission. The text identifies exhaled droplets as a major route for transmission of breathing diseases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NONVOLATILE RESIDUAL NUCLEI">
      <data key="d0">NONVOLATILE RESIDUAL NUCLEI</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Residual droplet nuclei that may carry infectious viral or bacterial material after liquid evaporation. The text notes contact with these residual nuclei as a transmission route and highlights residual transmission as a major issue in studies because it is difficult to prevent.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DROPLET TRAVEL PATH">
      <data key="d0">DROPLET TRAVEL PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The trajectory followed by respiratory droplets through indoor air; the text states that this path depends on initial velocity, particle size, relative humidity, environmental temperature, and especially surrounding air velocity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PATHOGEN-LADEN EXPIRATORY DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">PATHOGEN-LADEN EXPIRATORY DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory droplets carrying pathogens, referenced as a key mechanism of airborne or residual transmission in indoor environments. | Respiratory particles emitted during breathing and coughing that may carry infectious pathogens. Wu et al. simulated their Lagrangian trajectories to assess dispersion and infection risk. | Respiratory droplets carrying pathogens, referenced in the context of transmission in a coach bus. The term represents infectious expiratory material transported by enclosed-space airflow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_3,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_12,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_38,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
      <data key="d6">PATHOGEN-LADEN EXPIRATORY PARTICLES,PATHOGEN-LADEN EXPIRATORY DROPLETS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SNEEZE DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">SNEEZE DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory droplets emitted during sneezing, discussed in cited studies on airborne transmission and indoor decontamination after sneezing. | Respiratory droplets released by sneezing and studied as airborne transmissible particles. No specific pathogen is named, so they are treated as potential pathogen-bearing airborne particles rather than confirmed pathogens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_3,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_46,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
      <data key="d6">SNEEZE DROPLETS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne respiratory particles associated with passenger exposure and potential infectious transmission. | Airborne respiratory particles referenced in a cited study on human exposure in ventilated rooms. They are relevant to infection-risk reduction through ventilation, emission conditions, and distancing. | Aerosol particles produced by human respiration and studied for their motion under the action of human thermal plumes of different intensities. Although the citation does not state that the aerosols are infectious, they are represented as an airborne-pathogen-relevant contaminant class because respiratory aerosols are a key carrier pathway in hospital air-quality and infection-control analysis. | Pathogen-bearing respiratory aerosol particles generated by events such as sneezing or coughing; large particles tend to sediment, while small particles can remain suspended and disseminate through indoor airflow. | Airborne biological particles generated by respiratory behaviors and relevant to transport, deposition, and containment studies in indoor or healthcare environments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_3,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_12,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
      <data key="d6">RESPIRATORY AEROSOLS,RESPIRATORY BIOAEROSOLS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SURROUNDING AIR VELOCITY">
      <data key="d0">SURROUNDING AIR VELOCITY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A dominant airflow parameter affecting droplet transport; the text emphasizes it as especially important in determining the path of respiratory droplets.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VELOCITY FIELDS">
      <data key="d0">VELOCITY FIELDS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Spatial airflow patterns referenced in experimental and CFD studies of sneeze-droplet airborne transmission, representing how air motion distributes particles indoors. | Airflow velocity structure characterized in the sneeze-droplet transmission study using experimental work and transient CFD modeling. It represents the indoor airflow pattern that affects droplet motion and airborne transmission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_3,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
      <data key="d6">VELOCITY FIELDS</data>
    </node>
