      <data key="d2">Ventilation systems referenced in the aircraft-cabin study title as innovative and personalized. They are HVAC-related systems intended to control localized airflow and contaminant transport, although the excerpt provides no technical specifications or performance values.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.58</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE INFECTION ISOLATION ROOM">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE INFECTION ISOLATION ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A specialized hospital room type referenced in a CFD study on design optimization for airborne infection isolation. Its relevance is containment and management of airborne infectious aerosols through room design and airflow behavior.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_13,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_67</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ADVECTION-DIFFUSION OF CO2 AND AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">ADVECTION-DIFFUSION OF CO2 AND AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A contaminant-transport pattern describing movement of CO2 and aerosols through bulk airflow and diffusion. It is referenced as part of evaluating air exchange and infection risk in enclosed environments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_13,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_66</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne particulate matter referenced with CO2 in ventilation and infection-risk studies. In this context, aerosols represent respiratory particles relevant to airborne disease transmission rather than a named pathogen. | Fine airborne particles referenced in the context of penetration mechanisms and filtration efficiency through masks. No specific pathogen is identified.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_13,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_38,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_66</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b,ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
      <data key="d6">AEROSOLS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory aerosols emitted by occupants and referenced as the contaminant whose concentration and exposure are predicted among healthcare workers in an operating room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED AEROSOL CONCENTRATION FIELD">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED AEROSOL CONCENTRATION FIELD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The spatial distribution of exhaled-aerosol concentration in the operating room, referenced through the study predicting exposure among healthcare workers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HEALTHCARE WORKERS">
      <data key="d0">HEALTHCARE WORKERS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The exposed occupant group identified in the operating-room aerosol study. They are relevant to exposure assessment, though the excerpt does not explicitly identify them as aerosol sources.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.67</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SMALL HOSPITAL ELEVATOR">
      <data key="d0">SMALL HOSPITAL ELEVATOR</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A confined hospital elevator cabin modelled with CFD as the primary indoor airspace for evaluating cough-droplet dispersion and breathing-generated CO2 accumulation during a 15 s journey.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CEILING FAN">
      <data key="d0">CEILING FAN</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The elevator-mounted air-moving device used to generate the active ventilation cases in the CFD model, including upward- and downward-blowing airflow within the cabin. | A room air-movement device included in numerical modelling of an indoor environment with an upper-room ultraviolet germicidal irradiation system. It can redistribute air, alter mixing, and affect how airborne contaminants encounter UVGI fields.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
      <data key="d6">CEILING FAN</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NO VENTILATION CONDITION (NF)">
      <data key="d0">NO VENTILATION CONDITION (NF)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The baseline simulated condition with no active ventilation or fan-driven airflow in the elevator cabin, used to compare CO2 accumulation and cough-droplet dispersion against mechanically driven airflow cases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPWARD-BLOWING VENTILATION (UF)">
      <data key="d0">UPWARD-BLOWING VENTILATION (UF)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A simulated air distribution pattern in which the ceiling fan drives airflow upward in the elevator cabin, affecting the transport of exhaled CO2 and cough-generated droplets. | The upward-flow ventilation configuration generated by the upwards blowing fan at the ceiling opening. It is one of the three simulated cases used to quantify removal of droplets and residual nuclei in the clinical elevator.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
      <data key="d6">UPWARDS BLOWING VENTILATION (UF)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO STANDING OCCUPANTS">
      <data key="d0">TWO STANDING OCCUPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated occupancy load consisting of two standing people facing each other and positioned 20 cm from the longitudinal axis. Both occupants breathe and therefore contribute to CO2 accumulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ASYMPTOMATIC INFECTED OCCUPANT">
      <data key="d0">ASYMPTOMATIC INFECTED OCCUPANT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">One of the two simulated occupants, modelled as infected and asymptomatic. This occupant breathes and coughs at second 5 of the elevator journey, acting as the source of infectious respiratory emissions. | Occupancy condition in which infectious individuals are present without symptoms. The cited work assesses airborne COVID-19 transmission risk from asymptomatic individuals in practical indoor settings.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">ASYMPTOMATIC INFECTIOUS OCCUPANCY</data>
    </node>
    <node id="30 CM DIAMETER CIRCULAR CEILING HOLE">
      <data key="d0">30 CM DIAMETER CIRCULAR CEILING HOLE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">A 30 cm diameter circular opening modeled at the center of the hospital lift ceiling. Depending on the simulated case, it is treated as a closed wall for no ventilation, an upward-blowing fan boundary, or a downward-blowing air inlet.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPWARDS BLOWING FAN">
      <data key="d0">UPWARDS BLOWING FAN</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled ceiling-mounted fan condition used in the upward-flow case. It drives air upward through the ceiling opening and produces the upwards blowing ventilation configuration inside the hospital lift. | Modeled fan configuration that drives air upward inside the elevator. It is one of the evaluated ventilation cases and changes the internal airflow structure represented by velocity streamlines.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
      <data key="d6">UPWARDS-BLOWING FAN</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DOWNWARDS BLOWING AIR INLET">
      <data key="d0">DOWNWARDS BLOWING AIR INLET</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled ceiling air-supply inlet used in the downward-flow case. It introduces air downward into the hospital lift through the ceiling opening and produces the downwards blowing ventilation configuration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WITHOUT VENTILATION (NF)">
      <data key="d0">WITHOUT VENTILATION (NF)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The baseline no-ventilation case in which the ceiling hole is modeled as a wall. This condition provides a reference for comparing tracer dispersion and persistence of droplets and residual nuclei against the ventilated cases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.79</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DOWNWARDS BLOWING VENTILATION (DF)">
      <data key="d0">DOWNWARDS BLOWING VENTILATION (DF)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The downward-flow ventilation configuration generated by the downward blowing ceiling inlet. It is one of the three CFD cases evaluated for aerosol transport and particle-removal behavior in the hospital lift. | Air distribution pattern produced by downward-blowing ventilation. It expelled the most CO2 gas and achieved the fastest droplet removal, but the study noted that it was difficult to conclude that it was safer than the upward-blowing fan case based on risk probability.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
      <data key="d6">DOWNWARDS-BLOWING VENTILATION CASE</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DROPLETS AND RESIDUAL NUCLEI">
      <data key="d0">DROPLETS AND RESIDUAL NUCLEI</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne respiratory particles whose removal is quantitatively evaluated across the no-ventilation, upward-flow, and downward-flow ventilation setups in the hospital lift. CO2 is used as a numerical tracer to support analysis of their transport and removal behavior.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LIFT">
      <data key="d0">LIFT</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled enclosed clinical-condition zone where ventilation airflow, breathing, and coughing are simulated. The lift interior is modeled at 25 °C and 50% relative humidity according to UNE 100713:2005, and contains two human mannequins positioned face to face 1.5 m apart.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.97</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_16,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_29,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_33,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_35,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAN">
      <data key="d0">FAN</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation unit producing the supply airflow for the modeled lift. When ventilation is used, the air supply velocity through the fan is 6.5 m/s. The fan-generated stream is simplified in the model as flow through a simple hole.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_16,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_23,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THREE AIR SUPPLY RACKS">
      <data key="d0">THREE AIR SUPPLY RACKS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Three modeled supply-air openings located on one sidewall of the lift. Each rack is 0.01 cm thick and 1.5 m long, located 15 cm from the floor, with 15 cm vertical spacing between racks. They define a major ventilation-air entry path into the lift.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SIMPLE HOLE">
      <data key="d0">SIMPLE HOLE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Idealized air opening used to simplify the stream produced by the fan. It represents the fan outlet or discharge path in the ventilation model rather than explicitly modeling detailed fan geometry.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAN-PRODUCED STREAM">
      <data key="d0">FAN-PRODUCED STREAM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation-driven airflow pattern generated by the fan and represented as a simplified jet or stream through a simple hole. This pattern affects air movement and potential transport of exhaled material inside the lift.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO 1.7 M TALL HUMANS">
      <data key="d0">TWO 1.7 M TALL HUMANS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled occupancy load inside the lift consisting of two 1.7 m tall human mannequins positioned face to face and spaced 1.5 m apart. The mannequins include nose and mouth openings to reproduce breathing and coughing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NOSE AND MOUTH OPENINGS">
      <data key="d0">NOSE AND MOUTH OPENINGS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory openings configured on the human mannequins to reproduce breathing and coughing. The nostril outlets are two elliptical holes approximately 1.7 cm long and 0.5 cm wide, while the mouth is a 4 cm long and 0.5 cm opening.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY AEROSOLS AND DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY AEROSOLS AND DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne respiratory material associated with breathing and coughing simulation from the human mannequins. These aerosols and droplets are relevant to infection-risk evaluation because their transport depends on ventilation airflow and indoor air distribution. | Respiratory particles emitted during breathing or other respiratory events. They are not pathogens themselves but are modeled as potential carriers of infectious agents within the available airborne-pathogen schema category. | Particles or droplets emitted by the infected spreader manikin during respiratory events such as breathing, speaking, sneezing, or coughing. They are the simulated airborne contaminant whose dissemination is evaluated in the ventilated coach. | Aerosol and droplet particles expelled from the singers' respiratory tract during classical singing; the text treats them as potential airborne transmission-relevant particles, though pathogen content was not directly measured.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
      <data key="d6">RESPIRATORY DROPS AND DROPLETS,RESPIRATORY PARTICLES AND DROPLETS,RESPIRATORY AEROSOL AND DROPLET PARTICLES</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPUTATIONAL DOMAIN">
      <data key="d0">COMPUTATIONAL DOMAIN</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled indoor airspace shown in the computational-domain figures and measurements table. It is the zone into which the mouth and nose inlet airflow profiles are introduced and where respiratory airflow transport is evaluated.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MOUTH INLET">
      <data key="d0">MOUTH INLET</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled oral opening used as an airflow inlet for mouth breathing and coughing. The mouth-breathing velocity profile has a maximum peak of 4.4 m/s, and coughing occurs between seconds 5 and 5.5.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NOSE INLET">
      <data key="d0">NOSE INLET</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled nasal opening used as an airflow inlet for nose breathing. The nose-breathing velocity profile has a maximum peak of 2.2 m/s.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMITTER OCCUPANT">
      <data key="d0">EMITTER OCCUPANT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled person who emits respiratory airflow through breathing and coughing. The emitter breath profile is sinusoidal for exhalation and inhalation, with a noncontinuous breathing sequence because coughing starts at second 5 and ends at second 5.5.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RECEPTOR OCCUPANT">
      <data key="d0">RECEPTOR OCCUPANT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled person exposed to the airflow field. The receptor breathing velocity profile is described as cosine-shaped with the same mouth and nose velocity peaks used for the emitter breathing profiles.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MOUTH BREATHING AND COUGHING VELOCITY PROFILE">
      <data key="d0">MOUTH BREATHING AND COUGHING VELOCITY PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Time-varying oral airflow distribution pattern for breathing and coughing. Mouth breathing reaches a maximum peak velocity of 4.4 m/s, while the cough interrupts the breathing cycle from second 5 to second 5.5.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NOSE BREATHING VELOCITY PROFILE">
      <data key="d0">NOSE BREATHING VELOCITY PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Time-varying nasal airflow distribution pattern for breathing. Nose breathing reaches a maximum peak velocity of 2.2 m/s and is modeled as part of the respiratory inlet boundary conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COUGH EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">COUGH EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated infected occupant who coughs and breathes in the model. The cough occurs from second 5 to second 5.5, making the breathing profile noncontinuous during that interval. The cough total volume is 0.64 L, and this occupant is the only monitored source of exhaled CO2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RECEPTOR">
      <data key="d0">RECEPTOR</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated receiving occupant exposed to the cough emitter. The receptor breath is modeled as a continuous cosine profile with the same velocity peaks as the cough emitter and a total breathing cycle time of 6 seconds.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.64</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED CO2">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED CO2</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">Carbon dioxide exhaled only by the cough emitter and modeled as an Eulerian phase. It is monitored to isolate the CO2 increase attributable to the infected occupant and to represent dispersion of exhaled gas in the simulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_18,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_32,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_50</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MOUTH EXHALATION AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">MOUTH EXHALATION AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled oral exhalation pathway carrying part of the pulmonary ventilation flow. The mouth accounts for 33.6 L/min of the total 40.7 L/min pulmonary ventilation rate, and the mouth-exhaled gas mixture is described as 78% N2, 17% O2, and 5% CO2. | The modeled nasal exhalation pathway carrying 7.1 L/min of the total 40.7 L/min pulmonary ventilation rate.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
      <data key="d6">NOSE EXHALATION AIR PATH</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED GAS MIXTURE">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED GAS MIXTURE</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">The gas composition exhaled through the mouth, consisting of 78% nitrogen, 17% oxygen, and 5% carbon dioxide. Within the model context, the CO2 fraction is the monitored component used to track the infected person's contribution.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.52</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTED PERSON">
      <data key="d0">INFECTED PERSON</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The infected occupant was represented by the cough emitter and served as the sole source of the monitored CO2 increase and cough emission. | Occupant source who can emit SARS-CoV-2-containing droplets and aerosol particles through respiratory activities, contributing to indoor airborne infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_19,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_35,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_40,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b,ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
      <data key="d6">INFECTED PERSON</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COUGH INLET VELOCITY PROFILE">
      <data key="d0">COUGH INLET VELOCITY PROFILE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated cough airflow pattern had a total cough volume of 0.64 L and a total cough duration of 0.5 s. Its velocity profile was divided into four phases: an immediate rise to 17.7 m/s, followed by decreases ending at 3.9 m/s, 1.995 m/s, and 1.575 m/s.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR PATH BETWEEN EMITTER AND RECEPTOR MANNEQUINS">
      <data key="d0">AIR PATH BETWEEN EMITTER AND RECEPTOR MANNEQUINS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled downstream region extending from the emitter mannequin’s head toward the receptor mannequin, including the space between the two human bodies where airflow or emitted respiratory material would be transported.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMITTER AND RECEPTOR MANNEQUINS">
      <data key="d0">EMITTER AND RECEPTOR MANNEQUINS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Two human-shaped mannequins represented in the computational model: one acting as the emitter and the other as the receptor. Their body shapes influence the discretized flow domain.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COUGH AIRFLOW PATH DOWNSTREAM OF EMITTER MOUTH">
      <data key="d0">COUGH AIRFLOW PATH DOWNSTREAM OF EMITTER MOUTH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Airflow path evaluated 10 cm downstream from the mouth of the emitter during the numerical mesh dependency study; the studied case used a maximum cough velocity of 17.7 m/s.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AXIAL VELOCITY DISTRIBUTION AT 10 CM DOWNSTREAM">
      <data key="d0">AXIAL VELOCITY DISTRIBUTION AT 10 CM DOWNSTREAM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Numerical airflow distribution represented by axial velocity measurements taken 10 cm downstream from the emitter mouth to assess mesh independence using fine, medium, and coarse meshes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ELEVATOR CABIN">
      <data key="d0">ELEVATOR CABIN</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled lift interior representing a clinical enclosed zone where ventilation-driven airflow was simulated under constant ambient conditions of 25 °C and 50% relative humidity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR SUPPLY RACKS">
      <data key="d0">AIR SUPPLY RACKS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Air-introduction paths in the elevator CFD model. The racks were configured as stagnation inlets and supplied air with the same composition as the initial clinical atmosphere.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MOUTH INLETS">
      <data key="d0">MOUTH INLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Additional inlet paths included in the elevator ventilation boundary conditions. They contributed to the specified airflow field inside the modeled cabin.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAN EXHAUST PRESSURE OUTLET AT −35 PA">
      <data key="d0">FAN EXHAUST PRESSURE OUTLET AT −35 PA</data>
      <data key="d1">PRESSURE_RELATIONSHIP</data>
      <data key="d2">The negative-pressure boundary condition applied when the fan was used to exhaust air from the elevator cabin. The −35 Pa pressure outlet generated a maximum outlet velocity of 6.5 m/s near the fan-connected zone.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPWARD FAN-DRIVEN AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">UPWARD FAN-DRIVEN AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A simulated airflow case associated with fan exhaust operation, described in the convergence comparison as the upward-blowing fan case. | A simulated airflow case in which the fan was configured as a velocity inlet blowing downward at 6.5 m/s into the elevator cabin.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
      <data key="d6">DOWNWARD FAN-DRIVEN AIRFLOW</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NO-FAN AIRFLOW CASE">
      <data key="d0">NO-FAN AIRFLOW CASE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The baseline simulated airflow condition in the elevator cabin without fan-assisted ventilation, used for comparison with the upward and downward fan configurations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ELEVATOR">
      <data key="d0">ELEVATOR</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Enclosed simulation domain in which airflow, fan configurations, respiratory emissions, aerosols, and droplets are modeled. Although not explicitly identified as a hospital room, it functions as the occupied indoor zone in the ventilation and contaminant-transport analysis.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DOWNWARDS-BLOWING FAN">
      <data key="d0">DOWNWARDS-BLOWING FAN</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled fan configuration that drives air downward inside the elevator. It provides a contrasting ventilation condition and modifies the simulated airflow and contaminant-transport behavior. | Mechanical ventilation configuration in the lift that blows air downward. It rapidly drives many droplets toward the floor, removing most from the airborne domain, while allowing some particles to avoid impact and recirculate.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_24,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_35,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_36,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
      <data key="d6">DOWNWARDS BLOWING FAN</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ELEVATOR INTERNAL AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">ELEVATOR INTERNAL AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Continuous air motion inside the elevator simulation domain. Once established, it provides the carrier flow for respiration-generated aerosol and droplet parcels modeled in the Lagrangian phase.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VELOCITY STREAMLINES">
      <data key="d0">VELOCITY STREAMLINES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Simulated airflow distribution pattern shown for the no-fan, upward-blowing-fan, and downward-blowing-fan cases. The streamlines visualize how air moves through the elevator under each ventilation condition.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATION-GENERATED AEROSOL AND DROPLET PARCELS">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATION-GENERATED AEROSOL AND DROPLET PARCELS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory emission particles injected from the emitter mouth and modeled as a Lagrangian phase in the two-phase flow simulation. The text describes the samples as pure water droplets without residue, so this entity represents an airborne contaminant or pathogen-transport surrogate rather than a confirmed pathogen.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TURBULENT PARTICLE DISPERSION WITH EXACT EDDY INTERACTION TIME">
      <data key="d0">TURBULENT PARTICLE DISPERSION WITH EXACT EDDY INTERACTION TIME</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A modeled particle-transport pattern in which injected droplets disperse under turbulent flow conditions using an exact eddy interaction time approach. This pattern is relevant to predicting airborne droplet or pathogen movement, although the excerpt does not specify a hospital zone or HVAC system.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EVAPORATING RESPIRATORY DROPLET PLUME">
      <data key="d0">EVAPORATING RESPIRATORY DROPLET PLUME</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated airborne droplet plume undergoing injection, breakup, turbulent dispersion, and evaporation. Droplet diameters are selected using a Rosin–Rammler distribution over a 10–300 µm range with an 80 µm mean diameter.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COUGH-GENERATED DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">COUGH-GENERATED DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory droplets released by a cough and modeled as dispersed airborne particles whose motion is influenced by drag, gravity, buoyancy, pressure gradients, and surrounding air streams. | Saliva droplets produced by coughing and studied for their indoor transport behavior; represented as airborne infectious material or pathogen-carrying droplets within the valid type system.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_26,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_33,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
      <data key="d6">COUGH-GENERATED SALIVA DROPLETS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EULERIAN AIR PHASE">
      <data key="d0">EULERIAN AIR PHASE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The surrounding air medium through which droplets move; droplet drag is calculated as a function of relative velocity within this air phase.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRFLOW-DRIVEN DROPLET DISPERSION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">AIRFLOW-DRIVEN DROPLET DISPERSION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The unsteady spatial dispersion behavior of cough-generated droplets as affected by air streams and applied forces over time.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PRESSURE GRADIENT AFFECTING DROPLET PATH">
      <data key="d0">PRESSURE GRADIENT AFFECTING DROPLET PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">PRESSURE_RELATIONSHIP</data>
      <data key="d2">A pressure-gradient force identified as one of the factors influencing droplet trajectory after the initial cough-driven motion subsides.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.45</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPIRATORY AIRFLOW DURING BREATHING AND COUGHING">
      <data key="d0">EXPIRATORY AIRFLOW DURING BREATHING AND COUGHING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled airflow path from the mouth during breathing and coughing, with maximum velocities of 4.4 m/s during breathing and 17.7 m/s during coughing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DROPLET DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">DROPLET DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated spatial distribution and movement of droplets generated by breathing and coughing airflow. | Spatial spread pattern of expelled respiratory droplets referenced in the study of face shields and masks with exhalation valves. It is relevant to evaluating how respiratory particles distribute through surrounding air.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_27,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_37,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_66</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">DROPLET DISPERSAL</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NO FAN">
      <data key="d0">NO FAN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Non-ventilated baseline condition in the lift. CO2 followed a sinusoidal accumulative increase and reached the maximum reported concentration increase of 35 ppm at the end of the 15 s simulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPWARDS-BLOWING CASE">
      <data key="d0">UPWARDS-BLOWING CASE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilated airflow condition in which the fan blew air upward inside the lift. CO2 concentration was generally lower than in the no-fan case, except during the first second, and this case showed the highest increasing ratio during the first two CO2 expulsion cycles. | Ventilation airflow configuration in which air is blown upward. It is compared with no-fan and downward-blowing cases to assess how airflow direction affects droplet dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_29,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
      <data key="d6">UPWARDS BLOWING CASE</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PERSON COUGHING">
      <data key="d0">PERSON COUGHING</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The single occupant source of CO2 in the lift simulation. This person expelled CO2 and other gases in a sinusoidal breathing pattern, including expulsion and aspiration phases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CO2 EXHAUSTING STREAM">
      <data key="d0">CO2 EXHAUSTING STREAM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The CO2 exhausting stream is the removal pathway through which CO2 leaves the studied breathing/ventilation region. It was reported to become established at the 13th second in the upward-blowing fan case.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NO FAN CASE">
      <data key="d0">NO FAN CASE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The no fan case is the condition without fan-driven airflow. It was described as totally cyclic and harmonious, indicating regular and repeatable CO2 concentration behavior.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_30,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_31,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_32,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_33,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_34,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_35,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_37,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONTAGIOUS AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">CONTAGIOUS AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Contagious aerosols represent infectious airborne material used in the infection-probability model. The text describes emitted quanta as the number of contagious aerosols emitted per hour, with one quantum being the amount required to cause infection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLOSED SPACE">
      <data key="d0">CLOSED SPACE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The closed space is the indoor zone for which the cited infection-probability equation calculates risk. Although not specified as a hospital area, it functions as the occupied indoor zone in the ventilation and infection-risk context.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONTAGIOUS AEROSOL QUANTA">
      <data key="d0">CONTAGIOUS AEROSOL QUANTA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Infectious aerosol dose represented as quanta emitted per hour. The study assumes an emission rate of 20 quanta per hour, based on prior studies using 14 and 100 quanta per hour, and uses this value in the COVID-19 infection-probability calculation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PATHOGEN-BEARING COUGH DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">PATHOGEN-BEARING COUGH DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory droplets produced by coughing and treated as infection-relevant airborne material whose removal from the computational domain is tracked through the droplet quantity fraction. The droplets appeared suddenly around the 5th second, and their evaporation or expulsion differed substantially among the fan-direction and no-fan cases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DROPLET CLOUD">
      <data key="d0">DROPLET CLOUD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled respiratory droplet plume used as the airborne contaminant proxy in the dispersion analysis. Its position, particle number, and size change over time due to cough momentum, airflow conditions, gravity, drag, buoyancy, and evaporation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INITIAL COUGH JET">
      <data key="d0">INITIAL COUGH JET</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The initial exhaled airflow path from the mouth that provides the primary horizontal momentum to the droplet cloud, especially in the no-fan case.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_34,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHAUSTING FAN">
      <data key="d0">EXHAUSTING FAN</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The exhaust-associated fan or exhaust location in the upward-blowing fan case. Droplets near this fan disappear before being expelled because of evaporation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHAUSTING STREAM">
      <data key="d0">EXHAUSTING STREAM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The exhaust-related airflow path in the upward-blowing fan case that attracts cough droplets immediately after their initial forward movement.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RECIRCULATION BEHAVIOUR">
      <data key="d0">RECIRCULATION BEHAVIOUR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The recirculating airflow pattern produced in the upward-blowing fan case. It keeps droplets behind and to the left of the infected person, maintains some particles above the emitter's head, and prevents droplets from reaching the second occupant.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Cough-generated respiratory droplets emitted by the infected person and used as the airborne infectious-particle surrogate whose dispersion is affected by lift airflow, fan direction, recirculation, and evaporation. | Respiratory droplets represented in the simulation as airborne contaminant particles. They are transported by exhaled airflow, pass through the mask and leak zones in the poorly fitted mask case, and are driven upward by the buoyant plume toward the top of the simulation domain.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_35,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">DROPLETS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SECOND OCCUPANT">
      <data key="d0">SECOND OCCUPANT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The other occupant in the lift used to evaluate potential droplet exposure. In the upward-blowing fan case, no droplet reaches this occupant because recirculation keeps particles near the infected person.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_35,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLINICAL LIFT">
      <data key="d0">CLINICAL LIFT</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The enclosed hospital lift compartment used as the CFD study domain. Two occupants face each other inside it, one coughs, and droplet and CO2 transport are evaluated under simplified fan-flow conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CIRCULAR HOLE">
      <data key="d0">CIRCULAR HOLE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">A simplified modeled opening used to represent the downwards-blowing fan case. The study notes that representing the fan as a circular hole with negative pressure may alter real airflow results.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_36,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VELOCITY INLET">
      <data key="d0">VELOCITY INLET</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">A simplified airflow boundary condition used to represent the upwards-blowing fan case. It replaces detailed fan geometry with an imposed inlet velocity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_36,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DROPLET DISPERSION INSIDE THE LIFT">
      <data key="d0">DROPLET DISPERSION INSIDE THE LIFT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The observed particle transport pattern in the lift for the downwards-blowing fan case. Droplets move downward rapidly, most attach to the bottom surface or evaporate, while a small number recirculate and travel farther from the source.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LIMITED RECIRCULATION">
      <data key="d0">LIMITED RECIRCULATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A secondary airflow-driven particle pathway in which a few particles avoid floor attachment and evaporation, pass through the main stream, move upward, and approach positions near the second occupant.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOW-LEVEL TOTAL DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">LOW-LEVEL TOTAL DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The study's characterization of the downwards-blowing fan case: dispersion may be considered total across Cartesian axes, but at a low level because only a few particles reach positions far from the source.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO FACE-TO-FACE OCCUPANTS">
      <data key="d0">TWO FACE-TO-FACE OCCUPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled occupancy condition in the clinical lift: two subjects face each other in a confined lift, creating a possible but poorly likely exposure scenario.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COUGHING PERSON">
      <data key="d0">COUGHING PERSON</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The source occupant in the lift scenario. This person coughs, emits droplets, and is the only modeled source of exhaled CO2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DOWNWARDS-BLOWING FAN VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">DOWNWARDS-BLOWING FAN VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">A simulated fan-ventilation configuration in which air is driven downward. In the DF case, supply air immediately interacted with respiratory emissions, directly affecting CO2 transport and droplet dispersion, and it was reported as the most suitable approach based on the CO2 concentration results.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUPPLY AIR">
      <data key="d0">SUPPLY AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The incoming or renewed air supplied in the fan-ventilation cases. The text emphasizes that supply air strongly affects interactions with respiratory flows and contaminant transport, including CO2 emission and droplet dispersion. | The incoming air stream to the modeled venue. Its temperature and boundary-condition characteristics are measured and used to define the room-air flow and thermal simulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">SUPPLY AIR</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY FLOWS">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY FLOWS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Exhaled airflow carrying respiratory emissions. The text states that supply air has an important effect on interactions with these flows, especially in determining how CO2 and droplets disperse.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.81</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GAS MIXING HOMOGENEITY INSIDE THE DOMAIN">
      <data key="d0">GAS MIXING HOMOGENEITY INSIDE THE DOMAIN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The degree to which gas is uniformly mixed within the simulated domain. The cited work indicates that the simplified fan approximation is not valid for calculating this property because it lacks realistic turbulence and fan-induced flow structures.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HELICAL STREAMS OF A FAN">
      <data key="d0">HELICAL STREAMS OF A FAN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The typical swirling or rotational airflow pattern produced by a real fan. The simulation did not generate these helical streams, limiting its ability to represent detailed turbulent mixing behavior.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.73</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ELEVATOR DOMAIN">
      <data key="d0">ELEVATOR DOMAIN</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled enclosed elevator volume in which ventilation setup performance, contaminant concentration, and droplet removal were evaluated. The reported results were averaged over the entire computational domain, and future work was recommended to divide the domain into height-based volume controls to identify higher-risk zones.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPANISH SECONDARY SCHOOL AND UNIVERSITY CLASSROOMS">
      <data key="d0">SPANISH SECONDARY SCHOOL AND UNIVERSITY CLASSROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor classroom spaces referenced from a cited study on indoor air quality and COVID-19 infection risk. They are included as comparative ventilation zones because the cited work recommended a specific top-supply and bottom-outlet airflow arrangement.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_38,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INLET SUPPLY AIR AT THE TOP">
      <data key="d0">INLET SUPPLY AIR AT THE TOP</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">An upper supply-air entry path recommended in the cited classroom ventilation study. It introduces air from the top of the enclosure and forms one part of a top-to-bottom ventilation strategy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OUTLET AT THE BOTTOM">
      <data key="d0">OUTLET AT THE BOTTOM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">A lower exhaust or outlet path recommended in the cited classroom ventilation study. It removes air from the bottom of the enclosure and completes the top-inlet, bottom-outlet ventilation arrangement.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TOP-INLET BOTTOM-OUTLET SETUP">
      <data key="d0">TOP-INLET BOTTOM-OUTLET SETUP</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A recommended air distribution pattern in which supply air enters at the top of the room and exits at the bottom. It is referenced as a comparative ventilation recommendation for reducing indoor contaminant and COVID-19 infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DOMAIN-AVERAGED CONTAMINANT CONCENTRATION">
      <data key="d0">DOMAIN-AVERAGED CONTAMINANT CONCENTRATION</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">The reported ppm-based concentration value representing a single averaged result for the whole computational domain volume. The two proposed ventilation setups coincided at approximately 20.2 ppm around the 15-second point.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COUGHING OCCUPANT">
      <data key="d0">COUGHING OCCUPANT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The occupant source represented by the coughing event that introduced respiratory droplets into the elevator domain. This source event drives the short-term contaminant release scenario evaluated across ventilation cases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_38,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_79</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HEIGHT-BASED VOLUME CONTROLS">
      <data key="d0">HEIGHT-BASED VOLUME CONTROLS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Proposed subdivisions of the elevator computational domain by height and volume. The authors recommended using such controls in future work to locate the riskiest vertical zones rather than relying only on a single domain-averaged value.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRABLE PATHOGENS">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRABLE PATHOGENS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respirable pathogens are referenced through the cited work on secondary airborne infection risk. They represent infectious agents that may be emitted and transported in respirable airborne particles, although the passage does not identify a specific pathogen or quantify transmission risk. | General class of pathogens referenced in the cited work on emissions contributing to secondary airborne infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_39,c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_75</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
