    <node id="VENTILATION RATIOS">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION RATIOS</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation-rate variable recommended for future testing. Different ventilation ratios could affect contaminant transport and help build a database for predicting improved ventilation systems in small closed spaces. | Ventilation rate represents the level of outdoor-air replacement or air-change effectiveness in indoor spaces. The references discuss seasonal changes in ventilation, natural ventilation, and ventilation-related mitigation of airborne infection risk. | Ventilation flow rates or air-exchange conditions that must be optimized to balance airborne transmission risk against operating costs. The text notes that increasing flow rates does not always necessarily improve results. | Ventilation rate refers to the air-exchange or ventilation condition discussed as a preventive measure affecting indoor airborne transmission risk. It is cited in the context of reducing aerosol accumulation indoors. | The effective rate of room air exchange associated with active ventilation. Prior aerosol-transport studies cited in the text identify ventilation rate as an important factor affecting indoor aerosol and tracer distribution. | The implied air-renewal or ventilation intensity considered for optimization; no numerical air-change value is provided in the text.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">VENTILATION RATE,VENTILATION RATES</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NO FAN CASE DROPLET DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">NO FAN CASE DROPLET DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Droplet movement pattern in the lift without mechanical ventilation. Transport is mainly caused by the initial cough jet, followed by vertical gravitational settling opposed by air drag, producing the smallest dispersion among the three compared cases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPWARDS-BLOWING FAN RECIRCULATION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">UPWARDS-BLOWING FAN RECIRCULATION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Air distribution pattern generated by the upward fan. The fan-induced recirculation maintains many particles near the origin or emitter zone, giving greater dispersion than the no-fan case but relatively lower direct exposure in the healthy passenger area.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DOWNWARDS BLOWING FAN FLOOR-IMPACT AND RECIRCULATION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">DOWNWARDS BLOWING FAN FLOOR-IMPACT AND RECIRCULATION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Air distribution pattern generated by the downward fan. Most droplets are quickly driven onto the floor and removed from the airborne computational domain, but a smaller fraction can avoid collision, recirculate inside the lift, and reach the healthy passenger breathing region.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RECIRCULATION INSIDE THE LIFT">
      <data key="d0">RECIRCULATION INSIDE THE LIFT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Internal looping airflow path within the lift. It is important in fan-driven cases because it can keep particles near the emitter region or transport residual particles toward the healthy passenger respiration volume.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMITTER REGION">
      <data key="d0">EMITTER REGION</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Subregion of the lift near the infected person where cough droplets originate. In the upwards-blowing fan case, recirculation keeps many droplets concentrated around this origin zone.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
