      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Air distribution pattern produced by the upward-blowing fan. It was evaluated for mass CO2 concentration, cough-particle removal, droplet deletion, liquid droplet dispersion, and risk probability relative to the other ventilation cases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COUGH-RELEASED DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">COUGH-RELEASED DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Liquid respiratory droplets released into the air when the infected person coughed after 5 seconds. Their removal, deletion rate, evaporation, fall behavior, and dispersion were compared under the three ventilation scenarios. | Respiratory droplets generated by coughing and modeled as airborne infectious-risk carriers whose dispersion, transmission, and removal are assessed in train or subway carriage studies.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
