      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Broad class of pathogens referenced in the cited article title, 'Recognition of aerosol transmission of infectious agents.' The text does not specify individual organisms, so this is retained as a general airborne-pathogen category. | Generic infectious material whose airborne dispersion in confined and ventilated spaces is evaluated using CFD-based modeling of respiratory particle transport. | Infectious agents are mentioned in the context of aerosol transmission, representing pathogens that may remain suspended in air and spread through airborne routes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_43</data>
