      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONFINED AND POORLY VENTILATED INDOOR SPACES">
      <data key="d0">CONFINED AND POORLY VENTILATED INDOOR SPACES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor occupied zones with limited air exchange and confinement, described as settings where SARS-CoV-2 transmission events have been reported due in part to accumulation of infectious aerosols.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INDOOR EVENT VENUES">
      <data key="d0">INDOOR EVENT VENUES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor venues used for large- or small-scale events. These occupied indoor zones were subject to closure during the pandemic because gatherings were assumed to increase SARS-CoV-2 transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WELL-FUNCTIONING VENTILATION SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">WELL-FUNCTIONING VENTILATION SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation systems described as capable of keeping event-related SARS-CoV-2 infection risk very low when operating effectively and combined with appropriate mitigation strategies.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ADEQUATE VENTILATION AIR EXCHANGE">
      <data key="d0">ADEQUATE VENTILATION AIR EXCHANGE</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Sufficient ventilation-driven air exchange implied by well-functioning ventilation systems, reducing exposure to infectious aerosols in indoor event environments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LARGE- AND SMALL-SCALE EVENTS">
      <data key="d0">LARGE- AND SMALL-SCALE EVENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Gatherings of people at varying scales that increase the number of potential emitters and exposed occupants in shared indoor air, thereby increasing assumed transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INDOOR VENUES">
      <data key="d0">INDOOR VENUES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor occupied spaces such as live music venues where heterogeneous ventilation strategies shape room airflow and the accumulation of airborne pathogens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OCCUPIED ZONE">
      <data key="d0">OCCUPIED ZONE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The portion of an indoor room where people are present and exposed to supplied air, mixed room air, contaminants, and pathogen-laden aerosols.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_3,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MECHANICALLY VENTILATED ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">MECHANICALLY VENTILATED ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Rooms using mechanical air supply and exhaust systems, contrasted with naturally ventilated rooms. Displacement and mixing ventilation are described as mechanically ventilated concepts.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.79</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INDOOR MASS-GATHERING LIVE MUSIC EVENT">
      <data key="d0">INDOOR MASS-GATHERING LIVE MUSIC EVENT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A high-density indoor event context in which SARS-CoV-2 screening and transmission prevention were studied. Such gatherings increase the number of potential aerosol emitters and exposed occupants.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_3,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_64</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH OCCUPANCY BUILDINGS">
      <data key="d0">HIGH OCCUPANCY BUILDINGS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Buildings with large numbers of occupants, referenced in relation to ventilation strategies intended to reduce airborne disease transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_3,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_64,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_65</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISPLACEMENT VENTILATION (DV)">
      <data key="d0">DISPLACEMENT VENTILATION (DV)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A ventilation distribution concept in which low-velocity air is supplied above the floor directly to the occupied zone, rises through the room because of buoyancy, and is exhausted at the ceiling. | A displacement ventilation air-distribution pattern considered in venue-specific risk recommendations. For events longer than 3 hours under Omicron conditions, the text recommends surgical masks or reduced occupancy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">DISPLACEMENT VENTILATION CASE DVV</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MIXING VENTILATION (MV)">
      <data key="d0">MIXING VENTILATION (MV)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A ventilation distribution concept in which high-velocity air is introduced from the ceiling or side wall outside the occupied zone, mixes with indoor air, dilutes contaminants, and is then exhausted.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NATURAL VENTILATION (NV)">
      <data key="d0">NATURAL VENTILATION (NV)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A ventilation concept that uses natural forces such as wind or buoyancy rather than mechanical ventilation to create indoor airflow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR SUPPLY AND EXTRACTION CONFIGURATION">
      <data key="d0">AIR SUPPLY AND EXTRACTION CONFIGURATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The arrangement of how air is supplied to and extracted from a room. The text identifies this configuration as a key determinant of room-specific airflow and airborne pathogen accumulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM-SPECIFIC AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">ROOM-SPECIFIC AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The airflow pattern produced within a particular room by its ventilation strategy and supply/exhaust layout. It strongly influences whether airborne pathogens accumulate or are removed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOW-VELOCITY FLOOR-LEVEL SUPPLY AIR">
      <data key="d0">LOW-VELOCITY FLOOR-LEVEL SUPPLY AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The displacement-ventilation supply path in which air is delivered at low velocity above the floor directly into the occupied zone.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BUOYANCY-DRIVEN UPWARD AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">BUOYANCY-DRIVEN UPWARD AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The upward air movement in displacement ventilation, where supplied air rises from the occupied zone because of buoyancy effects.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CEILING EXHAUST AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">CEILING EXHAUST AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The exhaust route described for displacement ventilation, where air that has risen through the room is removed at the ceiling.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH-VELOCITY CEILING OR SIDE-WALL SUPPLY AIR">
      <data key="d0">HIGH-VELOCITY CEILING OR SIDE-WALL SUPPLY AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The mixing-ventilation supply route in which air is introduced at high velocity from ceiling or side-wall locations outside the occupied zone.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MIXED INDOOR AIR DILUTION PATH">
      <data key="d0">MIXED INDOOR AIR DILUTION PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The airflow process in mixing ventilation where supplied air mixes with indoor air to dilute contaminants before exhaust.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.81</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WIND- OR BUOYANCY-DRIVEN NATURAL AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">WIND- OR BUOYANCY-DRIVEN NATURAL AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The air movement created in natural ventilation by wind pressure or buoyancy effects rather than by mechanical supply or exhaust equipment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE CONTAMINANTS">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE CONTAMINANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Contaminant-laden indoor air constituents, including possible pathogen-containing aerosols, that mixing ventilation aims to dilute before removal by exhaust.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.77</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISPLACEMENT VENTILATION SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">DISPLACEMENT VENTILATION SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Displacement ventilation systems, abbreviated as DV systems, are presented as an air-distribution approach associated in many studies with higher ventilation effectiveness and a lower risk of airborne disease transmission than mixing ventilation or natural ventilation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_4,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_38,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_75,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_77</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MIXING VENTILATION SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">MIXING VENTILATION SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Mixing ventilation systems, abbreviated as MV systems, are described as supplying air that mixes with indoor air to dilute contaminants, which are then exhausted. MV systems are used as a comparator to displacement ventilation for airborne disease transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NATURAL VENTILATION SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">NATURAL VENTILATION SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Natural ventilation systems, abbreviated as NV systems, rely only on natural forces such as wind or buoyancy effects to create air movement and supply fresh air. NV systems are compared with displacement and mixing ventilation in relation to airborne disease transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_4,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE CONTAMINANTS AND PATHOGENS">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE CONTAMINANTS AND PATHOGENS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne contaminants, including pathogen-bearing aerosols implicated in airborne disease transmission, are described as being diluted by mixed indoor air and exhausted, with transmission risk influenced by the ventilation distribution pattern.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FRESH AIR SUPPLY PATH">
      <data key="d0">FRESH AIR SUPPLY PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The pathway by which fresh outdoor air is supplied into an indoor space. In natural ventilation, this air movement is driven by wind or buoyancy effects rather than mechanical fans.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHAUST AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">EXHAUST AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The pathway by which diluted indoor contaminants are removed from the indoor environment after mixing with room air.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="≥3 AIR CHANGES PER HOUR">
      <data key="d0">≥3 AIR CHANGES PER HOUR</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">A ventilation-rate threshold identified as sufficient for effectively reducing infection risk when displacement ventilation is used. The text highlights this rate as at least three air changes per hour. | Air exchange rate of the actual ventilation system, produced by an air supply of 198,000 m3 h-1. It defines the baseline dilution condition for aerosol-dispersion modeling in the arena. | Air exchange rate of the modified ventilation system, produced by the reduced air supply of 115,000 m3 h-1. It defines the dilution condition for the virtual displacement-flow scenario.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">1.46 AIR CHANGES PER HOUR,0.85 AIR CHANGES PER HOUR</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OFFICE VENTILATION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">OFFICE VENTILATION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation system context in the referenced office study comparing mixing and displacement ventilation for airborne particle exposure. | A ventilation condition presumed to provide adequate aerosol control. Under this condition, indoor mass gatherings with suitable hygiene practices were estimated to have very small, if any, effect on epidemic spread.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">EFFECTIVE VENTILATION SYSTEM</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THREE DIFFERENT VENTILATION SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">THREE DIFFERENT VENTILATION SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation systems referenced in a two-bed hospital ward study evaluating the dispersion of exhaled droplet nuclei under different ventilation configurations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_5,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_66</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO-BED HOSPITAL WARD">
      <data key="d0">TWO-BED HOSPITAL WARD</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A clinical indoor zone referenced as the setting for studying dispersion of exhaled droplet nuclei under three ventilation systems.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_5,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_66,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_67</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED DROPLET NUCLEI">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED DROPLET NUCLEI</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne respiratory particle nuclei referenced in the hospital ward dispersion study. In this extraction they represent infectious aerosol carriers whose transport is affected by ventilation configuration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_5,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_66,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_67</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MECHANICAL VENTILATION SYSTEMS OF VENUES">
      <data key="d0">MECHANICAL VENTILATION SYSTEMS OF VENUES</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation systems serving complex venue spaces. The text notes that such systems historically received lower priority for airborne disease prevention than for quiet operation, thermal comfort, and energy economy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MECHANICALLY VENTILATED THEATRE">
      <data key="d0">MECHANICALLY VENTILATED THEATRE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">An occupied theatre space from a cited study on thermal comfort and indoor air quality. Its mechanical ventilation strategy is relevant to dilution of occupant-generated contaminants and potential airborne-transmission risk. | An occupied zone of the venue that receives mechanical ventilation. In the described HVV condition, the passive emitter was located in this zone.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_6,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_67</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">MECHANICALLY VENTILATED STALLS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MECHANICAL VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">MECHANICAL VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The room ventilation system evaluated in the experiments. It was off during the aerosol dispersion period, switched on at t=0 when measurements began, and operated at 0, 3, or 6 air changes per hour. | The room ventilation system used to clear released carbon dioxide from the unoccupied room. Its supplied airflow contributed to the stated room ventilation rate used in the Far-UVC equivalent air-change calculation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_24,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_25,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_26,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_27,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">MECHANICAL VENTILATION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LARGE LECTURE THEATRE">
      <data key="d0">LARGE LECTURE THEATRE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A large occupied lecture-theatre space evaluated in relation to stratified air distribution. Its size and occupancy make air distribution important for thermal comfort, energy performance, and aerosol exposure patterns.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STRATIFIED AIR DISTRIBUTION SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">STRATIFIED AIR DISTRIBUTION SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Air distribution systems that create or use vertical stratification of air within a large lecture theatre. They are relevant to comfort optimization, energy saving, and spatial variation in contaminant dilution.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_6,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LARGE INDOOR ENVIRONMENT">
      <data key="d0">LARGE INDOOR ENVIRONMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A large enclosed occupied environment associated with thermal comfort prediction for an underfloor air distribution system. It represents a venue where supply-air location and flow regime affect comfort and contaminant transport. | Shared indoor environments are the indoor spaces discussed as settings where airborne transmission risk indicators can be applied to COVID-19 outbreaks; they are represented as indoor zones under the constrained schema.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">SHARED INDOOR ENVIRONMENTS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNDERFLOOR AIR DISTRIBUTION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">UNDERFLOOR AIR DISTRIBUTION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">An air distribution strategy that supplies air from floor level or below the occupied zone. It can influence vertical airflow, thermal stratification, contaminant removal, and occupant exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.77</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_6,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NATURALLY VENTILATED LECTURE THEATRE">
      <data key="d0">NATURALLY VENTILATED LECTURE THEATRE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A lecture theatre evaluated for performance and post-occupancy outcomes under natural ventilation. Its ventilation performance depends on passive airflow drivers rather than dedicated mechanical supply.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.69</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIFFERENTLY SIZED AND VENTILATED THEATRES">
      <data key="d0">DIFFERENTLY SIZED AND VENTILATED THEATRES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A group of up to 10 theatre spaces monitored during 90 regular events with spectators. The theatres varied in size and ventilation configuration, making them relevant for comparing ventilation effectiveness and airborne-transmission mitigation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIFFERENT VENTILATION CONCEPTS">
      <data key="d0">DIFFERENT VENTILATION CONCEPTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The range of ventilation configurations or concepts discussed as needing comprehensive risk comparison and classification. These concepts influence infectious aerosol dilution, removal, and spatial exposure risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPECTATORS">
      <data key="d0">SPECTATORS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The occupant group present during the monitored regular theatre events. Spectators generate CO2 through respiration and may contribute to infectious aerosol emissions if infectious individuals are present. | Modeled exposed occupants represented by dummies. Each dummy is equipped with a virtual mouth for respiration, and aerosol exposure is quantified at the mouth opening to estimate virus exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_6,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_15,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_16,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_21,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_37,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">SPECTATORS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION EFFECTIVENESS">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION EFFECTIVENESS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Performance characteristic of indoor airflow and ventilation assessed in live theatre and mass gathering studies using high-resolution CO2 monitoring. The text notes that uncontrolled study conditions and limitations of CO2-based approaches mean further research is needed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_7,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_69,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_70</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH EMITTERS">
      <data key="d0">HIGH EMITTERS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupant category representing individuals who may emit unusually high levels of infectious respiratory aerosols or have elevated infectivity. The text identifies high emitters as a factor that CO2-based approaches generally cannot capture when estimating SARS-CoV-2 aerosol transmission risk. | Higher aerosol-emission occupant scenario, identified as the 90th-percentile emitter case. It was used in the numerical infection-risk plots as a stronger infectious aerosol source than the silent passive emitter.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_7,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">HIGH EMITTER CASE</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASS GATHERING OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">MASS GATHERING OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Large indoor event occupancy, such as live theatre or mass gathering attendees, relevant to indoor air quality, ventilation performance assessment, and aerosol transmission risk. | The number of attendees present at mass gathering events. The text indicates that smaller event sizes reduce simulated infection numbers, implying that higher occupancy increases opportunities for contact and SARS-CoV-2 transmission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_7,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">MASS GATHERING EVENT OCCUPANCY</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INSTANTANEOUSLY AND UNIFORMLY DISTRIBUTED AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">INSTANTANEOUSLY AND UNIFORMLY DISTRIBUTED AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Idealized well-mixed aerosol distribution assumption used by analytical approaches such as Wells-Riley and dose-response models. This assumption neglects spatio-temporal aerosol variation and treats infection risk as equal for every person in the room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENUE-SPECIFIC AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION PATTERNS">
      <data key="d0">VENUE-SPECIFIC AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION PATTERNS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Spatially and temporally varying aerosol distribution patterns that depend on the geometry and ventilation conditions of a specific indoor venue. CFD analysis can simulate and visualize these patterns to support calculation of individual infection risks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INDOOR ROOM">
      <data key="d0">INDOOR ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor occupied space referenced in the text where analytical models may assume aerosols are uniformly distributed, producing the same estimated infection risk for every person regardless of position.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGLE VENUES">
      <data key="d0">SINGLE VENUES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Specific indoor venues such as live theatres, mass-gathering spaces, concert halls, and confined spaces where ventilation effectiveness and aerosol transmission of SARS-CoV-2 are assessed through monitoring, experiments, or CFD studies.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION PERFORMANCE">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION PERFORMANCE</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Effective ventilation level or air exchange performance assessed in the cited indoor air quality studies. Although no numeric ACH value is given, ventilation performance is central to aerosol dilution, distribution, and airborne transmission mitigation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_8,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_70</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STATIONARY AIRFLOW PATTERNS">
      <data key="d0">STATIONARY AIRFLOW PATTERNS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Simplified airflow patterns assumed in some CFD models of airborne pathogen transport in confined indoor spaces. The text identifies these assumptions as a limitation because modeled stationary patterns require experimental validation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTIOUS AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">INFECTIOUS AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Spatial distribution of infectious aerosols in indoor venues. The passage states that current experimental methodologies investigate this distribution using CO2, tracer gas, optical systems, artificial aerosols, and virus surrogates. | The aerosol transport pattern observed under DVV, characterized by preferential movement of aerosols in a specific direction rather than uniform mixing throughout the venue. | Simulated spatial distribution of SARS-CoV-2-containing aerosols within the modeled arena indoor space, used to estimate exposure of healthy subjects under different hygiene practices, mask use, event sizes, and ventilation conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">DIRECTIONAL AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION,INFECTIOUS AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DELTA VARIANT OF SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d0">DELTA VARIANT OF SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Variant of SARS-CoV-2 referenced in relation to airborne transmission in an auditorium, illustrating the relevance of indoor airflow and aerosol distribution to variant-specific transmission events.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_9,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_28,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_72</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PHI6 SURROGATE VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">PHI6 SURROGATE VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Phi6 is referenced as a surrogate virus used to experimentally study airborne transmission behavior relevant to SARS-CoV-2 in indoor environments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="IMMEDIATE EMISSION-SOURCE VICINITY">
      <data key="d0">IMMEDIATE EMISSION-SOURCE VICINITY</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The near-field zone directly around the aerosol emission source, such as the area close to an emitting dummy, where direct measurement of sputum-like aerosol particles is described as challenging.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAR-FIELD INDOOR POSITIONS">
      <data key="d0">FAR-FIELD INDOOR POSITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Locations farther away from the emission source within the indoor environment where aerosol and droplet transmission can be assessed over larger distances.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INDOOR AIRFLOW PATHS">
      <data key="d0">INDOOR AIRFLOW PATHS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Air movement routes within indoor spaces that transport aerosols and droplets from an emission source toward other environmental positions, affecting airborne transmission and exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.81</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">ROOM AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The spatial distribution pattern of respiratory aerosols and droplets in an indoor room, used to evaluate exposure and the effects of ventilation settings or mitigation strategies. | Room air distribution is implied by the modeling of UVGI device performance in ventilated rooms, where airflow patterns influence how air passes through the upper-room treatment zone.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
      <data key="d6">ROOM AIR DISTRIBUTION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INDOOR VENTILATION SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">INDOOR VENTILATION SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation arrangements or settings in indoor environments that are assessed as part of scenarios influencing aerosol distribution and airborne transmission. | Indoor ventilation systems are referenced as an environmental control factor affecting the spread of COVID-19 and respiratory particles indoors.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">INDOOR VENTILATION SYSTEMS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DVV">
      <data key="d0">DVV</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">One of the four studied indoor venues, characterized by displacement ventilation and assessed for airborne transmission risk using CFD and ATMoS-based measurements.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_11,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_12,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_13,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_14,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_16,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_17,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_18,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_20,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_23,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_25,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_26,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_33,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_34,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_36,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MVV">
      <data key="d0">MVV</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">One of the four studied indoor venues, characterized by mixing ventilation and included in comparative venue-specific infection-risk calculations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_11,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_12,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_13,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_14,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_16,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_17,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_18,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_20,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_25,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_26,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_33,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_34,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NVV">
      <data key="d0">NVV</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">One of the four studied indoor venues, characterized by natural ventilation and evaluated for airborne transmission risk under venue-specific conditions. | The occupied indoor venue or room under natural ventilation conditions where infection-risk control is evaluated for spectators during an event.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_11,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_12,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_13,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_16,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_17,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_18,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_20,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_33,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_34,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_41,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">NATURALLY VENTILATED VENUE</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HVV">
      <data key="d0">HVV</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">One of the four studied indoor venues, characterized by a hybrid ventilation strategy that combines displacement ventilation and natural ventilation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_11,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_12,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HYBRID VENTILATION STRATEGY">
      <data key="d0">HYBRID VENTILATION STRATEGY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The combined ventilation approach used in the HVV venue, explicitly combining displacement ventilation with natural ventilation to affect aerosol dispersion and infection-risk outcomes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_11</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MULTI-TIERED SEATED INDOOR EVENT LOCATION">
      <data key="d0">MULTI-TIERED SEATED INDOOR EVENT LOCATION</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The indoor venue setting analyzed in the study. Although it is an event venue rather than a hospital, it functions as the enclosed zone in which ventilation, aerosol dispersion, audience exposure, and infection risk were evaluated.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OCCUPANTS' BREATHING ZONES">
      <data key="d0">OCCUPANTS' BREATHING ZONES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Localized exposure zones around each audience member where the concentration of infectious quanta was evaluated. These breathing-zone concentrations were used to calculate position-specific individual infection risks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEATS BEHIND THE EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">SEATS BEHIND THE EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Audience positions located behind the sedentary passive emitter. In the DVV scenario, these seats were the most exposed because the aerosol plume was directed behind the emitter.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_12,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEATS IN FRONT OF AND NEXT TO THE EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">SEATS IN FRONT OF AND NEXT TO THE EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Audience positions located in front of or beside the sedentary passive emitter. Under DVV, these locations remained almost unaffected compared with the seats behind the emitter.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PRONOUNCED AEROSOL PLUME BEHIND THE EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">PRONOUNCED AEROSOL PLUME BEHIND THE EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A localized high-exposure aerosol plume observed behind the sedentary passive emitter in the DVV scenario. This plume caused the seats behind the emitter to be the most exposed positions. | A small aerosol plume observed in the hybrid venue by CFD analyses and experimental measurements. It produced increased exposure behind the emitter at position R8S21, while spectators in front of and next to the emitter were almost unaffected.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_12,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_14,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">LOCALIZED AEROSOL PLUME BEHIND THE EMITTER</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEDENTARY, PASSIVE EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">SEDENTARY, PASSIVE EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The seated source occupant emitting infectious aerosols in the modeled infection-risk scenario. The emitter position influenced which audience seats experienced the greatest exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_12,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_52,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_56</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AUDIENCE">
      <data key="d0">AUDIENCE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The seated occupants distributed across the event venue. Their positions relative to the emitter and ventilation pattern determined their breathing-zone exposure and individual infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_12,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PREFERENTIAL BACKWARD AEROSOL FLOW TOWARD THE UPPER RIGHT CORNER">
      <data key="d0">PREFERENTIAL BACKWARD AEROSOL FLOW TOWARD THE UPPER RIGHT CORNER</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A specific aerosol distribution pattern identified for MVV, described as preferential but less directional movement of aerosol particles backward toward the upper right corner of the venue.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTIOUS AEROSOL PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">INFECTIOUS AEROSOL PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne aerosol particles emitted by a sedentary passive emitter and used in the study context to evaluate infection-risk distributions across the venues.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AUDIENCE SPECTATORS">
      <data key="d0">AUDIENCE SPECTATORS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The seated audience population exposed to the modeled aerosol dispersion. The text notes that 0 to 11 spectators, corresponding to 0–11% of the audience, exceeded the acceptable infection-risk threshold in the evaluated scenarios.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ENTIRE VENUE">
      <data key="d0">ENTIRE VENUE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The full indoor spectator venue evaluated for aerosol dispersion and airborne transmission risk under DVV, MVV, and NVV ventilation scenarios. Under NVV, aerosol particles contaminated this whole zone, whereas DVV and MVV produced lower global COVID-19 risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_14,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPPER RIGHT CORNER">
      <data key="d0">UPPER RIGHT CORNER</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A localized region of the venue toward which MVV produced a preferential, backward aerosol flow. It functioned as a receiving area for transported aerosol particles.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AROUND THE EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">AROUND THE EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The spatial region surrounding the aerosol emitter. Under MVV, increased CFD-derived exposure probability values were observed in all directions around this source region.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEAR- AND FAR-FIELD OF THE EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">NEAR- AND FAR-FIELD OF THE EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Zones close to and distant from the aerosol emitter where spectators under MVV exceeded the accumulated infection-risk threshold of R_acc above 10^-2, showing that risk was not restricted to immediate proximity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ASCENDING SPECTATOR AREA">
      <data key="d0">ASCENDING SPECTATOR AREA</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A rising or sloped audience seating geometry in the NVV scenario. This geometry was associated with directional aerosol transport and a pronounced plume behind the emitter.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_14,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMITTER POSITION A14">
      <data key="d0">EMITTER POSITION A14</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A specific source location in the venue from which aerosol particles were emitted. Under NVV with an ascending spectator area, this position was especially associated with a pronounced aerosol plume behind the emitter. | A specific audience-seat emitter location used as a comparison against the stage actor position. Aerosols from this position mainly exposed spectators behind the emitter.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">EMITTER POSITION B9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NVV WITH AN ASCENDING SPECTATOR AREA">
      <data key="d0">NVV WITH AN ASCENDING SPECTATOR AREA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A ventilation and venue-geometry condition that produced directional aerosol distribution, a pronounced plume behind the emitter, and broad contamination of the entire venue. It had the highest reported global COVID-19 transmission risk, with R_CFD about 2 to 2.6.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.97</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PREFERENTIAL BACKWARD AEROSOL FLOW">
      <data key="d0">PREFERENTIAL BACKWARD AEROSOL FLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">An aerosol transport pathway observed under MVV. It moved backward from the emitter region toward the upper right corner, but was less directional than the plume described for NVV.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONTAMINATION OF THE ENTIRE VENUE">
      <data key="d0">CONTAMINATION OF THE ENTIRE VENUE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A broad aerosol distribution outcome under NVV in which emitted particles spread throughout the venue, not only to seats directly behind the emitter. This outcome was associated with 22 to 170 spectators exceeding the accumulated risk threshold.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="5 TO 10 SPECTATORS EXCEEDING R_ACC UNDER MVV">
      <data key="d0">5 TO 10 SPECTATORS EXCEEDING R_ACC UNDER MVV</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A subset of the audience, approximately 5–10%, that reached accumulated infection risk R_acc above 10^-2 under MVV in the near- and far-field of the emitter. | A larger subset of the audience, approximately 9–70%, that exceeded the accumulated infection-risk threshold under NVV due to broader aerosol contamination of the venue.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">22 TO 170 SPECTATORS EXCEEDING R_ACC UNDER NVV</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH EMITTER 90TH PERCENTILE">
      <data key="d0">HIGH EMITTER 90TH PERCENTILE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">An occupant source condition representing a high aerosol emitter at the 90th percentile. The text introduces this as a distinct infection-risk scenario in which aerosol distribution remained dependent on emitter position and ventilation strategy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PASSIVE EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">PASSIVE EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The baseline emitter condition referenced for comparison with the high emitter. For passive emission, aerosol distribution and CFD-derived exposure probability depended on emitter position and ventilation strategy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_14,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_15,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_16,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENUES">
      <data key="d0">VENUES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled indoor occupied spaces in which aerosol-particle distribution and infection-risk patterns were evaluated under displacement, mixing, and natural ventilation. The term is mapped to HOSPITAL_ZONE because the valid schema represents occupied indoor exposure zones.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH EMITTING INDIVIDUAL">
      <data key="d0">HIGH EMITTING INDIVIDUAL</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A 90th-percentile aerosol emitter acting as the infectious source. Enhanced aerosol release from this occupant increased both individual and global modeled infection risk across the studied venues.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMITTER POSITIONS H5 E6 B9">
      <data key="d0">EMITTER POSITIONS H5 E6 B9</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Specific modeled source-location zones within the venues. The text reports that under displacement ventilation, risk-threshold exceedance was unchanged for H5 but increased substantially for E6 and B9.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">HIGH EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">An infectious aerosol-emitting occupant scenario used in the infection-risk plots. Compared with a passive emitter, the high emitter increased CFD-derived infection risk by approximately a factor of 13 to 14 across all emitter positions and ventilation cases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_16,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_24,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_44,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE PATHOGEN AEROSOL">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE PATHOGEN AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The infectious aerosol contaminant emitted by the source occupant and transported by the ventilation-driven airflow. Its spatial dispersion under each ventilation pattern determines the individual and global infection-risk estimates.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DVV HIGH-EMITTER POSITIONS">
      <data key="d0">DVV HIGH-EMITTER POSITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The specific audience-seat source positions H5, E6, and B9 used for the high-emitter scenarios in the displacement-ventilation venue case. | The specific audience-seat source positions J20, E5, and A14 used for the high-emitter scenarios in the natural-ventilation venue case.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.67</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">NVV HIGH-EMITTER POSITIONS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATED VENUES">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATED VENUES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor venues or zones evaluated for airborne infection risk under different ventilation-driven air distribution patterns. The text compares experimental, CFD, and analytical risk estimates across these venues and emission modes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COVID-19-ASSOCIATED AIRBORNE INFECTIOUS AEROSOL">
      <data key="d0">COVID-19-ASSOCIATED AIRBORNE INFECTIOUS AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The airborne pathogen exposure context underlying the cited analytical risk framework for shared indoor environments and COVID-19 outbreaks. In the passage, the main outcome is global airborne infection risk rather than direct pathogen measurement.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WILD-TYPE SARS-COV-2 VIRUS VARIANT">
      <data key="d0">WILD-TYPE SARS-COV-2 VIRUS VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Reference airborne pathogen variant used in the CFD-based COVID-19 transmission-risk evaluation. The modeled secondary-case counts and R_CFD values are evaluated under different occupant activity, airflow, masking, and event-duration assumptions. | The lower-infectivity SARS-CoV-2 reference variant in the recommendations. The text states that surgical face masks were sufficient for the wild-type variant in the MVV case.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">WILD-TYPE SARS-COV-2 VARIANT</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FULL OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">FULL OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Reference high-occupancy condition for the modeled indoor event. It defines the baseline exposure setting in which COVID-19 secondary cases are estimated under full airflow, a 2-hour duration, wild-type SARS-CoV-2, and no face coverings.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_18,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_19,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_40,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_53</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGING OR SHOUTING EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">SINGING OR SHOUTING EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">High-emission occupant activity condition representing an infected emitter who is singing or shouting. In the CFD analysis, this activity profile greatly increases modeled airborne SARS-CoV-2 transmission risk compared with a silent, passive emitter.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SILENT, PASSIVE, NON-MASKED EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">SILENT, PASSIVE, NON-MASKED EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Baseline low-emission infected occupant condition used for comparison with higher-activity emission profiles. This condition represents a non-masked emitter who is silent and passive, producing lower respiratory aerosol and quanta emissions than singing or shouting.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FULL AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">FULL AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Reference ventilation or airflow condition used in the modeled event. Although no numeric air-change rate is provided in the excerpt, full airflow is part of the baseline case for estimating R_CFD and secondary COVID-19 infections.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISPLACEMENT-VENTILATED VENUES (DVV)">
      <data key="d0">DISPLACEMENT-VENTILATED VENUES (DVV)</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled occupied indoor venues using a displacement-ventilation concept. They are treated as zone-like indoor spaces in the CFD parameter study, where ventilation behavior influences airborne quanta distribution and global infection risk. | One of the four indoor venues modeled in the CFD study. It is treated as a venue/zone with a displacement ventilation concept and was evaluated under full versus checkerboard occupancy, 100% versus 50% airflow-rate boundary conditions, and varied emitter positions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">DISPLACEMENT VENTILATION VENUE (DVV)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MIXING-VENTILATED VENUES (MVV)">
      <data key="d0">MIXING-VENTILATED VENUES (MVV)</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled occupied indoor venues using a mixing-ventilation concept. These venues are compared with displacement- and natural-ventilated venues for their influence on dilution, spatial exposure, and infection-risk outcomes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NATURALLY VENTILATED VENUES (NVV)">
      <data key="d0">NATURALLY VENTILATED VENUES (NVV)</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled occupied indoor venues using a natural-ventilation concept. They are included in the CFD comparison of different ventilation approaches and their effects on airborne infection risk. | A modeled indoor venue/zone described as an ascending-stage case with a nonspecific ventilation concept identified as natural ventilation. It was included to compare airborne transport under a non-mechanical or less-defined ventilation strategy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">NATURAL VENTILATION VENUE (NVV)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FULL AIRFLOW RATE">
      <data key="d0">FULL AIRFLOW RATE</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The reference ventilation-rate condition used in the parameter study. Although no numeric air-change rate is given, it represents the baseline airflow rate for comparing mitigation scenarios.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2 WILD-TYPE INFECTIOUS QUANTA">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2 WILD-TYPE INFECTIOUS QUANTA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The airborne infectious quanta associated with the SARS-CoV-2 wild-type variant used in the reference scenario. Emitted and inhaled quanta determine the modeled individual and global infection risks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGLE SILENT, SEDENTARY EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">SINGLE SILENT, SEDENTARY EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The reference source condition consisting of one infected occupant who is silent and sedentary. This emitter releases infectious quanta according to the assumed respiratory and exhalation-flow conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY RATE AND EXHALATION VOLUME FLOW">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY RATE AND EXHALATION VOLUME FLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The occupant breathing-emission condition discussed in the text. The study fixed respiratory rate, but the text notes that halving respiratory rate and exhalation volume flow would theoretically halve emitted quanta and comparably halve inhaled quanta dose.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACTIVITY LEVELS">
      <data key="d0">ACTIVITY LEVELS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupant activity conditions varied in the parameter study. Activity level is relevant because it can alter breathing rates, exhalation flow, and the amount of infectious quanta emitted or inhaled.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HYBRID VENUE (HVV)">
      <data key="d0">HYBRID VENUE (HVV)</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">An indoor venue with a mixed ventilation configuration, consisting of displacement-ventilated stalls and two naturally ventilated balconies. In this venue, CFD analyses and experimental measurements identified a localized aerosol plume behind the emitter at position R8S21.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISPLACEMENT-VENTILATED STALLS">
      <data key="d0">DISPLACEMENT-VENTILATED STALLS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The stalls area within the hybrid venue. This sub-zone is described as displacement-ventilated and therefore represents the mechanically driven displacement-ventilation component of HVV.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NATURALLY VENTILATED BALCONIES">
      <data key="d0">NATURALLY VENTILATED BALCONIES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Two balcony sub-zones within the hybrid venue that are naturally ventilated. They form the natural-ventilation component of the hybrid ventilation arrangement.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="REDUCED AIRFLOW RATE IN DVV">
      <data key="d0">REDUCED AIRFLOW RATE IN DVV</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">A reduced airflow-rate condition investigated for the DVV configuration using CFD analysis. Lowering airflow under DVV increased airborne infection risk by a factor ranging from 1.7 to 9.86. | A reduced ventilation or air-exchange condition associated with DVV. The text reports that this condition was associated with an up to approximately 10-fold increase in airborne-transmission risk and nearly all spectators exceeding the acceptable risk threshold.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">REDUCED AIRFLOW RATE AT DVV</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ALPHA VARIANT">
      <data key="d0">ALPHA VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A SARS-CoV-2 variant of concern considered in the infection-risk modeling. It was modeled as increasing the number of secondary infections by a factor of 1.5 compared with the baseline variant assumption.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DELTA VARIANT">
      <data key="d0">DELTA VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A SARS-CoV-2 variant of concern considered in the infection-risk modeling. It was modeled as increasing the number of secondary infections by a factor of 2 compared with the baseline variant assumption.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OMICRON VARIANT">
      <data key="d0">OMICRON VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A SARS-CoV-2 variant of concern with the highest modeled transmission multiplier in the text. It was modeled as increasing secondary infections by a factor of 3, produced R_CFD values of 1.04 to 1.25 under MVV, and produced 6.13 to 7.84 secondary infections under NVV with a silent and resting emitter.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_20,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_40,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SILENT AND RESTING EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">SILENT AND RESTING EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">An infected occupant/source condition in which the emitter is silent and resting. Under NVV with Omicron infection, this source condition resulted in 6.13 to 7.84 modeled secondary infections.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OCCUPANTS BEHIND THE EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">OCCUPANTS BEHIND THE EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The occupants located behind the emitter at or near position R8S21. This group experienced increased exposure due to the localized aerosol plume observed in the hybrid venue.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPECTATORS IN FRONT OF AND NEXT TO THE EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">SPECTATORS IN FRONT OF AND NEXT TO THE EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Spectators positioned in front of and adjacent to the emitter. They were reported to remain almost unaffected by the localized aerosol plume and showed low individual infection risks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MODELED SECONDARY INFECTIONS">
      <data key="d0">MODELED SECONDARY INFECTIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled count of newly infected occupants resulting from airborne transmission. The text reports variant-dependent increases in this count and specifically reports 6.13 to 7.84 secondary infections for Omicron under NVV with a silent and resting emitter.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STALLS">
      <data key="d0">STALLS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Lower occupied seating zone of the venue. Under the hybrid ventilation configuration, the stalls receive displacement ventilation. When a silent, sedentary infectious emitter was placed in the stalls, infectious aerosols were numerically shown to spread upward as far as the balconies. | Occupant area where mean exposure increased from 6.75 exposed individuals in VV1 to 24.25 in VV2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_21,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">STALLS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BALCONIES">
      <data key="d0">BALCONIES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Upper occupied seating zones of the venue. In the hybrid ventilation configuration, the balconies are described as unventilated. Aerosols emitted from the balconies vanished slowly and did not expose the stalls, but balcony-origin scenarios produced a 2.1- to 2.7-fold higher infection risk than comparable stalls-origin scenarios.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HYBRID VENTILATION (HVV)">
      <data key="d0">HYBRID VENTILATION (HVV)</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Venue ventilation configuration combining displacement ventilation in the stalls with unventilated balconies. It determines the modeled aerosol transport and infection-risk distribution shown in Fig. 4.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNVENTILATED BALCONY CONDITION">
      <data key="d0">UNVENTILATED BALCONY CONDITION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Air-distribution condition representing the absence of active ventilation in the balconies under the hybrid ventilation configuration. This condition is linked to slow aerosol removal when the emitter is placed in the balconies.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPWARD AEROSOL TRANSPORT PATH">
      <data key="d0">UPWARD AEROSOL TRANSPORT PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled air/aerosol movement pathway by which infectious aerosols released in the stalls can travel upward to the balconies. The text supports upward transport from the stalls to the balconies but not a corresponding exposure pathway from balconies to stalls.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SILENT, SEDENTARY EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">SILENT, SEDENTARY EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Passive infectious aerosol source representing a seated, non-speaking emitter. When placed in the stalls, this emitter still released aerosols that spread up to the balconies.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMITTER SEAT POSITIONS">
      <data key="d0">EMITTER SEAT POSITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Specific modeled source locations in the seating layout, including R8S21, R2S15, and 1RR2S21. These positions determine whether emissions originate in the stalls or balconies and therefore affect the simulated infection-risk distribution.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="50% REDUCED AIR FLOW RATE">
      <data key="d0">50% REDUCED AIR FLOW RATE</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The reduced ventilation airflow condition referenced for the DVV stage-position experiment. It is relevant because ventilation rate affects aerosol dilution, dispersion, and modeled infection risk. | A lower ventilation airflow condition considered in the actor-emission scenario. The text states that under reduced airflow, a high-emitting actor can lead to a super-spreading event.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">REDUCED AIRFLOW RATE</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STAGE">
      <data key="d0">STAGE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The stage area of the venue where the emitter was placed to simulate an infectious actor. Although this is not a hospital space, it is represented as a distinct indoor zone for airflow and aerosol-dispersion extraction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AUDIENCE SEATING">
      <data key="d0">AUDIENCE SEATING</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The occupied audience area containing spectator seats. It includes the stalls and balcony levels where infection risk was evaluated.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BALCONY">
      <data key="d0">BALCONY</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The elevated audience seating region over which aerosol from a high emitter partially dispersed, producing a large increase in modeled airborne infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="1ST BALCONY">
      <data key="d0">1ST BALCONY</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The first balcony level in the audience seating area, identified in the venue plots as a spatial region relevant to aerosol spread.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.58</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="2ND BALCONY">
      <data key="d0">2ND BALCONY</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The second balcony level in the audience seating area, identified in the venue plots as a spatial region relevant to aerosol spread.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.58</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTIOUS ACTOR">
      <data key="d0">INFECTIOUS ACTOR</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">An infectious occupant placed on stage to simulate aerosol emission from an actor. The scenario was tested under silent/passive and high-emission conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_50</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SILENT, PASSIVE ACTOR">
      <data key="d0">SILENT, PASSIVE ACTOR</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A low-emission actor condition on stage. This condition produced low individual infection risks and a low summed modeled risk value of R_CFD = 0.07. | A low-emission actor source condition that nevertheless generated almost uniform exposure across DVV under reduced airflow, increasing global infection risk 9.9-fold to 0.69.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">SILENT PASSIVE ACTOR</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH EMITTING ACTOR">
      <data key="d0">HIGH EMITTING ACTOR</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A high-aerosol-emission actor condition on stage. This scenario exposed the entire venue, produced 1.02 predicted secondary infections, and led to 44 spectators exceeding the critical acceptable-risk threshold. | An infectious performer with elevated aerosol or pathogen emission. Under reduced airflow conditions, this scenario can result in a super-spreading event.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">HIGH-EMITTING ACTOR</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NON-DIRECTIONAL AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">NON-DIRECTIONAL AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The aerosol distribution observed for the infectious actor on stage, described as lacking a pronounced directional aerosol plume.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.79</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PRONOUNCED AEROSOL PLUME">
      <data key="d0">PRONOUNCED AEROSOL PLUME</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A directional plume-like aerosol distribution observed for emitter position B9, contrasting with the non-directional distribution from the infectious actor on stage.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BALCONY-WIDE PARTIAL DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">BALCONY-WIDE PARTIAL DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A broad aerosol dispersion pattern in which emissions from a high emitter partially spread over the entire balcony, increasing airborne infection risk by 13.6 to 14.3 times.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ENTIRE VENUE EXPOSURE">
      <data key="d0">ENTIRE VENUE EXPOSURE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A whole-space exposure pattern caused by the high-emitting actor, in which infectious aerosol affected the entire venue rather than remaining localized.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BEHIND-EMITTER EXPOSURE">
      <data key="d0">BEHIND-EMITTER EXPOSURE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A localized directional exposure pattern at emitter position B9, where mainly spectators behind the emitter were exposed to infectious aerosols.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WELL-VENTILATED BASELINE AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">WELL-VENTILATED BASELINE AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The lower-risk comparative ventilation condition referenced as the well-ventilated venue baseline, against which the 50% reduced airflow scenarios were compared.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PRONOUNCED AEROSOL PLUME AT B9">
      <data key="d0">PRONOUNCED AEROSOL PLUME AT B9</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A concentrated aerosol plume observed in the CFD analysis for emitter position B9 under the 50% reduced airflow condition, indicating localized but strong aerosol transport from the source.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENUE-WIDE INFECTIOUS AEROSOL DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">VENUE-WIDE INFECTIOUS AEROSOL DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A broad dispersion pattern in which infectious aerosols spread throughout DVV rather than remaining localized, contributing to increased exposure among spectators.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ALMOST UNIFORM VENUE-WIDE EXPOSURE">
      <data key="d0">ALMOST UNIFORM VENUE-WIDE EXPOSURE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A near-uniform exposure pattern across the entire venue, reported for the silent, passive actor scenario under reduced airflow and associated with a large increase in global infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2 / COVID-19 INFECTIOUS AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2 / COVID-19 INFECTIOUS AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The infectious aerosol hazard modeled in the CFD-based risk assessment, used to estimate accumulated infection risk, secondary infections, and new COVID-19 cases in the audience. | Airborne infectious aerosol particles associated with COVID-19 transmission in indoor environments. The excerpt discusses infection risk as a function of exposure duration, occupancy, seating layout, and ventilation-related measures. | The COVID-19 pandemic context that increased research attention on ventilation strategies in transport. The text refers to COVID-19 as the motivating infectious-risk context rather than providing pathogen-specific measurements.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">SARS-COV-2/COVID-19 INFECTIOUS AEROSOLS,SARS-COV-2 / COVID-19 INFECTIOUS AEROSOL CONTEXT</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH EMITTING SPECTATOR AT B9">
      <data key="d0">HIGH EMITTING SPECTATOR AT B9</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A high-emission spectator source at position B9. Combined with 50% reduced airflow, this scenario caused nearly all spectators to exceed the accumulated risk threshold and predicted 8.36 new COVID-19 cases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SILENT PASSIVE EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">SILENT PASSIVE EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A lower-emission occupant source condition. With 50% reduced airflow, this scenario doubled the number of spectators exceeding the accumulated risk threshold and increased secondary infections 2.3-fold to 0.61. | A low-emission infectious occupant scenario. The text identifies a silent, passive background actor as posing only a low risk of airborne transmission compared with active performing scenarios.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.81</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_23,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">SILENT, PASSIVE EMITTER</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CHECKERBOARD SEATING ARRANGEMENT">
      <data key="d0">CHECKERBOARD SEATING ARRANGEMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The seating/occupancy arrangement used in the analyzed scenarios, defining the spatial distribution of spectators exposed to aerosols in DVV.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_23,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_24,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_29,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENUE WITH DISPLACEMENT VENTILATION (DVV)">
      <data key="d0">VENUE WITH DISPLACEMENT VENTILATION (DVV)</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The indoor performance venue modeled for airborne infection risk under displacement ventilation, different airflow rates, emitter positions, and audience seating conditions. Although not a hospital zone, it is the occupied air-handled zone in the available schema. | Studied theatre venues characterized by displacement ventilation, included to represent a commonly installed indoor ventilation approach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">VENUES WITH DISPLACEMENT VENTILATION (DVV)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STAGE ACTOR EMITTER POSITION">
      <data key="d0">STAGE ACTOR EMITTER POSITION</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The stage location occupied by the actor when the actor is the infectious aerosol emitter. Its position relative to the audience changes the spatial exposure pattern and can exceed the risk from an audience emitter under high-emission and reduced-airflow conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_24,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AUDIENCE SEATING AREA">
      <data key="d0">AUDIENCE SEATING AREA</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The spectator seating region where individual infection risk is evaluated at seat positions. It contains the exposed spectators and may also contain the comparison emitter position B9.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AUDIENCE EMITTER POSITION B9">
      <data key="d0">AUDIENCE EMITTER POSITION B9</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A specific seat location in the audience used as the comparison infectious emitter position against the stage actor position.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_24,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FULL AIRFLOW RATE (4500 M³/H)">
      <data key="d0">FULL AIRFLOW RATE (4500 M³/H)</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The standard ventilation condition for the venue, reported as a volumetric airflow rate rather than explicit air changes per hour. It represents the well-ventilated baseline used in risk comparisons. | The standard full-airflow condition of 4500 m³/h used with the full-occupancy baseline in the DVV infection-risk plots.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">FULL AIRFLOW RATE 4500 M3/H</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STANDARD OCCUPANCY RATE (99 SPECTATORS)">
      <data key="d0">STANDARD OCCUPANCY RATE (99 SPECTATORS)</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The full audience occupancy condition used under standard conditions. It defines the number of potentially exposed spectators and contributes to the global risk calculation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE INFECTIOUS AEROSOL">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE INFECTIOUS AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The infectious airborne contaminant released by the emitter and transported through the venue airflow. Its dilution and distribution determine the individual and global infection risks estimated by CFD.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MVV2">
      <data key="d0">MVV2</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A second studied venue with mixing ventilation. It is compared with DVV and MVV to assess how ventilation pattern and seating configuration influence infection-risk distributions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_25,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_26,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="99 SPECTATORS">
      <data key="d0">99 SPECTATORS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The standard full-occupancy condition used in the baseline case. The number of spectators affects the number of potentially exposed occupants and the global infection-risk burden.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="50% REDUCED OCCUPANCY WITH CHECKERBOARD SEATING">
      <data key="d0">50% REDUCED OCCUPANCY WITH CHECKERBOARD SEATING</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A reduced-occupancy seating arrangement where spectators are placed in a checkerboard pattern. This changes the spatial distribution of occupied seats and exposure opportunities in DVV, MVV, and MVV2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH-EMITTER INFECTIOUS AEROSOL">
      <data key="d0">HIGH-EMITTER INFECTIOUS AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The infectious aerosol emission condition for a high emitter, described as the 90th percentile emitter. It is the source condition used for comparing infection risk from the stage actor and audience B9 emitter positions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATED INDOOR VENUE ZONES">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATED INDOOR VENUE ZONES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor venue spaces studied experimentally and numerically as air-handled zones with different ventilation strategies. The text evaluates spatial infection-risk and propagation-risk behavior in these zones under different seating or occupancy loads.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FULL SEATING OR FULL OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">FULL SEATING OR FULL OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The baseline higher-occupancy seating condition used for comparison with checkerboard or halved occupancy. The reported reductions in R_CFD under reduced occupancy imply that full occupancy generally corresponded to higher propagation-risk values.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CHECKERBOARD OR HALVED OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">CHECKERBOARD OR HALVED OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A reduced-occupancy seating condition in which seats are occupied in a checkerboard pattern or the occupancy rate is halved. It was associated overall with reduced R_CFD values for DVV and MVV, although local or emitter-specific effects occurred, including a broadened elevated-risk zone for DVV emitter position B9 and only slight R_CFD reduction for MVV emitter position I16.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2 OR COVID-19 AIRBORNE TRANSMISSION CONTEXT">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2 OR COVID-19 AIRBORNE TRANSMISSION CONTEXT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The infectious airborne-transmission context motivating the risk assessment. The COVID-19 pandemic is cited as demonstrating the need for more specific venue risk assessment rather than general venue closures. | COVID-19-related airborne pathogen transmission context from the CFD modeling citation. The disease name COVID-19 is used in the reference, but the relevant airborne pathogen is SARS-CoV-2; the entity is therefore framed as SARS-CoV-2/COVID-19 airborne transmission rather than COVID-19 as a pathogen itself.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">SARS-COV-2 / COVID-19 AIRBORNE TRANSMISSION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MULTI-TIERED VENUES">
      <data key="d0">MULTI-TIERED VENUES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupied indoor venue zones studied to estimate aerosol distribution, exposure, venue-specific infection probability, and transmission risk. In the schema, these non-hospital venues are represented as occupied zones.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTIOUS EMITTER POSITION">
      <data key="d0">INFECTIOUS EMITTER POSITION</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The occupied location of the infectious person within the spectator area. The text states that plume expansion and airborne transmission risk depend strongly on this position.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION AND EXPOSURE FIELD">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION AND EXPOSURE FIELD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Spatial pattern of aerosol concentration and exposure evaluated experimentally and numerically to calculate venue-specific infection probabilities and risks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH-EXPOSURE POSITIONS BEHIND THE EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">HIGH-EXPOSURE POSITIONS BEHIND THE EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Spectator positions in the near-field and far-field behind the infectious emitter that were highly exposed due to the pronounced aerosol plume.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOW-EXPOSURE POSITIONS IN FRONT OF AND NEXT TO THE EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">LOW-EXPOSURE POSITIONS IN FRONT OF AND NEXT TO THE EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Spectator positions in front of and beside the infectious emitter that were reported to be almost unaffected by the aerosol plume, forming low-exposure areas.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PASSIVE INFECTIOUS EMITTER SCENARIO WITH 18.6 QUANTA H−1">
      <data key="d0">PASSIVE INFECTIOUS EMITTER SCENARIO WITH 18.6 QUANTA H−1</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled infectious occupant scenario with a quanta emission rate of 18.6 quanta per hour. It was used to evaluate aerosol distribution, individual transmission risk, reproduction-related R values, and venue-specific infection probability.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE INFECTIOUS QUANTA">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE INFECTIOUS QUANTA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne infectious dose proxy emitted by the passive infectious person. The quanta emission rate is used to estimate infection probability and transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENUE-SPECIFIC INFECTION PROBABILITY AND TRANSMISSION RISK">
      <data key="d0">VENUE-SPECIFIC INFECTION PROBABILITY AND TRANSMISSION RISK</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled airborne infection outcome derived from aerosol exposure and quanta emission. In the studied displacement-ventilated multi-tiered venue, most spectators had low individual transmission risk and R values well below one.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTIOUS PERSON">
      <data key="d0">INFECTIOUS PERSON</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A pathogen-emitting occupant whose position strongly affects aerosol plume expansion and airborne transmission risk, particularly under displacement ventilation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL PLUME">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL PLUME</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The airborne pathway or spatial spread of aerosols emitted by an infectious person. Its expansion is described as strongly dependent on the infectious person's position.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HOSPITAL ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">HOSPITAL ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Clinical rooms referenced in a cited study assessing displacement ventilation systems and airborne infection risk, illustrating that ventilation pattern can influence pathogen exposure in healthcare spaces. | Hospital rooms are healthcare zones in which ultraviolet germicidal irradiation systems are evaluated for controlling airborne pathogens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_28,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_38,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_75</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
      <data key="d6">HOSPITAL ROOMS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MV VENUES/CASES">
      <data key="d0">MV VENUES/CASES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor study venues or cases operated with mixing ventilation. The excerpt reports that infectious aerosols in these spaces were dispersed throughout the venue, producing many low- and medium-risk positions and a few high-risk positions in both near- and far-field regions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DV CASES">
      <data key="d0">DV CASES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor study cases operated with displacement ventilation. They are used as the comparison condition against MV cases and are associated with lower aerosol inhalation probability at 1.5 m and 4 m.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEAR-FIELD OF THE EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">NEAR-FIELD OF THE EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The region close to the emitting person. In MV venues, high-risk positions can occur in this near-field area because aerosols are not confined to a single directional plume. | The spatial region close to the infectious aerosol emitter. All three studied ventilation strategies showed high-risk positions in this near-field region.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">NEAR FIELD OF THE EMITTER</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMITTING PERSON">
      <data key="d0">EMITTING PERSON</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The source occupant who emits respiratory particles into the indoor environment. The near-field and far-field exposure regions are defined relative to this person.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MV-DRIVEN AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">MV-DRIVEN AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The less directional airflow behavior associated with mixing ventilation. It disperses aerosols broadly through the venue and makes highly exposed positions harder to predict because outcomes are sensitive to boundary conditions. | Air movement generated by the four fans within the test chamber; it distributes particles through the chamber and supports well-mixed conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
      <data key="d6">FAN-DRIVEN AIRFLOW</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPECTATOR LAYOUT">
      <data key="d0">SPECTATOR LAYOUT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The spatial arrangement of occupants in a large open space. The text identifies spectator layout as a factor shown in recent studies to affect airflow characteristics under different air distribution methods.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DV VENUE">
      <data key="d0">DV VENUE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A studied indoor venue using displacement ventilation. It is compared with the naturally ventilated venue and the mixing-ventilated venue for aerosol distribution and airborne transmission risk. | Occupied indoor venues using the displacement ventilation case DVV. The text discusses these venues in relation to 1-, 2-, and 3-hour events and recommends additional risk-reduction measures for longer events when Omicron is considered.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
      <data key="d6">DVV VENUES</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NATURALLY VENTILATED ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">NATURALLY VENTILATED ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor rooms ventilated naturally rather than by a controlled mechanical displacement or mixing system. The passage states that in such rooms airborne transmission risk does not necessarily decrease with distance from the infectious source.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WIDESPREAD HIGH-CONCENTRATION AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">WIDESPREAD HIGH-CONCENTRATION AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The reported aerosol distribution pattern in the naturally ventilated venue, where aerosol occurs at high concentrations throughout the venue regardless of where the infectious source is located.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISTANCE-INDEPENDENT AIRBORNE TRANSMISSION RISK PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">DISTANCE-INDEPENDENT AIRBORNE TRANSMISSION RISK PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A risk-related distribution pattern in naturally ventilated rooms where infection probability does not necessarily decline with increasing distance and may be highest at longer distances beyond physical distancing guidelines.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MIXING OF POLLUTED PLUMES AND AIR IN OCCUPIED ZONE">
      <data key="d0">MIXING OF POLLUTED PLUMES AND AIR IN OCCUPIED ZONE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">An undesirable air-distribution condition in which polluted plumes mix with air in the occupied zone. The passage cites the need for appropriate system design to avoid this exposure condition.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The airborne contaminant or infectious aerosol discussed in the passage. Its concentration and spatial distribution are used to assess airborne transmission risk across ventilation strategies.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COVID-19 AIRBORNE PATHOGEN CONTEXT">
      <data key="d0">COVID-19 AIRBORNE PATHOGEN CONTEXT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The disease/pathogen context referenced in cited studies on airborne pathogen transmission in confined spaces under different ventilation strategies.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPEN WINDOWS OR DOORS">
      <data key="d0">OPEN WINDOWS OR DOORS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Openings that provide airflow paths for natural ventilation by connecting the occupied indoor space with the outdoor environment. They are identified as important determinants of natural ventilation performance. | Openings that provide airflow pathways between the office-type room and adjacent environments. Their position can alter indoor air movement and influence whether airborne particles are diluted, redirected, or spread harmfully.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">OPEN WINDOWS AND DOORS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNSTABLE AND CHANGING AIRFLOW PATTERNS">
      <data key="d0">UNSTABLE AND CHANGING AIRFLOW PATTERNS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Variable indoor airflow distributions associated with natural ventilation. These patterns arise because airflow is affected by wind, openings, and air temperature, producing potentially uneven infection-risk distributions in the room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
