      <data key="d0">SPECTATOR OCCUPANCY: 92 PEOPLE (38%)</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A reduced spectator occupancy level identified as one option for keeping the modeled infection-risk metric below 1 in the naturally ventilated venue.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPECTATOR OCCUPANCY: 121 PEOPLE (50%) FOR 1.5 H EVENT">
      <data key="d0">SPECTATOR OCCUPANCY: 121 PEOPLE (50%) FOR 1.5 H EVENT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The maximum spectator load reported for a 1.5-hour event while maintaining the modeled infection-risk constraint under the natural ventilation scenario.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MORE INFECTIOUS SARS-COV-2 VARIANTS">
      <data key="d0">MORE INFECTIOUS SARS-COV-2 VARIANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">More infectious variants of SARS-CoV-2 identified as one contributor to high-emission or high-risk airborne transmission scenarios. The text states that such scenarios are associated with increased airborne transmission risk at all venues.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH-EMITTING SPECTATOR">
      <data key="d0">HIGH-EMITTING SPECTATOR</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">An infectious occupant with unusually high respiratory emission potential, such as from high viral load, more infectious virus, or increased activity. The text identifies this occupant type as a major driver of elevated airborne transmission risk and potential super-spreading events.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH VIRAL LOAD">
      <data key="d0">HIGH VIRAL LOAD</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">An occupant-related emission condition contributing to a high-emission scenario. The text groups high viral loads with more infectious variants and increased activity as factors associated with increased airborne transmission risk at all venues.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INCREASED ACTIVITY">
      <data key="d0">INCREASED ACTIVITY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">An occupant-activity condition that can raise respiratory aerosol emission. The text lists increased activity as one of the high-emission scenario factors associated with greater airborne transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CROWDING INDEX">
      <data key="d0">CROWDING INDEX</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">An occupancy-control metric used to limit airborne transmission risk. In the high-emitter case, the maximum crowding index was markedly reduced to six spectators to keep the reproduction metric R below 1.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.81</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SIX SPECTATORS">
      <data key="d0">SIX SPECTATORS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A reduced occupancy threshold reported for the high-emitter case. The text states that the maximum crowding index had to be reduced to six spectators, along with a 3-minute residence time, to keep R below 1.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.73</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH EMITTING INDIVIDUALS">
      <data key="d0">HIGH EMITTING INDIVIDUALS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occasional occupants who emit unusually high quantities of respiratory aerosols. Although infrequent, they are emphasized in risk assessment because they can provoke super-spreading events and substantially increase airborne transmission potential.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGING SPECTATORS">
      <data key="d0">SINGING SPECTATORS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Spectators engaged in singing, identified as high emitters in Pop/Rock concert settings. Singing increases respiratory aerosol emission and can elevate airborne pathogen transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SHOUTING SPECTATORS">
      <data key="d0">SHOUTING SPECTATORS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Spectators engaged in shouting, identified as high emitters in sporting-event settings. Shouting increases aerosol emission and can play a major role in airborne transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POORLY VENTILATED INDOOR AREAS">
      <data key="d0">POORLY VENTILATED INDOOR AREAS</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor spaces characterized by insufficient ventilation or low effective air exchange, associated with increased residence time of infectious aerosols and higher airborne transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PROLONGED INDOOR RESIDENCE">
      <data key="d0">PROLONGED INDOOR RESIDENCE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Extended presence of occupants in shared indoor environments, increasing cumulative exposure to virus-laden aerosols, particularly where ventilation is poor.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.58</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INDOOR AEROSOL TRANSMISSION PATHWAY">
      <data key="d0">INDOOR AEROSOL TRANSMISSION PATHWAY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The airborne route by which aerosol particles carrying SARS-CoV-2 can move through and persist in indoor air, contributing to transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR PURIFIER UNIT">
      <data key="d0">AIR PURIFIER UNIT</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Air-cleaning device referenced in an experimental study of indoor aerosol dynamics; relevant as a local air-treatment unit that may reduce aerosol particle concentration indoors.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.64</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_35,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_74</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOW-MOMENTUM VENTILATION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">LOW-MOMENTUM VENTILATION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation system referenced in a cited experimental study of indoor aerosol dynamics, relevant because its supply-air characteristics influence mixing, aerosol transport, and residence time.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_35,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_74</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOW-MOMENTUM AIR DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">LOW-MOMENTUM AIR DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Air distribution pattern associated with low-momentum ventilation, influencing how aerosols disperse, mix, and are removed from indoor spaces.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.48</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INDOOR EPIDEMIC EVENT SETTING">
      <data key="d0">INDOOR EPIDEMIC EVENT SETTING</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">An occupied indoor environment where epidemic transmission risk is considered during an event. Although not specifically a hospital area, it is represented with the closest available spatial-zone type in the schema.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESIDENCE TIME IN EPIDEMIC SETTINGS">
      <data key="d0">RESIDENCE TIME IN EPIDEMIC SETTINGS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The duration for which occupants remain in an indoor epidemic setting. The text states that infection risk increases substantially with event duration, motivating recommendations to minimize residence time or introduce breaks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPECTATOR COUNT">
      <data key="d0">SPECTATOR COUNT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The number of spectators present in the indoor event environment. Reducing the spectator count is identified as an effective mitigation measure for lowering infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DENSE SEATING ARRANGEMENT">
      <data key="d0">DENSE SEATING ARRANGEMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A higher-density seating condition implied as the comparator to reduced or checkerboard seating. Greater seating density increases proximity and occupancy load, which can elevate airborne infection risk relative to reduced-density layouts.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONTINUOUS OCCUPANCY WITHOUT BREAKS">
      <data key="d0">CONTINUOUS OCCUPANCY WITHOUT BREAKS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A temporal occupancy pattern in which people remain indoors for the full event without interruption. The excerpt recommends limiting residence time or considering breaks, implying that uninterrupted occupancy increases cumulative aerosol exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM-APPROPRIATE DV OPERATION">
      <data key="d0">ROOM-APPROPRIATE DV OPERATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The properly adjusted operating condition required for DV to be effective in the specific room. It represents the need to match the displacement-ventilation pattern and airflow rate to room geometry and occupancy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISTANT UNVENTILATED BALCONIES">
      <data key="d0">DISTANT UNVENTILATED BALCONIES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A distant occupied balcony zone lacking direct ventilation. Spectators in this zone experienced measurable exposure from an emitter located in the mechanically ventilated stalls.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENUE ROOM">
      <data key="d0">VENUE ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The overall indoor venue environment containing the stalls and balconies. The passage emphasizes that all areas of this room require good ventilation to reduce airborne exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE PATH FROM STALLS TO BALCONIES">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE PATH FROM STALLS TO BALCONIES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">An inferred transport pathway by which respiratory aerosols from a passive emitter in the mechanically ventilated stalls reached spectators in distant unventilated balconies.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH EMISSION SCENARIO">
      <data key="d0">HIGH EMISSION SCENARIO</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A high source-strength condition for respiratory aerosol emission. Under HVV, this condition distinctly increased exposure among spectators in distant unventilated balconies.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CARBON DIOXIDE (CO2)">
      <data key="d0">CARBON DIOXIDE (CO2)</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">Carbon dioxide is used as a tracer-gas proxy for respiratory aerosols, allowing ventilation and aerosol-accumulation conditions to be inferred from measured CO2 levels.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_38,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_69</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BALCONY VENTILATION CONDITIONS">
      <data key="d0">BALCONY VENTILATION CONDITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilated and non-ventilated balcony conditions are discussed as airflow/ventilation conditions where CO2 levels were found to be elevated, indicating that nominal ventilation does not necessarily prevent aerosol accumulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION FLOW RATE / AIR CHANGE RATE">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION FLOW RATE / AIR CHANGE RATE</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation flow rate, including maximum ventilation rates and air change rate, is discussed as a key ventilation metric. The passage emphasizes that increasing flow rates or using 100% outdoor air does not necessarily reduce infection risk, especially for close-proximity exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MERS-COV">
      <data key="d0">MERS-COV</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">MERS-CoV is referenced in a cited hospital-setting bioaerosol risk assessment, illustrating the broader relevance of ventilation and airborne pathogen exposure studies. | A coronavirus referenced as one of the airborne-transmission-related viruses for which distancing and facial protection measures may reduce exposure risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_38,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_83</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
      <data key="d6">MERS-COV</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OVERHEAD MIXING VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">OVERHEAD MIXING VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Overhead mixing ventilation is cited as an air-distribution pattern for which air change rate alone may be an inadequate indicator of airborne infectious disease mitigation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_38,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_82</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLOSE-PROXIMITY OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">CLOSE-PROXIMITY OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Close-proximity occupancy represents the exposure condition in which people are near one another, making infection risk likely even when ventilation flow rates are increased.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MVV VENUES">
      <data key="d0">MVV VENUES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupied indoor venues using MVV, interpreted as a mechanically ventilated mixing-ventilation concept. The text states that face-covering recommendations are provided for increasing event duration regardless of viral-variant infectivity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NV VENUES">
      <data key="d0">NV VENUES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Naturally ventilated occupied venues. The text identifies these venues as difficult for airborne-transmission risk prediction and as having observed high infection risk, supporting a general FFP2/N95 mask recommendation and possible temporary closure during prolonged exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OMICRON">
      <data key="d0">OMICRON</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A more infectious SARS-CoV-2 variant considered in the study's airborne-transmission risk recommendations. Omicron leads to stricter controls, including surgical masks or reduced occupancy in DVV for events longer than 3 hours and FFP2/N95 masks in MVV for 3-hour events.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_39,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRUS VARIANTS WITH INCREASED INFECTIVITY">
      <data key="d0">VIRUS VARIANTS WITH INCREASED INFECTIVITY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">More infectious viral variants that may make masking alone insufficient during prolonged exposure, particularly in naturally ventilated venues.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.77</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENUE OCCUPANCY LOAD">
      <data key="d0">VENUE OCCUPANCY LOAD</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The number of occupants present in a venue. The text recommends reduction in occupancy as a risk-control measure for displacement-ventilated events longer than 3 hours when Omicron is considered, implying that higher occupancy increases airborne exposure opportunity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENUE">
      <data key="d0">VENUE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled event space where venue-specific airborne infection risk was evaluated under different emitter positions, event durations, occupancy levels, ventilation concepts, airflow rates, and mitigation strategies. Within the constrained type list, it is treated as the primary occupied air-handling zone.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The air-handling infrastructure associated with the venue. Its ventilation concept and airflow rate influence modeled airborne infection risk, and the text notes that the stage may often be outside its effective service area. | The air-handling system that generates turbulent airflow in the modeled occupied space. The text states that its configuration can strongly influence particle dispersion and may be favorable for air decontamination when judiciously configured. | The cabin air-handling and ventilation system used to impose different ventilation approaches and operating conditions during the experimental assessment of aerosol and pathogen transmission. | The indoor event ventilation system evaluated in two versions with different air exchange rates and airflow patterns. Its performance was a major determinant of infectious aerosol exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.99</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_40,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">VENTILATION SYSTEM</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2 WILD-TYPE">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2 WILD-TYPE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The wild-type SARS-CoV-2 virus considered in the venue-specific CFD infection-risk calculations and safe-event recommendations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGING AND SHOUTING ACTOR">
      <data key="d0">SINGING AND SHOUTING ACTOR</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A high-activity infectious performer scenario with substantially greater aerosol emission than a silent passive emitter. The text states that infection risk increases dramatically for a singing and shouting actor.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ENSEMBLE">
      <data key="d0">ENSEMBLE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The group of performers or associated participants who may be exposed to infectious aerosols from actors or singers. The text identifies the ensemble as another group requiring protection from airborne transmission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.71</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENUES WITH DV OR NV">
      <data key="d0">VENUES WITH DV OR NV</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor venue zones evaluated for airborne transmission risk under displacement ventilation or natural ventilation. The text emphasizes that these ventilation conditions create non-uniform flow and exposure patterns that challenge analytical risk prediction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIRECTIONAL FLOW PATTERNS">
      <data key="d0">DIRECTIONAL FLOW PATTERNS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation-driven flow structures that cause strong spatial and temporal dependence of airborne infection risk. These patterns influence aerosol transport and create location-specific high- and low-risk exposure zones.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DROPLET AEROSOLS GENERATED BY OCCUPANTS">
      <data key="d0">DROPLET AEROSOLS GENERATED BY OCCUPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne infection-relevant aerosol particles emitted by occupants. Their transport and concentration distribution depend on ventilation-driven flow patterns and the relative locations of emitters and absorbers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ABSORBER-SPECIFIC AEROSOL CONCENTRATIONS">
      <data key="d0">ABSORBER-SPECIFIC AEROSOL CONCENTRATIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Local aerosol concentration levels experienced at absorber or receiver positions. These concentrations vary strongly with absorber location relative to the emitter, making representative risk estimation difficult.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OCCUPANTS">
      <data key="d0">OCCUPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">People present in the indoor venue who may generate droplet aerosols and contribute to airborne infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_41,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_57,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_65</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The source occupant emitting droplet aerosols. The spatial relationship between the emitter and absorbers determines local aerosol concentration and exposure risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_41</data>
