      <data key="d0">PERFECTLY AIRBORNE AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled airborne contaminant represented as remaining suspended in both experiments and simulations. The passage discusses general aerosol droplets rather than a specific pathogen, but this type is the closest valid airborne-contaminant category.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DEPOSITION-AND-EVAPORATION-FREE AEROSOL BEHAVIOR">
      <data key="d0">DEPOSITION-AND-EVAPORATION-FREE AEROSOL BEHAVIOR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A simplifying modeled aerosol behavior in which evaporation and deposition effects are not included, so the aerosol is treated as perfectly airborne.</data>
