    <node id="CONNECTION OF THE STAGE AREA TO THE VENTILATION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">CONNECTION OF THE STAGE AREA TO THE VENTILATION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation linkage between the stage area and the HVAC system. The text specifically recommends enforcing this connection as part of pandemic preparedness to improve mitigation of aerosol transmission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">ROOM AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The indoor air-movement pattern within the venue. It is influenced by air inlets and outlets, windows, room height, volume, and other boundary conditions, and it controls aerosol transport between an infectious emitter and exposed occupants. | Modeled indoor airflow pattern in the arena. Pre-calculations showed that the trajectories of CO2 and aerosols with diameter d ≤ 10 µm became directly dependent on this room air flow from an air velocity of 0.05 m s−1.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.97</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_48,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_51</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">ROOM AIR FLOW</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE INFECTIOUS PERSON (EMITTER)">
      <data key="d0">ONE INFECTIOUS PERSON (EMITTER)</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The single infectious occupant placed in the fully occupied audience in all three study approaches. This person is the assumed source of infectious aerosol emissions for the transmission-risk analyses.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FULLY OCCUPIED AUDIENCE">
      <data key="d0">FULLY OCCUPIED AUDIENCE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The occupancy condition used in the study design, representing a venue filled with audience members. It increases the number of people potentially exposed to aerosols from the infectious emitter and affects ventilation demand.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEDENTARY PASSIVE EMITTER WITH AVERAGE VIRAL LOAD">
      <data key="d0">SEDENTARY PASSIVE EMITTER WITH AVERAGE VIRAL LOAD</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled infectious-occupant emission profile representing a sedentary, passive person with an average viral load. This profile provides a baseline respiratory aerosol or quanta source term for calculating individual infection probability and global event risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_49</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SLIGHTLY ACTIVE EMITTER WITH 90TH-PERCENTILE HIGH VIRAL LOAD">
      <data key="d0">SLIGHTLY ACTIVE EMITTER WITH 90TH-PERCENTILE HIGH VIRAL LOAD</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled infectious-occupant emission profile representing a slightly active person with a high viral load set at the 90th percentile. The text states that this percentile was chosen as a moderate high-emission case to avoid overestimating quanta emission given uncertainty and long-tailed emission distributions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_49</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGLE INFECTIOUS OCCUPANT AT AN EVENT">
      <data key="d0">SINGLE INFECTIOUS OCCUPANT AT AN EVENT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupancy condition in which one infectious person is present at an event and acts as the source of airborne virus transmission. The text links this source to estimates of individual infection probability and global risk, analogous to an event reproduction number or number of secondary infections.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_49</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2 VARIANTS">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2 VARIANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Virus variants investigated as factors that may change infection risk under the modeled indoor ventilation and occupancy scenarios. | Airborne viral pathogen variants considered in the venue-specific infection risk assessment. The text identifies Alpha, Delta, and Omicron as variants whose enhancement factors are applied to quanta absorption and modeled infection risk. | Different variants of SARS-CoV-2 referenced as potentially having different UV sensitivities, implying that pathogen variant identity may affect UV susceptibility and inactivation outcomes. | The WA1 variant of SARS-CoV-2 is referenced in a study title concerning aerosol transmission blocked by UV-C light in a hamster model. No built-environment ventilation parameters or spatial containment details are provided in the excerpt.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_50</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
      <data key="d6">SARS-COV-2 VIRUS VARIANTS,SARS-COV-2 VARIANTS,SARS-COV-2 WA1 VARIANT</data>
    </node>
