    <node id="SARS-COV-2 INFECTIOUS QUANTA">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2 INFECTIOUS QUANTA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The airborne infectious-quanta proxy used for modeling COVID-19/SARS-CoV-2 airborne transmission risk. Its modeled concentration and associated infection probability are influenced by emitter source strength, ventilation conditions, and occupancy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_53</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENUE-SPECIFIC INDOOR VOLUME">
      <data key="d0">VENUE-SPECIFIC INDOOR VOLUME</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The reconstructed indoor venue volume used as the CFD domain. Its geometry and boundary conditions are derived from construction plans, staff interviews, on-site inspection, and measurements of environmental, supply-air, and surrounding temperatures.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM AIR FLOW AND THERMAL FIELD">
      <data key="d0">ROOM AIR FLOW AND THERMAL FIELD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated room-air distribution and temperature field solved with segregated flow and energy transport methods. It includes effects of gravity, turbulence modeling, thermal boundary conditions, occupant heat, lighting and device heat fluxes, and surface-to-surface radiation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONVECTIVE-DIFFUSIVE SCALAR TRANSPORT">
      <data key="d0">CONVECTIVE-DIFFUSIVE SCALAR TRANSPORT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled transport pattern by which source-specific passive scalars released at occupant mouths are carried through the venue by convection and diffusion, producing local concentration fields in each computational cell.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPUTER SIMULATED PERSONS (CSP)">
      <data key="d0">COMPUTER SIMULATED PERSONS (CSP)</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Simplified seated occupants included in the simulation. Each CSP contributes an 80 W heat flux and may function as an emitter or receiver for breath-tracer exposure assessment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PRE-SELECTED EMITTER CSP">
      <data key="d0">PRE-SELECTED EMITTER CSP</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A selected computer simulated person designated as an aerosol or tracer source. Each emitter releases a personalized passive scalar through mouth-area surface cells without added momentum.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ABSORBING CSP">
      <data key="d0">ABSORBING CSP</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A computer simulated person treated as an exposure receiver. A hemispherical sampling zone around its mouth is used to estimate locally experienced relative amounts of aerosols or tracer material from different emitters.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MOUTH-AREA RELEASE CELLS">
      <data key="d0">MOUTH-AREA RELEASE CELLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Localized mouth-area surface cells through which each pre-selected emitter introduces a personalized, passive, momentum-free scalar mass flux into the room air.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MOUTH-HEMISPHERE SAMPLING ZONE">
      <data key="d0">MOUTH-HEMISPHERE SAMPLING ZONE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A small hemispherical volume of radius 0.23 m defined around the mouth normal vector of each absorbing CSP. It is used as a volume-averaged sampling zone for local exposure to source-specific tracer concentrations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BREATH TRACER GASES">
      <data key="d0">BREATH TRACER GASES</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled tracer material inserted at the mouth area of simulated occupants to represent exhaled breath transport and to support evaluation of aerosol movement through the indoor air.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PERSONALIZED PASSIVE SCALAR">
      <data key="d0">PERSONALIZED PASSIVE SCALAR</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">A source-specific passive tracer released by each pre-selected emitter. Because each emitter has its own scalar, local non-interacting concentrations can be attributed to individual sources throughout the venue.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED AEROSOL OR QUANTA PROXY">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED AEROSOL OR QUANTA PROXY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled aerosol or infectious-quanta-bearing material represented indirectly by passive scalar concentrations. The approach allows uncertain quanta emission rates to be assigned after the CFD simulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FULL-SCALE ROOM MODEL">
      <data key="d0">FULL-SCALE ROOM MODEL</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">An enclosed full-scale indoor room used as the validation benchmark zone for airflow, temperature, and contaminant-transport behavior. Although not explicitly a hospital room, it is the relevant ventilated indoor zone in the cited displacement ventilation experiments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PASSIVE SCALAR">
      <data key="d0">PASSIVE SCALAR</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">A modeled scalar contaminant field solved after the flow variables on a frozen flow field. It is used as a tracer-like surrogate for evaluating transport, fluxes, and emission behavior, including later assignment of uncertain quanta emission rates.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QUANTA EMISSION">
      <data key="d0">QUANTA EMISSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A representation of infectious airborne emission potential whose rate is assigned a posteriori because it is typically uncertain. In the model context, it is linked to passive scalar transport rather than directly measured pathogen release.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2 AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2 AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne infectious aerosol associated with SARS-CoV-2 transmission. The text discusses uncertainty in its quanta emission rate and uses it as the pathogen-related contaminant for calculating numerical infection risk in CFD-based analysis. | Airborne infectious aerosol context underlying the cited COVID-19 exposure study. The entity is represented as SARS-CoV-2-laden aerosols rather than the disease name itself to align with the airborne-pathogen schema. | Aerosolized SARS-CoV-2 is the airborne pathogen whose UV susceptibility and inactivation response are compared across multiple studies. The text emphasizes that the UV dose received by these pathogen-containing aerosols depends on accurately modeled airflow and fluence-rate conditions. | Airborne viral aerosols associated with COVID-19 transmission, referenced in related article titles discussing exhaled aerosols, airborne infection risk, and indoor transmission. | Airborne viral particles emitted in respiratory aerosols. The text assumes aerosol viral load is equal to sputum at approximately 10^9 RNA copies/ml and discusses exposure thresholds of about 40 to 4000 virus particles per concert as a possible minimal infectious-dose range.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_56</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">SARS-COV-2-LADEN AEROSOLS,SARS-COV-2 AEROSOLS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACTIVITY AND VOCALIZATION LEVELS">
      <data key="d0">ACTIVITY AND VOCALIZATION LEVELS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupancy-related behavioral factors that affect SARS-CoV-2 aerosol quanta emission rates. The text notes that Buonanno et al. specify emission rates for different activity and vocalization levels.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_56</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NON-PASSIVE BEHAVIOUR">
      <data key="d0">NON-PASSIVE BEHAVIOUR</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupant behavior category beyond passive sedentary emission, including actions such as quiet speaking. The text states that such non-passive behavior is not incorporated in the discussed passive-emitter distribution, despite being relevant to emission-rate estimation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_56</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QUIET SPEAKING">
      <data key="d0">QUIET SPEAKING</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Specific example of non-passive occupant vocalization mentioned in the text. It is relevant because vocalization level can change SARS-CoV-2 aerosol quanta emission compared with passive breathing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.61</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_56</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NON-PASSIVE OCCUPANT BEHAVIOR">
      <data key="d0">NON-PASSIVE OCCUPANT BEHAVIOR</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupant activities such as quiet speaking that are explicitly noted as affecting emission profiles and needing inclusion in the quanta emission-rate distribution.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_57</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2 ALPHA VARIANT">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2 ALPHA VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">SARS-CoV-2 variant included in the risk analysis with an enhancement factor used to modify modeled airborne infection risk. | Specific SARS-CoV-2 variant mentioned in a cited study comparing Delta and Omicron responses to ultraviolet radiation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
      <data key="d6">SARS-COV-2 DELTA VARIANT</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2 OMICRON VARIANT">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2 OMICRON VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">SARS-CoV-2 variant included in the risk analysis with an enhancement factor used to modify modeled airborne infection risk. | Specific SARS-CoV-2 variant mentioned in a cited study comparing Omicron and Delta responses to ultraviolet radiation. | A highly transmissible airborne virus cited as an example of an indoor infection-control concern for which far-UVC germicidal disinfection may be relevant.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">SARS-COV-2 OMICRON VARIANT,SARS-COV-2 OMICRON SUBVARIANT</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPECTATOR OCCUPANCY LOAD">
      <data key="d0">SPECTATOR OCCUPANCY LOAD</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The venue population whose individual infection risk is assessed and intended to remain below the acceptable risk threshold during future events.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ALPHA">
      <data key="d0">ALPHA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">SARS-CoV-2 variant included in the modeled airborne infection risk comparisons, with a variant-specific enhancement factor used in the quanta absorption calculation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DELTA">
      <data key="d0">DELTA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">SARS-CoV-2 variant included in the airborne transmission risk assessment, represented through an enhancement factor affecting quanta absorption and analytical infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIFFERENT VENTILATION SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">DIFFERENT VENTILATION SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation systems considered in the analytical venue-specific infection risk assessment. Their differing air distribution performance is accounted for through the ventilation effectiveness parameter.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">AIR DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor airflow and mixing behavior produced by ventilation systems. The text emphasizes that air distribution effectiveness must be considered because real venues may not conform to a perfect well-mixed condition.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WELL-MIXED ASSUMPTION">
      <data key="d0">WELL-MIXED ASSUMPTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Idealized analytical air distribution pattern in which airborne contaminants are assumed to be uniformly mixed throughout the indoor space. The text identifies this assumption as imperfect and modifies it using ventilation effectiveness.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION EFFECTIVENESS EZ">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION EFFECTIVENESS EZ</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Model parameter introduced to represent the effectiveness of air distribution for different ventilation systems. It is used to improve the analytical Wells–Riley/Peng approach by accounting for deviations from ideal well-mixed airflow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_59,2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OCCUPIED INDOOR ENVIRONMENT / STUDIED VENUES">
      <data key="d0">OCCUPIED INDOOR ENVIRONMENT / STUDIED VENUES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The indoor spaces or venues to which the analytical airborne-transmission model is applied. The model uses indoor environment volume, ventilation rate, ventilation effectiveness, event duration, and occupancy-related factors to estimate airborne exposure or infection outcomes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR EXCHANGE RATE (AER) Λ">
      <data key="d0">AIR EXCHANGE RATE (AER) Λ</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation air exchange rate in the analytical model. It appears in the denominator of the equation and is multiplied by ventilation effectiveness Ez, so higher effective ventilation reduces modeled airborne exposure when other removal mechanisms are neglected.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EFFECTIVE AIR EXCHANGE RATE ΛEZ">
      <data key="d0">EFFECTIVE AIR EXCHANGE RATE ΛEZ</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation removal term formed by multiplying the air exchange rate λ by ventilation effectiveness Ez. This term was introduced to improve the imperfect well-mixed assumption by accounting for how air distribution alters the effective dilution or removal of airborne contaminants.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRUS-CONTAINING PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">VIRUS-CONTAINING PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne infectious particles considered in the model. In the stated worst-case scenario, virus decay and particle deposition rates were assumed to be low and therefore neglected, making ventilation dilution/removal the key modeled loss process. | Pathogen-laden airborne or droplet particles whose dispersion, transport, and potential transmission are the main subject of the numerical and CFD studies summarized in the text.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">VIRION-CONTAINING PARTICLES</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUSCEPTIBLE PERSONS NSUS">
      <data key="d0">SUSCEPTIBLE PERSONS NSUS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The number of susceptible people present in the indoor environment. Nsus appears in the numerator of the equation, scaling the modeled infection or exposure outcome by the number of occupants who may be infected.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WILD-TYPE SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d0">WILD-TYPE SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne viral pathogen and variant used in the basic infection-risk scenario. The model considers exhaled SARS-CoV-2-containing particles from an infectious person, with virus decay and particle deposition neglected under a worst-case assumption.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_61</data>
      <data key="d5">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE INFECTIOUS PERSON">
      <data key="d0">ONE INFECTIOUS PERSON</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
