      <data key="d6">AIRBORNE BACTERIA</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATED ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATED ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilated rooms are indoor zones where upper-room UVGI disinfection systems are designed or optimized using airflow and pathogen-transport modeling.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_12,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_19,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_20,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_62,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_63,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_64</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPPER-ROOM UVGI DISINFECTION SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">UPPER-ROOM UVGI DISINFECTION SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Upper-room ultraviolet germicidal irradiation disinfection systems are room-level environmental control systems evaluated for pathogen inactivation in ventilated rooms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_12,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_19,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_63,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_64</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HOSPITAL ULTRAVIOLET GERMICIDAL IRRADIATION SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">HOSPITAL ULTRAVIOLET GERMICIDAL IRRADIATION SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Hospital ultraviolet germicidal irradiation systems are healthcare environmental control systems assessed for inactivating airborne mycobacteria.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_12,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_65</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CFD-PREDICTED AIRBORNE PATHOGEN TRANSPORT PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">CFD-PREDICTED AIRBORNE PATHOGEN TRANSPORT PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled distribution pattern describes how airborne pathogens are transported by room airflow, ventilation, and human activity within indoor or hospital environments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HUMAN ACTIVITIES">
      <data key="d0">HUMAN ACTIVITIES</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Human activities represent occupant-related movement and behavior that can influence airborne pathogen transport within indoor spaces. | Human activities are real-world occupancy-related factors absent from empty-cabin simulations. They may introduce variations in bioaerosol transmission patterns by changing movement, airflow disturbance, and contaminant release.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_12,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_20,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_64</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
      <data key="d6">HUMAN ACTIVITIES</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPPER-ROOM ULTRAVIOLET GERMICIDAL IRRADIATION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">UPPER-ROOM ULTRAVIOLET GERMICIDAL IRRADIATION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">An upper-room ultraviolet germicidal irradiation air-disinfection system evaluated in hospital and indoor-room modelling studies for reducing airborne infectious microorganisms. The text specifically links these systems to inactivation of airborne mycobacteria and airborne coronavirus under different airflow modelling assumptions. | Upper-room air ultraviolet germicidal irradiation is an air-treatment system studied for inactivating airborne mycobacteria in indoor air.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_13,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_65</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
      <data key="d6">UPPER-ROOM AIR ULTRAVIOLET GERMICIDAL IRRADIATION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NATURALLY VENTILATED HOSPITAL WARD">
      <data key="d0">NATURALLY VENTILATED HOSPITAL WARD</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A hospital ward using natural ventilation, cited as a setting where an upper-room ultraviolet germicidal irradiation system was computationally modelled and optimized. Its ventilation and spatial airflow patterns are central to pathogen transport and UVGI performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_13,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_20,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_65,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_66</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MODELED INDOOR ROOM ZONE">
      <data key="d0">MODELED INDOOR ROOM ZONE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A generalized indoor room or ward-like zone represented in the cited modelling studies, including naturally ventilated hospital wards and populated rooms. It is the spatial setting where airflow, aerosol transport, virus exposure, and UVGI effectiveness are evaluated.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPLETE MIXING">
      <data key="d0">COMPLETE MIXING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A simplified air distribution assumption used in analytical models, where airborne contaminants are treated as uniformly mixed throughout the room. This contrasts with CFD-resolved spatially non-uniform airflow and concentration fields.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CFD-RESOLVED AIRFLOW AND CONTAMINANT DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">CFD-RESOLVED AIRFLOW AND CONTAMINANT DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A spatially resolved representation of airflow, aerosol transport, contaminant concentration, and radiation-coupled inactivation generated by computational fluid dynamics models. It captures heterogeneous transport patterns that complete-mixing models cannot resolve.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNSPECIFIED INDOOR AIR-EXCHANGE RATE">
      <data key="d0">UNSPECIFIED INDOOR AIR-EXCHANGE RATE</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The implied ventilation or air-exchange parameter governing dilution and removal in indoor modelling studies. No numerical ACH value is provided in the text, but ventilation and mixing assumptions are relevant to pathogen concentration and exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HUMAN OCCUPANCY IN POPULATED ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">HUMAN OCCUPANCY IN POPULATED ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The presence of people in rooms where airborne coronavirus inactivation is modelled. Although no occupant count is given, occupancy is relevant because people can generate respiratory aerosols and increase exposure potential.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM OF INTEREST">
      <data key="d0">ROOM OF INTEREST</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The indoor room or zone being modeled. Its 3D geometry is created in CAD and then used for optical UVGI simulation and CFD-based airflow calculation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPLETE MIXING AIR DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">COMPLETE MIXING AIR DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">An idealized air distribution assumption used in simple analytical models, where air and airborne material are treated as uniformly mixed throughout the room. It supports quick estimates and scenario comparisons but may be inaccurate when the assumption is not valid.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CFD-RESOLVED ROOM AIRFLOW PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">CFD-RESOLVED ROOM AIRFLOW PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A detailed spatial airflow distribution in the room calculated using high-fidelity CFD modeling. This pattern can account for room geometry and local airflow structures but requires greater computational effort and time.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM">
      <data key="d0">ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The indoor room environment represented in the 3D model where UV fluence, air flow, and aerosol transport are simulated. | An unnamed indoor room used in an airflow and particle-spread study. The space contained human-body thermal plume effects and cough-generated particle dispersion, and partition configurations were evaluated for exposure-risk reduction. | The assessed room is the primary zone for the ventilation and air-exchange evaluation. Its air exchange is characterized using supply airflow, room volume, carbon dioxide tracer decay measurements, and qualitative assessment of supply and exhaust layout.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_15,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_16,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_17,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_18,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_25,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_26,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_32,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">ROOM</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL PARTICLE TRAJECTORIES">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL PARTICLE TRAJECTORIES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The time-dependent paths of released aerosol particles through the room, computed using Lagrangian particle tracking based on the modeled velocity vector field. The particles are assumed to follow the bulk air flow without influencing it.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_15,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BULK FLUID FLOW">
      <data key="d0">BULK FLUID FLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The room-scale airflow field that governs aerosol-particle motion. The model assumes particles follow this bulk flow and do not influence it.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PATHOGEN-LADEN AEROSOL PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">PATHOGEN-LADEN AEROSOL PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne active particles carrying the pathogen. Their active number in the room decreases due to ventilation-driven extraction, UV germicidal inactivation, deposition, and natural decay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTICLE TRAJECTORIES">
      <data key="d0">PARTICLE TRAJECTORIES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled movement paths of airborne particles through the room. These trajectories determine each particle's residence time and the time-varying exposure history used to evaluate pathogen persistence.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTICLE EXTRACTION PATH">
      <data key="d0">PARTICLE EXTRACTION PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The removal route by which particles leave the room when ventilation is active. It represents the airflow-mediated pathway associated with particle extraction and residence-time termination.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PATHOGENS">
      <data key="d0">PATHOGENS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne pathogens modeled as particles whose active surviving fraction is calculated relative to the initial number of particles. Their decay and survival are evaluated over time and can be compared with measured values. | Pathogenic airborne contaminants requiring targeted disinfection in subway cabins, cabin airflow, air ducts, and air-conditioning units.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
      <data key="d6">PATHOGENS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE MICROORGANISMS">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE MICROORGANISMS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne microorganisms referenced in the context of susceptibility to irradiation by an upper-room UVGI system. They represent airborne biological agents whose survival can be reduced by germicidal ultraviolet exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_18,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_69,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_70</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EQUIVALENT AIR CHANGES PER HOUR (EACH)">
      <data key="d0">EQUIVALENT AIR CHANGES PER HOUR (EACH)</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">An equivalent air-change rate in h−1 derived from the exponential decay constant λ fitted to the survival fraction SF(t), using eACH = 3600λ. It represents UV-disinfection-equivalent airborne inactivation or removal performance, not necessarily mechanical ventilation ACH.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTICLE-TRACKING AIRFLOW PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">PARTICLE-TRACKING AIRFLOW PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A modeled air distribution representation in which particle trajectories are tracked through the room and UV fluence rate values are interpolated along those trajectories to estimate pathogen inactivation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POPULATED ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">POPULATED ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor rooms containing occupants, referenced in connection with predicting airborne coronavirus inactivation by far-UVC. Occupant presence makes these rooms relevant to pathogen emission, transport, and exposure modeling.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_20,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_67</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POPULATED OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">POPULATED OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A qualitative occupancy condition indicating that people are present in the room. No numerical occupant count is provided, but the condition is important because occupants can emit infectious aerosols and alter airflow through movement and activities.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE PATHOGEN TRANSPORT DUE TO HUMAN ACTIVITIES">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE PATHOGEN TRANSPORT DUE TO HUMAN ACTIVITIES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A CFD-modeled airborne transport pattern describing how occupant activities influence the movement and distribution of pathogen-laden aerosols indoors.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_20,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_64</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CEILING-FAN-DRIVEN AIR CIRCULATION">
      <data key="d0">CEILING-FAN-DRIVEN AIR CIRCULATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">An indoor air circulation pattern associated with a ceiling fan, referenced in a numerical modeling study involving an upper-room ultraviolet germicidal irradiation system. The fan-driven circulation can affect air mixing and pathogen exposure to disinfection zones.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POPULATED ROOM">
      <data key="d0">POPULATED ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">An occupied indoor room used as the modeled environment for evaluating airborne pathogen concentration and UV-based inactivation throughout the space.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="M. PARAFORTUITUM">
      <data key="d0">M. PARAFORTUITUM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A mycobacterial organism used as the biological target in a UV inactivation validation case. The text reports its UV susceptibility as k = 0.12 m2/J, and calculated surviving fractions are compared with experimental measurements.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_21,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR MIXING">
      <data key="d0">AIR MIXING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Air mixing is cited as a factor influencing the effectiveness of ultraviolet germicidal irradiation for inactivating airborne bacteria because it affects how contaminated air circulates through treated upper-room air zones.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_22,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_71,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_72</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION EFFICIENCY">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION EFFICIENCY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation efficiency is referenced in the cited Xu and Miller work as a factor influencing UVGI effectiveness; it characterizes how effectively room airflow removes or redistributes airborne contaminants.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_22,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_71,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_72</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FULL-SCALE MEASUREMENT FACILITY">
      <data key="d0">FULL-SCALE MEASUREMENT FACILITY</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The measurement facility used by Xu et al. is described as the experimental full-scale environment in which airborne UVGI inactivation measurements were performed and characterized across several publications.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPERIMENTAL ROOM">
      <data key="d0">EXPERIMENTAL ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Experimental indoor room used for airborne-pathogen transport, ventilation, air-mixing, and upper-room UV-C germicidal irradiation evaluation. The room is approximately 6.10 m by 5.79 m in floor area and 2.47 m high, and contains mechanical ventilation, box fans, a seated heated mannequin aerosol source, and five UV-C luminaires.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.97</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_23,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_30,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MECHANICAL VENTILATION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">MECHANICAL VENTILATION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Engineered ventilation system serving the experimental room. It includes two supply-air points with circular diffusers and two exhaust-air points located on opposite sides of the room, establishing the primary supply and removal airflow pathways.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO AIR SUPPLY POINTS WITH CIRCULAR DIFFUSERS">
      <data key="d0">TWO AIR SUPPLY POINTS WITH CIRCULAR DIFFUSERS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Supply-air delivery paths of the mechanical ventilation system. Each supply point includes a circular diffuser that introduces mechanically supplied air into the experimental room and contributes to dilution and airflow distribution.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO AIR EXHAUST POINTS">
      <data key="d0">TWO AIR EXHAUST POINTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Exhaust-air removal paths of the mechanical ventilation system. The exhaust points are located on opposite sides of the experimental room and remove room air as part of the mechanical ventilation airflow circuit.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO FLOOR BOX FANS">
      <data key="d0">TWO FLOOR BOX FANS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Two Lasko Inc. 3723 box fans placed on the floor of the experimental room. They provide supplemental recirculating air movement and are used to promote room air mixing, but they do not constitute outdoor-air supply or exhaust.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.81</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM AIR MIXING">
      <data key="d0">ROOM AIR MIXING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Air distribution behavior promoted by the floor-mounted box fans together with the room ventilation. The mixing pattern affects how pathogen-containing aerosols disperse, dilute, and interact with the upper-room UV-C treatment environment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_23,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEATED HEATED MANNEQUIN SOURCE">
      <data key="d0">SEATED HEATED MANNEQUIN SOURCE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Mannequin placed in a seated position in the middle of the room to emulate an infected person producing pathogen-containing aerosols. The mannequin is covered with heating tape producing 108 W of heat, representing an occupant-like thermal plume that can influence aerosol transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PATHOGEN-CONTAINING AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">PATHOGEN-CONTAINING AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Aerosolized infectious material emitted by the simulated infected occupant source. These aerosols are transported, mixed, diluted, removed by exhaust, and potentially inactivated under the combined influence of room airflow and UV-C irradiation. | Droplets emitted by the infected passenger that may carry the pathogen. Their remaining number, velocity, spatial distribution, upward transport, and removal by ventilation are central outcomes of the simulations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_23,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">PATHOGEN-CONTAINING DROPLETS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FIVE UV-C LUMINAIRES">
      <data key="d0">FIVE UV-C LUMINAIRES</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Set of upper-room UV-C germicidal irradiation fixtures installed in the experimental room for airborne-pathogen inactivation. The set includes one pendant UV-C luminaire, Lumalier PM, in the center of the room and four corner-mounted UV-C luminaires, Lumalier CM-218, one in each corner; their top sides are approximately 10 cm below the ceiling.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PENDANT UV-C LUMINAIRE">
      <data key="d0">PENDANT UV-C LUMINAIRE</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Central upper-room UV-C germicidal fixture identified as Lumalier PM. It is pendant-mounted in the center of the experimental room and forms part of the five-luminaire UV-C air treatment configuration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FOUR CORNER-MOUNT UV-C LUMINAIRES">
      <data key="d0">FOUR CORNER-MOUNT UV-C LUMINAIRES</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Four upper-room UV-C germicidal fixtures identified as Lumalier CM-218, with one installed in each corner of the experimental room. Their placement supports UV-C coverage near the room perimeter and upper-room region.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MEASUREMENT FACILITY">
      <data key="d0">MEASUREMENT FACILITY</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The full-scale controlled indoor experimental room used as the basis for the 3D model verification and validation. It was the space where pathogen-containing aerosols were released, dispersed, and measured under different mechanical ventilation and UV-C operating conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FANS">
      <data key="d0">FANS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Air-moving devices that were already running during the pre-measurement aerosol dispersion period. They promoted mixing of pathogen-containing aerosols throughout the room before mechanical ventilation and UV-C operation began.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_24,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_29,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UV-C SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">UV-C SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The upper-room ultraviolet germicidal irradiation system used in the experimental facility. It was switched on at t=0 with the mechanical ventilation and tested at 100%, 50%, and 0% operating power, although exact UV fluence rate distribution could not be calculated because luminaire photometric files and surface UV reflectivity were unavailable.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="0 ACH">
      <data key="d0">0 ACH</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">A mechanical ventilation setting of zero air changes per hour, representing the no-ventilation air-exchange condition tested in the measurement facility.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_24,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_30,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_31,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_35,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_36,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="3 ACH">
      <data key="d0">3 ACH</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">A mechanical ventilation setting of three air changes per hour used to evaluate the effect of moderate room air exchange on airborne aerosol removal and surviving fraction. | The reported high air exchange rate for the mouse-cage changing room, calculated from the supply airflow and room volume. The text notes that this high air exchange rate makes detectable far-UVC-related changes in ozone or particulate matter unlikely.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_24,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">36 ACH</data>
    </node>
    <node id="6 ACH">
      <data key="d0">6 ACH</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">A mechanical ventilation setting of six air changes per hour, the highest ventilation rate described for the experiments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_24,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MANNEQUIN OCCUPANT SURROGATE">
      <data key="d0">MANNEQUIN OCCUPANT SURROGATE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The occupant surrogate used as a spatial reference for aerosol release. Pathogen-containing aerosols were emitted near the mannequin's head, approximately 1 m above the floor.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.63</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPPER ROOM">
      <data key="d0">UPPER ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Upper portion of the room where the UV-C fluence-rate band is defined and where upper-room UV exposure is modeled for airborne microbial inactivation studies.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_25,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="30 CM UPPER-ROOM UV BAND">
      <data key="d0">30 CM UPPER-ROOM UV BAND</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A 30 cm wide upper-room subzone in which the spatially averaged UV-C fluence rate is specified as 0.42 W/m2 at full UV power or 0.2 W/m2 at half UV power.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UV-C LUMINAIRES">
      <data key="d0">UV-C LUMINAIRES</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Upper-room UV-C air-treatment fixtures operating at either full power, 100% UV, or half power, 50% UV. Their fluence field is represented using artificial uniform and nonuniform spatial distributions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNIFORM UPPER-ROOM UV FLUENCE DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">UNIFORM UPPER-ROOM UV FLUENCE DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Artificial spatial field with a uniform UV-C fluence rate of 0.42 W/m2 at full power or 0.2 W/m2 at half power inside the 30 cm upper-room band, and 0 W/m2 elsewhere in the room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NONUNIFORM LINE-SOURCE UV FLUENCE DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">NONUNIFORM LINE-SOURCE UV FLUENCE DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Artificial nonuniform UV-C fluence-rate field in which luminaires are idealized as line sources located at the room center and corners. The field is scaled to match the average fluence rate in the 30 cm upper-room band and set to 0 W/m2 elsewhere.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO FANS">
      <data key="d0">TWO FANS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Pair of fans modeled by imposing a volume flux on the side facing into the room and an equal-magnitude negative volume flux on the opposite side, producing internal air circulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_25,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_26,19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR INLET POINT">
      <data key="d0">AIR INLET POINT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Supply airflow path where mechanical ventilation is imposed as a volume flux entering the room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR EXHAUST POINTS">
      <data key="d0">AIR EXHAUST POINTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Outlet airflow paths where a static pressure boundary condition of 1 atm is applied to represent exhaust from the modeled room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STATIC PRESSURE BOUNDARY CONDITION OF 1 ATM">
      <data key="d0">STATIC PRESSURE BOUNDARY CONDITION OF 1 ATM</data>
      <data key="d1">PRESSURE_RELATIONSHIP</data>
      <data key="d2">Outlet pressure condition applied at the air exhaust points in the airflow simulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MODELED ROOM AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">MODELED ROOM AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airflow field produced by the combined effects of mechanical ventilation, exhaust pressure boundaries, fan-imposed volume fluxes, wall temperature, and mannequin heat input.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MANNEQUIN HEAT LOAD">
      <data key="d0">MANNEQUIN HEAT LOAD</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Simulated occupant thermal load represented by a 108 W heat source applied to the mannequin surface.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="0 ACH SCENARIO">
      <data key="d0">0 ACH SCENARIO</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">A zero-air-changes-per-hour condition in which mechanical ventilation is off. This condition is used for the 14-minute initial dispersion of particles before subsequent case analyses.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAN-DRIVEN ROOM AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">FAN-DRIVEN ROOM AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The airflow pattern in the room generated by the two fans. It governs aerosol-particle dispersion during the no-mechanical-ventilation condition.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAN THROUGH-FLOW PATH">
      <data key="d0">FAN THROUGH-FLOW PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled path through each fan, where particles entering a fan are ejected at a random location on the room-facing surface of the same fan to emulate particle motion inside the fan. | Air passage through the mask material. In the poorly fitted mask case, droplets can exit through this path in addition to escaping via leak zones.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">19fa3b4e-2c3d-44b1-ae20-59902abc601a,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">MASK THROUGH-FLOW PATH</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MANNEQUIN">
      <data key="d0">MANNEQUIN</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
