    <node id="ASYMPTOMATIC SPREADERS">
      <data key="d0">ASYMPTOMATIC SPREADERS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupant/source category capable of producing respiratory particles and viral-load droplets. The text indicates their particle number, particle size, and viral-load shedding can differ from symptomatic spreaders.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SYMPTOMATIC PEOPLE">
      <data key="d0">SYMPTOMATIC PEOPLE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupant category implied as producing higher viral-load drops and droplets than asymptomatic people, making them a higher-emission source for potential airborne SARS-CoV-2 transmission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ASYMPTOMATIC PEOPLE">
      <data key="d0">ASYMPTOMATIC PEOPLE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupant category explicitly referenced as producing lower viral-load drops and droplets than symptomatic or higher-shedding individuals, while still being relevant to possible COVID-19 transmission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUPER-SPREADERS">
      <data key="d0">SUPER-SPREADERS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">High-emission occupant category described as producing up to 17 times more particles during a cough compared with other individuals.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OCCUPANTS COUGHING">
      <data key="d0">OCCUPANTS COUGHING</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupants generating particles through coughing, with the text reporting approximately 100 to 1000 particles per second at a speed of around 10 m s−1.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OCCUPANTS SNEEZING">
      <data key="d0">OCCUPANTS SNEEZING</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupants generating particles through sneezing, with the text reporting approximately 1000 to 10,000 particles per second at speeds up to 20 m s−1.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OCCUPANTS BREATHING OR SPEAKING">
      <data key="d0">OCCUPANTS BREATHING OR SPEAKING</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupants generating droplets through cyclic respiratory activities such as breathing or speaking, reported as producing from at least 3000 up to 20,000 droplets per minute with diameters from 0.8 to 5.5 µm and up to 1 mm.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INHALABLE INFECTIOUS AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">INHALABLE INFECTIOUS AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Potentially infectious aerosol particles emitted by humans that can be inhaled by other people and contribute to virus transmission risk. | Airborne aerosol particles exhaled by infectious participants and dispersed through the arena. Their spatial distribution and exposure intensity are modeled under the different ventilation variants.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">EXHALED INFECTIOUS AEROSOLS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BREATHING AND SPEAKING EXHALATION AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">BREATHING AND SPEAKING EXHALATION AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Recurrent human exhalation airflow from breathing and speaking, described as a common source of inhalable aerosols with velocities on the order of 1 m/s.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COUGHING AND SNEEZING EXHALATION AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">COUGHING AND SNEEZING EXHALATION AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Intermittent human exhalation airflow from coughing or sneezing that can generate infectious aerosols, but is described as less important for contamination than breathing and speaking.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HUMAN OCCUPANCY WITH RESPIRATION AND SPEECH">
      <data key="d0">HUMAN OCCUPANCY WITH RESPIRATION AND SPEECH</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Presence of people who repeatedly breathe and speak, thereby creating recurring aerosol emissions in occupied spaces.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EVAPORATED SOLID AEROSOL NUCLEI">
      <data key="d0">EVAPORATED SOLID AEROSOL NUCLEI</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Residual non-evaporable solid nuclei formed after liquid aerosol particles evaporate below a threshold volume; these may remain relevant to airborne transmission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED AEROSOL DISPERSION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED AEROSOL DISPERSION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The spatial and flow behavior of aerosol particles emitted in human exhalation jets from breathing, speaking, coughing, or sneezing. | The respiratory emission pattern generated by the singer during the tasks, including visible aerosol from inhaled e-cigarette basic liquid and ballistic droplets larger than 5 μm observed in the dark chamber. | The observed behavior of smaller aerosol particles, approximately 0.3–10.0 μm in diameter, which can remain suspended, hover, and follow ambient air movement.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
      <data key="d6">EXHALED DROPLET AND AEROSOL DISPERSION PATTERN,SMALL AEROSOL DISPERSION PATTERN</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OUTDOOR AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">OUTDOOR AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Outdoor airflow is identified as a factor influencing respiratory particle evaporation through its effect on ambient vapour conditions around particles.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.58</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_11</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED SATURATED WARM AIR">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED SATURATED WARM AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Warm, saturated air exhaled from the nose and mouth during breathing. It entrains liquid respiratory particles and forms a near-field airflow path in front of individuals.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BUOYANT PLUME">
      <data key="d0">BUOYANT PLUME</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A buoyancy-driven plume formed by exhaled warm saturated air carrying liquid particles in front of the nose and mouth. The plume can reduce heat and mass transfer between particles and surrounding air, limiting evaporation and influencing near-field particle transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_12,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_21,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_22,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_44,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_47,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_48,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_63,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_69</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STRATIFIED ENVIRONMENT">
      <data key="d0">STRATIFIED ENVIRONMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A vertically stratified indoor air condition referenced in relation to exhaled droplet evaporation and dispersion. Stratification can alter plume movement, particle residence time, and droplet dispersion behavior.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_12,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_110</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOCAL VENTILATION AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">LOCAL VENTILATION AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Localized airflow generated by ventilation that can influence respiratory particle motion, including trajectory, suspension, and deposition. | Ventilation-driven component of the airflow inside the railway coach. In the anisothermal calculation, it interacts with thermal plumes generated by warm passenger manikins.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_12,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_110,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_111</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">COACH VENTILATION AIRFLOW</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE INFLUENZA VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE INFLUENZA VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">An airborne viral pathogen referenced in relation to humidity effects on survival, transmission, and incidence. Its airborne persistence is associated with respiratory droplet evaporation, ambient humidity, temperature, and airflow patterns. | Airborne respiratory virus for which airborne MNV is described as a conservative model when evaluating far-UVC germicidal efficacy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_12,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_111</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">AIRBORNE HUMAN INFLUENZA VIRUS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BREATHING INDIVIDUALS">
      <data key="d0">BREATHING INDIVIDUALS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupants who generate respiratory droplets through breathing; these droplets may remain suspended in indoor airflow after evaporation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.64</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POSSIBLY INFECTED MASK WEARER">
      <data key="d0">POSSIBLY INFECTED MASK WEARER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">An occupant who may be infected and who exhales respiratory emissions from the mouth and nose. The text identifies this person as the source whose bacteria, viruses, droplets, and fine aerosols may spread to the immediate surrounding environment, with surgical-mask performance limiting but not eliminating dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTED PEOPLE">
      <data key="d0">INFECTED PEOPLE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupants infected with respiratory disease who can shed airborne viruses in exhaled breath, coughs, or sneezes. The text discusses infected people as sources of airborne viral transmission that can be reduced by surgical masks, especially for larger respiratory drops.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SURROUNDING INDIVIDUALS">
      <data key="d0">SURROUNDING INDIVIDUALS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Nearby occupants located around a possibly infected mask wearer. The text frames these individuals as the population intended to be protected from respiratory droplets, bacteria, and viruses emitted by the wearer.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.62</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED BACTERIA AND VIRUSES">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED BACTERIA AND VIRUSES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Pathogens emitted from the respiratory tract of an infected or possibly infected person. The text states that surgical masks are intended to limit the spread of these exhaled bacteria and viruses into the immediate environment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE VIRUSES">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE VIRUSES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory viruses capable of airborne transmission through exhaled breath, droplets, and aerosols. The text notes that surgical masks can greatly limit transmission of such viruses by infected people, while being less effective for the finest aerosols smaller than 5 µm. | The airborne pathogenic target measured in the study. Far-UVC light was reported to produce major reductions in airborne virus levels in the occupied indoor location, although the measured inactivation is affected by airflow-related exposure uncertainty. | Airborne infectious agents referenced as the pandemic-related exposure hazard associated with singing. The study context treats singing as a high-risk activity because respiratory aerosols and droplets can transport airborne viruses.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_14,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_119</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff,ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
      <data key="d6">AIRBORNE VIRUSES</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFLUENZA">
      <data key="d0">INFLUENZA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A respiratory virus cited as an example of an airborne virus found in human exhaled breath. The text references influenza in the context of airborne viral transmission and the particle-size-dependent effect of surgical masks. | A specific airborne viral pathogen mentioned as susceptible to inactivation by far-UVC. | A respiratory viral pathogen cited as an example of viruses whose airborne transmission risk can be lowered by distancing and facial protection measures.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_14,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff,ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
      <data key="d6">INFLUENZA</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CORONAVIRUS">
      <data key="d0">CORONAVIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A respiratory virus category referenced in relation to COVID-19 and airborne-virus transmission. The text identifies coronavirus as one of the airborne viruses whose spread from infected people may be limited by surgical masks, particularly for larger droplets. | An airborne virus category referenced as another example pathogen for which murine norovirus may serve as a conservative surrogate in airborne virus reduction studies.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_14,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_25,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_122</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">CORONAVIRUS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY EXHALATION AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY EXHALATION AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Airflow generated during sneezing, coughing, or normal respiratory cycles; the text notes that surgical masks can reduce its velocity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK PERIMETER LEAKAGE AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">MASK PERIMETER LEAKAGE AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Air passing around the edges of a surgical or fabric mask through gaps between the wearer’s face and the mask, allowing aerosols to bypass filtration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNFILTERED MASK-EDGE AEROSOL LEAKAGE PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">UNFILTERED MASK-EDGE AEROSOL LEAKAGE PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Distribution pattern in which a substantial fraction of aerosol-laden air bypasses the mask filter through face-mask gaps; cited studies report significant leakage, including over 70% unfiltered passage for some fabric masks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIRECT MOUTH OR NOSE RESPIRATORY JET">
      <data key="d0">DIRECT MOUTH OR NOSE RESPIRATORY JET</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The primary exhaled airflow path emitted directly from the mouth or nose during breathing, coughing, or sneezing, carrying aerosols outward from the wearer.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK PERIMETER LEAK JETS">
      <data key="d0">MASK PERIMETER LEAK JETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Turbulent, directional airflow leaks around the perimeter of a mask caused by inhalation and exhalation pumping effects; these leaks redirect aerosols away from the direct mouth-or-nose jet path.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRANSVERSE AEROSOL DISPERSION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">TRANSVERSE AEROSOL DISPERSION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A lateral aerosol-spreading pattern increased by turbulent mask-edge leak jets, dispersing aerosols in transverse directions rather than primarily forward from the mouth or nose.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIRECT FORWARD RESPIRATORY PLUME PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">DIRECT FORWARD RESPIRATORY PLUME PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The forward-directed aerosol plume pattern associated with breath, cough, or sneeze airflow emitted directly from the mouth or nose.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.69</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED AIRFLOW FROM MASKED WEARER">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED AIRFLOW FROM MASKED WEARER</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Air expelled during breathing or coughing while a mask is worn; its direction and range are modified by the mask type and by leakage around the filtering area.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRFLOW THROUGH MASK FILTERING MATERIAL">
      <data key="d0">AIRFLOW THROUGH MASK FILTERING MATERIAL</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The intended air path through the filtering portion of a mask, where filtration occurs before air exits the mask.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LEAK AIRFLOW AROUND MASK FILTERING PART">
      <data key="d0">LEAK AIRFLOW AROUND MASK FILTERING PART</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Air that bypasses the filtering material by flowing through leaks around the mask or seal; leakage may account for up to two thirds of total airflow and was simulated with leak velocities of approximately 0.2–0.4 m/s.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COUGH-GENERATED DROPLET-LADEN AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">COUGH-GENERATED DROPLET-LADEN AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">A cyclical cough airflow evaluated over five seconds, with a maximum expectoration velocity of 5 m/s and carrying respiratory droplets through and around a surgical mask.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY DROPLETS FROM MASKED COUGH">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY DROPLETS FROM MASKED COUGH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Droplet particles released during coughing, modeled as 1,008 droplets per cough cycle with particle diameters between 1 and 300 micrometers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK-MODIFIED EXHALED AIRFLOW PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">MASK-MODIFIED EXHALED AIRFLOW PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The distribution pattern of exhaled air after interaction with a mask, including altered direction, reduced or redirected range, and partial bypass through leaks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LEAKAGE-DOMINATED BYPASS PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">LEAKAGE-DOMINATED BYPASS PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">An airflow distribution pattern in which a substantial portion of exhaled air escapes through leak locations instead of passing through the mask filter.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK-FACE LEAKAGE AIR PATHS">
      <data key="d0">MASK-FACE LEAKAGE AIR PATHS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Spaces between the wearer’s face and the mask that allow air, droplets, and incoming aerosols to bypass the mask material. Simulations identified main leak locations and estimated airflow velocities through these leaks at approximately 0.2–0.4 m s−1.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THROUGH-MASK AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">THROUGH-MASK AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Air and aerosol flow route passing directly through the mask filtration material. The text reports that a proportion of aerosols can penetrate through the mask depending on mask design, number of layers, filtration material, and imposed airflow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INCOMING RESPIRATORY AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">INCOMING RESPIRATORY AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Aerosol particles approaching the mask from outside and potentially penetrating inside the mask either through the mask material or through mask-face leakage gaps. Reported penetration ranges include 20–80% for aerosols less than 1 µm or between 1 and 3 µm, depending on mask and airflow conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE SARS-COV-2 AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE SARS-COV-2 AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Pathogen-bearing aerosols referenced in the context of studies on mask-wearing, inhalability, and deposition. The cited CFD example involved a humanoid manikin inhaling aerosols through a perfectly fitted surgical mask.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_19,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_20,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_119,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_120</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK LEAKAGE DISTRIBUTION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">MASK LEAKAGE DISTRIBUTION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Distribution of droplets and aerosols among different outcomes: blocked by the mask, passing through the mask material, or escaping through leakage paths. The text notes that prior work estimated these proportions but did not relate particle size to leakage behavior. | Air distribution pattern in the leaky-mask case where the same total respiratory flow rate is split among mask and leak inlet surfaces according to available surface areas under mass conservation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">MASK LEAK FLOW DISTRIBUTION PATTERN</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK-ALTERED NASAL AND ORAL AIRFLOW PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">MASK-ALTERED NASAL AND ORAL AIRFLOW PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airflow pattern near the nose and mouth produced by mask wearing. The text reports lower air velocities, shallower particle penetration into the respiratory tract, and increased aerosol deposition in the nose.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK PERIMETER LEAK AIR PATHS">
      <data key="d0">MASK PERIMETER LEAK AIR PATHS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Leakage pathways around the perimeter of a mask on a humanoid manikin during breathing. Leaks were reported mainly at the nose, less near the cheeks, and least near the chin. | Leakage routes around the perimeter of the poorly fitting mask through which droplets escape. The text highlights these paths because droplets originating from them follow notably different trajectories in the isothermal and anisothermal cases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">MASK PERIMETER LEAKAGE PATHS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK PERIMETER LEAK DISTRIBUTION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">MASK PERIMETER LEAK DISTRIBUTION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Observed distribution of mask leakage around the mask perimeter: approximately 35–50% at the nose, 20–25% near the cheeks, and 6–12% near the chin.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HUMAN OCCUPANT">
      <data key="d0">HUMAN OCCUPANT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">An individual human source of heat, exhaled air, and expectorated respiratory particles. The person’s uncovered head and respiratory emissions contribute to the formation of a buoyant plume and influence local airflow. | Presence of people in indoor spaces, creating the occupied setting in which airborne infectious disease transmission is a concern. The excerpt does not quantify the number of occupants.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">HUMAN OCCUPANCY</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPECTORATED RESPIRATORY PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">EXPECTORATED RESPIRATORY PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory particles emitted by a human during exhalation or expectoration. Although the passage does not identify a specific pathogen, these particles are relevant as potential airborne infectious carriers and may be entrained into the buoyant plume.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THERMALLY ALTERED NEAR-PERSON AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">THERMALLY ALTERED NEAR-PERSON AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Local airflow modified by thermal effects from warm exhaled air and the warm human body. The text notes that experiments with real human volunteers, wearing masks or not, demonstrated changes in airflow caused by these thermal effects.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.64</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PATHOGENIC BIOLOGICAL AGENTS">
      <data key="d0">PATHOGENIC BIOLOGICAL AGENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Pathogenic biological agents are referenced as infectious agents carried by particles expectorated by humans and studied through CFD simulations of dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.79</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY JETS">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY JETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory jets are directional flows of exhaled air and particles that can carry aerosols away from a person. The cited work visualizes how face masks obstruct or redirect these jets.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_31,ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_44,ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SURGICAL MASK LEAKS">
      <data key="d0">SURGICAL MASK LEAKS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Surgical mask leaks are airflow escape paths through or around a surgical mask, allowing exhaled air and potentially particles to bypass mask obstruction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED-PARTICLE DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED-PARTICLE DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Exhaled-particle dispersion describes the spatial spread of particles produced by humans, including particles potentially loaded with infectious agents, and is examined experimentally and through CFD simulations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FACE-TO-FACE BREATHING OR TALKING OCCUPANTS">
      <data key="d0">FACE-TO-FACE BREATHING OR TALKING OCCUPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">This occupancy condition represents two people positioned face to face while breathing or talking, a situation used to examine respiratory plume behavior and potential exposure paths.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.67</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VARIOUS HOSPITAL ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">VARIOUS HOSPITAL ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Clinical indoor environments cited as locations where simulations of virion-containing particle dispersion have been performed; these spaces are relevant to ventilation effectiveness and interpersonal contamination risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION DEVICES">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION DEVICES</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation-related systems or devices discussed as interventions evaluated by CFD studies for their effectiveness in limiting transmission of COVID-19 and dispersal of virion-containing particles.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INDOOR PARTICLE DISPERSION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">INDOOR PARTICLE DISPERSION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne transport and dispersion behavior of pathogen-laden droplets or virion-containing particles in indoor environments, as analyzed in CFD simulations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INTERPERSONAL INDOOR OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">INTERPERSONAL INDOOR OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Presence and proximity of people in indoor premises, referenced through social distancing and interpersonal contamination concerns in environments where airborne or droplet transmission can occur.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY PARTICLE AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY PARTICLE AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory particle air path refers to the modeled route followed by particles expelled from the mouth into the surrounding air during coughs, sneezes, or conversation. The path was evaluated over distances including at least 2.5 m and up to or beyond a 6 m simulation domain under certain airflow conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STILL AMBIENT AIR">
      <data key="d0">STILL AMBIENT AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Still ambient air is the modeled air distribution condition in which particles expelled during respiratory activities move without imposed background airflow. It was used in simulations with initial respiratory-jet velocities of 1, 5, or 10 m s−1.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AMBIENT AIRFLOW AT 0, 1, OR 4 M S−1">
      <data key="d0">AMBIENT AIRFLOW AT 0, 1, OR 4 M S−1</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Ambient airflow at 0, 1, or 4 m s−1 describes the background airflow conditions used to simulate the dispersion of particles emitted during coughing. Under the strongest airflow condition, the smallest particles remained suspended 6 m beyond their point of origin.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HUMAN PRESENCE AND RESPIRATORY ACTIVITY">
      <data key="d0">HUMAN PRESENCE AND RESPIRATORY ACTIVITY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Human presence and respiratory activity represents occupants as sources of coughs, sneezes, and conversation, as well as physical bodies that can influence airflow and particle dispersion. The text notes that some simulations ignored human presence and its effect on airflow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGLE UNFURNISHED AND VENTILATED OFFICE-REPRESENTATIVE ROOM">
      <data key="d0">SINGLE UNFURNISHED AND VENTILATED OFFICE-REPRESENTATIVE ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled indoor room used in the cited CFD studies. Although representative of an office rather than a hospital, it is the defined occupied ventilation zone where droplet, particle, and infectious-agent transport were simulated.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR-CONDITIONING UNIT RECIRCULATING ROOM AIR">
      <data key="d0">AIR-CONDITIONING UNIT RECIRCULATING ROOM AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The air-conditioning unit in Al-Baghdadi et al.'s office simulation that recirculates the same air inside the room. Its airflow was reported to increase particle spread and potentially create a virion-laden indoor environment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR-CONDITIONING SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">AIR-CONDITIONING SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation or cooling systems whose placement in the office-type room was examined in simulations. Their positioning can generate airflow patterns that are either beneficial or harmful for airborne particle transport. | Sophisticated air-conditioning systems listed as one of the ventilation methods used in railway coaches. These systems can condition and circulate air in the occupied coach environment. | Normally functioning air-conditioning systems provide the primary driving airflow for cabin ventilation and for the operation of purification devices, especially the CP generator.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_25,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
      <data key="d6">AIR CONDITIONING SYSTEMS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXTRACTION AND AIR FILTRATION OR GERMICIDAL AIR-TREATMENT SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">EXTRACTION AND AIR FILTRATION OR GERMICIDAL AIR-TREATMENT SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Recommended additions to existing ventilation systems to reduce recirculated infectious particles. The text states that ventilation systems should include extraction, air filtration, and/or germicidal processes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RECIRCULATING INDOOR AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">RECIRCULATING INDOOR AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">An airflow distribution pattern produced when the air-conditioning unit recirculates the same indoor air. This pattern can keep respiratory particles suspended and redistribute them through the occupied room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BENEFICIAL OR HARMFUL AIRFLOW PATTERNS">
      <data key="d0">BENEFICIAL OR HARMFUL AIRFLOW PATTERNS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Air-movement patterns created by the placement of air-conditioning systems, open windows, and doors. The simulations indicated that such patterns can either mitigate or worsen airborne particle transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_25,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTIOUS AGENT CARRIED BY DROPS AND DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">INFECTIOUS AGENT CARRIED BY DROPS AND DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The airborne infectious hazard transported by respiratory drops, droplets, and particles in the simulated room. It represents the pathogen-bearing material whose spread limits and pathways were evaluated.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGLE PERSON COUGHING OR SNEEZING">
      <data key="d0">SINGLE PERSON COUGHING OR SNEEZING</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A simulated source occupancy condition in which one unmasked occupant releases respiratory droplets and particles by coughing or sneezing. This condition provides the emission source for infectious-particle dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE OR TWO OCCUPANTS">
      <data key="d0">ONE OR TWO OCCUPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The occupancy condition studied in an office-type room by Mills and Hamad. The number and placement of occupants influence exposure pathways and airflow-mediated transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.73</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_25,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNMASKED HUMANOID MANIKINS">
      <data key="d0">UNMASKED HUMANOID MANIKINS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Simplified simulated human occupants used in the CFD domains, generally represented by cylindrical or parallelepipedic bodies and heads. The text specifies that none of the manikins wore masks, making emitted particles unobstructed by face coverings.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="E-TYPE ROOM OCCUPIED BY ONE OR TWO OCCUPANTS">
      <data key="d0">E-TYPE ROOM OCCUPIED BY ONE OR TWO OCCUPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A modeled indoor room used for airflow and airborne-particle transport simulations. Although not explicitly a hospital room, it is treated as the relevant occupied zone in which ventilation layout, air-conditioning placement, window and door openings, and exposure between occupants are evaluated.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGHER VENTILATION RATE">
      <data key="d0">HIGHER VENTILATION RATE</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">A qualitative increased ventilation or air-change condition considered in the simulations. The text emphasizes that a higher ventilation rate alone does not necessarily improve particle removal, because the resulting flow pattern and exhaust pathway also matter.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CEILING-TO-SIDE WALL VENTILATION DESIGN">
      <data key="d0">CEILING-TO-SIDE WALL VENTILATION DESIGN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A ventilation distribution arrangement in which airflow is configured from the ceiling toward a side-wall pathway or exhaust. The cited work suggests this design may perform better than a ceiling-to-ceiling configuration for both standing and sitting occupants.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CEILING-TO-CEILING CONFIGURATION">
      <data key="d0">CEILING-TO-CEILING CONFIGURATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A ventilation distribution arrangement using ceiling-based air delivery and ceiling-based removal or return. It is used as a comparator and is described as potentially less favorable than ceiling-to-side wall ventilation for particle removal and exposure control.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRION-LADEN PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">VIRION-LADEN PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Virus-containing airborne particles whose room-scale dissemination is affected by airflow patterns, ventilation configuration, air-conditioning placement, and openings such as windows and doors.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_26,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COVID-19 VECTORS">
      <data key="d0">COVID-19 VECTORS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Pathogen-bearing respiratory emissions associated with COVID-19 transmission. The cited simulations examine their release during respiratory mechanisms such as coughing, sneezing, normal speaking, and loud speaking.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COUGH AND SNEEZE PARTICLES OF 70 TO 80 MICROMETERS">
      <data key="d0">COUGH AND SNEEZE PARTICLES OF 70 TO 80 MICROMETERS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Larger respiratory particles emitted during discrete events such as coughs and sneezes in the Mariam et al. simulations. These particles are contrasted with smaller speaking-generated particles and rapidly settling drops.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPEAKING-GENERATED PARTICLES OF 1 AND 5 MICROMETERS">
      <data key="d0">SPEAKING-GENERATED PARTICLES OF 1 AND 5 MICROMETERS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Small respiratory particles generated during continuous speaking events, including normal and loud speech at different flow rates. Their small size makes them relevant to airborne persistence and source-to-receptor transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO HUMANOID MANIKINS SEATED OR STANDING FACE TO FACE">
      <data key="d0">TWO HUMANOID MANIKINS SEATED OR STANDING FACE TO FACE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A modeled source-receptor occupancy arrangement in which two humanoid manikins are positioned face to face, either seated or standing. This setup is used to evaluate exposure during coughs, sneezes, and speaking events.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO REALISTIC FACE-TO-FACE MANIKINS WITH ONE INFECTED">
      <data key="d0">TWO REALISTIC FACE-TO-FACE MANIKINS WITH ONE INFECTED</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A short-term exposure scenario with two realistic manikins facing each other, one acting as the infected emitter. This configuration supports analysis of direct airborne transmission between a source and a receptor.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TYPICAL VENTILATED OFFICE">
      <data key="d0">TYPICAL VENTILATED OFFICE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The indoor ventilated office used as the modeled room environment for close-proximity airborne-transmission studies. Although it is not a hospital space, it is the relevant enclosed zone for airflow, ventilation, respiratory emissions, and pathogen-dispersion analysis.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FACE-TO-FACE INFECTED-SUSCEPTIBLE OCCUPANT PAIR">
      <data key="d0">FACE-TO-FACE INFECTED-SUSCEPTIBLE OCCUPANT PAIR</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A two-occupant close-proximity condition in which one person or manikin is infected and positioned face to face with a susceptible counterpart. This occupancy configuration drives short-range exposure through breathing, coughing, or talking emissions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRACER-GAS APPROACH">
      <data key="d0">TRACER-GAS APPROACH</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">A tracer-gas method used as a surrogate for exhaled droplet nuclei to study airborne transport and dispersion in the built environment. It was used instead of explicitly modeling discrete aerosol phases in the close-proximity breathing scenario.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DILUTION VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">DILUTION VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A room-scale mixing ventilation pattern intended to dilute airborne contaminants. In the described studies, it had limited effectiveness against direct short-range airborne transmission but influenced conditions for indirect transmission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIRECT EXHALATION JET">
      <data key="d0">DIRECT EXHALATION JET</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A short-range respiratory airflow jet carrying exhaled aerosols from an infected source toward a nearby face-to-face receptor. It was identified as a key mechanism explaining why direct airborne transmission predominated in close-proximity exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COUGH JET">
      <data key="d0">COUGH JET</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A high-momentum respiratory airflow generated during coughing. In the CFD office scenario, it transported virion-containing particles and slowed the upward buoyant plume generated by the human body.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_27,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TALKING EXHALATION FLOW">
      <data key="d0">TALKING EXHALATION FLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A lower-velocity airflow through the mouth during speaking. Unlike the cough jet, this speaking flow did not produce the same observed slowing of the upward human-body thermal plume.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPWARD HUMAN-BODY BUOYANT PLUME">
      <data key="d0">UPWARD HUMAN-BODY BUOYANT PLUME</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A thermally driven upward airflow generated by the heat of seated occupants or humanoid manikins. The plume interacts with respiratory emissions and was slowed by the cough jet in the modeled office.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTITION-BLOCKED LARGE-PARTICLE PATHWAY">
      <data key="d0">PARTITION-BLOCKED LARGE-PARTICLE PATHWAY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">An airflow-and-particle transport condition created by room partitions or physical barriers that captured particles larger than approximately 50 µm, thereby limiting their direct spread from the source.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM-WIDE SMALL-PARTICLE DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">ROOM-WIDE SMALL-PARTICLE DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The dispersal pattern in which smaller particles, especially those below approximately 50 µm and not captured by barriers, spread throughout the room and contribute to broader indirect airborne exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR CONDITIONING">
      <data key="d0">AIR CONDITIONING</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The classroom HVAC system in the Abuhegazy et al. simulation. It conditions and moves air within the classroom, influencing transport, removal, and deposition of emitted particles. | Air-conditioning system referenced in a cited COVID-19 restaurant outbreak report from Guangzhou, China. It is an HVAC-related unit that can influence indoor airflow and airborne exposure patterns, though the passage does not specify ACH, pressure relationships, duct paths, or a measured distribution pattern.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_28,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_125</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
      <data key="d6">AIR CONDITIONING</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXTRACTION VENTS">
      <data key="d0">EXTRACTION VENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation air-removal pathways in the classroom. Particles smaller than 15 µm mostly exited the room through these vents, indicating their role in clearing fine airborne particles.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_28,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_89</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOW-VELOCITY SPEAKING EXHALATION">
      <data key="d0">LOW-VELOCITY SPEAKING EXHALATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A lower-momentum exhalation pattern through the mouth during speaking. Unlike the cough jet, it was not observed to slow the upward buoyant plume generated by the human body.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPWARD BUOYANT PLUME GENERATED BY THE HUMAN BODY">
      <data key="d0">UPWARD BUOYANT PLUME GENERATED BY THE HUMAN BODY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A thermally driven upward airflow pattern around an occupant's body. The text states that this plume was slowed by a cough jet but not by the lower-velocity airflow associated with speaking.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTICLE DISTRIBUTION AND DEPOSITION FROM 1 TO 50 ΜM">
      <data key="d0">PARTICLE DISTRIBUTION AND DEPOSITION FROM 1 TO 50 ΜM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated airborne transport and surface deposition behavior of particles with diameters from 1 to 50 µm in an air-conditioned classroom. Smaller particles tended to leave via extraction vents, while larger particles tended to settle on accessible surfaces, including glass barriers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY DISEASE AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY DISEASE AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The infectious aerosol contamination context motivating the classroom studies, including COVID-19-relevant aerosol transport. These aerosols represent the airborne infection risk associated with occupants emitting respiratory particles. | Infectious respiratory agents transported by droplets in the coach air. Mask wearing strongly limits contamination by these agents but does not entirely prevent infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">RESPIRATORY DISEASE AGENTS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STUDENTS AND THEIR TEACHER">
      <data key="d0">STUDENTS AND THEIR TEACHER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The classroom occupant group identified as being at high risk of respiratory-disease contamination. Their co-presence creates opportunities for emission, exposure, and transmission of respiratory aerosols.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE PARTICLE-EMITTING STUDENT">
      <data key="d0">ONE PARTICLE-EMITTING STUDENT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The single student assumed to emit particles in the Abuhegazy et al. classroom simulation. This occupant acts as the modeled source of particles, although the text notes that the duration of the release was not specified.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INLET IN A WALL CLOSE TO THE CEILING">
      <data key="d0">INLET IN A WALL CLOSE TO THE CEILING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation supply air path through which air enters the classroom. The numerical model varied the entering airflow velocity at this inlet across 3, 5, and 7 m/s, making it a key driver of particle dispersion and removal.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPEN DOOR OF THE CLASSROOM">
      <data key="d0">OPEN DOOR OF THE CLASSROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The outlet air path through which classroom air exits. Together with the ceiling-adjacent wall inlet, it defines the main modeled ventilation route from supply entry to exhaust through the open door.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION AIRFLOW AT 3, 5, AND 7 M/S">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION AIRFLOW AT 3, 5, AND 7 M/S</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled classroom airflow condition produced by supply velocities of 3, 5, and 7 m/s. The study found that increasing velocity generally shortened the time required to reach negligible particle concentration, but also produced counter-intuitive changes in the number of small suspended particles between 5 and 7 m/s.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTITIONED CLASSROOM AIRFLOW CONFIGURATION">
      <data key="d0">PARTITIONED CLASSROOM AIRFLOW CONFIGURATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The airflow and particle-dispersion configuration when transparent solid barriers are installed in front of seats. This configuration altered particle transport and was associated with lower average particle concentration at seats and a shorter time to negligible concentration compared with the no-partition case.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNPARTITIONED CLASSROOM AIRFLOW CONFIGURATION">
      <data key="d0">UNPARTITIONED CLASSROOM AIRFLOW CONFIGURATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The airflow and particle-dispersion configuration in the classroom without transparent barriers in front of seats. In this case, seats closest to the infected person had the highest average particle concentration, and the time required to reach negligible particle concentration was longer than in the partitioned case.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COUGH-GENERATED PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">COUGH-GENERATED PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The emitted infectious particle surrogate used to evaluate airborne dispersion from the coughing teacher. Particle diameters of 0.15, 1, 10, 50, 100, and 150 µm were modeled to assess concentration patterns and ventilation-driven removal. | Cough-produced particles described as containing coronavirus SARS-CoV-2. They represent the infectious airborne exposure vehicle considered in the air-curtain protection study.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">COUGH-GENERATED FLUID PARTICLES</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TEACHER WHO COUGHED IN FRONT OF A CLASS">
      <data key="d0">TEACHER WHO COUGHED IN FRONT OF A CLASS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The infected occupant source in the numerical model. The teacher’s cough releases particles in front of the class, creating the source term for evaluating how airflow velocity and transparent partitions influence exposure at classroom seats.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLASSROOM OCCUPANTS AND SEATED STUDENTS">
      <data key="d0">CLASSROOM OCCUPANTS AND SEATED STUDENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The exposed occupancy in the classroom, represented by individuals and seats located at varying distances from the coughing teacher. Their placement affects exposure because obstacle shape and proximity to the source influence particle concentration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRANSPARENT CABINS AROUND STUDENTS">
      <data key="d0">TRANSPARENT CABINS AROUND STUDENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Transparent student enclosures placed inside the classroom to alter local airflow, limit lateral particle spread, and support upward extraction or filtration of air emitted near students.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SURROUNDING CLASSROOM OCCUPIED AREA">
      <data key="d0">SURROUNDING CLASSROOM OCCUPIED AREA</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The classroom area outside the transparent cabins, occupied by other students or class members and potentially protected when contaminated cabin air is exhausted upward or filtered before release.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLASSROOMS WITHOUT PRE-INSTALLED VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">CLASSROOMS WITHOUT PRE-INSTALLED VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Typical classroom environments noted by Jain et al. as lacking built-in ventilation systems despite being occupied by many breathing students and a speaking teacher.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.58</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR-CONDITIONING CONFIGURATION">
      <data key="d0">AIR-CONDITIONING CONFIGURATION</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled air-handling setup optimized in the CFD study, including supply and exhaust arrangements intended to introduce fresh air and remove stale air carrying virion-loaded particles.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HEPA FILTER ATOP CUBICLES">
      <data key="d0">HEPA FILTER ATOP CUBICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">A high-efficiency filtration component installed above transparent cubicles to remove particles from air leaving the cubicle space before that air reaches the surrounding classroom.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CUBICLE EXHAUST FAN">
      <data key="d0">CUBICLE EXHAUST FAN</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">An airflow-driving component that sucks particle-laden air from the cubicle region; higher fan suction was associated with fewer particles remaining in the classroom.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LARGE AIR PURIFIERS">
      <data key="d0">LARGE AIR PURIFIERS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Portable or supplemental air-cleaning devices considered by Jain et al. as classroom interventions affecting aerosol or particle transport and dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.79</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_30,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_124</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SIDE-WALL FRESH AIR SUPPLY AT 1 M HEIGHT">
      <data key="d0">SIDE-WALL FRESH AIR SUPPLY AT 1 M HEIGHT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The optimized supply-air path in which fresh air enters the classroom through side-wall openings located approximately one meter above the floor.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CEILING STALE AIR EXHAUST">
      <data key="d0">CEILING STALE AIR EXHAUST</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The exhaust-air path through which stale air carrying virion-loaded particles exits upward through the classroom ceiling.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CEILING EXIT HOLES">
      <data key="d0">CEILING EXIT HOLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Ceiling openings that provide an upward outlet for particle-laden air, helping direct particles out of the occupied classroom or cubicle region.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.77</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPEN-ROOF CUBICLE AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">OPEN-ROOF CUBICLE AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">A cubicle configuration with an open top or roof, allowing air and particles to move upward from the cabin region toward exhaust or filtration pathways.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HOURLY AIR EXCHANGE VOLUME IN THE CLASSROOM">
      <data key="d0">HOURLY AIR EXCHANGE VOLUME IN THE CLASSROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The classroom ventilation exchange metric reported as inversely correlated with the number of airborne particles; greater hourly air exchange volume corresponds to lower particle presence in the airflow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SIDE-WALL SUPPLY AND CEILING-EXHAUST VENTILATION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">SIDE-WALL SUPPLY AND CEILING-EXHAUST VENTILATION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The optimal airflow pattern identified in the CFD experiments, with fresh air supplied low from side walls and contaminated stale air removed upward through the ceiling.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPWARD CUBICLE PARTICLE REMOVAL PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">UPWARD CUBICLE PARTICLE REMOVAL PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The particle movement pattern in which contaminated air is drawn upward from transparent cabins and routed out through ceiling exit holes or through filters, reducing lateral spread in the classroom.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRION-LOADED RESPIRATORY PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">VIRION-LOADED RESPIRATORY PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne respiratory particles carrying coronavirus virions, generated by infected occupants through breathing or sneezing and transported by classroom airflow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTED STUDENT BREATHING OR SNEEZING">
      <data key="d0">INFECTED STUDENT BREATHING OR SNEEZING</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled infectious source condition in which one infected student emits virion-loaded respiratory particles into the classroom by breathing or sneezing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MANY STUDENTS BREATHING AND TEACHER SPEAKING LOUDLY">
      <data key="d0">MANY STUDENTS BREATHING AND TEACHER SPEAKING LOUDLY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A high-emission classroom occupancy condition described by Jain et al., involving numerous students breathing while a teacher speaks loudly, increasing respiratory aerosol generation if infectious individuals are present.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR PURIFIER INSTALLED IN THE CLASSROOM">
      <data key="d0">AIR PURIFIER INSTALLED IN THE CLASSROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">A localized air-cleaning unit installed in the classroom. Its placement, volumetric flow rate, and removal efficiency were varied in simulations, and its location strongly influenced particle dissemination except for the occupant seated very close to the infected student.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR PURIFIER VOLUMETRIC FLOW RATE">
      <data key="d0">AIR PURIFIER VOLUMETRIC FLOW RATE</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The air-cleaning flow parameter of the classroom air purifier. It is typed as an ACH-rate-like ventilation parameter because it controls the amount of room air processed by the purifier and therefore affects airborne particle removal and dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HALF CLASS CAPACITY">
      <data key="d0">HALF CLASS CAPACITY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A reduced classroom occupancy condition created by limiting attendance to half capacity. It represents the physical-distancing strategy described as effective for reducing infection risk in the modeled classroom.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FULL CLASS CAPACITY">
      <data key="d0">FULL CLASS CAPACITY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A full-occupancy classroom condition used for comparison with half-capacity operation. Under mask-wearing assumptions, modeled infection risk was reported to be comparable between half and full capacity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STUDENT ASSUMED TO BE INFECTED">
      <data key="d0">STUDENT ASSUMED TO BE INFECTED</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The infectious classroom occupant who acts as the source of emitted virulent particles in the simulation scenario. Nearby occupants experience stronger source-proximity effects.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PERSON SITTING NEXT TO THE STUDENT ASSUMED TO BE INFECTED">
      <data key="d0">PERSON SITTING NEXT TO THE STUDENT ASSUMED TO BE INFECTED</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A receptor occupant seated adjacent to the infected student. This person’s exposure was less affected by air-purifier location than that of other occupants, indicating the importance of near-source exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.73</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK-WEARING STUDENTS">
      <data key="d0">MASK-WEARING STUDENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A classroom occupancy condition in which students wear respiratory masks. The cited study did not explicitly model mask geometry but incorporated mask effectiveness during inhalation when estimating infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRULENT PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">VIRULENT PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Pathogen-bearing airborne particles emitted by the infected classroom occupant. Their simulated transport and dispersion determine exposure and modeled infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLASSROOM PARTICLE TRANSPORT AND DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">CLASSROOM PARTICLE TRANSPORT AND DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated spatial movement and spread of virulent particles within the classroom. This distribution pattern depends on occupancy, occupant locations, air-purifier placement, purifier flow rate, and purifier efficiency.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESTAURANT IN GUANGZHOU">
      <data key="d0">RESTAURANT IN GUANGZHOU</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">An occupied indoor restaurant in Guangzhou, China, modeled as an enclosed ventilation zone in a CFD study of an observed COVID-19 outbreak. It is typed as a zone because the schema lacks a general non-hospital indoor-zone category. | Indoor occupied zone referenced in the outbreak-associated air-conditioning article. Although it is a restaurant rather than a hospital space, it is typed as HOSPITAL_ZONE because this schema uses that type for indoor zones served or affected by HVAC systems. The excerpt does not define room boundaries, adjacency, occupancy, or ventilation parameters.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
      <data key="d6">RESTAURANT IN GUANGZHOU</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESTAURANT VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">RESTAURANT VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation system or ventilation-driven airflow conditions in the Guangzhou restaurant. The CFD study examined how ventilation affected the airborne transmission environment during the outbreak.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE PATHOGENS IN THE RESTAURANT">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE PATHOGENS IN THE RESTAURANT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Infectious airborne agents modeled in the Guangzhou restaurant outbreak simulation. Their spatial and temporal distribution was simulated to assess airborne transmission patterns.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESTAURANT SPATIAL AND TEMPORAL PATHOGEN DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">RESTAURANT SPATIAL AND TEMPORAL PATHOGEN DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled time-varying and location-dependent distribution of airborne pathogens in the Guangzhou restaurant, generated using CFD to represent outbreak-related airborne transmission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESTAURANT DINING ROOM">
      <data key="d0">RESTAURANT DINING ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled indoor occupied zone in the CFD study. Although it is a restaurant rather than a healthcare space, it is the enclosed ventilated area where aerosol transport, pathogen concentration, table-level exposure, and infection-risk trends were evaluated. | The restaurant is the indoor occupied zone in the cited COVID-19 outbreak. Although not a hospital space, it is represented as a zone under the available schema because the valid entity types do not include a generic indoor-zone category.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">RESTAURANT DINING AREA</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SURROUNDING TABLE AREAS">
      <data key="d0">SURROUNDING TABLE AREAS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupied sub-zones around the infected customer where simulated infection-risk trends were compared with observed infection rates reported for different tables in the real restaurant outbreak.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUPPLIED FRESH AIR">
      <data key="d0">SUPPLIED FRESH AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Outdoor-air component introduced into the total air blown into the restaurant. Increasing this air path diluted and removed airborne pathogen mass, reducing the simulated accumulated pathogen burden.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RECIRCULATED AIR">
      <data key="d0">RECIRCULATED AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor air reused within the ventilated restaurant space. The text identifies recirculation as a condition that increased pathogen concentration and therefore infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RECIRCULATION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">RECIRCULATION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Air distribution condition in which air is circulated back through the occupied space. In the simulations, recirculation increased the airborne pathogen concentration and raised infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POOR VENTILATION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">POOR VENTILATION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Unfavorable ventilation condition with insufficient dilution or removal of contaminated air. The text states that poor ventilation increased pathogen concentration and infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FRESH-AIR FRACTION OF 10%, 50%, OR 100%">
      <data key="d0">FRESH-AIR FRACTION OF 10%, 50%, OR 100%</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation dilution parameter describing the percentage of the total supplied air that is fresh outdoor air. It is not a literal air-changes-per-hour value, but within the valid schema it functions as the ventilation-rate parameter controlling dilution of airborne pathogen mass.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2-CONTAINING AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2-CONTAINING AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Infectious respiratory aerosols emitted by the infected customer during breathing. These aerosols represent the airborne pathogen burden whose concentration, accumulated mass, and infection-risk implications were simulated.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTED CUSTOMER">
      <data key="d0">INFECTED CUSTOMER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Source occupant whose breathing generated infectious aerosols in the restaurant simulation. The infected customer determined the primary emission location and drove exposure patterns at surrounding tables.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="METRO STATION">
      <data key="d0">METRO STATION</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilated semi-confined public transport space studied using CFD to assess airborne particle spread from an infected passenger. Although not a hospital area, it is typed as a zone because the schema provides HOSPITAL_ZONE as the available spatial-zone category.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PLATFORM">
      <data key="d0">PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Metro-station subzone where the simplified breathing humanoid manikin representing an infected passenger was placed in some simulation cases. | The passenger area outside the vehicle door. Bioaerosols escaping from the compartment can reach this area, creating potential exposure risk for passengers during subway travel.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
      <data key="d6">PLATFORM</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ESCALATOR">
      <data key="d0">ESCALATOR</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Metro-station subzone where the infected-passenger manikin was alternatively positioned to evaluate particle spread under different source locations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CROSS-PLATFORM PASSAGE CORRIDORS">
      <data key="d0">CROSS-PLATFORM PASSAGE CORRIDORS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Station areas identified by CFD as having some of the highest aerosol particle concentration levels, associated with recirculating eddies and air stagnation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUPPLY VENTILATION CONDITIONS">
      <data key="d0">SUPPLY VENTILATION CONDITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation configurations applied in the metro-station simulations. Two conditions were defined by different air exchange rates and affected aerosol particle concentration and travel time.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RECIRCULATING EDDIES">
      <data key="d0">RECIRCULATING EDDIES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Localized airflow recirculation patterns identified by CFD as contributing to elevated particle concentrations in parts of the metro station, particularly cross-platform passage corridors.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR STAGNATION">
      <data key="d0">AIR STAGNATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Low-movement airflow condition associated with poor local particle clearance and high aerosol concentration zones in the metro station.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRAIN PISTON EFFECT">
      <data key="d0">TRAIN PISTON EFFECT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Train-induced airflow effect that was removed from the simulated metro-station scenario by assuming full-height screen doors.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.62</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTICLES CARRYING INFECTIOUS AGENTS">
      <data key="d0">PARTICLES CARRYING INFECTIOUS AGENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Broader category of infectious airborne particles discussed in relation to transport and dispersion in ventilated indoor spaces, including vehicle interiors.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VEHICLE INTERIOR SPACE">
      <data key="d0">VEHICLE INTERIOR SPACE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilated interior environment of vehicles mentioned as another setting studied for transport and dispersion of particles carrying infectious agents, particularly SARS-CoV-2. Typed as a zone under the available schema.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CITY BUS INTERIOR">
      <data key="d0">CITY BUS INTERIOR</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The enclosed, occupied indoor environment modeled in the CFD study. Although it is not a hospital space, it is typed as a zone because it is the air-handled compartment where ventilation, turbulent circulation, and respiratory-particle dispersion were evaluated.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DRIVER'S LOCATION">
      <data key="d0">DRIVER'S LOCATION</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The driver-area zone within the bus, served by a dedicated defrost ducting and heating system. It is also one of the modeled particle-emission locations when the driver breathes or talks without a mask.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PASSENGER CABIN">
      <data key="d0">PASSENGER CABIN</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The main occupied passenger area of the bus, served by an HVAC system that recirculates cabin air and injects fresh air for heating or cooling. It is the primary zone where passenger-emitted particles disperse under ventilation-driven flow patterns.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO HVAC SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">TWO HVAC SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The two heating, ventilation, and air-conditioning systems in the bus: one serving the driver area for visibility and heating, and one serving the passenger cabin through recirculation and fresh-air injection. Their operating conditions strongly shape bus air circulation, turbulence levels, and particle dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DEFROST DUCTING AND HEATING SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">DEFROST DUCTING AND HEATING SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The HVAC subsystem dedicated to maintaining visibility and providing heating at the driver's location. It creates localized airflow near a possible respiratory-particle source.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PASSENGER CABIN HVAC SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">PASSENGER CABIN HVAC SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The HVAC subsystem responsible for recirculating air and injecting fresh air into the passenger cabin to heat or cool the occupied space. It is central to the cabin's air circulation and particle-transport behavior.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HEPA FILTRATION">
      <data key="d0">HEPA FILTRATION</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">A potential air-cleaning intervention mentioned as suitable for evaluation using CFD when particles are recirculated in the bus. The text does not state that it was installed, only that simulations could assess its effectiveness. | Filtration-based air-treatment approach referenced for controlling infectious airborne disease transmission in indoor environments. It is associated with risk reduction potential as well as operational cost considerations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
      <data key="d6">HVAC FILTRATION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UV DISINFECTION">
      <data key="d0">UV DISINFECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">A potential air-disinfection intervention mentioned as suitable for evaluation when particles are recirculated through bus airflow systems. It is discussed as a possible CFD-assessed control measure rather than a modeled installed component.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.64</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DEFROST DUCTING">
      <data key="d0">DEFROST DUCTING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The ducted airflow path associated with the driver-area defrost and heating system. It delivers air near the driver's location and contributes to local flow structures.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RECIRCULATING AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">RECIRCULATING AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The cabin-air recirculation pathway created by the passenger cabin HVAC system. It can redistribute emitted particles through the bus and is the flow condition under which HEPA filtration and UV disinfection were noted as potentially valuable to evaluate.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FRESH AIR INJECTION">
      <data key="d0">FRESH AIR INJECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The outside-air supply component injected by the passenger cabin HVAC system for heating or cooling. It modifies ventilation conditions and can affect dilution and circulation in the passenger cabin.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.71</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TURBULENT FLOW">
      <data key="d0">TURBULENT FLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The turbulent air movement predicted in the bus using the LES AVBP solver. This Eulerian flow field was used for Lagrangian particle tracking and is central to particle-dispersion predictions. | More chaotic airflow condition presumed for room-scale chambers relative to the laminar aerosol chamber; may change aerosol mixing, residence time, and UV exposure conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_71</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">TURBULENT AIRFLOW</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION-GENERATED FLOW PATTERNS">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION-GENERATED FLOW PATTERNS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The airflow patterns generated by the bus ventilation systems under different operating conditions. The text identifies these patterns as decisive for particle trajectories and concentrations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR CIRCULATION IN THE BUS">
      <data key="d0">AIR CIRCULATION IN THE BUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The overall movement of air throughout the bus interior. Duchaine et al. highlighted that ventilation conditions drastically affect this circulation and the associated turbulence levels.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TURBULENCE LEVELS">
      <data key="d0">TURBULENCE LEVELS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The intensity of turbulent fluctuations in the bus airflow, reported as strongly affected by ventilation conditions. These turbulence levels influence particle dispersion and mixing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY PARTICLES OF 0.1-1000 MICROMETERS">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY PARTICLES OF 0.1-1000 MICROMETERS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory particles released by modeled occupants while breathing or talking. The text treats them as airborne contaminant particles rather than explicitly viable pathogens, but they are the contaminant surrogate tracked for dispersion, trajectories, and concentrations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTICLE TRAJECTORIES AND CONCENTRATIONS">
      <data key="d0">PARTICLE TRAJECTORIES AND CONCENTRATIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled spatial movement paths and concentration distributions of respiratory particles in the bus. These outcomes are controlled by emitter position, ventilation operating conditions, and turbulence.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FOUR PASSENGERS AND DRIVER">
      <data key="d0">FOUR PASSENGERS AND DRIVER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled bus occupancy load consisting of four passengers and the driver, none wearing masks. These occupants are possible respiratory-particle emitters during breathing or talking.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PASSENGERS IN MIDDLE OR REAR OF BUS">
      <data key="d0">PASSENGERS IN MIDDLE OR REAR OF BUS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Location-specific passenger emitter scenarios in which passengers seated in the middle or rear of the bus release respiratory particles. Their positions affect dispersion because particle transport depends on the source location relative to ventilation-generated flow patterns.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DRIVER AS PARTICLE EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">DRIVER AS PARTICLE EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The driver source scenario in which the driver releases respiratory particles while breathing or talking. This source is located in the driver area served by the defrost ducting and heating system.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INTERIOR SPACE OF A METRO COACH">
      <data key="d0">INTERIOR SPACE OF A METRO COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The life-size metro coach interior represented as the modeled occupied air-handled zone. It is described as geometrically and operationally complex because of high passenger density, seated and standing occupants, and variable operating conditions that influence airflow and pathogen-laden particle dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="METRO COACH VENTILATION STRATEGIES">
      <data key="d0">METRO COACH VENTILATION STRATEGIES</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation approaches considered for the metro coach with the objective of reducing respiratory disease transmission risk by influencing airflow, particle transport, and diffusion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION SYSTEMS PRODUCING LOW AIR VELOCITIES">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION SYSTEMS PRODUCING LOW AIR VELOCITIES</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Low-air-speed ventilation systems discussed as conditions under which buoyancy from occupants and thermal boundary conditions can become especially important for airflow and contaminant transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TURBULENT AIRFLOW IN THE METRO COACH">
      <data key="d0">TURBULENT AIRFLOW IN THE METRO COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated turbulent airflow field in the metro coach, modeled by Wu et al. with a k-epsilon RNG approach. It controls the transport and diffusion of expiratory particles.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AVERAGE SPEED AND TURBULENCE FIELDS">
      <data key="d0">AVERAGE SPEED AND TURBULENCE FIELDS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airflow quantities criticized as being obtainable with the less time-consuming RANS formalism rather than requiring high-fidelity LES when only mean velocity and turbulence fields are analyzed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BUOYANT PLUME PHENOMENA">
      <data key="d0">BUOYANT PLUME PHENOMENA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Buoyancy-driven airflow arising from heat released by people and affected by wall and window temperatures. The text states that these effects should be studied under low-velocity ventilation conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPIRATORY BREATHING AND COUGHING JETS">
      <data key="d0">EXPIRATORY BREATHING AND COUGHING JETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The respiratory release paths through which Lagrangian particles are emitted during breathing and coughing, with modeled release velocities of 1 or 10 m s−1.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPIRATORY PARTICLE SIZE SCENARIOS OF 10 50 OR 100 MICROMETERS">
      <data key="d0">EXPIRATORY PARTICLE SIZE SCENARIOS OF 10 50 OR 100 MICROMETERS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled pathogen-laden particle size cases of 10, 50, and 100 µm, investigated as parameters affecting particle transport, diffusion, and potential exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PASSENGER DENSITY OF 2 OR 4 PER SQUARE METER">
      <data key="d0">PASSENGER DENSITY OF 2 OR 4 PER SQUARE METER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Two modeled passenger-density scenarios used to evaluate how crowding affects airflow obstruction, particle transport, diffusion, and respiratory infection-risk conditions in the metro coach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="28 SEATED PASSENGERS AND 68 OR 124 STANDING PASSENGERS">
      <data key="d0">28 SEATED PASSENGERS AND 68 OR 124 STANDING PASSENGERS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Specific simulated occupancy configurations in the metro coach. These configurations define the number and arrangement of seated and standing passengers that shape airflow pathways and exposure conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="METRO COACH">
      <data key="d0">METRO COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">An enclosed passenger-compartment zone used in a CFD study of respiratory-droplet dispersion under ventilation and crowding conditions. In the schema it is typed as a zone, although it is a transit coach rather than a hospital space.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH-SPEED TRAIN COACH">
      <data key="d0">HIGH-SPEED TRAIN COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled passenger-coach zone in Xu et al.'s CFD study, containing simplified seated and standing passenger manikins and an infected seated source located at the front, middle, or rear of the coach. | The enclosed passenger carriage or coach environment in which ventilation supply locations, exhaust locations, airflow patterns, particle dispersion, and infection-transmission control are evaluated. It is typed as a zone because the schema provides HOSPITAL_ZONE as the available enclosed-space category.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">HIGH-SPEED TRAIN CABIN</data>
    </node>
    <node id="METRO COACH VENTILATION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">METRO COACH VENTILATION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation system serving the metro coach. Its ability to eliminate droplets emitted by the infected manikin varied with the source position inside the coach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH-SPEED TRAIN VENTILATION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">HIGH-SPEED TRAIN VENTILATION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The train-coach ventilation system investigated by Xu et al. for its influence on flow-field structure, particle dissemination, capture, retention, and removal efficiency.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FRESH AIR SUPPLY">
      <data key="d0">FRESH AIR SUPPLY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The supply-air path through which fresh ventilating air entered the high-speed train coach. Changes to this supplied airflow altered internal vortices and particle behavior.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TURBULENT AIRFLOW FIELD">
      <data key="d0">TURBULENT AIRFLOW FIELD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated turbulent air movement in the high-speed train coach, calculated with ANSYS Fluent using the realizable k-epsilon model. This flow field governed Lagrangian trajectories of cough particles.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LARGE VORTICES">
      <data key="d0">LARGE VORTICES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Large recirculating airflow structures in the train coach. When air supply was doubled, these vortices became more stable and contributed to stronger particle capture and retention by the airflow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_36,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PASSENGER DENSITY OF 2 OR 4 PER M2">
      <data key="d0">PASSENGER DENSITY OF 2 OR 4 PER M2</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled metro-coach passenger-density condition. Higher density increased the number of droplets intercepted or trapped by passenger bodies, supporting the recommendation to limit occupant numbers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEATED AND STANDING PASSENGER LOAD">
      <data key="d0">SEATED AND STANDING PASSENGER LOAD</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled passenger load consisting of 28 seated passengers and either 68 or 124 standing passengers. The manikins were simplified and did not wear masks, and their bodies affected droplet interception in the coach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.81</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PASSENGER BODY DROPLET TRAPPING">
      <data key="d0">PASSENGER BODY DROPLET TRAPPING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory droplets intercepted or trapped by passenger bodies under crowded coach conditions. This represents the portion of emitted droplets removed from free airborne transport through contact with occupant bodies.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="10-ΜM DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">10-ΜM DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Small respiratory droplets emitted by the infected manikin or infected passenger. They evaporated rapidly, remained suspended for long periods, and spread widely through the coach, making them strongly influenced by airflow and ventilation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="50-ΜM COUGH PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">50-ΜM COUGH PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Intermediate-size cough particles released by the infected seated passenger in the high-speed train coach simulation. Their trajectories were calculated with a Lagrangian particle approach to evaluate ventilation-driven dissemination and removal.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="100-ΜM DROPS">
      <data key="d0">100-ΜM DROPS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Large respiratory drops emitted by the infected manikin or passenger. In the metro-coach study, 100-µm drops settled onto the coach floor before evaporating, indicating limited long-range airborne persistence compared with smaller droplets.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="KOREAN HIGH-SPEED TRAIN (KTX) COACH">
      <data key="d0">KOREAN HIGH-SPEED TRAIN (KTX) COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled occupied train-coach compartment used as the airflow-controlled zone for evaluating turbulent airflow, respiratory-particle trajectories, and ventilation interventions relevant to infection-risk reduction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FRONT AREA OF THE COACH">
      <data key="d0">FRONT AREA OF THE COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A spatial sub-zone of the KTX coach where the reported infection risk was lower than in the rear area under the studied ventilation configuration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="REAR AREA OF THE COACH">
      <data key="d0">REAR AREA OF THE COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A spatial sub-zone of the KTX coach where the modeled infection risk was higher than in the front area under the same ventilation configuration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VERTICAL DROP AIRFLOW (VDA) SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">VERTICAL DROP AIRFLOW (VDA) SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">A proposed ventilation system for the train coach using ceiling and floor inlets and outlets near seats to create vertical airflow, restrict flow circulation, and reduce particle dissemination.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CEILING AND FLOOR INLETS AND OUTLETS AT EACH SEAT">
      <data key="d0">CEILING AND FLOOR INLETS AND OUTLETS AT EACH SEAT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The air-supply and exhaust pathways forming the VDA system. These openings route air vertically between the ceiling and floor around passenger seats.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VERTICAL DROP AIRFLOW (VDA)">
      <data key="d0">VERTICAL DROP AIRFLOW (VDA)</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The vertical airflow distribution pattern generated by the VDA system, intended to limit recirculation and mitigate respiratory-particle transport inside the coach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DOUBLED AIR SUPPLY">
      <data key="d0">DOUBLED AIR SUPPLY</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">A higher ventilation-rate condition in which the supplied air was doubled. Although no numeric ACH value is given, it represents increased airflow affecting vortex stability, particle capture, and particle retention.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY PARTICLES FROM 3 TO 750 ΜM">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY PARTICLES FROM 3 TO 750 ΜM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled respiratory particles used as surrogates for infectious particle transport. Their Lagrangian trajectories were simulated to assess particle dissemination and infection-risk mitigation in the coach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HUMANOID PASSENGER MANIKIN">
      <data key="d0">HUMANOID PASSENGER MANIKIN</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A detailed modeled passenger source considered either without a mask or with a well-fitted porous mask. The manikin represents occupant presence and the source context for respiratory-particle trajectory simulations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PUBLIC RAILWAY TRANSPORT COACH">
      <data key="d0">PUBLIC RAILWAY TRANSPORT COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The semi-confined, ventilated passenger coach used as the modeled indoor zone for airborne particle dispersion and infection-risk assessment. Although it is not a hospital room, it is the enclosed occupied space to which the ventilation and airborne-transmission concepts are applied.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COACH VENTILATION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">COACH VENTILATION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation system considered in the train-coach simulations. The text states that ventilation and room geometry are important determinants of the dissemination of virion-laden particles and that the system reduced both particle number and particle transmission in the coach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISSEMINATION OF VIRION-LADEN PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">DISSEMINATION OF VIRION-LADEN PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The spatial transport and spread of infectious particles within the train coach, influenced by ventilation, coach geometry, passenger/manikin configuration, and mask fit or leakage. It is investigated through CFD-based simulation rather than tracer-gas measurement.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DROPS AND DROPLETS FROM HUMAN RESPIRATORY EVENTS">
      <data key="d0">DROPS AND DROPLETS FROM HUMAN RESPIRATORY EVENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory particles produced by humans that can carry viruses such as SARS-CoV-2. They form the particle phase modeled in the airborne-transmission simulations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HUMANOID MANIKINS">
      <data key="d0">HUMANOID MANIKINS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Digital human representations used in the CFD simulations to populate the coach. The text emphasizes that realistic manikins, including whether they wear masks and whether masks leak, are important for credible airflow and particle-dispersion modeling.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_38,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_50,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_90,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_99</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONTAMINATED MANIKIN">
      <data key="d0">CONTAMINATED MANIKIN</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Simulated infected occupant used as the respiratory emission source. The manikin breathes and releases droplets that may carry SARS-CoV-2, enabling evaluation of pathogen-laden droplet dispersion around the body and in a railway-coach scenario.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OTHER PASSENGERS">
      <data key="d0">OTHER PASSENGERS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Additional occupants included in the railway-coach simulation scenario. They provide an occupied exposure context around the contaminated manikin, although the excerpt does not state that they emit pathogens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARALLELEPIPEDIC SIMULATION DOMAIN">
      <data key="d0">PARALLELEPIPEDIC SIMULATION DOMAIN</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Controlled computational enclosure representing a still atmosphere around the head and bust of the manikin. The domain is described as 1.7 m long, 1.4 m wide, and 0.7 m high and is used to isolate and evaluate thermal phenomena in droplet dispersion. | The simulated room-like air volume where temperature fields and micrometric droplet distributions are evaluated. Droplets that reach its boundary surfaces leave the modeled domain and are removed from the computation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">PARALLELEPIPEDIC COMPUTATIONAL DOMAIN</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ISOTHERMAL FLOW">
      <data key="d0">ISOTHERMAL FLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Earlier airflow-modeling assumption in which thermal effects were neglected. It served as the baseline condition in previous simulations of respiratory particle dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ANISOTHERMAL FLOW">
      <data key="d0">ANISOTHERMAL FLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airflow condition that includes thermal effects. It is used in the present modeling approach to capture temperature-driven buoyancy and its effect on turbulent flow and respiratory droplet dispersion. | Airflow regime in which temperature gradients are explicitly considered, causing density variation and buoyancy effects that alter particle and droplet dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">NON-ISOTHERMAL FLOWS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="3D TURBULENT FLOW AND DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">3D TURBULENT FLOW AND DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Three-dimensional computational airflow and droplet-transport behavior considered in the simulations. It represents how turbulent motion distributes droplets produced by breathing around the manikin and within the modeled environment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BUOYANT PLUMES">
      <data key="d0">BUOYANT PLUMES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Thermally generated upward airflow structures identified as influencing the trajectories and spatial distributions of emitted respiratory droplets.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STILL ATMOSPHERE">
      <data key="d0">STILL ATMOSPHERE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Initial controlled ambient-air condition around the manikin’s head and bust, with no imposed background motion. It is used to evaluate thermal phenomena in a simplified simulation domain.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_39,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CFD SIMULATION DOMAIN">
      <data key="d0">CFD SIMULATION DOMAIN</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The enclosed computational domain used to simulate particle dispersion in a still atmosphere. It is 1.7 m long, 1.4 m wide, and 0.7 m high, sized according to CFD practice to reduce boundary effects around the humanoid manikin.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INDIVIDUAL CARRYING PATHOGENIC BIOLOGICAL AGENTS">
      <data key="d0">INDIVIDUAL CARRYING PATHOGENIC BIOLOGICAL AGENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A single humanoid manikin representing an individual who emits particles carrying pathogenic biological agents. The individual is modeled under three mask-wearing configurations: no mask, perfectly worn mask, and leaky mask.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTICLES CARRYING SARS-COV-2 VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">PARTICLES CARRYING SARS-COV-2 VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Pathogen-laden particles produced by the individual and used to study airborne dispersion. The text references particles carrying the SARS-CoV-2 virus and emphasizes that their distribution changes with mask use and thermal effects.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK-DEPENDENT PARTICLE DISPERSION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">MASK-DEPENDENT PARTICLE DISPERSION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The particle dispersion behavior associated with the three mask configurations shown in the manikin meshes: no mask, perfectly worn mask, and leaky mask. The text states that dispersion differs significantly depending on whether the person wears a mask properly, improperly, or not at all.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THERMALLY DRIVEN AIRFLOW AROUND AND ABOVE THE INDIVIDUAL">
      <data key="d0">THERMALLY DRIVEN AIRFLOW AROUND AND ABOVE THE INDIVIDUAL</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Thermal effects forming around and above the individual, likely corresponding to buoyant airflow generated near the human body. The text states that these thermal effects very strongly influence the distribution of emitted particles.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BREATHING MANIKIN">
      <data key="d0">BREATHING MANIKIN</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A simulated human occupant limited to the head and bust. It provides both respiratory flow through breathing cycles and thermal loading through body heat, making it the source of droplet dissemination and buoyancy-driven airflow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_41,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_83</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NO-MASK BREATHING CONDITION">
      <data key="d0">NO-MASK BREATHING CONDITION</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulation case in which the breathing manikin wears no mask. Under this condition, exhaled air and micrometric droplets are released directly into the computational domain without mask filtration or redirection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WARM EXHALED AIR JET">
      <data key="d0">WARM EXHALED AIR JET</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The respiratory airflow path emitted by the manikin during exhalation. It is warmer than the ambient air and initially carries micrometric droplets before buoyancy and free convection draw the particles upward.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BUOYANT PLUME ABOVE THE MANIKIN'S HEAD">
      <data key="d0">BUOYANT PLUME ABOVE THE MANIKIN'S HEAD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A thermally driven upward airflow pattern generated by heat from the manikin. It forms above the manikin's head and becomes established from approximately t = 6.7 s, transporting droplets toward the upper part of the computational domain.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FREE CONVECTION">
      <data key="d0">FREE CONVECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A buoyancy-driven air movement mechanism caused by warmer exhaled and body-heated air rising relative to ambient air. It pulls droplets upward and strongly influences the resulting particle distribution.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_41,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_69</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TEMPERATURE FIELD">
      <data key="d0">TEMPERATURE FIELD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated spatial distribution of air temperature, shown in degrees Celsius. It reveals the warmer exhaled jet and the thermal plume that drive buoyancy-influenced droplet transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.81</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPPER-PART DROPLET DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">UPPER-PART DROPLET DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The observed final droplet distribution pattern at t = 120 s, where droplets are concentrated in the upper portion of the computational domain because buoyant air carries them upward.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MICROMETRIC DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">MICROMETRIC DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory-sized airborne droplets released during breathing and used as the particle contaminant surrogate in the simulation. Their motion is governed by the exhaled jet, free convection, and the buoyant thermal plume.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2-LADEN RESPIRATORY DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2-LADEN RESPIRATORY DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory droplets or particles referenced as potential carriers of the SARS-CoV-2 virus. The excerpt discusses their simulated dispersion from a manikin under a no-mask condition and compares how thermal effects influence their movement. | Pathogen-containing respiratory aerosols implied by references to COVID-19 spread, coronavirus pandemic conditions, and airborne transmission in classrooms. This replaces broader disease labels such as COVID-19 with the airborne infectious aerosol hazard relevant to ventilation modeling. | Virus-containing exhaled respiratory aerosols emitted by infectious participants and transported through the arena air. These aerosols represent the modeled airborne infection hazard used to estimate spectator virus exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_42,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">SARS-COV-2-LADEN RESPIRATORY AEROSOLS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NO-MASK RESPIRATORY EXHALATION JET">
      <data key="d0">NO-MASK RESPIRATORY EXHALATION JET</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The airflow path generated by the manikin without a mask, carrying droplets into the surrounding space during the simulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ANISOTHERMAL AIRFLOW AND DROPLET DISPERSION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">ANISOTHERMAL AIRFLOW AND DROPLET DISPERSION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The present-study airflow pattern that includes thermal effects, represented through temperature fields, velocity fields, and droplet locations over time. | The airflow and droplet movement pattern from the present anisothermal simulation, where thermal effects are included. In this case, droplets are carried upward regardless of their origin, producing a significantly different distribution by the end of the simulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">ANISOTHERMAL DROPLET DISPERSION PATTERN</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ISOTHERMAL AIRFLOW AND DROPLET DISPERSION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">ISOTHERMAL AIRFLOW AND DROPLET DISPERSION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The comparison airflow pattern from the previous simulation in which thermal effects were not included, while other assumptions were kept identical. | Modeled airflow and droplet transport condition including thermal effects, such as the influence of a warmer humanoid manikin on local air motion and droplet dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">ANISOTHERMAL AIRFLOW AND DROPLET DISPERSION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NO MASK MANIKIN EXHALATION">
      <data key="d0">NO MASK MANIKIN EXHALATION</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Case #1 simulation condition in which a manikin exhales without a mask. The manikin acts as the occupant/source generating exhaled airflow and droplets used to compare isothermal and anisothermal transport behavior.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED AIR JET NEAR MANIKIN MOUTH">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED AIR JET NEAR MANIKIN MOUTH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Initial airflow path emitted from the manikin's mouth. The text states that this near-mouth jet appears similar in both isothermal and anisothermal simulations before droplet trajectories diverge farther from the source.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Exhaled droplets visualized in the simulation as airborne contaminant/pathogen proxies. Their trajectories differ markedly depending on whether thermal effects are included.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ISOTHERMAL DROPLET DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">ISOTHERMAL DROPLET DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Distribution pattern from the isothermal simulation, where thermal effects are not included. Droplets follow the exhaled jet near the mouth but are later projected toward the bottom of the simulation domain and leave it.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ANISOTHERMAL DROPLET DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">ANISOTHERMAL DROPLET DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Distribution pattern from the anisothermal simulation, where thermal effects are included. Because the exhaled air is warmer than the surrounding environment, droplets are convected upward toward the top of the simulation domain.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DOWNWARD ISOTHERMAL DROPLET PATH">
      <data key="d0">DOWNWARD ISOTHERMAL DROPLET PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Droplet transport path observed in the isothermal case after the near-field region, in which droplets move toward the lower part of the simulation domain and depart from it.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPWARD ANISOTHERMAL BUOYANT PATH">
      <data key="d0">UPWARD ANISOTHERMAL BUOYANT PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Thermally driven upward transport path observed in the anisothermal case, where warmer exhaled air convects droplets toward the top of the simulation domain.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SIMULATION DOMAIN">
      <data key="d0">SIMULATION DOMAIN</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled indoor air volume in which the manikin exhalation, velocity field, and droplet positions are evaluated. The text describes droplets moving either toward the bottom or top of this domain depending on thermal modeling.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED AIR JET">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED AIR JET</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The respiratory airflow generated by the manikin during the five-second breathing cycle. The fitted mask drastically reduces the velocity of this jet and redirects warm exhaled air upward, contributing to the buoyant plume.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_44,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPWARD EVACUATION PATH">
      <data key="d0">UPWARD EVACUATION PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The upward route followed by droplets as they are entrained by the buoyant plume and evacuated through the top of the simulation domain by the end of the 120 s simulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RE-ASPIRATION PATH">
      <data key="d0">RE-ASPIRATION PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">A local airflow path by which some droplets are drawn back toward the manikin and removed from the computation, as noted for both the unmasked and masked cases.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGLE MANIKIN OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">SINGLE MANIKIN OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A simulated occupant represented by a manikin. The manikin is the source and partial re-aspiration sink for droplets in the computational domain.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.62</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MANIKIN OCCUPANCY SOURCE">
      <data key="d0">MANIKIN OCCUPANCY SOURCE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A single modeled occupant/manikin that exhales air and droplets into the coach. The simulations compare dispersion behavior from this source under different mask and thermal conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_46</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The flow path followed by exhaled air and entrained droplets from the manikin into the coach interior. Its behavior differs between isothermal and anisothermal simulations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_46</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ISOTHERMAL AIRFLOW DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">ISOTHERMAL AIRFLOW DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated airflow and droplet dispersion pattern when thermal effects are not taken into account. Compared with the anisothermal case, it produces significantly different droplet distributions by the end of the simulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_46</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ANISOTHERMAL FREE-CONVECTION DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">ANISOTHERMAL FREE-CONVECTION DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The thermally influenced airflow and droplet dispersion pattern in which free convection lifts warm air and droplets upward. The effect is more pronounced when exhalation velocity is reduced, such as with a perfectly fitting mask, with upward velocities above the manikin's head around 0.2–0.3 m/s.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_46</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="JET OF EXHALED AIR">
      <data key="d0">JET OF EXHALED AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Main respiratory airflow pattern emitted by the manikin during the five-second respiratory cycle. In masked cases, the mask reduces the jet velocity and redirects part of the warm exhaled air upward, contributing to plume formation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_47,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LEAK ZONES">
      <data key="d0">LEAK ZONES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Unsealed airflow paths caused by poor mask fit at the nose, cheeks, and chin. These paths allow exhaled air and droplets to bypass the mask seal.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="JETS OF AIR FROM LEAK AREAS">
      <data key="d0">JETS OF AIR FROM LEAK AREAS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Localized airflow jets emerging from mask leak areas around the nose, cheeks, and chin in the poorly fitted mask case. These jets provide additional airflow routes for droplet escape.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TOP EVACUATION PATH">
      <data key="d0">TOP EVACUATION PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Upper outlet or evacuation route of the simulation domain through which droplets are removed after being lifted by the buoyant plume.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPWARD DROPLET DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">UPWARD DROPLET DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Observed droplet movement pattern in which droplets are efficiently carried upward by the buoyant plume and evacuated through the top of the simulation domain.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CASE #3 SIMULATION DOMAIN">
      <data key="d0">CASE #3 SIMULATION DOMAIN</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled indoor space containing the manikin in the poorly fitting mask scenario. Droplets are tracked within this domain until they either leave through the top boundary or are removed from the computation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK LEAKAGE PATHS AROUND MANIKIN MOUTH">
      <data key="d0">MASK LEAKAGE PATHS AROUND MANIKIN MOUTH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Leakage pathways created by the poorly fitting mask around the manikin’s mouth. These leaks increase the number of droplets entering the simulation domain compared with the better-filtered case #2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TOP DOMAIN EXIT">
      <data key="d0">TOP DOMAIN EXIT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The upper boundary of the simulation domain through which droplets are evacuated after being carried upward by the buoyant plume.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2-LADEN DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2-LADEN DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory droplets or particles described as carrying the SARS-CoV-2 virus in the modeled dispersion study. Their trajectories and final spatial distributions differ substantially depending on whether thermal effects are included in the simulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_49</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ISOLATED HUMANOID MANIKIN">
      <data key="d0">ISOLATED HUMANOID MANIKIN</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Single modeled human surrogate used in the numerical study to demonstrate that the CFD model accounts for airflow and droplet dispersion near and above an individual warmer than the ambient environment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_50</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ISOTHERMAL AIRFLOW AND DROPLET DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">ISOTHERMAL AIRFLOW AND DROPLET DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled airflow and droplet transport condition in which temperature-driven buoyancy effects are not considered. It is compared against anisothermal results in the figures for droplet movement and velocity modulus.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_50</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRFLOW AND DROPLET DISPERSION NEAR AND ABOVE A WARMER INDIVIDUAL">
      <data key="d0">AIRFLOW AND DROPLET DISPERSION NEAR AND ABOVE A WARMER INDIVIDUAL</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">CFD-characterized air movement and respiratory droplet transport around a humanoid manikin that is warmer than its surroundings, capturing local thermal-plume-driven effects on particle dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_50</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2-BEARING DROPLETS AND DROPS">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2-BEARING DROPLETS AND DROPS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory droplets and drops carrying the SARS-CoV-2 virus whose dispersion is modeled in the railway coach and around humanoid manikins. | Virus-carrying respiratory particles whose dispersion in the railway coach is the modeled airborne-pathogen transport problem referenced by the cited simulation studies.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_50</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">SARS-COV-2-LADEN DROPLETS AND DROPS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTED PASSENGERS">
      <data key="d0">INFECTED PASSENGERS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Infected passengers are the source occupants who emit airborne particles potentially carrying SARS-CoV-2. The text notes that they may or may not wear facial masks according to local rules.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_51,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_93</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MILLIONS OF COMMUTERS">
      <data key="d0">MILLIONS OF COMMUTERS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Millions of commuters use regional rail and metro networks daily, creating frequent close contact among occupants and increasing the public-health relevance of airborne pathogen spread in transport spaces.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_51</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEMI-CONFINED VENTILATED RAILWAY COACH">
      <data key="d0">SEMI-CONFINED VENTILATED RAILWAY COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The railway coach is the enclosed occupied zone where airborne pathogen dispersion is studied. Although it is not a hospital space, it is typed as a zone because the valid schema uses HOSPITAL_ZONE for enclosed spaces served by airflow or ventilation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_51</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="REGIONAL RAIL AND METRO NETWORKS">
      <data key="d0">REGIONAL RAIL AND METRO NETWORKS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Regional rail and urban metro networks are the broader transport environments that bring large numbers of commuters into daily contact. They are represented as occupied transport zones within the available schema.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.63</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_51</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE DISPERSION IN THE VENTILATED COACH">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE DISPERSION IN THE VENTILATED COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The text focuses on how airborne pathogen-containing particles can spread through the semi-confined, ventilated space of a railway coach, corresponding to an air distribution or dispersion pattern.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_51</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RAILWAY PASSENGER COACH CFD DOMAIN">
      <data key="d0">RAILWAY PASSENGER COACH CFD DOMAIN</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Three-dimensional digital twin of a typical commuter railway passenger coach used as the CFD computational domain. The coach geometry was generated from high-precision train data and converted into a triangulated STL surface mesh; its dimensions are 15.5 m long, 2.5 m wide, and 2.6 m high. Although this is a transport setting rather than a hospital, it is typed as HOSPITAL_ZONE because it represents the modeled indoor occupied zone.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPARTMENTS 1 AND 3">
      <data key="d0">COMPARTMENTS 1 AND 3</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupied passenger compartments within the railway coach CFD geometry. These compartments contain humanoid manikins representing seated or present passengers and therefore form the primary occupied zones for dispersion analysis.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPARTMENT 2 BOARDING AREA">
      <data key="d0">COMPARTMENT 2 BOARDING AREA</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Intermediate compartment of the railway coach from which people get into and out of the train. It functions as the boarding and alighting area between the occupied passenger compartments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HUMANOID PASSENGER MANIKINS">
      <data key="d0">HUMANOID PASSENGER MANIKINS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Full-body humanoid manikins integrated into the 3D digital twin of the railway coach to represent passengers. Their presence defines the occupancy load in compartments 1 and 3 and affects the modeled flow obstruction and potential respiratory emission locations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASKED AND UNMASKED PASSENGER CONFIGURATIONS">
      <data key="d0">MASKED AND UNMASKED PASSENGER CONFIGURATIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupant source configurations in which manikin heads may be masked or non-masked. This configuration is relevant to respiratory particle release and to prior CFD studies evaluating the impact of mask wearing on particle dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.73</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CFD RESPIRATORY PARTICLE DISPERSION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">CFD RESPIRATORY PARTICLE DISPERSION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airflow-associated dispersion pattern computed in the railway coach CFD model for droplets, drops, or particles released by occupants. It represents how respiratory material may spread through the coach geometry rather than a ventilation rate or pressure condition.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2-BEARING RESPIRATORY PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2-BEARING RESPIRATORY PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Virus-carrying respiratory droplets, drops, or particles referenced from prior railway-coach CFD studies of SARS-CoV-2 dispersion. These particles are the airborne pathogen-related contaminant whose transport is influenced by coach geometry, occupancy, masking status, and airflow patterns.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPARTMENT 1">
      <data key="d0">COMPARTMENT 1</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Identified compartment within the railway coach. It is occupied by seated passenger manikins at a reported occupancy rate of 92%. | An occupied end ventilation zone of the rail coach model. Like compartment #1, it receives fresh outdoor air and has imposed extraction velocity and flow rate conditions through roof slits.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_53</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">COMPARTMENT #3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="92% SEATED-PASSENGER OCCUPANCY IN COMPARTMENT 1">
      <data key="d0">92% SEATED-PASSENGER OCCUPANCY IN COMPARTMENT 1</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupancy load for compartment 1, where seated passenger manikins occupy 92% of the compartment capacity. | Occupancy load for compartment 3, where seated passenger manikins occupy the compartment at full seated capacity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_53</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">100% SEATED-PASSENGER OCCUPANCY IN COMPARTMENT 3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COACH OCCUPATION RATE">
      <data key="d0">COACH OCCUPATION RATE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Variable passenger-occupancy condition for the railway coach. The text states that this rate could be varied to examine its influence on the distribution of drops and droplets secreted by passengers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_53</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PASSENGER-SECRETED DROPS AND DROPLETS DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">PASSENGER-SECRETED DROPS AND DROPLETS DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Spatial distribution pattern of respiratory drops and droplets secreted by passengers inside the railway coach. These drops and droplets are relevant because they may carry SARS-CoV-2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_53</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASKED AND NON-MASKED MANIKINS">
      <data key="d0">MASKED AND NON-MASKED MANIKINS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Simulated occupants placed within the railway coach, with masking status represented. Their presence defines the occupied condition of the coach and affects local airflow obstruction and particle-dispersion modeling near passenger bodies and masks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONVERGED ANISOTHERMAL FLOW FIELD">
      <data key="d0">CONVERGED ANISOTHERMAL FLOW FIELD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Computed airflow and thermal-gradient-dependent distribution pattern inside the coach. The mesh of approximately 10 million cells was stated to be sufficient for convergence of this flow field.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOCAL FLOW NEAR MANIKINS AND MASKS">
      <data key="d0">LOCAL FLOW NEAR MANIKINS AND MASKS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">High-resolution local airflow region around manikins and masks where mesh refinements were required to resolve demanding thermal gradients near boundaries.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_54</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ENTIRE SPACE OF THE CARRIAGE">
      <data key="d0">ENTIRE SPACE OF THE CARRIAGE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The full internal air volume of the railway coach involved in the ventilation process, including occupied regions around passengers and manikins.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FRESH-AIR SUPPLY FROM EACH END OF THE CARRIAGE">
      <data key="d0">FRESH-AIR SUPPLY FROM EACH END OF THE CARRIAGE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled supply-air path through which only fresh outside air enters the coach from both ends of the carriage.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CEILING SLOTS">
      <data key="d0">CEILING SLOTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Slots located in the ceiling of the coach that function as the upper air extraction or outlet path toward which the ventilation flow moves.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INLET BOUNDARY CONDITIONS">
      <data key="d0">INLET BOUNDARY CONDITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Computational boundary conditions representing where ventilation air is introduced into the airflow simulation. | Computational boundary conditions representing where ventilation air exits or is extracted from the airflow simulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">OUTLET BOUNDARY CONDITIONS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="8.7 AIR RENEWAL RATE">
      <data key="d0">8.7 AIR RENEWAL RATE</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The stated air renewal rate for the railway coach, corresponding to the carriage air being refreshed approximately every 7 minutes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_55,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_90</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BOTTOM-TO-TOP VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">BOTTOM-TO-TOP VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The vertical component of the coach ventilation pattern, in which air moves from lower regions of the coach upward toward the ceiling slots.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="END-TO-CEILING-SLOT AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">END-TO-CEILING-SLOT AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The longitudinal and vertical airflow pattern in which fresh air supplied from the carriage ends moves toward slots located in the ceiling.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="3D TURBULENT AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">3D TURBULENT AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated turbulent airflow field generated by the coach ventilation system before passenger breathing effects are introduced.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PASSENGERS">
      <data key="d0">PASSENGERS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The occupants of the railway coach whose breathing is considered after the initial ventilation-only stationary airflow simulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_55,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_59,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_83,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_85,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_86,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_88,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_89</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASKED MANIKINS">
      <data key="d0">MASKED MANIKINS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled passenger surrogates wearing masks, represented in the coach surface mesh and used to represent occupied passenger locations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_55,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_83</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ALTERNATIVE BLOWING OR EXTRACTING AIR VENTS">
      <data key="d0">ALTERNATIVE BLOWING OR EXTRACTING AIR VENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Possible alternative supply or extraction vent arrangements mentioned as configurations that could be considered in other simulations for different rail coaches.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.56</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_55</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PASSENGERS REPRESENTED BY HUMANOID MANIKINS">
      <data key="d0">PASSENGERS REPRESENTED BY HUMANOID MANIKINS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled occupants in the railway coach. Their heads, and masks when present, are set to 32 °C while other simulation-domain surfaces are at 20 °C, making them thermal sources that alter the airflow field.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_56,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_67</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BUOYANT FREE CONVECTION">
      <data key="d0">BUOYANT FREE CONVECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Thermally induced upward air motion generated because the humanoid manikins are warmer than the surrounding coach surfaces and air. This buoyant flow modifies the overall velocity and temperature fields in the carriage.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_56</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TEMPERATURE AND VELOCITY FIELDS">
      <data key="d0">TEMPERATURE AND VELOCITY FIELDS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Computed flow-field outputs shown in vertical sections and oblique 3D views, including temperature distribution, velocity modulus, and velocity vectors across rows of humanoid manikins and within the carriage.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_56</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION AT THE ENDS OF THE RAIL COACH">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION AT THE ENDS OF THE RAIL COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation source located or acting at the ends of the rail coach. It produces visible lateral airflows in the lower part of the carriage and contributes to the overall internal air movement.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_57</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LATERAL AIRFLOWS FROM VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">LATERAL AIRFLOWS FROM VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation-driven lateral airflow paths visible in the lower part of the rail coach near the carriage ends. These flows interact with occupant-generated buoyant motion and help shape the lower-level air distribution.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_57</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HUMANOID MANIKINS REPRESENTING TRAIN PASSENGERS">
      <data key="d0">HUMANOID MANIKINS REPRESENTING TRAIN PASSENGERS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The passenger load represented by humanoid manikins in the simulated carriage. The manikins act as thermal sources that drive free convection and generate buoyant plumes above the occupied seating row.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_57</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BUOYANT PLUME ABOVE THE PASSENGERS">
      <data key="d0">BUOYANT PLUME ABOVE THE PASSENGERS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A thermally driven plume observed above the humanoid manikins or passengers, visible in temperature and velocity representations. It forms at approximately 22 °C and is associated with free convection from occupant heat release.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_57</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FREE-CONVECTION ASCENDING CURRENT">
      <data key="d0">FREE-CONVECTION ASCENDING CURRENT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The upward air movement produced by free convection above the passengers. Its speed is approximately 0.1 m s−1, indicating a relatively gentle but clearly observable occupant-driven vertical airflow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_57</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SLIGHTLY WARMER UPPER AIR LAYER">
      <data key="d0">SLIGHTLY WARMER UPPER AIR LAYER</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A slightly warmer stratified air layer in the upper part of the carriage, approximately 40 cm thick. It reflects vertical thermal stratification and accumulation of warmer air near the upper region of the rail coach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_57</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTED BREATHING PASSENGER">
      <data key="d0">INFECTED BREATHING PASSENGER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupant emission source located at the same position as in previous studies. The passenger breathes on a five-second cycle with approximately two seconds of exhalation, two seconds of inhalation, and a one-second pause, emitting droplets during dissemination events.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PASSENGERS WEARING PERFECTLY FITTED MASKS">
      <data key="d0">PASSENGERS WEARING PERFECTLY FITTED MASKS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupancy scenario in which passengers in the coach are assumed to wear perfectly fitted masks. This defines the exposure and source-control context for the simulated dissemination event.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE MICROMETER EXHALED DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">ONE MICROMETER EXHALED DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Pathogen-carrying respiratory droplets with an aerodynamic diameter of around 1 µm, produced by the infected breathing passenger and dispersed through the coach airflow during the transient simulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNSTEADY AIRFLOW AND PARTICLE DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">UNSTEADY AIRFLOW AND PARTICLE DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Transient computed airflow and associated particle-dispersion behavior in the rail coach. The simulation lasts 600 seconds, allowing emitted droplets to spread through the compartment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VELOCITY VECTORS IN THE RAIL COACH">
      <data key="d0">VELOCITY VECTORS IN THE RAIL COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airflow visualization showing velocity vectors in the coach, with vector length proportional to velocity magnitude. The vectors represent airflow direction and relative intensity relevant to droplet transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.62</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION OF COMPARTMENT #1">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION OF COMPARTMENT #1</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation or air-handling process serving compartment #1. It evacuates airborne droplets from the compartment and contributes to the approach toward a near-stationary balance between droplet production, distribution, and removal.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASKED INFECTED MANIKIN">
      <data key="d0">MASKED INFECTED MANIKIN</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The seated infected humanoid manikin acting as the spreader/source occupant in compartment #1. Its breathing initiates the dissemination event and produces warm exhaled air and respiratory droplets.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PASSENGER OPPOSITE THE SPREADER">
      <data key="d0">PASSENGER OPPOSITE THE SPREADER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The passenger seated opposite the infected manikin/spreader. The text emphasizes that the exhaled-air jet does not directly impact this passenger because the warm exhaled air is quickly caught in the spreader’s buoyant plume and transported upward.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BUOYANT THERMAL PLUMES ABOVE PASSENGERS">
      <data key="d0">BUOYANT THERMAL PLUMES ABOVE PASSENGERS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Thermally driven upward airflow structures generated above seated passengers. These plumes capture the warmer exhaled air from the spreader and carry it upward, strongly shaping near-source airflow and droplet dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEAR-STATIONARY DROPLET DISPERSION REGIME">
      <data key="d0">NEAR-STATIONARY DROPLET DISPERSION REGIME</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The approximate steady dispersion condition approached during the 600 s simulation, representing a balance between droplet production by the breathing infected manikin, distribution throughout compartment #1, and evacuation by ventilation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RAIL COACH COMPARTMENT">
      <data key="d0">RAIL COACH COMPARTMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Enclosed passenger compartment used as the simulated indoor zone where airflow, temperature fields, and droplet dispersion were evaluated.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CEILING AIR EXTRACTION VENTS">
      <data key="d0">CEILING AIR EXTRACTION VENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Air extraction vents located in the ceiling of the compartment that evacuate warm air and suspended droplets from the upper part of the coach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPREADER AND NEIGHBOURING PASSENGERS">
      <data key="d0">SPREADER AND NEIGHBOURING PASSENGERS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Passenger manikin identified as the spreader, with nearby occupants represented in the simulated coach environment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED DROPLET CLOUD">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED DROPLET CLOUD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Individual droplets exhaled by the spreader and tracked over time as they disperse through the coach air volume.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BUOYANT UPWARD PLUME">
      <data key="d0">BUOYANT UPWARD PLUME</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Free-convection-driven upward airflow caused by the spreader exhaling air warmer than the surrounding atmosphere, rapidly transporting droplets toward the upper coach region.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPPER WARM-AIR EXTRACTION PATHWAY">
      <data key="d0">UPPER WARM-AIR EXTRACTION PATHWAY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne transport route in which droplets accumulate in the warm upper layer of the coach before being drawn toward the ceiling extraction vents.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_60</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPPER CEILING REGION OF RAILWAY COACH">
      <data key="d0">UPPER CEILING REGION OF RAILWAY COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The upper part of the coach near the ceiling where droplets accumulate when thermal effects are included. This region contains or is near the air extractors, enabling faster removal of accumulated contaminants.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_61</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEATED PASSENGER OCCUPIED LOWER REGION">
      <data key="d0">SEATED PASSENGER OCCUPIED LOWER REGION</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The lower occupied area of the coach where seated passengers are located. The text indicates that passengers in this region are less exposed when droplets are transported toward and concentrated in the upper ceiling region.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_61</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR EXTRACTORS">
      <data key="d0">AIR EXTRACTORS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Ceiling-located extraction components of the ventilation system that remove air and accumulated droplets from the upper part of the railway coach, supporting rapid elimination of aerosolized contaminants. | Exhaust components of the ventilation system that remove air and airborne particles from the occupied space. The text stresses that risk reduction is effective when these extractions are placed in the upper part of the environment, specifically on the ceiling of the coach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_61</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">AIR EXTRACTIONS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BOTTOM TO TOP VENTILATION STRATEGY">
      <data key="d0">BOTTOM TO TOP VENTILATION STRATEGY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The described ventilation approach in which airflow moves contaminants upward from the occupied region toward ceiling extractors. The text presents this strategy as favorable for limiting contamination by aerosols carrying pathogenic biological agents.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_61</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BOTTOM TO TOP FLOW PATH">
      <data key="d0">BOTTOM TO TOP FLOW PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The upward airflow route through the coach that transports exhaled droplets from lower occupied areas toward the upper ceiling region and air extractors.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_61</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED CONTAMINATING DROPLETS AND AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED CONTAMINATING DROPLETS AND AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Droplets and aerosolized particles exhaled by the spreader that may carry pathogenic biological agents. Their spatial and temporal distribution is the main contamination behavior compared between cases with and without thermal effects.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_61</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LARGER VOLUME DROPLET DISPERSION WITHOUT THERMAL EFFECTS">
      <data key="d0">LARGER VOLUME DROPLET DISPERSION WITHOUT THERMAL EFFECTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated contaminant distribution observed when thermal effects are ignored, in which exhaled droplets appear more numerous and disperse through a much larger volume of the coach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_61</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPPER PART DROPLET ACCUMULATION WITH THERMAL EFFECTS">
      <data key="d0">UPPER PART DROPLET ACCUMULATION WITH THERMAL EFFECTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated contaminant distribution observed when thermal effects are considered, in which droplets accumulate mainly in the upper part of the coach near the ceiling and close to the air extractors, favoring removal by ventilation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_61</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPREADER">
      <data key="d0">SPREADER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The contaminant-emitting occupant who exhales droplets into the railway coach and acts as the source of airborne biological contamination in the modeled scenario.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_61</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEATED PASSENGERS">
      <data key="d0">SEATED PASSENGERS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Passengers seated in the coach whose exposure is discussed. Their lower seated position makes them less exposed in the thermal-effects case because more droplets are concentrated near the ceiling rather than in the occupied breathing zone. | Occupant condition represented by the 1.1 m breathing-zone sampling height. The text uses seated passengers to define the exposure-relevant measurement level, not as an active bioaerosol source.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_61</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
      <data key="d6">SEATED PASSENGERS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RAILWAY COACH INTERIOR">
      <data key="d0">RAILWAY COACH INTERIOR</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Enclosed rail-coach compartment used as the modeled occupied indoor space where respiratory droplets remain suspended or are removed over the 0 to 600 s simulation period.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_62,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_64</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISSEMINATING PASSENGER">
      <data key="d0">DISSEMINATING PASSENGER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The infected or droplet-spreading passenger whose exhalation releases respiratory droplets into the railway coach; simulations compare cases where this passenger wears or does not wear a surgical mask.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALATION PLUME FROM SPREADER">
      <data key="d0">EXHALATION PLUME FROM SPREADER</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The droplet-bearing airflow path generated by the disseminating passenger's breathing or exhalation, affected by mask use and by simulated thermal effects.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THERMALLY INFLUENCED DROPLET DISPERSION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">THERMALLY INFLUENCED DROPLET DISPERSION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled spatial and temporal distribution pattern of suspended droplets in the coach when thermal effects are included; the text reports that this further reduces suspended droplets compared with simulations without thermal effects.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_62</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPPER PART OF RAILWAY COACH">
      <data key="d0">UPPER PART OF RAILWAY COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The upper region of the railway coach where warm exhaled air and droplets rise after being entrained into the buoyant plume, before being carried away by ventilation. | Upper region of the coach near the ceiling where droplets are entrained by airflow and then rapidly removed by ceiling extraction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_63</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">UPPER PART OF THE RAILWAY COACH</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PASSENGER SEATED OPPOSITE">
      <data key="d0">PASSENGER SEATED OPPOSITE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The occupant seated across from the infected passenger. The text identifies airflow toward this passenger as greatly reduced when the infected passenger wears a mask.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_63</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASKED EXHALATION AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">MASKED EXHALATION AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The reduced-velocity exhaled air path produced when the infected passenger wears a well-fitted or leaky mask. The text states that air and droplets emitted through the mask or through leaks at the nose, cheeks, and chin remain low velocity and are drawn into the buoyant plume.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_63</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNMASKED EXHALATION AIRFLOW TOWARD OPPOSITE PASSENGER">
      <data key="d0">UNMASKED EXHALATION AIRFLOW TOWARD OPPOSITE PASSENGER</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The stronger direct airflow pathway from the infected passenger toward the passenger seated opposite when no mask is worn. This pathway is greatly reduced when a mask is used.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_63</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RAIL COACH VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">RAIL COACH VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation configuration included in the 3D digital twin of the rail coach and used to drive airflow in the semi-confined coach interior. | The ventilation system or ventilating condition responsible for transporting and dispersing droplets, drops, dried residues, and suspended particles through the railway coach environment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_64</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
      <data key="d6">RAILWAY COACH VENTILATION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TURBULENT AIRFLOW AND RESPIRATORY DROPLET DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">TURBULENT AIRFLOW AND RESPIRATORY DROPLET DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled pattern of turbulent air movement and dispersion of drops and droplets emitted during respiratory events by humanoid manikins inside the ventilated rail coach. | Airflow and droplet movement generated by respiratory activities such as coughing, speech, or other expiratory events, characterized using optical flow-visualization methods.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_64</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
      <data key="d6">EXHALED AIRFLOW AND RESPIRATORY DROPLET DISPERSION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LONG NARROW COACH AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">LONG NARROW COACH AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The airflow and particle-transport pathway shaped by the long, narrow geometry of the rail coach, which differs from conventional building airflow environments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_64</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RAIL COACH INTERIOR VOLUME">
      <data key="d0">RAIL COACH INTERIOR VOLUME</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The enclosed occupied space of the digital-twin rail coach where airflow and droplet dispersion were simulated and assessed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_66</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BREATHING MANIKIN OCCUPANTS">
      <data key="d0">BREATHING MANIKIN OCCUPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Simulated passengers represented by breathing manikins, including an infected spreader passenger wearing a perfectly fitted mask. | Human occupants whose breathing and talking generate exhaled airflow patterns that can influence indoor aerosol transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_66</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
      <data key="d6">BREATHING AND TALKING OCCUPANTS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THERMAL-EFFECT-INFLUENCED AIRFLOW AND DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">THERMAL-EFFECT-INFLUENCED AIRFLOW AND DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled air movement and particle dispersion pattern affected by human thermal effects, which strongly influenced particle distribution around and above the emitting individual.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_66</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QUIESCENT MANIKIN TEST ATMOSPHERE">
      <data key="d0">QUIESCENT MANIKIN TEST ATMOSPHERE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">An atmosphere initially at rest around the head and bust of a breathing manikin, used to verify modeled flow and dispersion results against literature experiments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_66</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMMUTER TRAIN">
      <data key="d0">COMMUTER TRAIN</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The overall ventilated semi-confined transport environment modeled in the study. Although not a hospital zone, it is typed as a zone because the valid schema uses this category for enclosed occupied spaces where ventilation and airborne infectious-agent dispersion are assessed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_67</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FORCED MECHANICAL VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">FORCED MECHANICAL VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The mechanical ventilation system included in the railway coach model. It drives part of the internal airflow and is considered together with passenger breathing and heat-driven buoyant flows.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_67,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_84</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TURBULENT AIRFLOW INSIDE THE RAILWAY COACH">
      <data key="d0">TURBULENT AIRFLOW INSIDE THE RAILWAY COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The internal turbulent air distribution pattern produced by the combined effects of forced mechanical ventilation, passenger breathing or other dissemination events, and buoyant thermal plumes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_67</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BUOYANT PASSENGER PLUMES">
      <data key="d0">BUOYANT PASSENGER PLUMES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Thermally driven upward airflow generated by heat-emitting passengers represented by manikins. These plumes contribute to free-convection effects and influence respiratory-particle transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.81</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_67</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FREE CONVECTION AROUND MANIKINS">
      <data key="d0">FREE CONVECTION AROUND MANIKINS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Natural-convection airflow around the modeled passengers, included to represent occupant heat effects on the flow field inside the train coach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_67</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK-ALTERED EXHALATION AND LEAKAGE FLOW">
      <data key="d0">MASK-ALTERED EXHALATION AND LEAKAGE FLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The flow path around an individual mask, including leakage flow, used to represent how mask filtration efficiency and imperfect fit alter respiratory emissions before they enter the coach airflow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.79</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_67</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONFINED AND VENTILATED SPACES">
      <data key="d0">CONFINED AND VENTILATED SPACES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor occupied spaces with ventilation where dispersion of infectious agents is simulated. Although not explicitly hospital-specific, this is the relevant modeled zone in which airflow, buoyant plumes, and respiratory emissions determine particle transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DROPLET AEROSOL">
      <data key="d0">DROPLET AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Small respiratory droplets forming an aerosol that follows the surrounding airflow almost perfectly. This particle class is contrasted with larger drops that deviate from the flow because of inertia and sedimentation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LARGER RESPIRATORY DROPS">
      <data key="d0">LARGER RESPIRATORY DROPS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Larger emitted drops that do not follow the airflow as closely as aerosols. Their movement is influenced by inertia and deposition through sedimentation, leading them to move away from the main flow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONTAGIOUS INDIVIDUAL">
      <data key="d0">CONTAGIOUS INDIVIDUAL</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">An infectious occupant who emits warm exhaled air and aerosol during the respiratory cycle. This individual is central to evaluating contamination transfer and the effect of mask wearing on respiratory jet velocity and aerosol movement.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_68,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_69</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WARM MANIKINS">
      <data key="d0">WARM MANIKINS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Human surrogates in the simulations that are warmer than the surrounding environment. Their heat exchange with the air produces a buoyancy-driven plume near and above them.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POSITIVELY BUOYANT PLUME">
      <data key="d0">POSITIVELY BUOYANT PLUME</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">An upward thermal airflow pattern forming near and above warm manikins. It carries emitted aerosol upward, and this effect is amplified when mask wearing reduces the horizontal exhaled jet velocity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The background air movement in the confined ventilated space. Aerosol droplets follow this flow closely, while larger drops depart from it because of inertia and sedimentation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONFINED ENVIRONMENTS">
      <data key="d0">CONFINED ENVIRONMENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">General enclosed occupied settings mentioned in the text, including public transport, professional premises, schools, and similar places. These environments require effective upper-level air extraction because buoyant plumes can carry aerosols upward.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_69</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR INJECTION">
      <data key="d0">AIR INJECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Supply-side component of the ventilation arrangement. The text notes that a different arrangement of air injection and extraction could change airflow behavior and therefore alter particle dissemination and risk reduction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_69</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPPER-PART CEILING EXTRACTION PATH">
      <data key="d0">UPPER-PART CEILING EXTRACTION PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The upper-zone or ceiling-level pathway through which air and aerosol-laden flow are extracted from the coach or confined environment. This pathway aligns with upward aerosol transport caused by buoyant plume effects.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_69</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASKED EXHALED AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">MASKED EXHALED AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Exhaled airflow pattern modified by mask wearing. The mask filters exhaled air, decreases air velocity through the mask, and reduces droplet number and dissemination extent, even under realistic loose-wearing conditions with face leaks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_69</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASKED COUGH EMISSION">
      <data key="d0">MASKED COUGH EMISSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Cough-related emission pattern when a mask is worn. The mask blocks larger drops and slows droplets, reducing the particle spectrum associated with coughing and making it closer to a lower-velocity breathing emission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_69</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOW-VELOCITY BREATHING EMISSION">
      <data key="d0">LOW-VELOCITY BREATHING EMISSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory emission condition described as involving droplets emitted at low velocity. The text uses this as the comparison state toward which masked cough emissions are shifted.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_69</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE DROPLETS AND AEROSOLS CARRYING SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE DROPLETS AND AEROSOLS CARRYING SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory droplets and aerosol particles capable of carrying SARS-CoV-2. Their number, velocity, particle-size spectrum, and spatial dissemination are reduced by mask wearing and influenced by upper-level extraction and buoyancy-driven transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_69</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FACE-TO-FACE OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">FACE-TO-FACE OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Two-person arrangement in which one individual faces another, enabling direct interpersonal contamination. The text states that mask wearing limits contamination in this configuration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_69</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION SYSTEM LOCATED ON THE CEILING">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION SYSTEM LOCATED ON THE CEILING</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Ceiling-mounted ventilation system that extracts droplet-laden air from the coach. Its ceiling location is central to the reported reduction in suspended droplets.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_70</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR EXTRACTIONS ON THE CEILING OF THE COACH">
      <data key="d0">AIR EXTRACTIONS ON THE CEILING OF THE COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Ceiling exhaust paths through which air and entrained droplets leave the railway coach. Their placement explains why the studied ventilation strategy was effective.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_70</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR INJECTION AND EXTRACTION DEVICES">
      <data key="d0">AIR INJECTION AND EXTRACTION DEVICES</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation supply and exhaust devices whose spatial arrangement controls air movement and droplet distribution inside the coach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_70</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EFFECTIVE ENTRAINMENT OF DROPLETS TOWARDS THE UPPER PART OF THE RAILWAY COACH">
      <data key="d0">EFFECTIVE ENTRAINMENT OF DROPLETS TOWARDS THE UPPER PART OF THE RAILWAY COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Observed airflow-driven droplet transport pattern in which droplets are carried upward toward ceiling extraction, producing about a fivefold reduction in suspended droplets under the study conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_70</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIFFERENT DISTRIBUTION OF DROPLETS IN THE COACH">
      <data key="d0">DIFFERENT DISTRIBUTION OF DROPLETS IN THE COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Alternative droplet distribution expected if the arrangement of air injection and extraction devices were changed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_70</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FREE CONVECTION AND BUOYANT PLUME PHENOMENA">
      <data key="d0">FREE CONVECTION AND BUOYANT PLUME PHENOMENA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Thermally driven airflow patterns that should be included in airflow assessment because they affect droplet transport and health-risk estimates in confined ventilated spaces.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_70</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUSPENDED RESPIRATORY DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">SUSPENDED RESPIRATORY DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne or suspended respiratory droplets that may carry infectious agents in the confined atmosphere of the coach; masks reduce but do not completely eliminate their passage and persistence.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_70</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISSEMINATING INDIVIDUAL">
      <data key="d0">DISSEMINATING INDIVIDUAL</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Infectious source occupant whose position in the ventilated coach affects droplet dissemination and quantified health risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.77</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_70</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASKED PASSENGERS">
      <data key="d0">MASKED PASSENGERS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Passenger occupancy condition in which masks are worn. The study reports a significant reduction in contamination risk under this condition, while noting that droplets can still pass through masks and remain suspended.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_70</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNMASKED PASSENGERS">
      <data key="d0">UNMASKED PASSENGERS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Passenger occupancy condition without mask wearing, used as a comparison case showing higher contamination risk than when masks are worn.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_70</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATED SPACE OF A RAILWAY COACH">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATED SPACE OF A RAILWAY COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The enclosed ventilated compartment used as the modeled indoor environment for CFD analysis of airborne infectious-agent propagation. Although it is a railway coach rather than a clinical space, it is typed as a defined ventilated zone because the available schema has no transportation-cabin zone type.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_71</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTIOUS AGENT">
      <data key="d0">INFECTIOUS AGENT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The biological contaminant whose airborne propagation is modeled in the ventilated railway-coach space. Its transport depends on airflow, turbulence, particle dispersion, mixing, dilution, and potentially droplet-size evolution.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_71</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LIQUID DROPS OR DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">LIQUID DROPS OR DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne liquid particles that may carry the infectious agent during transport through the ventilated space. The text notes that evaporation and condensation were not modeled, but including these mass-transfer processes would allow droplet-size evolution to be studied.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_71</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTICLE PROPAGATION, MIXING AND DILUTION">
      <data key="d0">PARTICLE PROPAGATION, MIXING AND DILUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The set of transport processes by which airborne particles spread, mix with surrounding air, and become diluted within the ventilated railway-coach space. LES is described as capable of providing more detailed information on these processes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_71</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THERMALLY INFLUENCED AIRFLOW AND PARTICLE DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">THERMALLY INFLUENCED AIRFLOW AND PARTICLE DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airflow and particle dispersion behavior affected by thermal phenomena in the ventilated space. The study accounts for thermal effects on transport, while noting that evaporation and condensation mass transfers remain unmodeled.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_71</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATED RAILWAY COACH">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATED RAILWAY COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The enclosed ventilated space used as the modeled environment for studying airflow, thermal phenomena, and dispersion of suspended particles. Although the setting is a railway coach rather than a hospital room, it functions as the occupied ventilation zone in the extraction schema.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_72</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRFLOW AND PARTICLE DISPERSION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">AIRFLOW AND PARTICLE DISPERSION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled dynamic and thermal air-movement pattern governing the spatial and temporal distribution of suspended droplets, dried particles, and pathogen-bearing aerosols in the ventilated coach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_72</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PEOPLE IN THE VICINITY OF THE SPREADER">
      <data key="d0">PEOPLE IN THE VICINITY OF THE SPREADER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Nearby occupants who may inhale droplets, dried particles, and virions emitted by the infected passenger. They are exposure recipients rather than pathogen sources.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_72</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="IDENTICAL HUMANOID MANIKINS">
      <data key="d0">IDENTICAL HUMANOID MANIKINS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Simplified modeled occupants distributed in the railway coach. The study used identical humanoid manikins to represent occupancy while testing the feasibility of simulating particle dissemination in a ventilated space.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_72</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTED SPREADER MANIKIN">
      <data key="d0">INFECTED SPREADER MANIKIN</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated infected passenger acting as the source of emitted particles or droplets. Its location in the coach, seated or standing posture, mask adjustment, and respiratory activity are proposed variables for future 3D calculations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_73</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIVERSE PASSENGER MANIKINS">
      <data key="d0">DIVERSE PASSENGER MANIKINS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Additional manikin types proposed for improving the realism of the digital twin, including men, women, children, seated passengers, and standing passengers. Their differing body shapes, sizes, and positions may modify airflow blockage and particle dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_73</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTICLE SIZE SPECTRUM">
      <data key="d0">PARTICLE SIZE SPECTRUM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The range of emitted particle or droplet sizes associated with different dissemination events. The text notes that particle size spectra could be considered, but also emphasizes that the literature lacks consensus, especially for coughing, and that masked breathing reduces the usefulness of modeling a full emitted size spectrum.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_73</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK-FILTERED BREATHING EMISSIONS">
      <data key="d0">MASK-FILTERED BREATHING EMISSIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The preferred studied emission case in which the infected manikin breathes through a mask. The mask selects or filters droplets, thereby modifying the emitted particle population and limiting the relevance of a broad particle-size spectrum.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_73</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPACE AND TIME DISTRIBUTION OF PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">SPACE AND TIME DISTRIBUTION OF PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated spatial and temporal distribution of airborne particles in the railway coach. The text proposes building a database of these distributions from 3D calculations under varying spreader positions, postures, mask fit, and respiratory events, then using the database to train an artificial intelligence model for rapid prediction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.97</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_73,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_75</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR-CONDITIONING SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">AIR-CONDITIONING SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The HVAC system serving the railway coach. It conditions and circulates air through the coach and may partially recycle air, thereby influencing aerosol and particle dispersion depending on the presence of filtration or sterilising treatment. | Mechanical air-handling system serving the subway compartment. The self-designed purification devices were integrated into this system to improve compartment air quality while maintaining passenger comfort.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_74</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
      <data key="d6">AIR CONDITIONING SYSTEM</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HEPA FILTER">
      <data key="d0">HEPA FILTER</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">A high-efficiency particulate absorbing filter identified as an example of effective filtration that could reduce the adverse dispersion effects associated with recycled air in the coach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_74</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR PURIFICATION OR STERILISING SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">AIR PURIFICATION OR STERILISING SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">A treatment component or system that may be included in the air-conditioning or ventilation system to sterilise or purify recycled air before it is redistributed through the coach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_74</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RECYCLED AIR">
      <data key="d0">RECYCLED AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The recirculated portion of air that passes through the coach and is returned through the air-conditioning system. The text identifies the recycled-air fraction as a key case-specific parameter because, without sterilising treatment or effective filtration, recycled air can accelerate aerosol dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_74</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FRESH AIR">
      <data key="d0">FRESH AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The non-recycled outdoor air fraction supplied through the ventilation system. The text identifies the fresh-air fraction as an important input for adapting simulations to real trains and coaches. | Fresh air is the supplied incoming air stream that passes through the mixing chamber together with return air and is treated by the IFD filter.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_74</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
      <data key="d6">FRESH AIR</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE PARTICLES AND AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE PARTICLES AND AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne particulate matter or aerosolised contaminants whose propagation through the railway coach is simulated. The text does not explicitly identify a pathogen, but this is the closest valid type for airborne contaminant transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_74</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISTRIBUTION OF PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">DISTRIBUTION OF PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The spatial distribution pattern of particles predicted for a given simulation situation, such as a specific spreader position, coach geometry, and ventilation condition.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_74</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISPERSION OF AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">DISPERSION OF AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The spreading and transport pattern of aerosols within the railway coach. The text specifically notes that partial air recycling can accelerate this dispersion if the system lacks sterilising treatment or effective filtration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_74</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RAILWAY COACH INTERNAL SPACE">
      <data key="d0">RAILWAY COACH INTERNAL SPACE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The enclosed interior of the railway coach studied as a semi-confined occupied space where airflow and airborne particle dissemination are simulated.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_75</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OTHER SEMI-CONFINED OCCUPIED SPACES">
      <data key="d0">OTHER SEMI-CONFINED OCCUPIED SPACES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Other private or collective-use indoor or transport spaces mentioned as possible simulation targets, including planes, boats, performance halls, restaurants, nurseries, school rooms, and open-space offices.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_75</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRFLOW IN RAILWAY COACH">
      <data key="d0">AIRFLOW IN RAILWAY COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The movement path of air inside the coach, affected by internal configuration changes such as seat orientation and partition walls.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.73</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_75</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTIOUS BIOLOGICAL AGENTS">
      <data key="d0">INFECTIOUS BIOLOGICAL AGENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Biological or infectious agents carried by some occupants and disseminated through semi-confined spaces; the simulations aim to reduce their airborne transmission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_75</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GATHERING OF PEOPLE">
      <data key="d0">GATHERING OF PEOPLE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The presence and aggregation of occupants in semi-confined spaces, some of whom may carry infectious agents, increasing the criticality of airborne dissemination.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_75</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION IN THE RAILWAY COACH">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION IN THE RAILWAY COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The air-supply and air-movement function within the railway coach. It contributes to mixed convection flows and influences the transport and dilution of droplets, aerosols, and infectious agents.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_76</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MIXED CONVECTION FLOWS">
      <data key="d0">MIXED CONVECTION FLOWS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airflow patterns generated jointly by mechanical ventilation and temperature differences between humanoid manikins and the railway-coach environment. These flows are central to the modeled transport of droplets, drops, and potentially pathogen-bearing aerosols.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_76</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LAMINAR AND TURBULENT FLOWS">
      <data key="d0">LAMINAR AND TURBULENT FLOWS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airflow regimes referenced as validation contexts for the CFD tool used to model aerosol dispersion. These regimes affect particle transport, mixing, and airborne spread in comparable flow conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_76</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL AND DROPLET DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL AND DROPLET DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled transport pathway of droplets, drops, and aerosols emitted by occupants through breathing. This pathway is shaped by ventilation, mixed convection, mask use, and thermal conditions in the railway coach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_76</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HUMANOID MANIKINS WEARING MASKS OR NOT">
      <data key="d0">HUMANOID MANIKINS WEARING MASKS OR NOT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The simulated occupant load in the digital railway-coach model. The manikins represent passengers who breathe, emit particles, wear fitted or leaky masks or no mask, and create thermal plumes that affect mixed convection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_76</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="REAL PASSENGERS WEARING MASKS OR NOT">
      <data key="d0">REAL PASSENGERS WEARING MASKS OR NOT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The real-world occupant condition referenced as difficult to reproduce experimentally in an actual train car. Such passengers may carry infectious agents and emit particles while breathing, with mask status affecting emission and leakage.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.62</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_76</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISPERSION OF DROPLETS, DROPS, AND PARTICLES CARRYING SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d0">DISPERSION OF DROPLETS, DROPS, AND PARTICLES CARRYING SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne dispersion pattern referenced from prior studies, involving respiratory droplets, drops, or particles carrying SARS-CoV-2 within a railway transport coach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_77</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DROPLETS CARRYING SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d0">DROPLETS CARRYING SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory droplets or particles that transport SARS-CoV-2 through the simulated airflow field and are affected by breathing, buoyancy, and non-isothermal flow conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_78</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WARM HUMANOID MANIKINS BREATHING">
      <data key="d0">WARM HUMANOID MANIKINS BREATHING</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Simulated warm human occupants that breathe into the surrounding air. They provide both respiratory emissions and thermal heat sources that influence buoyancy-driven airflow and droplet transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_78</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BUOYANT PLUME OF DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">BUOYANT PLUME OF DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Upward or thermally driven droplet transport pattern caused by air buoyancy from temperature-dependent density variation around warm breathing manikins.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_78</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RAILWAY COACH AIR ENVIRONMENT">
      <data key="d0">RAILWAY COACH AIR ENVIRONMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The enclosed air environment of the railway coach in which respiratory particles, heat transfer, non-isothermal airflow, and buoyancy-driven droplet movement are simulated.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_78</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STILL ATMOSPHERE AROUND MANIKINS">
      <data key="d0">STILL ATMOSPHERE AROUND MANIKINS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">A simulated air environment without imposed coach ventilation flow, used as a condition for evaluating breathing and thermal effects from warm humanoid manikins.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_78</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BUOYANCY-INFLUENCED AIRFLOW IN RAILWAY COACH">
      <data key="d0">BUOYANCY-INFLUENCED AIRFLOW IN RAILWAY COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Simulated indoor air movement in a railway coach, modeled with Reynolds-averaged Navier–Stokes equations and a k-epsilon turbulence closure including buoyancy terms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_79</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MIXED CONVECTION AIRFLOW PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">MIXED CONVECTION AIRFLOW PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The airflow distribution pattern considered in the study, characterized as mixed convection at low to moderate turbulence levels in an indoor environment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_79</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TURBULENT FLOW PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">TURBULENT FLOW PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The airflow behavior being modeled in the simulation using an updated k-epsilon linear production turbulence model.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_80</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEAR-WALL LAMINAR SUB-LAYER AND BUFFER-REGION AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">NEAR-WALL LAMINAR SUB-LAYER AND BUFFER-REGION AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The near-wall airflow distribution region requiring enhanced treatment through a scalable or hybrid wall function because standard interpolation is inadequate near walls.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_80</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RAILWAY TRANSPORT COACH INTERIOR">
      <data key="d0">RAILWAY TRANSPORT COACH INTERIOR</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The enclosed indoor space where CFD simulations of airflow and particle dispersion were performed. Although the source setting is a railway coach rather than a hospital, it functions as the modeled indoor zone for air-distribution analysis.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_81</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MANIKIN MOUTH REGION">
      <data key="d0">MANIKIN MOUTH REGION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The near-mouth airflow region around the simulated occupants. The y+ map showed good near-wall resolution in this region, with values between 1 and 80, supporting detailed modeling of particle transport near emission points.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_81</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MANIKINS">
      <data key="d0">MANIKINS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Simulated occupants inside the coach used to represent human presence and near-mouth particle-release regions in the CFD model.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_81</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TURBULENT FLOW SIMULATION">
      <data key="d0">TURBULENT FLOW SIMULATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The CFD-modeled airflow field used to represent turbulent air movement in the coach. It includes near-wall treatment for the laminar sub-layer and buffer region and provides average and fluctuating velocity components that couple to particle transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_81</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LAGRANGIAN PARTICLE DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">LAGRANGIAN PARTICLE DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The particle-transport approach used in the study, where individual micrometric particles are tracked by solving their equations of motion and coupling them to the turbulent airflow field.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_81</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MIXED-CONVECTION AIRFLOW IN THE RAILWAY COACH">
      <data key="d0">MIXED-CONVECTION AIRFLOW IN THE RAILWAY COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Stationary airflow pattern generated by mixed convection inside the railway coach and computed using Code_SATURNE before particle-dispersion results were inferred.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_82</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BREATHING MANIKINS">
      <data key="d0">BREATHING MANIKINS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupant surrogates whose breathing locally perturbed the unsteady airflow and provided the source condition for particle dispersion simulations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_82</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BREATHING-PERTURBED UNSTEADY AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">BREATHING-PERTURBED UNSTEADY AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Localized unsteady airflow pattern created around the manikins by breathing, simulated together with particle dispersion for mask and no-mask scenarios.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_82</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LAGRANGIAN PARTICLE DISPERSION IN THE COACH">
      <data key="d0">LAGRANGIAN PARTICLE DISPERSION IN THE COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Modelled airborne particle dispersion pattern used to infer concentration results in the railway coach based on the computed flow field.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_82</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRAIN HEATING, VENTILATION AND AIR CONDITIONING (HVAC) SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">TRAIN HEATING, VENTILATION AND AIR CONDITIONING (HVAC) SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation and air-conditioning systems associated with train models. Their characteristics determine the forced ventilation flow inside the railway coach. | Building HVAC systems into which physical-mechanical filters may be incorporated to reduce airborne particulate matter concentrations and support indoor air quality control. | The ventilation and air-handling system serving the tested room. Its native operation was maintained throughout the experiment, so ventilation conditions were not intentionally altered during measurements.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_83</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">HEATING, VENTILATION, AND AIR CONDITIONING SYSTEMS,HEATING, VENTILATION, AND AIR CONDITIONING (HVAC) SYSTEM</data>
    </node>
    <node id="3D FORCED AIRFLOW INSIDE THE RAILWAY COACH">
      <data key="d0">3D FORCED AIRFLOW INSIDE THE RAILWAY COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The mechanically driven three-dimensional airflow field inside the coach, conditioned by the ventilation characteristics of the train HVAC system.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_83</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FREE CONVECTION FROM OCCUPANT HEAT SOURCES">
      <data key="d0">FREE CONVECTION FROM OCCUPANT HEAT SOURCES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Thermally driven airflow generated by heat sources in the coach, including passengers and the warm air they exhale. This convective component interacts with the mechanically forced airflow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_83</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RAILWAY COACHES">
      <data key="d0">RAILWAY COACHES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupied passenger rail-coach interiors discussed as ventilation zones. Although not a hospital space, this is the closest valid zone type in the schema. The text describes multiple ventilation approaches for these coach zones, including open windows, forced mechanical ventilation, air conditioning, distributed air injection, floor-level fresh-air supply, and high-level extraction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_84</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRAIN HVAC SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">TRAIN HVAC SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Heating, ventilation, and air-conditioning systems installed in trains. The text notes that train models can have different HVAC systems and that detailed ventilation conditions are often known mainly to manufacturers and railway operators.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_84</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPEN WINDOWS">
      <data key="d0">OPEN WINDOWS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Natural ventilation pathway created by opening train windows, allowing outdoor air exchange with the coach interior. The text identifies window opening as a simple ventilation method and notes that natural ventilation should be used when possible.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_84,6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_129</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGLE INJECTION NOZZLE">
      <data key="d0">SINGLE INJECTION NOZZLE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">A localized air-supply pathway mentioned as a less favored alternative to distributing air injection along the coach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_84</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLOOR-LEVEL FRESH-AIR SUPPLY">
      <data key="d0">FLOOR-LEVEL FRESH-AIR SUPPLY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Fresh-air supply pathway in which incoming air is introduced at the level of the coach floor. The text describes this as part of a typical railway-coach ventilation arrangement.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.79</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_84</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH-LEVEL AIR EXTRACTION">
      <data key="d0">HIGH-LEVEL AIR EXTRACTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Air-extraction pathway located at an upper level of the coach. The source text is truncated after 'extracted at the level of the c', but the described pattern clearly pairs floor-level supply with higher-level extraction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_84</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISTRIBUTED AIR INJECTION ALONG THE COACH">
      <data key="d0">DISTRIBUTED AIR INJECTION ALONG THE COACH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Recommended air-distribution pattern in which air is injected at multiple or distributed locations along the railway coach, rather than through a single injection nozzle.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_84</data>
      <data key="d5">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </node>
