      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The indoor airflow pattern characterized in the text by air velocity, temperature, and humidity; it influences the dynamic behavior, suspension time, and dissemination of small respiratory aerosols.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION MODES">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION MODES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Different indoor air distribution configurations referenced as affecting transmission of coughing or respiratory droplets in compartments and indoor environments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_3,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FINE PATHOGEN-LADEN AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">FINE PATHOGEN-LADEN AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Fine pathogen-laden aerosols are described as small respiratory particles that can facilitate more widespread disease transmission than larger aerosols. After release, they evaporate rapidly within approximately 0.1 seconds and form droplet nuclei, allowing longer-range airborne transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PREVAILING INDOOR AIRFLOW PATTERNS">
      <data key="d0">PREVAILING INDOOR AIRFLOW PATTERNS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Prevailing indoor airflow patterns are identified as the primary factor governing the long-term movement and spread of fine aerosols or droplet nuclei in indoor environments. These patterns shape the transport pathways of airborne contaminants after aerosol release and evaporation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPLETE AIR DUCT SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">COMPLETE AIR DUCT SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The full network of air ducts and connected flow paths that should be included when modeling indoor environments. The text emphasizes that considering the complete duct system is necessary for accurately predicting airflow patterns and aerosol dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR SUPPLY VENTS">
      <data key="d0">AIR SUPPLY VENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Openings that introduce supplied air into an indoor space. Their positions are adjusted to form different ventilation modes that influence droplet, aerosol, and tracer-gas movement.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHAUST VENTS">
      <data key="d0">EXHAUST VENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Openings that remove air from an indoor space. Their placement, together with supply vents, helps define ventilation modes and affects airflow direction and contaminant transport.</data>
