      <data key="d0">SIX-STAGE AIR SAMPLERS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Air-sampling units positioned at both ends of the cabin to collect bioaerosol samples at seated-passenger breathing-zone height. In the door-opening scenario, an additional sampler is placed near the outside door.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PATHOGEN CONCENTRATIONS">
      <data key="d0">PATHOGEN CONCENTRATIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Measured airborne pathogen-related concentration in the cabin breathing zone and, during the door-opening case, near the outside door to characterize external bioaerosol levels.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXTERNAL BIOAEROSOL CONCENTRATION">
      <data key="d0">EXTERNAL BIOAEROSOL CONCENTRATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Bioaerosol concentration measured near the outside door during the door-opening scenario to assess the external environment’s airborne biological contaminant level.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.77</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OCCUPANT MODEL">
      <data key="d0">OCCUPANT MODEL</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Experimental human-source model that releases bioaerosols for 10 minutes after stable airflow conditions are verified.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH-TOUCH PHYSICAL SURFACE ZONES">
      <data key="d0">HIGH-TOUCH PHYSICAL SURFACE ZONES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Surface sampling locations within the cabin, including seats and window ledges, where Columbia agar plates are arranged to evaluate potential pathogen-related contact risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SURFACE-DEPOSITED PATHOGEN CONTAMINATION">
      <data key="d0">SURFACE-DEPOSITED PATHOGEN CONTAMINATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Pathogen-related biological contamination evaluated on high-touch surfaces using Columbia agar plates, representing possible deposition and contact exposure risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COLUMBIA AGAR PLATES">
      <data key="d0">COLUMBIA AGAR PLATES</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Sampling plates placed on high-touch physical surfaces such as seats and window ledges to assess pathogen-related contact risk. They are represented as sampling equipment within the available schema.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.63</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUBWAY COMPARTMENT">
      <data key="d0">SUBWAY COMPARTMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The enclosed experimental indoor zone where bioaerosol air sampling, sediment sampling, surface-plate collection, ventilation operation, purification-device testing, and airflow-distribution assessment were performed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_22,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR CONDITIONER">
      <data key="d0">AIR CONDITIONER</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation and air-conditioning unit serving the subway compartment. Between experimental rounds, it operated in full fresh air mode for 1 hour and then in standard air supply mode to reduce carryover effects from previous experiments and background contamination.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FULL FRESH AIR MODE">
      <data key="d0">FULL FRESH AIR MODE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A ventilation operating mode used between experimental rounds, during which the air conditioner supplied fresh air for 1 hour after disinfectant cleaning to help reset the indoor environment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STANDARD AIR SUPPLY MODE">
      <data key="d0">STANDARD AIR SUPPLY MODE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The standard ventilation/supply condition used before subsequent experimental sampling to ensure that results were not influenced by previous experimental rounds or background environmental conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLOW FIELD UNDER STANDARD VENTILATION MODE">
      <data key="d0">FLOW FIELD UNDER STANDARD VENTILATION MODE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The airflow distribution condition analyzed before the bioaerosol investigation because aerosol motion was stated to be closely linked to indoor airflow characteristics.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUBWAY COMPARTMENT INTERIOR">
      <data key="d0">SUBWAY COMPARTMENT INTERIOR</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The enclosed indoor space where airflow velocity and temperature distributions were investigated before bioaerosol analysis. Although the valid schema labels this as a zone type, here it represents the measured cabin environment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CENTRAL CABIN REGION">
      <data key="d0">CENTRAL CABIN REGION</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The middle region of the subway compartment, identified as region 2. It contains five sampling points and shows a higher average air velocity of 0.32 m/s, with the peak measured velocity of 0.51 m/s occurring at central sampling sites.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="END CABIN REGIONS">
      <data key="d0">END CABIN REGIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The two end regions of the subway compartment, corresponding to regions 1 and 3. Their average velocities, 0.26 m/s and 0.28 m/s, are slightly lower than the central cabin region.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RETURN AIR VENTS">
      <data key="d0">RETURN AIR VENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Air removal openings that extract compartment air back toward the ventilation system. Their relative position with supply air vents shapes the cabin airflow pattern.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STANDARD VENTILATION MODE">
      <data key="d0">STANDARD VENTILATION MODE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The operating ventilation condition under which temperature and velocity were measured in accordance with EN14750-1. Under this mode, most compartment air velocities are below 0.5 m/s and temperature variation is limited.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_23,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TOP-DISPERSED AIR SUPPLY MODE">
      <data key="d0">TOP-DISPERSED AIR SUPPLY MODE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">An air distribution arrangement in which supply air is dispersed from the top of the compartment. Together with the compartment's symmetrical structure, it supports generally uniform temperature and velocity fields.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_23,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNIFORM TEMPERATURE AND VELOCITY FIELDS">
      <data key="d0">UNIFORM TEMPERATURE AND VELOCITY FIELDS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The overall measured indoor airflow and thermal condition in the compartment. Most air velocities are below 0.5 m/s, temperature differences among sampling points do not exceed 2 °C, and the compartment is described as having uniform temperature and velocity fields.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CENTRAL-REGION HIGHER AIR VELOCITY PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">CENTRAL-REGION HIGHER AIR VELOCITY PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A localized airflow pattern in which the central cabin region has slightly higher velocity than the ends. The central average velocity is 0.32 m/s, compared with 0.26 m/s and 0.28 m/s at the two ends, and the peak velocity is 0.51 m/s.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.81</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LIMITED TEMPERATURE STRATIFICATION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">LIMITED TEMPERATURE STRATIFICATION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The observed temperature distribution in which variation across vertical and horizontal cross-sections does not exceed 2 °C. The average temperature at 1.7 m above the floor is lower than that at 1.1 m.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPARTMENT">
      <data key="d0">COMPARTMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The controlled indoor compartment where ventilation, airflow velocity, temperature fields, and bioaerosol dispersion are observed. The text indicates that its symmetrical structure contributes to uniform temperature and velocity fields.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPARTMENT AIRFLOW PATH">
      <data key="d0">COMPARTMENT AIRFLOW PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The internal airflow movement within the compartment. After the initial respiratory jet weakens, this room airflow becomes dominant and disperses bioaerosols into the surrounding space.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BREATH-MODE RESPIRATORY JET">
      <data key="d0">BREATH-MODE RESPIRATORY JET</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The forward-moving air jet produced by the manikin's breathing action during bioaerosol release. In the initial release phase, its strong momentum propels particles directly forward.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MANIKIN EQUIPPED WITH THE AEROSOL GENERATOR">
      <data key="d0">MANIKIN EQUIPPED WITH THE AEROSOL GENERATOR</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A simulated occupant and emission source used to release bioaerosols through breath mode. It represents a person-like source of airborne particles in the ventilated compartment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CABIN TURBULENCE">
      <data key="d0">CABIN TURBULENCE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Random low-velocity airflow behavior within the cabin, with air velocity reported below 0.3 Ma. It was identified as a likely contributor to variability in measured S. aureus bioaerosol concentrations at some sampling points.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LONG-DISTANCE TRANSPORT">
      <data key="d0">LONG-DISTANCE TRANSPORT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The predominant airborne transmission mechanism inferred for S. aureus bioaerosols in the subway cabin. High concentrations detected at air measurement points E1 and W1 indicated that bioaerosol particles could be transported over longer distances by cabin airflow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_25,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="E1 SAMPLING POINT">
      <data key="d0">E1 SAMPLING POINT</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">One of the cabin-end measurement locations where high bioaerosol concentrations are detected, supporting the conclusion that bioaerosols undergo long-distance transport through the subway cabin. | One of the cabin-end measurement locations where high bioaerosol concentrations are detected, providing evidence for longitudinal bioaerosol transmission across the cabin.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
      <data key="d6">W1 SAMPLING POINT</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RELATIVE UNIFORMITY">
      <data key="d0">RELATIVE UNIFORMITY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A spatial distribution pattern in which bioaerosol concentrations are relatively even across measured cabin locations. The passage supports this with less than a 10% difference in S. aureus colony counts between two measurement points at the 15th minute.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="1.1-2.0 MICROMETER BIOAEROSOL FRACTION">
      <data key="d0">1.1-2.0 MICROMETER BIOAEROSOL FRACTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The particle-size fraction in which peak bioaerosol concentrations are predominantly observed at both cabin ends, accounting for approximately 35% of the concentrations at the sampling sites.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUBWAY VENTILATION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">SUBWAY VENTILATION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The subway ventilation pattern is identified as a key airflow distribution condition influencing how pathogen-carrying bioaerosols move through the compartment and adhere to touchable surfaces.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL RELEASE DIRECTION">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL RELEASE DIRECTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The aerosol release direction is described as significantly affecting aerosol deposition patterns, with measurement point RS2 showing the highest surface concentration among the sampled locations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SMALL AEROSOL FLOW LESS THAN 10 MICROMETERS">
      <data key="d0">SMALL AEROSOL FLOW LESS THAN 10 MICROMETERS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">This represents the airflow-following movement pattern of small aerosols under 10 micrometers. The text notes that some studies simulate these small-aerosol flows using tracer gases, but this approach can neglect particle settling.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BIOAEROSOLS CARRYING PATHOGENS">
      <data key="d0">BIOAEROSOLS CARRYING PATHOGENS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Bioaerosols carrying pathogens are airborne biological particles that may deposit on touchable surfaces in subway compartments due to ventilation patterns and indoor geometry, creating potential fomite-transmission concerns.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STRATUM VENTILATION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">STRATUM VENTILATION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The stratum ventilation system is referenced through a cited experimental study as an air distribution strategy used to reduce exposure risk in hospital wards.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_27,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_35,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_53</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OUTSIDE OR PLATFORM ENVIRONMENT">
      <data key="d0">OUTSIDE OR PLATFORM ENVIRONMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The external environment connected to the subway cabin when doors open, allowing some cabin airflow and suspended bacteria or bioaerosol to move outward.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.69</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPEN DOOR AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">OPEN DOOR AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The airflow pathway created when subway doors open; it connects the cabin with the outside or platform environment and contributes to reduced airborne and surface-settled bacteria.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DOOR-OPEN PRESSURE FIELD">
      <data key="d0">DOOR-OPEN PRESSURE FIELD</data>
      <data key="d1">PRESSURE_RELATIONSHIP</data>
      <data key="d2">The altered cabin pressure condition caused by door opening, which changes airflow movement and helps drive some air directly outside the cabin.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.81</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DOOR-OPEN AIRFLOW PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">DOOR-OPEN AIRFLOW PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The changed airflow dynamics within the subway cabin during the door-open scenario; this pattern is associated with reduced bacterial concentration in air and on physical surfaces compared with the door-closed condition.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BIOAEROSOL">
      <data key="d0">BIOAEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne biological material whose distribution in the cabin and settlement on physical surfaces are examined under different subway door operation scenarios.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_28,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DOOR-OPEN BIOAEROSOL DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">DOOR-OPEN BIOAEROSOL DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The observed distribution pattern of bioaerosol and bacteria in the subway cabin during door opening, including lower airborne concentration and lower surface deposition relative to the door-closed scenario.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SMALL-SIZED DEPOSITING AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">SMALL-SIZED DEPOSITING AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Small aerosols capable of depositing on physical surfaces; the text states that tracer gases are not suitable for simulating their diffusion and deposition behavior.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SMALL AEROSOL DIFFUSION-DEPOSITION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">SMALL AEROSOL DIFFUSION-DEPOSITION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The movement and surface-deposition behavior of small-sized aerosols, which differs from tracer-gas diffusion because these aerosols can settle on physical surfaces.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PASSENGER BOARDING AND ALIGHTING">
      <data key="d0">PASSENGER BOARDING AND ALIGHTING</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Frequent passenger movement during subway operation that can alter airflow dynamics inside the cabin, especially when doors are open.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HUMAN CONTACT FREQUENCY">
      <data key="d0">HUMAN CONTACT FREQUENCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A factor affecting actual transmission risk because more frequent human contact can increase the practical opportunity for microorganism transmission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CABIN / COMPARTMENT">
      <data key="d0">CABIN / COMPARTMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The enclosed vehicle interior where airflow, pressure field, bioaerosol accumulation, and air-purification-device performance are evaluated. The text uses both cabin and compartment to refer to the main internal air volume.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VEHICLE DOOR">
      <data key="d0">VEHICLE DOOR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">A transient opening between the cabin/compartment and the outside platform. When opened, it changes the pressure field and airflow pattern, reduces the physical barrier, and allows bioaerosol-laden air to escape outward.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CABIN PRESSURE FIELD">
      <data key="d0">CABIN PRESSURE FIELD</data>
      <data key="d1">PRESSURE_RELATIONSHIP</data>
      <data key="d2">The pressure condition inside the cabin/compartment. It is changed by door opening and contributes to airflow redistribution and outward bioaerosol transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MEASUREMENT POINT M1 OUTSIDE COMPARTMENT">
      <data key="d0">MEASUREMENT POINT M1 OUTSIDE COMPARTMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The outside door-side measurement location where S. aureus was detected. Its measurement indicates that bioaerosols can pass through the vehicle door to the external platform-side area. | The internal air measurement location inside the compartment used as the reference point for comparing S. aureus amounts with the outside measurement point M1.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
      <data key="d6">MEASUREMENT POINT E1 INSIDE COMPARTMENT</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PASSENGERS ON THE PLATFORM">
      <data key="d0">PASSENGERS ON THE PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The occupant group located on the platform who may be exposed to bioaerosols escaping from the vehicle compartment through the open door.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CABIN ENVIRONMENT">
      <data key="d0">CABIN ENVIRONMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Enclosed occupied cabin space where ventilation, air purification performance, airborne bioaerosol concentrations, and sedimented biological contamination were evaluated.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BREATHING ZONE OF SEATED PASSENGERS">
      <data key="d0">BREATHING ZONE OF SEATED PASSENGERS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Localized inhalation zone around seated passengers in the cabin. The text emphasizes this zone because reductions in bioaerosol concentration there decrease the risk of inhaling respiratory pathogens.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR MONITORING POINTS">
      <data key="d0">AIR MONITORING POINTS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Cabin air sampling locations used to measure airborne bioaerosol purification performance. During continuous bacterial dispersal at t = 5 min, R values were reported at these points for the IFD filter and CP generator.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEDIMENT MONITORING POINTS">
      <data key="d0">SEDIMENT MONITORING POINTS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Cabin sediment or settling-plate sampling locations used to evaluate deposited biological contamination after operation of purification devices.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STANDARD VENTILATION MODES">
      <data key="d0">STANDARD VENTILATION MODES</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Baseline cabin ventilation condition relying on fresh-air dilution alone. It was used as the comparison case against the IFD filter and CP generator and was described as less effective for reducing bioaerosol concentrations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.73</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FRESH AIR DILUTION EFFECT">
      <data key="d0">FRESH AIR DILUTION EFFECT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Baseline dilution pattern produced by standard ventilation modes. It represents reduction of airborne contaminants by fresh-air supply without additional active purification.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.61</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY PATHOGENS">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY PATHOGENS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">General infectious airborne agents whose inhalation risk is associated with bioaerosol concentration in the breathing zone of seated passengers. | Pathogens that may be transmitted through aerosols, increasing infection risk for a given reproduction number. | Broad class of infectious agents referenced through discussion of respiratory pathogen emissions, aerosol transmission, and respiratory-virus transmission routes. The text frames droplets and aerosols as potential carriers of such pathogens after expulsion from the mouth.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d,ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
      <data key="d6">RESPIRATORY PATHOGENS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUBWAY CARRIAGE OCCUPIED AIRSPACE">
      <data key="d0">SUBWAY CARRIAGE OCCUPIED AIRSPACE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The enclosed passenger compartment used as the study environment for evaluating air purification. Although it is not a hospital area, it is mapped to HOSPITAL_ZONE as the closest valid schema type for an occupied indoor air-handled zone. Its large spatial volume, particle dispersion, constrained circulation, and stagnant regions reduce the apparent effectiveness of purification devices.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR CONDITIONING SYSTEM EQUIPPED WITH A PURIFIER">
      <data key="d0">AIR CONDITIONING SYSTEM EQUIPPED WITH A PURIFIER</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The subway carriage air-conditioning system that includes a purifier intended to remove particles from the air. The text emphasizes that released particles may not immediately enter this system, because they can first disperse through the carriage and become trapped in poorly circulating zones.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RELEASED AIRBORNE PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">RELEASED AIRBORNE PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Particles released into the subway carriage air and used as the contaminant load for evaluating purification efficiency. The article does not identify them specifically as pathogens; they are mapped to AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN as the closest valid type for airborne particulate contaminants affected by ventilation and purification.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONSTRAINED AIRFLOW CIRCULATION">
      <data key="d0">CONSTRAINED AIRFLOW CIRCULATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The overall airflow distribution pattern inside the spacious subway carriage. The carriage structure limits circulation, allowing particles to disperse away from the purifier intake and lowering effective filtration performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STAGNANT AREAS">
      <data key="d0">STAGNANT AREAS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Localized low-flow or poorly mixed regions within the subway carriage. These areas hinder particle transport to filtration or purification devices and contribute to reduced purification efficiency in the actual carriage setting.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RETURN AIR">
      <data key="d0">RETURN AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Return air is the recirculated air stream from the cabin that passes through the mixing chamber and is treated by the IFD filter.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CABIN AIR">
      <data key="d0">CABIN AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Cabin air is the treated indoor air environment of the subway cabin where microorganism concentration is reduced by air purification devices.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRFLOW ORGANIZATION">
      <data key="d0">AIRFLOW ORGANIZATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airflow organization is the structured air movement created by the air duct structure. It governs how CP-generated purifying materials are distributed throughout the indoor environment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MICROORGANISMS">
      <data key="d0">MICROORGANISMS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Microorganisms are airborne biological contaminants in cabin air whose concentration is reduced by IFD filter purification.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CABIN RESOURCE LOCATIONS">
      <data key="d0">CABIN RESOURCE LOCATIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Cabin resource locations refer to the spatial placement of resources or objects within the cabin, identified as a real-scenario factor that may alter observed bioaerosol transmission patterns.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TYPICAL SUBWAY CABIN">
      <data key="d0">TYPICAL SUBWAY CABIN</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Enclosed indoor transportation zone where experimental bioaerosol diffusion, airborne propagation, surface deposition, and air-purification performance were assessed. The cabin has symmetric interior geometry and air ducts that help produce relatively uniform aerosol distribution.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO DESIGNED AIR PURIFICATION DEVICES">
      <data key="d0">TWO DESIGNED AIR PURIFICATION DEVICES</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Air-cleaning devices evaluated both individually and in combination for reducing bioaerosol spread in the subway cabin. They function as indoor air-treatment units that can modify aerosol concentration and exposure risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COUPLED CABIN FLOW FIELDS">
      <data key="d0">COUPLED CABIN FLOW FIELDS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Combined airflow effects present in the subway cabin that drive cabin-scale bioaerosol movement. These coupled flows are described as a key reason bioaerosols can disperse throughout the entire cabin, especially without passenger interference.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RELATIVELY UNIFORM BIOAEROSOL DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">RELATIVELY UNIFORM BIOAEROSOL DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Observed spatial aerosol pattern in which bioaerosols disperse throughout the subway cabin, with less than 10% concentration difference between the two ends of the cabin. The pattern is attributed to coupled flow fields, symmetric indoor structure, and air ducts.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CABIN INTERIOR SURFACE ZONES">
      <data key="d0">CABIN INTERIOR SURFACE ZONES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Interior contact surfaces in the subway cabin, including aisles, seats, and windows, where bioaerosol deposition was observed at varying heights. These zones are relevant to potential contact-transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SURFACE DEPOSITION ON AISLES, SEATS, AND WINDOWS">
      <data key="d0">SURFACE DEPOSITION ON AISLES, SEATS, AND WINDOWS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Deposition pattern in which bioaerosols settle onto cabin surfaces at varying heights, including aisles, seats, and windows. This pattern indicates possible contact-transmission risk, although actual risk depends on microorganism viability and inactivation rate.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FLOW CHARACTERISTICS OF SMALL-SIZE AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">FLOW CHARACTERISTICS OF SMALL-SIZE AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Transport and airflow-following behavior of small aerosols in indoor environments with multiple obstacles. The text notes that tracer gases cannot fully reproduce this behavior, making it important for interpreting exposure and infection-risk predictions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.79</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTICLE SIZE-DEPENDENT TRANSMISSION">
      <data key="d0">PARTICLE SIZE-DEPENDENT TRANSMISSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Transmission behavior influenced by aerosol particle size. The text identifies particle size as a significant factor in disease transmission and recommends incorporating it into future infection-risk models for more specific passenger-health guidance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PASSENGER INTERFERENCE">
      <data key="d0">PASSENGER INTERFERENCE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Passenger presence or activity within the cabin that can alter bioaerosol transmission and distribution patterns. The study specifically notes that relatively uniform airborne dispersion was observed especially without passenger interference.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CABIN OCCUPANCY AND RESOURCE-PLACEMENT CONDITIONS">
      <data key="d0">CABIN OCCUPANCY AND RESOURCE-PLACEMENT CONDITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Real-scenario influencing factors including human activities and the location of resources or objects in the cabin. These conditions may introduce variation into transmission patterns and are proposed for consideration in future research.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRANSMISSION-PATTERN VARIABILITY">
      <data key="d0">TRANSMISSION-PATTERN VARIABILITY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Variation in bioaerosol transmission patterns that may occur in actual subway-cabin scenarios due to human activities, passenger interference, and resource or object locations. Future research is expected to consider these factors for more accurate infection-risk prediction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SMALL-SIZE AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">SMALL-SIZE AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Small aerosol particles whose flow characteristics in obstacle-rich indoor settings are not fully replicated by tracer gases. They are relevant to airborne exposure and indoor transport behavior.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIFFUSION PATTERNS OF INDOOR BIOAEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">DIFFUSION PATTERNS OF INDOOR BIOAEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The spatial and temporal dispersion behavior of bioaerosols in indoor air. The text states that opening subway cabin doors changes these patterns, reducing indoor bioaerosol concentration while allowing aerosols to escape toward the platform.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CABIN DOOR AIR EXCHANGE PATH">
      <data key="d0">CABIN DOOR AIR EXCHANGE PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The airflow and aerosol escape route created when subway cabin doors open, connecting the cabin interior to the platform and enabling bioaerosols to leave the cabin.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR FILTER">
      <data key="d0">AIR FILTER</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Filtration component experimentally tested for efficiency against the SARS-CoV-2 virus in the context of droplet and airborne transmission control.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_35,92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_58</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STRATUM AIR DISTRIBUTION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">STRATUM AIR DISTRIBUTION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Layered air distribution pattern produced by stratum ventilation, intended to affect how pollutants and infection-related aerosols move through a confined cabin.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INDOOR AIR VELOCITY FIELD">
      <data key="d0">INDOOR AIR VELOCITY FIELD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor airflow pattern describing velocity fields that influence the airborne transmission and dispersion of sneeze droplets.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.64</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DROPLET AND AIRBORNE TRANSMISSION ROUTE">
      <data key="d0">DROPLET AND AIRBORNE TRANSMISSION ROUTE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne and droplet-mediated pathway by which respiratory particles and pathogens such as SARS-CoV-2 may be transported through indoor air.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">92822355-ab82-4e40-9fca-0876f2fc943e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PUBLIC TOILETS">
      <data key="d0">PUBLIC TOILETS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
