      <data key="d0">MICROORGANISMS IN THE IRRADIATED ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Microorganisms targeted for inactivation by 222-nm far-UVC irradiation in the referenced room environment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.62</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE S. AUREUS">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE S. AUREUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne Staphylococcus aureus measured as the steady-state microbial aerosol load in a room-scale bioaerosol chamber study. The text reports that overhead 222 nm far-UVC exposure reduced this airborne pathogen load by more than 98% under U.S. daily exposure limits and by more than 92% under international daily exposure limits.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM-SIZED CHAMBER">
      <data key="d0">ROOM-SIZED CHAMBER</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A room-scale indoor test environment where far-UVC efficacy against an airborne pathogen was evaluated. The text does not identify it as a hospital room, but it functions as the relevant indoor zone in the available schema.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_10,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_59</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OCCUPIED INDOOR SETTINGS">
      <data key="d0">OCCUPIED INDOOR SETTINGS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Human-occupied indoor environments where far-UVC installations have begun to be used to reduce infectious disease transmission. The text discusses occupancy qualitatively and does not provide a numerical occupancy load.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COLUMBIA UNIVERSITY ANIMAL HOUSING FACILITY">
      <data key="d0">COLUMBIA UNIVERSITY ANIMAL HOUSING FACILITY</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The animal housing facility containing the occupied mouse-cage cleaning room. Although not a clinical hospital zone, it is the broader controlled indoor facility context in which the high-airborne-MNV test room is located. | Animal research facility setting where mouse cages are routinely sanitized and where contaminated bedding can serve as a source of airborne murine norovirus during cage-cleaning operations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_11</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">COLUMBIA UNIVERSITY ANIMAL FACILITIES</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MURINE NOROVIRUS MNV">
      <data key="d0">MURINE NOROVIRUS MNV</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A naturally occurring airborne viral contaminant found at high levels in the occupied mouse-cage cleaning room. MNV is endemic among laboratory mice and is described as not harmful to humans, making it a practical naturally occurring viral target for evaluating airborne intervention methods. | Virus naturally present in large quantities in used cage bedding from infected laboratory mice. Bedding disposal in the mouse-cage cleaning room releases MNV into occupied indoor air, producing a high pseudo steady-state airborne viral load used for field testing air disinfection.</data>
      <data key="d3">1.0</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_11</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">MURINE NOROVIRUS (MNV)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LABORATORY MICE OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">LABORATORY MICE OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The mouse population associated with the animal housing facility and mouse-cage cleaning room. Laboratory mice are described as a natural reservoir for endemic murine norovirus, contributing to the room's high airborne MNV burden.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_11</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BACTERIOPHAGES">
      <data key="d0">BACTERIOPHAGES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Viral microbial surrogates considered for controlled field-testing in occupied spaces. They are described as not harmful to humans, but deliberate introduction into occupied environments is limited by ethical and public perception concerns.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_11,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_67</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MOUSE-CAGE CLEANING ROOM">
      <data key="d0">MOUSE-CAGE CLEANING ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupied indoor animal-facility work zone where used mouse-cage bedding is disposed of and where airborne virus samples were collected during routine cage-cleaning activities. It is typed as HOSPITAL_ZONE as the closest valid spatial category for the studied indoor contamination zone. | A defined indoor animal-facility work room where air samples were collected during routine mouse-cage changing activities. It is the location where airborne MNV load was measured under far-UVC lamps on versus off conditions and where room air exchange was assessed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_12,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_15,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_35,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_36,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">MOUSE-CAGE CHANGING ROOM</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OC43 HUMAN CORONAVIRUS">
      <data key="d0">OC43 HUMAN CORONAVIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Human coronavirus included in benchtop far-UVC sensitivity comparisons as another clinically relevant airborne virus for assessing the surrogate value of MNV.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ANIMAL HUSBANDRY STAFF DAILY WORK ACTIVITIES">
      <data key="d0">ANIMAL HUSBANDRY STAFF DAILY WORK ACTIVITIES</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Routine occupied work condition in the mouse-cage cleaning room during which air samples were collected. Activities include handling and disposing of used cage bedding, which is associated with release of MNV into room air.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OCCUPIED INDOOR AIR OF MOUSE-CAGE CLEANING ROOM">
      <data key="d0">OCCUPIED INDOOR AIR OF MOUSE-CAGE CLEANING ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The room air volume into which MNV is released during bedding disposal and from which airborne virus samples were collected. This air environment carried the pseudo steady-state airborne MNV load used in the field study.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOLIZED HUMAN INFLUENZA A (H1N1) VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOLIZED HUMAN INFLUENZA A (H1N1) VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Human influenza A H1N1 virus in aerosolized form. The text reports survival-curve analysis and far-UVC inactivation metrics for this airborne virus, including k1,H1N1 = 20.06 ± 8.04 cm2 mJ−1 and D90,H1N1 = 0.11 mJ cm−2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOLIZED HUMAN CORONAVIRUS OC43">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOLIZED HUMAN CORONAVIRUS OC43</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Human beta coronavirus OC43 in aerosolized form, referenced from previous studies as a comparator for the aerosolized MNV and H1N1 results. Prior work measured its airborne far-UVC inactivation behavior.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOLIZED MNV">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOLIZED MNV</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Aerosolized murine norovirus tested in a benchtop aerosol chamber for dose-dependent survival after exposure to graded doses of 222 nm far-UVC light. The results indicate it is comparable but somewhat less sensitive to far-UVC than aerosolized H1N1 influenza virus and human OC43 coronavirus, supporting its use as a conservative surrogate for airborne human viruses.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_14,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HUMAN INFLUENZA A H1N1 VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">HUMAN INFLUENZA A H1N1 VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Aerosolized human influenza A H1N1 virus used as a comparator pathogen in the 222 nm far-UVC inactivation study. Its dose-dependent surviving fraction was compared with aerosolized MNV and human OC43 coronavirus.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HUMAN OC43 CORONAVIRUS">
      <data key="d0">HUMAN OC43 CORONAVIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Aerosolized human coronavirus OC43 evaluated for sensitivity to 222 nm far-UVC exposure. Reported inactivation parameters include k1,OC43 = 12.4 ± 0.4 cm2 mJ−1 and D90,OC43 = 0.19 mJ cm−2, and it serves as a comparator for assessing aerosolized MNV. | Airborne coronavirus used as a comparator pathogen in far-UVC susceptibility testing alongside airborne MNV.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">HUMAN CORONAVIRUS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFLUENZA A">
      <data key="d0">INFLUENZA A</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Human airborne virus cited as an example pathogen for which aerosolized MNV may serve as a conservative surrogate in airborne antiviral efficacy investigations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.62</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUPPLY AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">SUPPLY AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The incoming ventilation airflow supplied to the mouse-cage changing room. Together with the room volume, it was used to calculate the reported 36 ACH air exchange rate.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_16,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_43,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTIOUS AIRBORNE MNV">
      <data key="d0">INFECTIOUS AIRBORNE MNV</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Aerosolized murine norovirus measured in air samples from the mouse-cage changing room. The study reported a statistically significant 99.8% reduction, corresponding to a 412-fold reduction, in infectious airborne MNV when far-UVC lamps were on versus off. | A generic infectious airborne virus referenced in the article title as the airborne pathogen whose level is reduced in an occupied room. The text does not specify the virus species or measured concentration values.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.98</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_16,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">INFECTIOUS AIRBORNE VIRUS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ANIMAL HUSBANDRY STAFF DURING ROUTINE WORK ACTIVITIES">
      <data key="d0">ANIMAL HUSBANDRY STAFF DURING ROUTINE WORK ACTIVITIES</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The occupant and activity condition present during air sampling in the mouse-cage changing room. Routine animal husbandry work provided the operational context for measuring pseudo steady-state airborne MNV load.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="49 ± 20 ACHT">
      <data key="d0">49 ± 20 ACHT</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The average tracer-derived air changes per hour measured from carbon dioxide decay after controlled release across six positions in the room. The reported value agrees with the room's calculated 36 ACH air exchange rate.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="14,800 EACH">
      <data key="d0">14,800 EACH</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The calculated equivalent air changes per hour attributed to the far-UVC lamps, with a reported 95% confidence interval of 2000–36,000. This value was calculated using the 36 ACH room ventilation rate but depends on assumptions that may not be valid in a poorly mixed room. | The estimated equivalent air changes per hour for the poorly mixed room when a mixing factor of 10 is applied. The reported 95% confidence interval is 200–3600.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_17,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">1480 EACH</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FOUR CEILING SUPPLY DIFFUSERS">
      <data key="d0">FOUR CEILING SUPPLY DIFFUSERS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The four supply diffusers located in the ceiling toward the center of the room introduce supply air into the room. Their position relative to the exhaust path contributes to non-uniform air distribution.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DOUBLE DOOR EXHAUST PATH">
      <data key="d0">DOUBLE DOOR EXHAUST PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The double door on one side of the room is described as the primary exhaust route. Airflow is expected to move preferentially from the central supply diffusers toward this door, contributing to short-circuiting.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POOR MIXING">
      <data key="d0">POOR MIXING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The room is inferred to have poor mixing because the supply diffusers and exhaust location are arranged in a way that does not support a perfectly well-mixed single-compartment condition. This affects interpretation of calculated eACH values.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_17,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_23,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SHORT CIRCUITING OF FLOW">
      <data key="d0">SHORT CIRCUITING OF FLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A non-ideal airflow pattern in which supplied air is expected to streamline toward the door exhaust rather than mix uniformly throughout the room. | An air-distribution pattern in which supplied air travels rapidly toward the exhaust instead of mixing throughout the room. It reduces effective ventilation in parts of the room and contributes to poor air-disinfection performance under real-world mixing conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">SHORT CIRCUITING OF THE AIRFLOW</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DEAD SPACES">
      <data key="d0">DEAD SPACES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Poorly ventilated or stagnant regions expected to form because of the room's supply and exhaust configuration. These are especially relevant near the sampling location opposite the exhaust door.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_17,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WELL-MIXED SINGLE-COMPARTMENT ASSUMPTION">
      <data key="d0">WELL-MIXED SINGLE-COMPARTMENT ASSUMPTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The idealized airflow condition assumed in the initial eACH calculation. The text states that this assumption is not appropriate for the room because the supply and exhaust layout suggests poor mixing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POORLY MIXED AIR DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">POORLY MIXED AIR DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A nonideal air distribution condition in which the room air is not uniformly mixed. The text states that such rooms are typically assigned a mixing factor of 5 or 10, which reduces the effective ACH used in calculations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="36 EFFECTIVE ACH">
      <data key="d0">36 EFFECTIVE ACH</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The effective air-change rate before applying the poor-mixing correction. The text states that mixing factors reduce this value from 36 to either 7.2 or 3.6. | The effective air-change rate after applying a mixing factor of 10 to the initial value of 36 effective ACH.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">3.6 EFFECTIVE ACH</data>
    </node>
    <node id="7.2 EFFECTIVE ACH">
      <data key="d0">7.2 EFFECTIVE ACH</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The effective air-change rate after applying a mixing factor of 5 to the initial value of 36 effective ACH.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="2960 EACH">
      <data key="d0">2960 EACH</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The estimated equivalent air changes per hour for the poorly mixed room when a mixing factor of 5 is applied. The reported 95% confidence interval is 400–7200.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HUMAN-OCCUPIED INDOOR SPACES">
      <data key="d0">HUMAN-OCCUPIED INDOOR SPACES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupied rooms or indoor locations where whole-room far-UVC is proposed as a technology to reduce infectious disease transmission. The text is not limited to hospitals, but within the available schema this is represented as a zone-like indoor space.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM-SIZED BIOAEROSOL CHAMBER">
      <data key="d0">ROOM-SIZED BIOAEROSOL CHAMBER</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A room-sized experimental indoor chamber used to study far-UVC air disinfection under conditions involving a continuous airborne pathogen source.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAR-UVC SOURCES">
      <data key="d0">FAR-UVC SOURCES</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Far-UVC air-disinfection sources studied in the room-sized bioaerosol chamber and described as being installed in some human-occupied indoor locations. In the chamber study, far-UVC levels below regulatory safety recommendations produced high airborne disinfection rates.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HUMAN-OCCUPIED INDOOR LOCATIONS">
      <data key="d0">HUMAN-OCCUPIED INDOOR LOCATIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor settings occupied by people where far-UVC source installation has begun, indicating the technology is being considered or deployed in occupied environments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.58</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OCCUPIED MOUSE-CAGE CLEANING ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">OCCUPIED MOUSE-CAGE CLEANING ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupied indoor rooms in animal care facilities where mouse cages are cleaned. The passage identifies these rooms as the occupied indoor setting with high airborne murine norovirus levels used for quantitative far-UVC efficacy assessment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OCCUPIED STATUS OF MOUSE-CAGE CLEANING ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">OCCUPIED STATUS OF MOUSE-CAGE CLEANING ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The rooms are explicitly described as occupied. No numerical occupant count or density is provided, but occupancy is part of the stated indoor study condition associated with high airborne virus levels.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE MURINE NOROVIRUS MNV">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE MURINE NOROVIRUS MNV</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The airborne virus studied in the occupied mouse-cage cleaning rooms. It is not a human health hazard but was present at high airborne levels and was used as a conservative model for evaluating far-UVC germicidal efficacy against airborne human viruses.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.97</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE HUMAN INFLUENZA VIRUS H1N1">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE HUMAN INFLUENZA VIRUS H1N1</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne human influenza virus subtype H1N1, referenced as a comparator for far-UVC sensitivity in the benchtop study. Airborne MNV was reported to have similar, though slightly lower, far-UVC sensitivity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FOUR CEILING-MOUNTED 222-NM FAR-UVC SOURCES">
      <data key="d0">FOUR CEILING-MOUNTED 222-NM FAR-UVC SOURCES</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Ceiling-mounted far-UVC air-disinfection installation operated within current regulatory limits. In the room, these sources reduced infectious airborne MNV by 99.8% with a 95% CI of 98.2–99.9%, corresponding to a 412-fold reduction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.97</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUPPLY VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">SUPPLY VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation supply system delivering airflow to the room. Its airflow rate, together with room volume, was used in the eACH calculation, but the calculation depends on perfect mixing, which the text identifies as inappropriate for this room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CEILING EXHAUST">
      <data key="d0">CEILING EXHAUST</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Exhaust component located in the ceiling near the supply. Its proximity to the supply contributes to poor mixing and likely short-circuiting or incomplete distribution of air through the room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.81</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_23,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUPPLY-TO-EXHAUST CEILING AIRFLOW PATH">
      <data key="d0">SUPPLY-TO-EXHAUST CEILING AIRFLOW PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Air movement path associated with the close ceiling-level placement of supply and exhaust. This path can limit room-scale mixing and influence aerosol residence time and delivered far-UVC dose.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CEILING-TO-ONE-SIDE AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">CEILING-TO-ONE-SIDE AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Large directional flow of air from the ceiling toward one side of the room. This airflow contributes to nonuniform distribution, poor mixing, and uncertainty in aerosol transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.81</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="K-ADJUSTED EACH WITH MIXING FACTOR 5 OR 10">
      <data key="d0">K-ADJUSTED EACH WITH MIXING FACTOR 5 OR 10</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">More applicable equivalent air-change estimate that incorporates a K mixing factor of 5 or 10 to account for poor mixing in the room. This adjusted approach is preferred over the unadjusted 14,800 eACH estimate for this ventilation scenario.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="IRREGULAR AIRFLOW PATTERNS">
      <data key="d0">IRREGULAR AIRFLOW PATTERNS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Nonuniform airflow behavior that introduces uncertainty into aerosol residence time and the far-UVC dose delivered to aerosolized virus.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROUTINE HUSBANDRY STAFF WORK">
      <data key="d0">ROUTINE HUSBANDRY STAFF WORK</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupied work condition during which pseudo steady-state introduction of aerosolized MNV was assumed. The text does not identify the staff as a biological source of MNV; rather, their routine work defines the occupied experimental condition.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.69</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM VOLUME">
      <data key="d0">ROOM VOLUME</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The occupied or air-containing volume of the room across which mixing is expected to occur. Much of this volume is described as poorly mixed because of short-circuiting and dead-space formation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CEILING REGION">
      <data key="d0">CEILING REGION</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The upper region of the room containing the air supply and ceiling exhaust. It is important because the supply-exhaust proximity and ceiling-to-side airflow shape the room's nonuniform air distribution.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE SIDE OF THE ROOM">
      <data key="d0">ONE SIDE OF THE ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A lateral region of the room receiving a large flow of air from the ceiling. This directional airflow contributes to nonuniform distribution and poor mixing elsewhere in the room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM-SCALE CHAMBER">
      <data key="d0">ROOM-SCALE CHAMBER</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A controlled room-sized experimental chamber from a previous study evaluating far-UVC efficacy against aerosolized Staphylococcus aureus. The chamber provides a comparison context for effective air changes per hour.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SIMULATED HOSPITAL ROOM ENVIRONMENT">
      <data key="d0">SIMULATED HOSPITAL ROOM ENVIRONMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A simulated clinical room environment used in the McDevitt et al. study evaluating upper-room UVC inactivation of poxviruses. It provides a comparison context for reported equivalent air-disinfection performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_24,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_64,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_65</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CEILING SUPPLY">
      <data key="d0">CEILING SUPPLY</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The air supply component located in or near the ceiling that delivers ventilation air into the room. Its close proximity to the ceiling exhaust is identified as a key layout condition promoting airflow short-circuiting.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SHORT SUPPLY-TO-EXHAUST AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">SHORT SUPPLY-TO-EXHAUST AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">A short airflow route between the ceiling supply and ceiling exhaust. This path represents the likely bypass route that removes supply air rapidly and causes short-circuiting rather than uniform room mixing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CEILING-TO-SIDE AIRFLOW PATH">
      <data key="d0">CEILING-TO-SIDE AIRFLOW PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">A large directional airflow path moving from the ceiling region to one side of the room. This path contributes to uneven air distribution and the formation of poorly mixed regions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="IMPERFECT MIXING">
      <data key="d0">IMPERFECT MIXING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A real-world deviation from ideal well-mixed room conditions. It is accounted for by applying K mixing factors to effective air changes per hour estimates for far-UVC exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAR-UVC EACH 2960 WITH K=5">
      <data key="d0">FAR-UVC EACH 2960 WITH K=5</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">An effective air changes per hour estimate of 2960, with 95% confidence interval 400–7200, attributed to far-UVC exposure after applying a K mixing factor of 5 to account for imperfect mixing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAR-UVC EACH 1480 WITH K=10">
      <data key="d0">FAR-UVC EACH 1480 WITH K=10</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">An effective air changes per hour estimate of 1480, with 95% confidence interval 200–3600, attributed to far-UVC exposure after applying a K mixing factor of 10 to account for more severe imperfect mixing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM-SCALE FAR-UVC EACH 184">
      <data key="d0">ROOM-SCALE FAR-UVC EACH 184</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">An effective air changes per hour value of 184, with 95% confidence interval 128–322, reported in a previous room-scale chamber study of far-UVC efficacy against aerosolized Staphylococcus aureus.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPPER-ROOM UVC EACH UP TO 1000">
      <data key="d0">UPPER-ROOM UVC EACH UP TO 1000</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Reported effective air changes per hour values ranging up to 1000, with 95% confidence interval 740–1400, for an upper-room UVC system evaluated against poxviruses in a simulated hospital room environment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOLIZED STAPHYLOCOCCUS AUREUS">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOLIZED STAPHYLOCOCCUS AUREUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">An aerosolized bacterial pathogen used as the challenge organism in the previous room-scale chamber study of far-UVC air disinfection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POXVIRUSES">
      <data key="d0">POXVIRUSES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne viral pathogens evaluated in the McDevitt et al. simulated hospital room study using upper-room UVC light for air disinfection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_24,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_44,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_64,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_65</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM-SCALE STUDY SPACE">
      <data key="d0">ROOM-SCALE STUDY SPACE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The full-room environment in the current study where UVC effectiveness was evaluated at room scale. The text contrasts this space with a benchtop aerosol chamber and notes that room-scale eACH and inferred irradiance values differ substantially from chamber-derived expectations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BENCHTOP AEROSOL CHAMBER">
      <data key="d0">BENCHTOP AEROSOL CHAMBER</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A small-scale experimental aerosol chamber used to derive the k1 value of 2.36 cm2 mJ-1. The text identifies a disconnect between results from this chamber and results from room-scale testing, suggesting possible underestimation of k1 values in benchtop chamber studies.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAR-UVC ROOM-SIZED CHAMBER">
      <data key="d0">FAR-UVC ROOM-SIZED CHAMBER</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A room-sized chamber from a previous far-UVC study by Eadie et al. where far-UVC was reported to efficiently inactivate an airborne pathogen. The text compares its computed eACH and implied irradiance with values from the current room-scale study.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EACH VALUES UP TO 1000 [95% CI: 740-1400]">
      <data key="d0">EACH VALUES UP TO 1000 [95% CI: 740-1400]</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Previously reported equivalent air changes per hour for an upper-room UVC system. These values indicate very high ventilation-equivalent airborne pathogen removal or inactivation, with a 95% confidence interval of 740-1400.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EACH ESTIMATE OF 1480">
      <data key="d0">EACH ESTIMATE OF 1480</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Equivalent air changes per hour estimated for the current room-scale study after applying a K mixing factor of 10. The text states that this estimate aligns more closely with prior UVC system studies, while noting that its 95% confidence interval extends down to 200.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPUTED EACH OF 184">
      <data key="d0">COMPUTED EACH OF 184</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Equivalent air changes per hour computed in a previous room-scale far-UVC study. The text notes that this value would require an average irradiance of about 42 µW cm-2, which was much larger than the measured or modelled irradiance in that space.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="K MIXING FACTOR OF 10">
      <data key="d0">K MIXING FACTOR OF 10</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A mixing correction factor used to represent room-air mixing behavior when converting study results into eACH and average irradiance estimates. Applying this factor produced the eACH estimate of 1480 and reduced the inferred average irradiance from 1700 to 170 µW cm-2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL CHAMBER">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL CHAMBER</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Controlled experimental chamber used for aerosol inactivation studies and comparison with real-world measurements; previously simulated with computational fluid dynamics and described as operating under laminar flow conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM-SCALE CHAMBERS">
      <data key="d0">ROOM-SCALE CHAMBERS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Larger chamber or room-scale experimental environments contrasted with the smaller aerosol chamber; described as presumably having more turbulent airflow, which may affect aerosol transport and viral exposure dose.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAGE-CLEANING / CAGE-WASH ROOM">
      <data key="d0">CAGE-CLEANING / CAGE-WASH ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Room-scale space where aerosolized MNV exposure was discussed; its exact airflow pattern and aerosolization conditions are uncertain, making interpretation of viral susceptibility and inactivation results more difficult.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPOSURE AREA">
      <data key="d0">EXPOSURE AREA</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Localized area within the room-scale setting through which aerosols pass during UV exposure; complex aerosol motion through this area could alter the dose received by virus-containing particles.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL PATH THROUGH EXPOSURE AREA">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL PATH THROUGH EXPOSURE AREA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Movement route followed by aerosolized particles through the exposure area; described as potentially involving complex tumbling motion that could increase or vary viral UV dose.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LAMINAR FLOW CONDITIONS">
      <data key="d0">LAMINAR FLOW CONDITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Orderly airflow regime reported for the aerosol chamber, contrasting with the more turbulent conditions presumed in larger room-scale chambers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPLEX TUMBLING FLOW">
      <data key="d0">COMPLEX TUMBLING FLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Potential aerosol movement pattern through the exposure area involving complex, tumbling motion; suggested as a possible reason for higher apparent viral susceptibility in the cage-cleaning room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNCERTAIN ROOM AIRFLOW PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">UNCERTAIN ROOM AIRFLOW PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Uncharacterized airflow configuration in the cage-cleaning or cage-wash room; uncertainty leaves open the possibility of nonuniform aerosol trajectories and dose variation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.77</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRFLOW IRREGULARITIES">
      <data key="d0">AIRFLOW IRREGULARITIES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Possible nonuniform or irregular airflow features within the room-scale space that could cause variation in total UV dose delivered to aerosolized virus.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MNV">
      <data key="d0">MNV</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Murine norovirus discussed as the aerosolized virus in the cage-wash room; its observed susceptibility to UV inactivation may depend on airflow and aerosol generation conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_26,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOLIZED VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOLIZED VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Generic virus-containing aerosol particles whose total UV dose may vary depending on room airflow pattern, tumbling motion, and aerosolization conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_26,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MS2 PHAGE">
      <data key="d0">MS2 PHAGE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">RNA virus/phage referenced in a wavelength-dependent UVC inactivation study; its infectivity response around 220 nm was reported not to track RNA UV absorbance, suggesting non-genome-mediated inactivation mechanisms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_27,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_65,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_66</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PHI-X-174 VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">PHI-X-174 VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Virus referenced in earlier ultraviolet-sensitivity literature supporting the idea that far-UVC inactivation can involve mechanisms other than direct UV absorption by the viral genome.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_27,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_65</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Generic viral pathogen discussed in relation to far-UVC exposure, protein absorption of photon energy, RNA damage, and resulting loss of viral infectivity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_28,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_76</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DNA VIRUSES">
      <data key="d0">DNA VIRUSES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Class of viruses referenced as showing similar far-UVC inactivation behavior, where infectivity loss exceeds predictions based on direct genome absorption.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ADENOVIRUS">
      <data key="d0">ADENOVIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">DNA virus cited in connection with wavelength-dependent UV inactivation and DNA damage measurements.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.64</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_28,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_66,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_67</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LESS WELL-VENTILATED ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">LESS WELL-VENTILATED ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Rooms with poorer ventilation are identified as locations where further air-quality studies are warranted, particularly to assess whether far-UVC use affects airborne particle or ozone concentrations under different ventilation conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION AND FILTRATION">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION AND FILTRATION</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation and filtration are described as components of a layered strategy to reduce transmission of airborne pathogens in occupied indoor spaces.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LABORATORY MOUSE CAGE AND BEDDING ENVIRONMENT">
      <data key="d0">LABORATORY MOUSE CAGE AND BEDDING ENVIRONMENT</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The animal-housing environment where laboratory mice, cages, bedding, fluids, and other fomites may become contaminated or colonized with MNV. Although not a hospital area, it is the relevant controlled facility zone described in the text.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SURROUNDING AIR NEAR CONTAMINATED FOMITES">
      <data key="d0">SURROUNDING AIR NEAR CONTAMINATED FOMITES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The local air pathway into which viruses may be released directly by infected cells or reintroduced from contaminated surfaces, fluids, cages, or bedding through aerosolization.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR MOVEMENT AROUND CONTAMINATED SURFACES AND FLUIDS">
      <data key="d0">AIR MOVEMENT AROUND CONTAMINATED SURFACES AND FLUIDS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Air movement that can disturb contaminated fomites or fluids and disperse viruses back into the air through secondary aerosolization.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DEDICATED MOUSE-CAGE CLEANING ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">DEDICATED MOUSE-CAGE CLEANING ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Dedicated rooms within the Columbia University animal facilities where used mouse cages are cleaned and soiled bedding is manually discarded. These rooms are the built-environment location where MNV-contaminated bedding can generate airborne virus.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM AIR">
      <data key="d0">ROOM AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The local indoor air volume within the mouse-cage cleaning rooms into which MNV from contaminated bedding becomes aerosolized and circulated during manual bedding disposal.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MNV AEROSOLIZATION DURING BEDDING DISPOSAL">
      <data key="d0">MNV AEROSOLIZATION DURING BEDDING DISPOSAL</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Qualitative air-distribution and contamination pattern in which murine norovirus in soiled cage bedding becomes aerosolized during manual disposal and disperses into the room air.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DAILY MOUSE-CAGE SANITATION LOAD">
      <data key="d0">DAILY MOUSE-CAGE SANITATION LOAD</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Operational activity load at the animal facilities, described as approximately 3500 mouse cages sanitized daily, involving manual handling and disposal of soiled bedding that can increase airborne contamination potential.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BENCHTOP AEROSOL IRRADIATION CHAMBER">
      <data key="d0">BENCHTOP AEROSOL IRRADIATION CHAMBER</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Custom-built benchtop aerosol exposure apparatus used to generate, irradiate, and collect airborne viruses for far-UVC susceptibility testing. Although not a building HVAC component, it functions as a controlled aerosol air-handling unit in the experiment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE-PASS EXPOSURE SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">ONE-PASS EXPOSURE SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Controlled single-pass aerosol flow path within the benchtop exposure apparatus, integrating airborne virus generation, far-UVC exposure, and collection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ONE-PASS AEROSOL FLOW PATH">
      <data key="d0">ONE-PASS AEROSOL FLOW PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The controlled airflow route through the benchtop exposure system, integrating aerosol generation, passage through the UV exposure volume, and collection on gelatin membrane filters. Aerosol movement was driven at 11.6 LPM, and particles traversed the UV exposure window in approximately 23 seconds.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UV EXPOSURE VOLUME">
      <data key="d0">UV EXPOSURE VOLUME</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A defined chamber volume within the one-pass system measuring 279 mm tall by 254 mm wide by 63 mm deep. It contains a UV-transmitting window that allows far-UVC exposure of aerosols while they pass through the chamber.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SYSTEM VACUUM PUMP">
      <data key="d0">SYSTEM VACUUM PUMP</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Air-moving component that pulls aerosol through the one-pass exposure system. A precision flow orifice placed immediately before the pump sets the system flow rate to 11.6 LPM under choked-flow conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.61</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COUGHING BREATHING TALKING AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">COUGHING BREATHING TALKING AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The observed aerosol particle size distribution during testing, described as typical of human coughing, breathing, and talking, with more than 90% of particles below 1.0 µm diameter.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MURINE NOROVIRUS STRAIN MNV-1">
      <data key="d0">MURINE NOROVIRUS STRAIN MNV-1</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Murine norovirus strain MNV-1 (ATCC VR-1937) is one of the viruses used in the study. Its infectivity was tested as a function of 222 nm KrCl far-UVC dose using RAW 264.7 macrophage host cells. The excerpt describes the virus in an exposure/inactivation experiment rather than in a hospital HVAC or airflow-control context.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFLUENZA A H1N1 STRAIN A/PR/8/34">
      <data key="d0">INFLUENZA A H1N1 STRAIN A/PR/8/34</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Influenza A H1N1 strain A/PR/8/34 (ATCC VR-95) is one of the viruses used in the study. Its infectivity was tested as a function of 222 nm KrCl far-UVC dose using Madin-Darby canine kidney host cells. The passage does not specify any HVAC zone, air path, ACH rate, pressure relationship, or air-distribution pattern associated with this pathogen.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR SUPPLY LOCATIONS">
      <data key="d0">AIR SUPPLY LOCATIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation supply points shown in the supplemental room layout, representing where supplied air enters the mouse-cage cleaning room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHAUST LOCATIONS">
      <data key="d0">EXHAUST LOCATIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation exhaust points shown in the supplemental room layout, representing where air is removed from the mouse-cage cleaning room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPEN DOUBLE DOOR ENTRYWAY">
      <data key="d0">OPEN DOUBLE DOOR ENTRYWAY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The room's single double-door entryway, which was open throughout testing and therefore could provide an uncontrolled air exchange pathway between the mouse-cage cleaning room and adjacent spaces.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PORTABLE AIR FILTER">
      <data key="d0">PORTABLE AIR FILTER</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Portable air-cleaning or filtration unit positioned on a shelf in the room for each air sampling event. The excerpt identifies its placement but does not provide airflow rate, filtration efficiency, or operating parameters.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACTIVE MNV">
      <data key="d0">ACTIVE MNV</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Infectious murine norovirus targeted by the air sampling protocol. The text states that active MNV was sampled from air, making it the airborne viral pathogen of interest for infectivity measurements.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_38</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HUSBANDRY STAFF">
      <data key="d0">HUSBANDRY STAFF</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Personnel present and active in the mouse-cage cleaning room during all air sampling days. Their presence defines the occupancy/activity condition during sampling, although the text does not directly quantify their effect on airborne MNV levels.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_38,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ANIMAL FACILITY SAMPLING ROOM">
      <data key="d0">ANIMAL FACILITY SAMPLING ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Enclosed animal-facility room where airborne murine norovirus was sampled. The portable sampler was placed on a shelf at 2.1 m height at a specified room location; lamps were turned on about two hours before collection on source-on days, and husbandry staff were present and active during sampling.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MNV AIRBORNE CONCENTRATIONS">
      <data key="d0">MNV AIRBORNE CONCENTRATIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne murine norovirus collected from room air using a gelatin-filter air sampling method. The collected virus was later assessed for infectivity with a TCID50 assay.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BSL 2 FACILITY">
      <data key="d0">BSL 2 FACILITY</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Biosafety level 2 facility located about a 30-minute drive from the animal facility, where collected viral solutions were transported for aliquoting and infectivity assay preparation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.48</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_39</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPOSED VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">EXPOSED VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Virus recovered from the dissolved gelatin filter after air sampling. It was quantified by serial dilution on host cells, cytopathic-effect scoring, and TCID50 calculation, and the resulting log-transformed virus counts were analyzed against predictors including far-UVC exposure, month, year, lunchbreak, and time of day.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AMBIENT OZONE">
      <data key="d0">AMBIENT OZONE</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">Ambient ozone concentration monitored during the study as an air-quality gas potentially affected by far-UVC exposure. It was measured using a Model 202 ozone monitor positioned near the air sampler.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.48</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TESTED ROOM">
      <data key="d0">TESTED ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The indoor room where ozone and particle concentration measurements were collected over a five-hour period. The room was monitored during normal working hours while the HVAC system continued its native operation, and it was described as having a high air exchange rate. | The indoor room where air-quality measurements and room air-exchange assessment were performed. The room had a documented total volume of 3,405 ft3 and was measured during normal working hours, typically with animal-care staff present.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
      <data key="d6">TEST ROOM</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ANIMAL-CARE STAFF OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">ANIMAL-CARE STAFF OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The typical human occupancy condition during normal working hours in the tested room. Animal-care staff members were typically present while measurements were taken.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.63</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_41,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MEASURED SUPPLY AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">MEASURED SUPPLY AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The mechanical supply-air delivery into the test room. The AAALAC facility verification report documented a total measured supply airflow of 2068 CFM, which was used with the room volume to estimate air changes per hour.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACH OF APPROXIMATELY 36">
      <data key="d0">ACH OF APPROXIMATELY 36</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The estimated air-change rate for the test room, calculated from the documented room volume of 3,405 ft3 and total measured supply airflow of 2068 CFM, assuming perfect mixing throughout the room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PERFECT MIXING ASSUMPTION">
      <data key="d0">PERFECT MIXING ASSUMPTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The assumed room air-distribution pattern used to convert measured supply airflow and room volume into an estimated ACH. Under this assumption, supplied air is uniformly mixed throughout the entire room volume.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CO2 TRACER GAS">
      <data key="d0">CO2 TRACER GAS</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">A tracer gas associated with concentration-decay methods for measuring room air-change rate. The text cites CO2 tracer-gas decay methods as relevant to characterizing room-level ventilation and mechanical air exchange.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_42,d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_73</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNOCCUPIED ROOM">
      <data key="d0">UNOCCUPIED ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The study room where tracer-gas decay testing was performed under an unoccupied condition. Carbon dioxide was released into this space, measured at multiple locations, and removed by mechanical ventilation. The room's supply airflow and volume were used to assign a ventilation rate of 36 ACH.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR CHANGES PER HOUR OF THE TRACER (ACHT)">
      <data key="d0">AIR CHANGES PER HOUR OF THE TRACER (ACHT)</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The tracer-derived air exchange rate calculated from the inverse slope of the linear regression of the natural logarithm of carbon dioxide concentration versus time. The decay experiment was repeated 10 times.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EQUIVALENT AIR CHANGE RATE DUE TO FAR-UVC">
      <data key="d0">EQUIVALENT AIR CHANGE RATE DUE TO FAR-UVC</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation-equivalent air change rate attributed to Far-UVC inactivation, denoted as Nuv in the equation. It is calculated from the ratio of average active virus measured with lamps off to average active virus measured with Far-UVC lamps on.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACTIVE VIRUS">
      <data key="d0">ACTIVE VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The viable airborne virus measured in samples under Far-UVC lamps-off and lamps-on conditions. The reduction in active virus is used to calculate the Far-UVC equivalent air change rate.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNOCCUPIED CONDITION">
      <data key="d0">UNOCCUPIED CONDITION</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The zero-occupancy condition of the room during tracer-gas decay experiments, reducing occupant-generated carbon dioxide and allowing ventilation-driven tracer decay to be characterized.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATED ROOM OR SPACE">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATED ROOM OR SPACE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The indoor room or space being analyzed for ventilation effectiveness, air mixing, and UVC-equivalent air disinfection. The cited derivation refers to a simulated hospital room environment, while the passage also discusses real-life room ventilation where perfect mixing is rarely achieved.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EQUIVALENT AIR CHANGE RATE DUE TO FAR-UVC, NUV">
      <data key="d0">EQUIVALENT AIR CHANGE RATE DUE TO FAR-UVC, NUV</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The equivalent air change rate attributed to Far-UVC air disinfection. It represents pathogen inactivation by UVC as an air-change-equivalent removal rate rather than as mechanical ventilation alone.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACTUAL VENTILATION RATE, N">
      <data key="d0">ACTUAL VENTILATION RATE, N</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The nominal ventilation rate determined from supply airflow and room volume. It is the starting ventilation rate before adjustment for incomplete mixing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EFFECTIVE VENTILATION RATE, N'">
      <data key="d0">EFFECTIVE VENTILATION RATE, N'</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation rate corrected for incomplete mixing using the equation N' = N/K. It reflects the ventilation rate that is effectively achieved in the occupied space when room air is not perfectly mixed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MIXING FACTOR, K">
      <data key="d0">MIXING FACTOR, K</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A dimensionless descriptor of room mixing and ventilation efficacy. K accounts for incomplete mixing within a space, with K = 1 indicating perfect mixing and values up to 10 indicating poorly mixed conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PERFECT MIXING">
      <data key="d0">PERFECT MIXING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The ideal limiting mixing condition represented by K = 1. Under perfect mixing, the effective ventilation rate equals the actual ventilation rate.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POORLY MIXED ROOM CONDITION">
      <data key="d0">POORLY MIXED ROOM CONDITION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A room air distribution condition represented by high K values, up to about 10. It indicates incomplete mixing and reduced effective ventilation compared with the actual ventilation rate.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LONG-TERM CARE FACILITIES">
      <data key="d0">LONG-TERM CARE FACILITIES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Healthcare-associated residential care environments where far-UVC light devices are being studied to reduce infections, making them relevant indoor zones for airborne infection-control evaluation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.62</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_61</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOM-LEVEL SPACES IN SCHOOLS AND UNIVERSITIES">
      <data key="d0">ROOM-LEVEL SPACES IN SCHOOLS AND UNIVERSITIES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor room-level zones referenced in the ventilation study of schools and universities. Although the setting is educational rather than clinical, this entity represents the occupied indoor zones for which room-level ventilation performance may be characterized.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_73</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
