      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_74</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OCCUPIED ROOM">
      <data key="d0">OCCUPIED ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The indoor room environment referenced in the article title where infectious airborne virus levels are reduced. Although not explicitly identified as a hospital room, it is the relevant occupied indoor zone in the provided text.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff_chunk_77</data>
      <data key="d5">d8e5e6fb-91d7-40aa-8229-b92309abbaff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INDOOR MASS GATHERING EVENTS">
      <data key="d0">INDOOR MASS GATHERING EVENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">High-occupancy indoor sports and culture event scenarios studied for potential SARS-CoV-2 transmission. The abstract emphasizes that crowding and visitor contacts contribute to transmission opportunity, while hygiene practices can reduce direct contacts. | Indoor MGE represent a high-occupancy and potentially high-contact setting. The text emphasizes that their epidemic contribution is usually small under precautions but can become substantial in unfavorable cases, especially when ventilation is poor or precautions are absent.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_0,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">INDOOR MASS-GATHERING EVENTS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MEAN DIRECT CONTACTS PER VISITOR">
      <data key="d0">MEAN DIRECT CONTACTS PER VISITOR</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The measured contact burden during the experimental event, reported as an average of nine direct contacts per visitor. This represents an occupancy-related exposure opportunity rather than a physical HVAC component.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POORER-PERFORMING VENTILATION VERSION">
      <data key="d0">POORER-PERFORMING VENTILATION VERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation configuration that performed worst in the comparison. It was associated with a ten-fold increase in the number of individuals exposed to infectious aerosols.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR EXCHANGE RATE CONDITIONS">
      <data key="d0">AIR EXCHANGE RATE CONDITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The different air exchange rates compared between ventilation versions. These rates are relevant to dilution and removal of infectious aerosols in the indoor environment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRFLOW PATTERN CONDITIONS">
      <data key="d0">AIRFLOW PATTERN CONDITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The different airflow configurations compared between ventilation versions. These patterns affected how infectious aerosols were transported and distributed through the indoor event space.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTIOUS SARS-COV-2 AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">INFECTIOUS SARS-COV-2 AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Aerosolized infectious particles containing SARS-CoV-2. The number of people exposed to these aerosols depended strongly on ventilation performance, air exchange rate, and airflow pattern.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
