      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROOF-DIRECTED EXHAUST AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">ROOF-DIRECTED EXHAUST AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">VV2 exhaust path directing air toward exhaust pipes located under the roof.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LARGE EDDIES AT FACE LEVEL">
      <data key="d0">LARGE EDDIES AT FACE LEVEL</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Unwanted airflow pattern associated with intensified aerosol spread at face level; avoidance of this pattern motivated turning off jet nozzles and exhaust towers in VV2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WEAK BUOYANCY-INDUCED UPWARD FLOW">
      <data key="d0">WEAK BUOYANCY-INDUCED UPWARD FLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Intended upward displacement flow toward the roof in VV2, but it was too weak because of low occupancy and interfering nearby grandstand air supply.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STATIONARY EDDIES ABOVE GRANDSTANDS">
      <data key="d0">STATIONARY EDDIES ABOVE GRANDSTANDS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Recirculating airflow pattern that emerged above the grandstands in VV2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOW OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">LOW OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Low number of occupants, which weakened buoyancy-induced upward flow in VV2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SOLID GRANDSTANDS">
      <data key="d0">SOLID GRANDSTANDS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">An occupied seating area in the modeled environment where mean exposure to infectious aerosols increased from 4.25 in VV1 to 69.0 in VV2. This was the highest reported increase among the areas, at about 16-fold.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="0.85 H−1 ACH">
      <data key="d0">0.85 H−1 ACH</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The air exchange rate reported for VV2. This low air exchange rate was identified as one explanation for the larger number of exposed individuals under VV2 because it reduced dilution and removal of infectious aerosols.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIRECT MOUTH-TO-MOUTH AEROSOL FLOW">
      <data key="d0">DIRECT MOUTH-TO-MOUTH AEROSOL FLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The aerosol transport mechanism shown by aerosol concentration isosurfaces: direct aerosol flow from the mouth of the transmitting individual to the mouth of the recipient. The same mechanism was observed for both VV1 and VV2, irrespective of position.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LESS AIR MOVEMENT AND SLOWER AIR MIXING IN VV2">
      <data key="d0">LESS AIR MOVEMENT AND SLOWER AIR MIXING IN VV2</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The air distribution condition associated with VV2. The text states that less air movement caused slower mixing of air, helping explain the higher number of exposed individuals under VV2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPOSED VISITORS IN VV1">
      <data key="d0">EXPOSED VISITORS IN VV1</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled visitor group exposed in the VV1 setting. Hygiene practices reduced the mean number of exposed visitors to 1.9 ± 1.5 SD in Scenario 2 and 0.7 ± 1.0 SD in Scenario 3. | Modeled visitor group exposed in the VV2 setting. Hygiene practices reduced the mean number of exposed visitors to 11.8 ± 13.5 SD in Scenario 2 and 5.3 ± 6.4 SD in Scenario 3, indicating a larger exposure burden than VV1.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">EXPOSED VISITORS IN VV2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2 POSITIVE INDIVIDUALS">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2 POSITIVE INDIVIDUALS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Infected individuals whose presence and tracing are part of the modeled epidemic context. The text considers contact tracing of SARS-CoV-2 positive individuals and the introduction of new cases by visitors from regions with higher incidence.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUSCEPTIBLE POPULATION">
      <data key="d0">SUSCEPTIBLE POPULATION</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Population group assumed to be largely susceptible because seroprevalence was considered negligible. This increases the relevance of occupancy and contact patterns for SARS-CoV-2 transmission during modeled indoor events.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="100,000 PARTICIPANTS PER MONTH">
      <data key="d0">100,000 PARTICIPANTS PER MONTH</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A lower mass-gathering-event occupancy-load condition. The text states that expected case numbers are lower for events with an overall size of 100,000 participants per month than for larger participant volumes.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_11</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="200,000 PARTICIPANTS">
      <data key="d0">200,000 PARTICIPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A larger mass-gathering-event occupancy-load condition associated with increased positive cases attributed to the event. Under high incidence, the text reports percentage increases in positive cases for this participant volume across hygiene, mask, and ventilation scenarios.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_11</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VV1 BETTER VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">VV1 BETTER VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">A modeled better or best ventilation condition. Although no numeric air-change rate is provided, VV1 represents a more favorable ventilation-rate condition associated with lower predicted SARS-CoV-2 infections than non-optimal ventilation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_11</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VV2 NON-OPTIMAL VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">VV2 NON-OPTIMAL VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">A modeled non-optimal or bad ventilation condition. Although no numeric air-change rate is provided, VV2 represents a less favorable ventilation-rate condition associated with higher predicted SARS-CoV-2 infections, hospitalizations, and possible deaths.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_11</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BETTER VENTILATION VV1">
      <data key="d0">BETTER VENTILATION VV1</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Improved ventilation condition referred to as VV1 in the high-incidence mass gathering setting. The text states that better or adequate ventilation lowers transmission risk and is especially important when contact numbers are low under physical distancing scenarios.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POOR VENTILATION SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">POOR VENTILATION SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">A qualitative condition of inadequate ventilation or low effective air exchange in indoor event settings. The text states that poor ventilation can considerably increase aerosol exposure and lead to a high number of infections.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH-CONTACT OR NO-PRECAUTION MGE">
      <data key="d0">HIGH-CONTACT OR NO-PRECAUTION MGE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A mass-gathering occupancy condition where attendees have many contacts and events occur without precautions. The text states that events without precautions can make a substantial contribution to epidemic spread.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PHYSICALLY DISTANCED MGE">
      <data key="d0">PHYSICALLY DISTANCED MGE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A reduced-contact mass-gathering occupancy condition created by physical distancing. The text notes that contact numbers are low in such scenarios, so effective risk depends primarily on ventilation adequacy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INDOOR AEROSOL EXPOSURE PATHWAY">
      <data key="d0">INDOOR AEROSOL EXPOSURE PATHWAY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The airborne exposure route by which pathogen-laden aerosols accumulate or are diluted in indoor event spaces. The text links poor ventilation to higher aerosol exposure and good ventilation to reduced infection impact.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_13,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEATED VISITOR OCCUPANCY PERIODS">
      <data key="d0">SEATED VISITOR OCCUPANCY PERIODS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupancy condition in which visitors remain in their seats during an indoor event. This is emphasized as a higher-concern period because aerosol exposure time can accumulate while attendees are stationary.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH-ATTENDANCE MASS GATHERING EVENT">
      <data key="d0">HIGH-ATTENDANCE MASS GATHERING EVENT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Large event occupancy scenario involving potentially thousands of attendees within a short time window. The text discusses this scale in relation to testing logistics, hygiene organization, and transmission-risk management.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.67</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ENTRY HALF-TIME AND EXIT CROWDING PHASES">
      <data key="d0">ENTRY HALF-TIME AND EXIT CROWDING PHASES</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Transient occupancy phases during a mass gathering event when contacts occur as attendees enter, move during half time, or exit. The text notes these phases are important for contacts but are generally short-duration compared with seated exposure periods.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.56</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPECTATOR AREA">
      <data key="d0">SPECTATOR AREA</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The occupied arena zone for which minimum ventilation requirements and per-person air-supply rates are discussed. Although not a hospital space, it is the relevant ventilated occupied zone in the text.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LEIPZIG ARENA AIR SUPPLY OF 198,000 M3 H-1">
      <data key="d0">LEIPZIG ARENA AIR SUPPLY OF 198,000 M3 H-1</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation air supply serving the Leipzig arena, delivering 198,000 cubic meters per hour. This supply is used to calculate the available outdoor-air rate per person under seated and standing occupancy assumptions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ASHRAE STANDARD 62.1-2013 MINIMUM VENTILATION RATE OF 3.8 L S-1 PER PERSON">
      <data key="d0">ASHRAE STANDARD 62.1-2013 MINIMUM VENTILATION RATE OF 3.8 L S-1 PER PERSON</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The referenced minimum ventilation recommendation for the spectator area. The arena's calculated per-person ventilation rates are compared against this benchmark.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEATED VENTILATION RATE OF 6.7 L S-1 PER PERSON">
      <data key="d0">SEATED VENTILATION RATE OF 6.7 L S-1 PER PERSON</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The calculated per-person ventilation rate in the spectator area when the arena is occupied by a maximum of 8,200 seated persons. It exceeds the ASHRAE recommendation by approximately 1.75 times. | The calculated per-person ventilation rate in the spectator area when the arena is occupied by a maximum of 12,300 standing persons. It exceeds the ASHRAE recommendation by approximately 1.2 times but is lower than the seated configuration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">STANDING VENTILATION RATE OF 4.5 L S-1 PER PERSON</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MAXIMUM 8,200 SEATED PERSON OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">MAXIMUM 8,200 SEATED PERSON OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The seated-occupancy condition used to calculate the arena's per-person ventilation rate of 6.7 l s-1 per person.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MAXIMUM 12,300 STANDING PERSON OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">MAXIMUM 12,300 STANDING PERSON OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The standing-occupancy condition used to calculate the arena's per-person ventilation rate of 4.5 l s-1 per person. This configuration represents denser occupancy than the seated condition.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LARGER CROWD CONDITIONS">
      <data key="d0">LARGER CROWD CONDITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">High-occupancy event conditions, such as soccer games or standing concerts, where crowding during entry and close proximity among visitors may increase the number of contacts.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEATED CONCERT ARENA">
      <data key="d0">SEATED CONCERT ARENA</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor occupied event space described as well ventilated, where participants had many short contacts and few long-lasting contacts. Although not a hospital zone, it is represented as the relevant indoor zone under the available schema.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WELL-VENTILATED AIR DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">WELL-VENTILATED AIR DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">General air distribution condition implied by the well-ventilated arena. Specific airflow paths, diffuser layouts, or pressure relationships are not provided.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONCERT PARTICIPANT OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">CONCERT PARTICIPANT OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupancy load consisting of mass gathering event participants. The text notes many short contacts, few long-lasting contacts, and possible increased impact if the same groups attend multiple events or have additional linked contacts.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRANSIT AND POST-CONCERT VENUES">
      <data key="d0">TRANSIT AND POST-CONCERT VENUES</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Additional non-arena settings, such as transit, bars, or similar venues after the concert, where contacts linked to the mass gathering event could occur. These settings are assumed to have their own hygiene practices and crowding controls.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QUARTERBACK IMMOBILIEN ARENA (QIA)">
      <data key="d0">QUARTERBACK IMMOBILIEN ARENA (QIA)</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor arena in Leipzig, Germany where the RESTART-19 experimental pop concert was conducted. Although it is not a hospital area, it is typed as HOSPITAL_ZONE because the schema uses this type for defined indoor built-environment zones in which ventilation, aerosol behavior, occupancy, and airborne transmission risk are assessed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INDOOR MASS GATHERING EVENTS (MGE)">
      <data key="d0">INDOOR MASS GATHERING EVENTS (MGE)</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Crowded indoor event condition studied by RESTART-19, represented by an experimental pop concert with many participants. This occupancy load affects the number of contacts, aerosol exposure, and the number of subjects potentially at risk, especially when hygiene practices are absent or ventilation is inadequate.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTICIPANTS">
      <data key="d0">PARTICIPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Individuals aged 18 to 50 years who voluntarily registered and attended the experimental concert. They represent the measured human occupancy load responsible for person-to-person contacts and breathing-air exposure during the indoor event.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INADEQUATE VENTILATION CONDITIONS">
      <data key="d0">INADEQUATE VENTILATION CONDITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Qualitative insufficient ventilation condition described as substantially increasing the number of subjects at risk when present with lack of hygiene practices and/or poor ventilation. No numeric ACH value is given, but the condition is directly linked to increased airborne transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="4000 PLANNED PARTICIPANTS">
      <data key="d0">4000 PLANNED PARTICIPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The study planned to include 4000 participants, representing half of the arena capacity. This planned occupancy load was intended to create a realistic event-density condition for assessing risks in a large indoor gathering.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="4200 HISTORICAL MEAN EVENT PARTICIPANTS">
      <data key="d0">4200 HISTORICAL MEAN EVENT PARTICIPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The mean event size for sports and cultural events at the location in 2019 was 4200 participants. This value provides a historical reference occupancy load for realistic arena crowd density.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.62</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="1212 TOTAL EXPERIMENTAL PARTICIPANTS">
      <data key="d0">1212 TOTAL EXPERIMENTAL PARTICIPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A total of 1212 persons participated in the experiment. This was the actual total participant load across the study day, although not all participants were present during every scenario.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="1192 SCENARIO 1 PARTICIPANTS">
      <data key="d0">1192 SCENARIO 1 PARTICIPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Scenario 1 had 1192 participants present. This scenario-specific occupancy load represents the crowd size under the first hygiene-practice condition. | Scenario 3 had 1054 participants present. This was the lowest scenario-specific occupancy load among the three experimental scenarios.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">1054 SCENARIO 3 PARTICIPANTS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INDOOR CONCERT ARENA">
      <data key="d0">INDOOR CONCERT ARENA</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupied indoor event space where participants entered, sat, attended the live concert performance, and exited during each simulated scenario. Typed as a zone because the valid schema represents occupied indoor areas using HOSPITAL_ZONE.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTICIPANTS (N = 1212)">
      <data key="d0">PARTICIPANTS (N = 1212)</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Total participant population registered for the event. The text notes that the number present in individual scenarios was smaller because not all participants attended every scenario.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SCENARIO 1 UNRESTRICTED ARENA OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">SCENARIO 1 UNRESTRICTED ARENA OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Pre-pandemic-style, highest-density occupancy condition. Participants entered and exited through two main entrances without restrictions and were seated without free seats between them.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SCENARIO 2 CHECKERBOARD QUADRANT OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">SCENARIO 2 CHECKERBOARD QUADRANT OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Moderate hygiene and occupancy-management condition. The arena was divided into four quadrants, participants were restricted to their assigned quadrant, four entrances/exits were used, and every second seat was occupied in a shifted checkerboard pattern.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SCENARIO 3 PAIRWISE DISTANCED OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">SCENARIO 3 PAIRWISE DISTANCED OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Strongest contact-reduction condition. Participants were seated in pairs with at least 1.5 m between occupied seat pairs, and the number of entrances/exits was increased to eight.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ARENA QUADRANTS">
      <data key="d0">ARENA QUADRANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Four sub-zones into which the arena was divided in Scenario 2 to restrict participant mixing. Typed as zones because they represent separated occupied areas within the indoor venue.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.62</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO MAIN ENTRANCES AND EXITS">
      <data key="d0">TWO MAIN ENTRANCES AND EXITS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Unrestricted entry and exit routes used in Scenario 1. Although described as participant routes rather than ventilation airflow paths, they are represented as AIR_PATH because the valid schema includes path-like connections only under this type.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.52</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FOUR QUADRANT ENTRANCES AND EXITS">
      <data key="d0">FOUR QUADRANT ENTRANCES AND EXITS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Assigned entry and exit routes used in Scenario 2, with one entrance/exit arrangement associated with each arena quadrant to reduce cross-quadrant mixing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.56</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EIGHT ENTRANCES AND EXITS">
      <data key="d0">EIGHT ENTRANCES AND EXITS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Expanded set of entry and exit routes used in Scenario 3 as part of stronger contact-reduction measures.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="QUARTERBACK IMMOBILIEN ARENA">
      <data key="d0">QUARTERBACK IMMOBILIEN ARENA</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor multipurpose event arena in Leipzig with a total room volume of 135,000 m3 and seating capacity up to 8,228 people. It is the overall indoor domain served by the described 100% fresh-air mechanical ventilation system.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.97</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_20,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EVENT ROOM">
      <data key="d0">EVENT ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Main occupied event space reached from corridors branching off the tunnel system. It is the principal gathering area where spectators occupy seats and where airborne contaminant dilution and transport are relevant.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FOYER">
      <data key="d0">FOYER</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Entry and transition zone at the south end of the arena. The west and east main entrances open into this area before visitors move onward into the long tunnel system.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.67</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INNER SPACE">
      <data key="d0">INNER SPACE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Central interior arena volume toward which jet nozzles on the long side of the grandstand blow air. It is a key region affected by directed air distribution from the ventilation system.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO LONG TUNNELS">
      <data key="d0">TWO LONG TUNNELS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Two elongated circulation zones running parallel to the arena interior on each side of the hall. Visitors move from the foyer into these tunnels before reaching corridors that lead to the event room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CORRIDORS BRANCHING OFF THE TUNNELS">
      <data key="d0">CORRIDORS BRANCHING OFF THE TUNNELS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Secondary circulation spaces branching from the long tunnels and providing visitor access into the event room. They create physical connection routes between circulation and occupied event areas.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WEST AND EAST MAIN ENTRANCES">
      <data key="d0">WEST AND EAST MAIN ENTRANCES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The two usual pre-pandemic main entrance points on the west and east sides of the arena, both opening into the foyer. They function as major people-entry openings and potential air-exchange paths.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMERGENCY EXITS ON THE LONG SIDES">
      <data key="d0">EMERGENCY EXITS ON THE LONG SIDES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Emergency exit openings located on each long side of the building, described as four on each long side. These exits were used in Scenarios 2 and 3 for entering and exiting the arena, increasing the number of usable entrances/exits to eight.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OUTLETS UNDER THE GRANDSTANDS">
      <data key="d0">OUTLETS UNDER THE GRANDSTANDS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Supply-air outlets located under the grandstands with a stated airflow capacity of 114,000 m3 h-1. They deliver ventilation air into the spectator seating region. | Supply-air outlets located below the lateral grandstands. In the actual ventilation variant, they are one of the routes by which air reaches the arena.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">OUTLETS UNDER THE LATERAL GRANDSTANDS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="JET NOZZLES ABOVE THE HEADS OF THE SPECTATORS">
      <data key="d0">JET NOZZLES ABOVE THE HEADS OF THE SPECTATORS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">High-level supply nozzles positioned along the long side of the grandstand above spectator head height. They blow air downstream toward the inner arena space with a stated flow of 84,000 m3 h-1.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="APPROXIMATE 1.47 ACH FRESH-AIR VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">APPROXIMATE 1.47 ACH FRESH-AIR VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Derived approximate fresh-air air-change rate for the arena, calculated from the stated total ventilation capacity of 198,000 m3 h-1 divided by the arena room volume of 135,000 m3. Because the system uses 100% fresh air, this represents approximate outdoor-air ACH.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DOWNSTREAM AIRFLOW TOWARD THE INNER SPACE">
      <data key="d0">DOWNSTREAM AIRFLOW TOWARD THE INNER SPACE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Directional supply-air pattern in which jet nozzles above the spectators blow air downstream from the grandstand side toward the inner arena space. This pattern can influence dilution and aerosol transport within the arena.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEATING CAPACITY OF UP TO 8,228 PEOPLE">
      <data key="d0">SEATING CAPACITY OF UP TO 8,228 PEOPLE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Maximum stated seating capacity of the arena. This occupancy load is relevant because larger numbers of spectators can increase respiratory aerosol emission and potential airborne pathogen source strength.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OCCUPIED PAIRS OF SEATS WITH 1.5 M SPACING">
      <data key="d0">OCCUPIED PAIRS OF SEATS WITH 1.5 M SPACING</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Scenario-specific seating arrangement with 1.5 m distance between occupied pairs of seats. It describes a reduced-density occupancy pattern affecting proximity between spectators and aggregate aerosol source distribution.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.73</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTICIPANTS AND STAFF MEMBERS">
      <data key="d0">PARTICIPANTS AND STAFF MEMBERS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The human occupancy population for the event, including all participants and staff. They were subject to SARS-CoV-2 PCR testing before the event, onsite exclusion criteria, and mandatory N95 mask use from entering to leaving the arena and while queueing outside entrances and exits.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EVENT ARENA">
      <data key="d0">EVENT ARENA</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The main indoor event space where entry was restricted to individuals with valid registration, identification, acceptable SARS-CoV-2 test results, no fever, no recent COVID-19 symptoms, and no recent high-risk exposure. N95 mask use was mandatory inside this zone.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ENTRANCE AND EXIT QUEUES OUTSIDE THE ARENA">
      <data key="d0">ENTRANCE AND EXIT QUEUES OUTSIDE THE ARENA</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Outdoor or exterior queueing areas at the arena entrances and exits where participants were also required to wear N95 masks. These areas are operationally connected to the event arena because participants pass through them when entering or leaving.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OUTDOOR CATERING AREA">
      <data key="d0">OUTDOOR CATERING AREA</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">An exterior catering area outside the arena where participants were allowed to remove masks only if a distance of 1.5 meters could be maintained. Catering was provided free of charge to reduce waiting times and discourage participants from leaving the controlled event area.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.45</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTICIPANTS INSIDE THE ARENA">
      <data key="d0">PARTICIPANTS INSIDE THE ARENA</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Event participants occupying the indoor arena during the scenarios. They are the primary occupancy load relevant to potential SARS-CoV-2 exposure, although the protocol required distancing of 1.5 m except in the first scenario and included mask, hygiene, and contact-tracing measures.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="40 HYGIENE STEWARDS INSIDE THE ARENA">
      <data key="d0">40 HYGIENE STEWARDS INSIDE THE ARENA</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Forty hygiene stewards present inside the arena. They add to the indoor occupancy load but were specifically assigned to ensure compliance with distancing and hygiene practices, reducing risky participant behavior.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EVENT STAFF">
      <data key="d0">EVENT STAFF</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Staff involved in check-in, briefing, and event operations. They received detailed hygiene-practice training and interacted with participants, including providing information sheets on hygiene rules, N95 mask use, and hand sanitizer use.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EVENT PARTICIPANTS">
      <data key="d0">EVENT PARTICIPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Participants at the event wore personalized contact tracing devices around their necks. The text notes a high number of participants/devices transmitting simultaneously, which affected proximity signal recording.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_23,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION WITHIN THE ARENA">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION WITHIN THE ARENA</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled spatial distribution of aerosols inside the arena, assessed through CFD simulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPLETE VENTILATION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">COMPLETE VENTILATION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The full ventilation system included in the 1:1 CFD model of the Quarterback Immobilien Arena. It represents the air-handling infrastructure relevant to simulated airflow and aerosol transport; the text does not specify individual air-handling units, supply branches, return branches, airflow rates, or service zones.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_25,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRTUAL SPECTATORS">
      <data key="d0">VIRTUAL SPECTATORS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled occupants seated in the arena during the CFD simulation. They represent an occupancy load that may affect airflow obstruction, exposure locations, and aerosol source or receptor placement, although the excerpt does not provide their number, activity level, or emission characteristics.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="GRANDSTANDS AND SEATS">
      <data key="d0">GRANDSTANDS AND SEATS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The spectator seating areas included in the exact 1:1 CFD representation of the arena. They provide the physical area where virtual spectators were placed, but the text does not specify detailed airflow or pressure characteristics for this zone.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RBACK IMMOBILIEN ARENA">
      <data key="d0">RBACK IMMOBILIEN ARENA</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Primary indoor modeled space represented as an exact 1:1 3D model, including built-on components, the complete ventilation system, grandstands, and seats. Although it is not a hospital area, it is typed as HOSPITAL_ZONE because the valid schema uses this type for modeled occupied indoor zones.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FRONT OF THE STALLS">
      <data key="d0">FRONT OF THE STALLS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Front sub-zone of the stalls where infectious persons were placed to represent local airflow and aerosol-emission conditions in the forward part of the seating area.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BACK OF THE STALLS">
      <data key="d0">BACK OF THE STALLS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Rear sub-zone of the stalls where infectious persons were placed to represent local airflow and aerosol-emission conditions in the back part of the seating area.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.66</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STANDS">
      <data key="d0">STANDS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupied seating zone in the modeled arena. Room air flows in the stands were considered separately from those in the stalls, supporting comparison of airflow and aerosol transport across seating regions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWELVE INFECTIOUS-PERSON SEATING BLOCKS">
      <data key="d0">TWELVE INFECTIOUS-PERSON SEATING BLOCKS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Subset of 12 out of 32 seating blocks in which the 24 infectious persons were seated. These blocks define the spatial distribution of infectious aerosol sources in the simulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="4000 VIRTUAL SPECTATORS">
      <data key="d0">4000 VIRTUAL SPECTATORS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled spectator occupancy load installed in the arena. Spectators were seated in a checkerboard pattern, with every second chair left free, and all emitted breathing air containing CO2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWENTY-FOUR INFECTIOUS PERSONS">
      <data key="d0">TWENTY-FOUR INFECTIOUS PERSONS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Infectious subset of the modeled spectators. These persons were seated in 12 of 32 blocks and positioned to capture airflow differences in stalls and stands; they emitted infectious aerosols while breathing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTIOUS AEROSOLS OF 0.5, 5, AND 10 ΜM">
      <data key="d0">INFECTIOUS AEROSOLS OF 0.5, 5, AND 10 ΜM</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Pathogen-bearing aerosol particles emitted by infectious spectators while breathing. The modeled particle sizes were 0.5, 5, and 10 µm, with emission rate and particle-size assumptions adjusted to data for singing people.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGING, SHOUTING, OR CHEERING PARTICIPANTS">
      <data key="d0">SINGING, SHOUTING, OR CHEERING PARTICIPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled occupant activity condition associated with elevated respiration. The passage assumes a breathing volume of 12 l min−1 per person and increased associated CO2 because singing, shouting, or cheering is expected to raise respiratory output.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTIOUS PARTICIPANTS">
      <data key="d0">INFECTIOUS PARTICIPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupants treated as infectious aerosol sources. Their exhaled virus-containing aerosols are dispersed through the arena model and used to quantify exposure of spectators.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_27,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VIRTUAL MOUTH RESPIRATION OPENINGS">
      <data key="d0">VIRTUAL MOUTH RESPIRATION OPENINGS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled mouth openings assigned to each dummy for respiration and exposure assessment. These openings act as local air-exchange and sampling points where aerosol exposure is measured directly in the model.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.79</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACTUAL VENTILATION SYSTEM OF THE ARENA">
      <data key="d0">ACTUAL VENTILATION SYSTEM OF THE ARENA</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Baseline ventilation configuration representing the real arena system. Air is supplied through outlets under the lateral grandstands and jet nozzles, while air is extracted through suction towers in the hall corners. The system supplies 198,000 m3 h-1 and corresponds to 1.46 air changes per hour.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MODIFIED VENTILATION SYSTEM IN THE ARENA">
      <data key="d0">MODIFIED VENTILATION SYSTEM IN THE ARENA</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Virtual alternative ventilation configuration designed to enable displacement flow. It adds two long roof-level exhaust pipes along the arena length and switches off the jet nozzles and corner suction towers to avoid large eddies. The air supply is reduced to 115,000 m3 h-1, corresponding to 0.85 h-1.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CORNER AIR-SUCTION TOWERS">
      <data key="d0">CORNER AIR-SUCTION TOWERS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Air-extraction towers installed as two towers in each corner of the hall. They provide suction in the actual ventilation configuration and are switched off in the modified displacement-flow variant.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TWO LONG EXHAUST PIPES UNDER THE ROOF">
      <data key="d0">TWO LONG EXHAUST PIPES UNDER THE ROOF</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Virtual roof-level exhaust pathways installed along the full length of the arena in the modified ventilation scenario. They are intended to support displacement flow by removing air near the roof without using the original jet nozzles and corner suction towers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISPLACEMENT FLOW">
      <data key="d0">DISPLACEMENT FLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Targeted airflow pattern in the modified ventilation variant. The design attempts to move contaminated air upward and out through roof-level exhaust pipes while avoiding strong turbulent mixing from jet nozzles and suction towers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LARGE EDDIES">
      <data key="d0">LARGE EDDIES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Undesired turbulent airflow structures that the modified ventilation scenario seeks to avoid by switching off the jet nozzles and corner suction towers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEATED PARTICIPANTS IN THE ARENA">
      <data key="d0">SEATED PARTICIPANTS IN THE ARENA</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The occupied seating population used in the exposure analysis. Aerosol-dispersion results are mapped to the seating arrangement to identify affected persons and exposure levels.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AFFECTED PERSONS WITH INCREASED AEROSOL EXPOSURE">
      <data key="d0">AFFECTED PERSONS WITH INCREASED AEROSOL EXPOSURE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Participants whose modeled aerosol exposure exceeds or approaches the study-defined exposure threshold. Their number and level of exposure are derived from dispersion results mapped onto the seating arrangement.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_28</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR EXCHANGE RATE OF 0.85 H−1">
      <data key="d0">AIR EXCHANGE RATE OF 0.85 H−1</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The modeled ventilation condition, expressed as 0.85 air changes per hour. This air exchange rate is relevant to how quickly airborne aerosols are diluted or removed from the indoor environment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGING PERSON">
      <data key="d0">SINGING PERSON</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">An occupant activity condition associated with high aerosol emission. In the model, a singing person emits about 1000 aerosol particles, corresponding to 7.53 × 10−8 ml of aerosols per second.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESTING PERSON">
      <data key="d0">RESTING PERSON</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">An occupant activity condition associated with much lower aerosol emission. The text states that a resting person emits only about one-hundredth of the particles emitted by a singing person.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PRE-SYMPTOMATIC OR EARLY SYMPTOMATIC INFECTIOUS VISITORS">
      <data key="d0">PRE-SYMPTOMATIC OR EARLY SYMPTOMATIC INFECTIOUS VISITORS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Infectious occupants who are likely to be pre-symptomatic or at the beginning of symptoms, when viral load is described as peaking. Their presence is important because peak viral load increases potential aerosolized SARS-CoV-2 emission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGING INFECTIOUS SPECTATOR DURING 90-MINUTE CONCERT">
      <data key="d0">SINGING INFECTIOUS SPECTATOR DURING 90-MINUTE CONCERT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">An infectious concert spectator engaged in singing for a 90-minute concert. The text estimates this activity emits approximately 4 × 10^5 virus copies, reflecting substantially increased aerosol emission during singing. | An infectious concert spectator at rest during a 90-minute concert. The text estimates this condition emits approximately 4 × 10^3 virus copies, about 100-fold lower than the singing scenario.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">RESTING INFECTIOUS SPECTATOR DURING 90-MINUTE CONCERT</data>
    </node>
    <node id="100,000 EVENT PARTICIPANTS PER 30 DAYS">
      <data key="d0">100,000 EVENT PARTICIPANTS PER 30 DAYS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A modeled event occupancy scenario with 100,000 participants over 30 days, corresponding to approximately 3300 participants per day, used to assess COVID-19 outcomes under different incidence and mask assumptions. | A modeled higher event occupancy scenario with 200,000 participants over 30 days, corresponding to approximately 6700 participants per day and described as the pre-pandemic participation level.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">200,000 EVENT PARTICIPANTS PER 30 DAYS</data>
    </node>
    <node id="3300 PARTICIPANTS PER DAY">
      <data key="d0">3300 PARTICIPANTS PER DAY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The daily participant load corresponding to the 100,000-participant-per-30-day scenario. | The daily participant load corresponding to the 200,000-participant-per-30-day scenario and identified as the pre-pandemic event level.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.69</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
      <data key="d6">6700 PARTICIPANTS PER DAY</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HOUSEHOLD OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">HOUSEHOLD OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Model contact setting in which each person is assigned exactly one home place or household.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DAY-CARE OR SCHOOL CLASS OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">DAY-CARE OR SCHOOL CLASS OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Model contact setting for persons aged 0–19 years; each class consists of 20 children and one teacher aged 20–64 years.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WORKPLACE OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">WORKPLACE OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Model contact setting for persons aged 20–69 years, excluding teachers; workplace size is assigned using four categories reported by the Federal Statistical Office in Germany, with age-dependent random workplace selection.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EVENT ATTENDANCE OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">EVENT ATTENDANCE OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Daily event attendance is randomly drawn from the entire population, excluding people who tested positive and people below 15 years of age; event contacts include proximity and aerosol contacts based on an experimental concert.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OTHER-CONTACT SETTING OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">OTHER-CONTACT SETTING OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Non-household and non-school/work contact setting derived from POLYMOD categories including transport, leisure, and other contacts.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL CONTACT EXPOSURE">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL CONTACT EXPOSURE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Represents the modeled airborne or aerosol-related infectious exposure pathway considered for event contacts; the specific pathogen is not named in the provided text.</data>
