    </node>
    <node id="UNMASKED SINGING WIDE AEROSOL DISPERSION UP TO 1.3 M">
      <data key="d0">UNMASKED SINGING WIDE AEROSOL DISPERSION UP TO 1.3 M</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Observed air/aerosol distribution pattern during singing without a surgical mask. Exhaled aerosols spread widely away from the singer and reached measured distances up to 1.3 m.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_0</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CHOIR SINGERS">
      <data key="d0">CHOIR SINGERS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupants engaged in singing, an activity that generates and disperses aerosols. Their positioning and proximity are central to the discussion of contamination risk and mitigation by masks and aeration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMPACT CHOIR SINGER ASSEMBLY">
      <data key="d0">COMPACT CHOIR SINGER ASSEMBLY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A denser spatial arrangement of choir singers. The text states that, when surgical masks are combined with an appropriate aeration strategy, singers could potentially be positioned more compactly without contaminating neighboring singers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGING-GENERATED AEROSOL DISPERSION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">SINGING-GENERATED AEROSOL DISPERSION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The spread pattern of aerosols emitted during singing. The study focuses on reducing the range of this dispersion to lower exposure of neighboring singers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SURGICAL-MASK-LIMITED EXHALED AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">SURGICAL-MASK-LIMITED EXHALED AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The altered exhaled airflow and aerosol path produced when singers wear surgical masks. The entity represents the mask-modified air path rather than the mask as a standalone object, because mask/PPE is not an available entity type.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SURGICAL-MASK-LIMITED AEROSOL DISPERSION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">SURGICAL-MASK-LIMITED AEROSOL DISPERSION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The reduced-range aerosol distribution pattern observed when surgical masks are used during singing. This pattern is described as an effective means of limiting aerosol spread.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL REMOVAL AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL REMOVAL AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The airflow route by which aerosols are removed from the singer-occupied area. It represents the functional air path implied by the appropriate aeration strategy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL REMOVAL AERATION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL REMOVAL AERATION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation or aeration distribution pattern intended to remove aerosols from the occupied choir area. No specific ACH value or HVAC unit is provided in the text.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DROPLET AND AEROSOL TRANSMISSION PATH">
      <data key="d0">DROPLET AND AEROSOL TRANSMISSION PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The airborne pathway for respiratory droplets with diameters of at least 5 μm and smaller aerosol particles with diameters of 5 μm or less, as described for person-to-person COVID-19 transmission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_1</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2-LADEN DROPLETS AND AEROSOL PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2-LADEN DROPLETS AND AEROSOL PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Virus-containing respiratory particles in the approximate size range of 0.001–500 μm that can be expelled by infected occupants and contribute to close-range droplet exposure and longer-range aerosol inhalation risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLOSED ROOMS WITHOUT APPROPRIATE VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">CLOSED ROOMS WITHOUT APPROPRIATE VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor room environment lacking sufficient ventilation, where aerosol particles may accumulate and create potential inhalation exposure to SARS-CoV-2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INSUFFICIENT VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">INSUFFICIENT VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Inadequate air exchange condition implied by closed rooms without appropriate ventilation; this condition can allow exhaled aerosol particles to persist and accumulate indoors.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONVECTIVE AEROSOL SPREAD ACROSS LARGE ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">CONVECTIVE AEROSOL SPREAD ACROSS LARGE ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Distribution pattern in which aerosol particles remain suspended in air and are transported convectively through the indoor environment, spreading beyond close proximity to the emitter into larger regions and rooms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACCUMULATED AEROSOL PARTICLES IN CLOSED ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">ACCUMULATED AEROSOL PARTICLES IN CLOSED ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor aerosol persistence and buildup pattern associated with insufficient ventilation, creating conditions for inhalation of potentially infectious particles.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLOSE-PROXIMITY DROPLET EXPOSURE NEAR EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">CLOSE-PROXIMITY DROPLET EXPOSURE NEAR EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Short-range exposure pattern in which virus-laden droplets are mainly received when a susceptible person is close to the infected emitter.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUPER-EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">SUPER-EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupant emission profile characterized by expulsion of much larger quantities of droplets and aerosol particles, especially during loud speaking, singing, sneezing, or coughing, thereby posing elevated COVID-19 transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH-EMISSION EXHALATION ACTIVITIES">
      <data key="d0">HIGH-EMISSION EXHALATION ACTIVITIES</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupant activities such as extensive and loud speaking, singing, sneezing, and coughing that increase respiratory droplet and aerosol production; singing is specifically noted as a high-risk activity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CHOIR SINGING">
      <data key="d0">CHOIR SINGING</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">High-emission group vocal activity associated with documented severe or fatal SARS-CoV-2 infectious events in Amsterdam, Berlin, and Skagit County, Washington. It represents an occupancy/activity condition likely to elevate aerosol release.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_3,ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_64</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VOWEL-RICH SPOKEN PHRASES">
      <data key="d0">VOWEL-RICH SPOKEN PHRASES</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Spoken text passages containing a higher number of vowel sounds, described as increasing particle emission rates during speech.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.62</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POTENTIALLY VIRUS-LADEN RESPIRATORY AEROSOLS AND BALLISTIC DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">POTENTIALLY VIRUS-LADEN RESPIRATORY AEROSOLS AND BALLISTIC DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory particles expelled during singing, speaking, or breathing that may carry infectious virus. The text emphasizes that the directly expelled aerosol cloud contains the highest density of these potentially infectious aerosol particles and ballistic droplets.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIRECTLY EXPELLED AEROSOL CLOUD">
      <data key="d0">DIRECTLY EXPELLED AEROSOL CLOUD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A near-field aerosol distribution pattern expelled directly from a singer. It is described as having the highest density of potentially virus-laden aerosol particles and ballistic droplets and extending up to approximately 1.5 m in front of the singer and 1 m to the sides.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGING IN CHOIRS AND RELIGIOUS SERVICES">
      <data key="d0">SINGING IN CHOIRS AND RELIGIOUS SERVICES</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">An occupancy and activity scenario in which people sing together, often near one another. The text states that this setting was considered high risk for person-to-person transmission of infectious diseases and was therefore restricted or prohibited in some countries.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGERS IN CLOSE PROXIMITY">
      <data key="d0">SINGERS IN CLOSE PROXIMITY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A choir-related occupancy condition in which singers remain close to one another, increasing the chance that individuals are positioned within another singer's dense near-field aerosol cloud.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PEOPLE IN THE NEAR-FIELD AEROSOL REGION">
      <data key="d0">PEOPLE IN THE NEAR-FIELD AEROSOL REGION</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Individuals located within the high-density aerosol zone directly in front of and to the sides of a singer. The text identifies this region as a high infection-risk area because of concentrated potentially virus-laden aerosols and ballistic droplets.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CHOIR SINGERS IN CLOSE PROXIMITY">
      <data key="d0">CHOIR SINGERS IN CLOSE PROXIMITY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A close-spacing occupancy condition in choir performance where singers remain near one another. The text identifies this proximity as important for performance quality but relevant to airborne-transmission risk because respiratory emissions from one singer can more readily reach nearby singers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A coronavirus cited among viruses associated with airborne transmission risk that can be reduced by non-pharmaceutical measures such as distancing, masks, and face shields.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED RESPIRATORY JET">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED RESPIRATORY JET</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Airflow emitted from the mouth during respiratory activities such as speaking, coughing, or sneezing; discussed as the route by which droplets and aerosols move away from the wearer.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CHEEK AND NOSE-BRIDGE LEAKAGE FLOW">
      <data key="d0">CHEEK AND NOSE-BRIDGE LEAKAGE FLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Airflow escaping through gaps at the cheeks and nose bridge around surgical and KN95-style masks, identified in experimental and numerical studies as a pathway for aerosol escape.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AMBIENT AIR AROUND MASK WEARER">
      <data key="d0">AMBIENT AIR AROUND MASK WEARER</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The surrounding air into which leaked exhaled airflow and aerosol particles may disperse after escaping through mask gaps.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY AEROSOL PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY AEROSOL PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Small respiratory particles that can travel with leakage airflow through mask gaps; represented here as airborne pathogen carriers relevant to transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BALLISTIC COUGH AND SNEEZE DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">BALLISTIC COUGH AND SNEEZE DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Larger respiratory droplets generated especially by coughing and sneezing, described as having ballistic behavior and being effectively filtered by three-layer medical masks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MOUTH-TO-ENVIRONMENT RESPIRATORY EMISSION PATH">
      <data key="d0">MOUTH-TO-ENVIRONMENT RESPIRATORY EMISSION PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The path taken by droplets and aerosol particles after emission from the mouth into the surrounding environment. The distance along this path depends on loudness and activity type, with coughing-associated droplets reported up to 8 m from the mouth.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPIRATORY ACTIVITY LEVEL">
      <data key="d0">EXPIRATORY ACTIVITY LEVEL</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Human emission activity load represented by vocalizing, speaking, consonant articulation, and coughing. These activities affect the amount and distance of respiratory droplet emission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.81</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DROPLET BALLISTIC SETTLING PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">DROPLET BALLISTIC SETTLING PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Distribution behavior of larger expelled droplets after release, characterized by ballistic trajectories and relatively rapid descent toward the ground.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPELLED AEROSOL AND DROPLET DISPERSION PLUME">
      <data key="d0">EXPELLED AEROSOL AND DROPLET DISPERSION PLUME</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The spatial dispersion field formed by expelled aerosol particles and droplets. The text notes that this dispersion can be investigated using qualitative and quantitative flow visualization methods.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.79</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SMOKE OR ILLUMINATED TRACER VISUALIZATION">
      <data key="d0">SMOKE OR ILLUMINATED TRACER VISUALIZATION</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">Visualization medium used to reveal respiratory flow and particle dispersion patterns, including smoke visualization with bright light or laser light-sheet illumination. It represents the closest valid typed entity for the flow-visualization tracers described.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.67</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL TRANSMISSION OF AIRBORNE PATHOGENS IN ICU ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL TRANSMISSION OF AIRBORNE PATHOGENS IN ICU ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled movement and dispersion of pathogen-containing aerosols through ICU room air, relevant to airborne exposure risk and room airflow behavior.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SMOKE AND PARTICLE FLOW TRACERS">
      <data key="d0">SMOKE AND PARTICLE FLOW TRACERS</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">Tracer media used in smoke visualization and particle-based optical methods such as Particle Image Velocimetry and Particle Tracking Velocimetry to reveal airflow and droplet-dispersion patterns.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MANIKIN AND SINGLE-HUMAN-SUBJECT RESPIRATORY SOURCES">
      <data key="d0">MANIKIN AND SINGLE-HUMAN-SUBJECT RESPIRATORY SOURCES</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Experimental human or manikin source conditions used to generate or simulate exhaled airflow and respiratory droplet dispersion in visualization studies.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.62</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE RESPIRATORY AEROSOL ROUTE">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE RESPIRATORY AEROSOL ROUTE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The airborne route through which respiratory aerosol particles and droplets can travel from an emitting person and potentially contribute to SARS-CoV-2 transmission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THREE-DIMENSIONAL AEROSOL DISPERSION DURING PROFESSIONAL SINGING">
      <data key="d0">THREE-DIMENSIONAL AEROSOL DISPERSION DURING PROFESSIONAL SINGING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The spatial and temporal distribution pattern of aerosol particles emitted during professional singing, explicitly studied in all three spatial directions and compared with and without a surgical mask.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FORWARD BALLISTIC DROPLET PATH">
      <data key="d0">FORWARD BALLISTIC DROPLET PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The path of larger ballistic droplets detected in front of the singer during the second experiment, used to assess filtering efficiency with and without a mask.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BAYERISCHER RUNDFUNK STUDIO">
      <data key="d0">BAYERISCHER RUNDFUNK STUDIO</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The enclosed indoor experimental zone where the aerosol and droplet dispersion experiments were performed; typed as a zone because the valid schema does not include a general studio or room type.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BR STUDIO EXPERIMENTAL ROOM">
      <data key="d0">BR STUDIO EXPERIMENTAL ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The indoor studio of the Bayerischer Rundfunk where the singing aerosol experiments were performed. Although not a hospital space, it is represented as a zone in the available schema because it is the defined indoor environment in which airborne particle dispersion was studied.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_11</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TEN PROFESSIONAL SINGERS OF THE BR CHOIR">
      <data key="d0">TEN PROFESSIONAL SINGERS OF THE BR CHOIR</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A study occupant group of ten professional full-time choir singers, five male and five female, all nonsmokers and without pulmonary symptoms. Their professional singing activity represents the respiratory aerosol-generating occupancy load examined in the experiment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_11</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL DISPERSION DURING PROFESSIONAL SINGING">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL DISPERSION DURING PROFESSIONAL SINGING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The observed spatial distribution of expelled aerosol particles produced during professional singing, including assessment of where the highest aerosol concentration is localized and how dispersion changes with and without a surgical mask.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_11,ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_63</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIGH AEROSOL CONCENTRATION REGION IN FRONT OF THE SINGER">
      <data key="d0">HIGH AEROSOL CONCENTRATION REGION IN FRONT OF THE SINGER</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The localized region in front of singers where expelled aerosol or droplets were evaluated to determine maximum concentration and mask filtering influence during singing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_11</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COVID-19 AIRBORNE VIRUS PANDEMIC CONTEXT">
      <data key="d0">COVID-19 AIRBORNE VIRUS PANDEMIC CONTEXT</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The airborne-spreading virus pandemic context motivating the study. The text refers to CoVID-19 as the relevant infectious-risk scenario for which choir rehearsal and performance mitigation strategies are needed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_11</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BR STUDIO MEASUREMENT ROOM">
      <data key="d0">BR STUDIO MEASUREMENT ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Large indoor studio space where aerosol visualization measurements were performed; approximate dimensions were 27 m × 22 m × 9 m.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGLE SINGER OCCUPANCY">
      <data key="d0">SINGLE SINGER OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">One singer stood on a lifting platform during each singing task, with task duration approximately 6–10 seconds depending on individual singing speed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGING-GENERATED AEROSOL CLOUD">
      <data key="d0">SINGING-GENERATED AEROSOL CLOUD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Exhaled aerosol cloud produced during singing and visualized from side, front, and top perspectives in the studio.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_12</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGING SUBJECTS">
      <data key="d0">SINGING SUBJECTS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Human singers participating in the experiment; their singing activity generated exhaled airflow that was visualized and recorded.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGER EXHALATION PATH">
      <data key="d0">SINGER EXHALATION PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The path of expelled air moving from the singer’s mouth into the surrounding space during singing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPELLED AIR CLOUD DURING SINGING">
      <data key="d0">EXPELLED AIR CLOUD DURING SINGING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The visible spatial distribution of exhaled air produced during singing, recorded synchronously from side, front, and top perspectives.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="E-CIGARETTE VAPOR TRACER MIXTURE">
      <data key="d0">E-CIGARETTE VAPOR TRACER MIXTURE</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">Vapor from a Lynden Vox e-cigarette filled with basic liquid consisting of 50% glycerin and 50% propylene glycol, inhaled by subjects to visualize expelled air.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_13</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGER EXHALED AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d0">SINGER EXHALED AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The airflow path generated when singers exhaled after inhaling a controlled 0.5 L volume of e-cigarette vapor and then performed speech or singing tasks. The study traced how this exhaled air moved outward from the singer's position on the platform.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED VAPOR CLOUD">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED VAPOR CLOUD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The visible dispersion pattern formed by vapor exhaled by the singers after each task. Singers remained stationary for up to 60 seconds so the persistence and movement of the exhaled cloud could be traced against a dark background.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="E-CIGARETTE AEROSOL PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">E-CIGARETTE AEROSOL PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">E-cigarette aerosol particles were used as the experimental tracer medium for visualizing exhaled airflow. The cited particle diameter range was approximately 250–450 nm, placing the particles in the aerosol size range; although not a gas, they functioned as a tracer within the experiment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_14</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BR TELEVISION STUDIO">
      <data key="d0">BR TELEVISION STUDIO</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The enclosed indoor studio where the experimental singing and droplet/aerosol visualization tasks were conducted. It was aerated before each task, then closed and allowed to settle before measurements began.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DARK CHAMBER">
      <data key="d0">DARK CHAMBER</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A dark visualization chamber installed within the BR television studio. It was used to observe ballistic respiratory droplets larger than 5 μm during singing tasks with and without a mask.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PLATFORM AREA">
      <data key="d0">PLATFORM AREA</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The platform location where the singer performed the tasks. The fan, main gate, and lighting positions are described relative to this area.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAN BEHIND THE PLATFORM">
      <data key="d0">FAN BEHIND THE PLATFORM</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">A fan positioned behind the platform and used to aerate the studio before each task while the main gate was open.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MAIN GATE">
      <data key="d0">MAIN GATE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The large gate on the opposite side of the studio, approximately 20 m from the platform. It was opened during at least 2 minutes of fan-assisted aeration and closed before the task began.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESIDUAL AIR CIRCULATION AFTER ACTIVE VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">RESIDUAL AIR CIRCULATION AFTER ACTIVE VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The remaining air movement in the studio after fan-assisted aeration with the main gate open. The protocol included a 2-minute no-movement period to allow this airflow to settle before the singing task.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="E-CIGARETTE BASIC LIQUID AEROSOL">
      <data key="d0">E-CIGARETTE BASIC LIQUID AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">The visible aerosol surrogate produced after the singer inhaled e-cigarette basic liquid. Although it is an aerosol rather than a true tracer gas, it functioned as a tracer for visualizing exhaled respiratory flow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.64</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGER AND PEOPLE PRESENT">
      <data key="d0">SINGER AND PEOPLE PRESENT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The human occupants in the studio, including the singer performing the task and others present. Everyone was instructed to stop moving for 2 minutes before the task to reduce occupant-induced air disturbance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.58</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGER-EMITTED RESPIRATORY DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">SINGER-EMITTED RESPIRATORY DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory droplets or particles emitted by the singer and visualized in the experiment; the text does not identify a specific pathogen, but these droplets represent potential airborne pathogen carriers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DROPLET DISPERSION REGION IN FRONT OF SINGER'S MOUTH">
      <data key="d0">DROPLET DISPERSION REGION IN FRONT OF SINGER'S MOUTH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The observed spatial distribution of droplets within the region of interest directly in front of the singer's mouth, recorded at high speed during laser light-sheet visualization.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED AEROSOL CLOUD FROM SINGER">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED AEROSOL CLOUD FROM SINGER</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The path of exhaled vapor and aerosol emitted from the singer's mouth, recorded and segmented over time to evaluate its spatial evolution.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THREE-DIMENSIONAL AEROSOL DISPERSION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">THREE-DIMENSIONAL AEROSOL DISPERSION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The observed aerosol cloud spread defined by a coordinate system with x-direction forward from the mouth, y-direction transverse from left to right, and z-direction vertical from bottom to top.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PIV TRACER PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">PIV TRACER PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">Tracer particles commonly used in particle image velocimetry measurements, described as 1–5 μm in diameter; included as the valid-domain tracer medium used to characterize airflow or aerosol movement.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SEGMENTED AEROSOL CLOUD">
      <data key="d0">SEGMENTED AEROSOL CLOUD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">The visible aerosol cloud emitted by the singer and segmented frame-by-frame from grayscale video to quantify cloud area, contour, and maximum spatial dimensions over time. It is treated as an airborne contaminant proxy rather than a confirmed pathogen.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SIDE-VIEW DISPERSION PATH">
      <data key="d0">SIDE-VIEW DISPERSION PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The aerosol cloud movement observed from camera 1, used to compute maximum cloud dimensions in the x and z directions. | The aerosol cloud movement observed from camera 3, used to compute the maximum cloud dimension in the y direction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
      <data key="d6">TOP-VIEW DISPERSION PATH</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CAMERA 1 MEASUREMENT ROI">
      <data key="d0">CAMERA 1 MEASUREMENT ROI</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The side-view measurement region of interest with dimensions 260 cm × 270 cm × 180 cm, used to observe aerosol cloud dispersion in the x and z directions. Although not a hospital zone, it is modeled as a bounded spatial zone because no more specific valid entity type is available. | The top-view measurement region of interest with dimensions 190 cm × 270 cm × 180 cm, used to observe aerosol cloud dispersion in the y direction. Although not a hospital zone, it is modeled as a bounded spatial zone because no more specific valid entity type is available.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
      <data key="d6">CAMERA 3 MEASUREMENT ROI</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TELEVISION STUDIO INDOOR AIRSPACE">
      <data key="d0">TELEVISION STUDIO INDOOR AIRSPACE</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor experimental zone where laser-illuminated airborne particles were observed; mapped to HOSPITAL_ZONE as the relevant enclosed air zone, although the text describes a television studio rather than a hospital area.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.55</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE DUST PARTICLES IN STUDIO AIR">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE DUST PARTICLES IN STUDIO AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Background airborne particles present in the television studio air and illuminated by the laser light sheet; not described as infectious pathogens, but typed as AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN because it is the closest valid category for airborne contaminants.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY PARTICLES EMITTED BY SINGER">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY PARTICLES EMITTED BY SINGER</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Droplet or aerosol particles originating from the singer’s respiratory tract and detected/tracked during the experiment; not explicitly pathogenic, but represents the airborne respiratory particle source of interest.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTICLE DISPERSION DURING SINGING">
      <data key="d0">PARTICLE DISPERSION DURING SINGING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Observed spatial and temporal movement pattern of laser-illuminated respiratory particles during singing, reconstructed through particle detection and tracking.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INHALED AEROSOL TRACER CLOUD">
      <data key="d0">INHALED AEROSOL TRACER CLOUD</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">A visible inhaled aerosol cloud used as a tracer medium to visualize expelled airflow and particle dispersion during singing tasks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNMASKED SINGING AEROSOL DISPERSION">
