      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne aerosol cloud pattern observed during singing with a surgical mask, located around the singer’s head and extending mainly upward and in both transverse directions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK LEAKAGE AIR PATHS AT CHEEKS AND NOSE">
      <data key="d0">MASK LEAKAGE AIR PATHS AT CHEEKS AND NOSE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Air escape routes through surgical mask leakages at the cheeks and nose, causing aerosol to disperse upward and laterally around the singer’s head. | Observed escape routes through which aerosols passed out of the surgical mask during singing. These leak paths redirected aerosol movement toward the singer’s near-field and above the head rather than allowing the cloud to spread far forward.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
      <data key="d6">MASK LEAKAGE PATHS AT THE CHEEKS AND NOSE</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FORWARD-DOWNWARD EXHALED AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">FORWARD-DOWNWARD EXHALED AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Primary airflow route for aerosols emitted during unmasked singing, moving outward in front of the singer and downward.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGERS PERFORMING TASK">
      <data key="d0">SINGERS PERFORMING TASK</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Human occupants performing the singing task and generating the observed aerosol cloud dispersion patterns. | Individual singers participating in singing tasks, with observed variability in aerosol cloud expansion between singers and between mask/no-mask conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_20</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
      <data key="d6">SINGERS PERFORMING SINGING TASK</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGERS">
      <data key="d0">SINGERS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Human participants performing the singing task. They are the aerosol-emitting occupants whose individual aerosol cloud expansion curves were analyzed with and without surgical masks.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGING-GENERATED AEROSOL CLOUD DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">SINGING-GENERATED AEROSOL CLOUD DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Temporal and spatial dispersion pattern of the aerosol cloud produced during singing, assessed at the end of the task and 10 seconds afterward. The cloud expansion is described in frontal, transverse, and vertical directions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FRONTAL X-DIRECTION AEROSOL EXPANSION">
      <data key="d0">FRONTAL X-DIRECTION AEROSOL EXPANSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The forward air path of aerosol cloud movement from the singer, denoted as the x-direction or d_x in the excerpt. | The upward vertical air path of aerosol cloud movement, denoted as the z-direction.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.63</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
      <data key="d6">VERTICAL Z-DIRECTION AEROSOL EXPANSION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRANSVERSE Y-DIRECTION AEROSOL EXPANSION">
      <data key="d0">TRANSVERSE Y-DIRECTION AEROSOL EXPANSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The sideward air path of aerosol cloud movement transverse to the singer, denoted as the y-direction. | Side-to-side transverse direction in which aerosol cloud diameter dy was measured; the text notes this dimension was larger with a mask at the end of the task.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
      <data key="d6">TRANSVERSE Y-DIRECTION AEROSOL PATH</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK EDGE AEROSOL LEAKAGE AT CHEEKS AND NOSE">
      <data key="d0">MASK EDGE AEROSOL LEAKAGE AT CHEEKS AND NOSE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Localized aerosol escape pattern observed during singing with a surgical mask, where exhaled aerosol leaks around the mask edges at the cheeks and nose.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_21</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY AEROSOL CLOUD FROM SINGING">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY AEROSOL CLOUD FROM SINGING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne respiratory aerosol cloud generated during singing; treated as a potential pathogen-bearing aerosol rather than a named pathogen. Its spatial margin was tracked over time.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.92</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TEMPORAL AEROSOL CLOUD EXPANSION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">TEMPORAL AEROSOL CLOUD EXPANSION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Observed time-dependent distribution pattern of the aerosol cloud, including median expansion at the end of singing and 10 seconds after task completion, with reduced frontal expansion when surgical masks were worn.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FRONT X-DIRECTION AEROSOL PATH">
      <data key="d0">FRONT X-DIRECTION AEROSOL PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Forward direction from the singer’s mouth, where aerosol cloud margin distance dx was measured; the mouth is located at x = 0 m.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VERTICAL Z-DIRECTION AEROSOL PATH">
      <data key="d0">VERTICAL Z-DIRECTION AEROSOL PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Vertically upright direction in which aerosol cloud expansion was tracked as part of the three-dimensional aerosol margin measurements.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.69</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGING AEROSOL/VAPOR CLOUD">
      <data key="d0">SINGING AEROSOL/VAPOR CLOUD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Visible exhaled aerosol/vapor cloud emitted during singing; its borders and movement are used as a proxy for potential airborne exposure spread.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK-WORN AEROSOL DISPERSION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">MASK-WORN AEROSOL DISPERSION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Observed cloud behavior when a mask is worn: larger transverse spread, decreased vertical diameter, upward movement to about 1 m above the singer's mouth, and only slight change in vertical diameter after singing stops. | Observed cloud behavior without a mask: smaller transverse growth than with a mask, vertical rise to about 0.77 m above the singer's mouth, and only slight post-task increase in cloud diameters.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
      <data key="d6">UNMASKED AEROSOL DISPERSION PATTERN</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRANSVERSE SIDEWARD AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">TRANSVERSE SIDEWARD AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Side-to-side direction of aerosol cloud expansion, represented by diameter dy between upper and lower cloud margins.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VERTICAL UPWARD AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">VERTICAL UPWARD AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Upright z-direction cloud movement; the cloud moved upward after singing, reaching higher levels with a mask than without one.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FRONTAL AIR PATH FROM SINGER MOUTH">
      <data key="d0">FRONTAL AIR PATH FROM SINGER MOUTH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Forward x-direction cloud progression from the singer's mouth, where the mouth is located at x = 0 m.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VISIBLE VAPOR/AEROSOL PARTICLE TRACER">
      <data key="d0">VISIBLE VAPOR/AEROSOL PARTICLE TRACER</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">Visible vapor and aerosol-particle density used to identify the cloud border; dilution and evaporation reduce visibility and introduce uncertainty in border location.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_23</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACTIVE SINGING SOURCE LOAD">
      <data key="d0">ACTIVE SINGING SOURCE LOAD</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The singer during active singing, acting as the emission source for aerosol and droplet particles in the experiment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPELLED AEROSOL AND DROPLET PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">EXPELLED AEROSOL AND DROPLET PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne or ballistic particles expelled during singing; treated as a proxy for potentially infectious airborne material, although pathogens themselves were not directly measured.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FRONTWARD PARTICLE EMISSION PATH">
      <data key="d0">FRONTWARD PARTICLE EMISSION PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The path of particles emitted through the mouth and moving away from the singer in the positive x-direction, in the region in front of the singer’s head.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLOUD VERSUS NO-CLOUD DISTRIBUTION BOUNDARY">
      <data key="d0">CLOUD VERSUS NO-CLOUD DISTRIBUTION BOUNDARY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The observed spatial pattern separating particle cloud regions from no-cloud regions; the boundary location had small uncertainty during active singing because of high contrast.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK-REDUCED PARTICLE DISTRIBUTION PATTERN">
      <data key="d0">MASK-REDUCED PARTICLE DISTRIBUTION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The experimentally observed reduction in counted expelled particles during singing with a mask compared with singing without a mask, including a 47% average reduction in total tracked droplets and an 86% average reduction for exclusively front-moving particles.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGERS DURING VOCALIZATION">
      <data key="d0">SINGERS DURING VOCALIZATION</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Occupant group engaged in singing/vocalization, an expiratory activity discussed as producing substantially more aerosol particles and ballistic droplets than breathing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SINGING WITHOUT MASK">
      <data key="d0">SINGING WITHOUT MASK</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Experimental singer occupancy/activity condition in which participants sang without a mask. This condition showed greater fluctuation in particles moving forward and was statistically different from singing with a mask. | Experimental singer occupancy/activity condition in which participants sang while wearing a mask. Compared with singing without a mask, this condition was associated with significantly different total particle counts and forward-moving particle counts.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
      <data key="d6">SINGING WITH MASK</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TOTAL DROPLET PARTICLE DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">TOTAL DROPLET PARTICLE DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Measured overall distribution/count of droplet particles emitted during singing. The text reports statistically significant differences between singing with and without a mask for total particle number using the Wilcoxon rank test: z = -2.497, p = 0.013, n = 10.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FORWARD POSITIVE X-DIRECTION PARTICLE DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">FORWARD POSITIVE X-DIRECTION PARTICLE DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Directional air distribution pattern describing droplet particles moving to the front of the singer in the positive x-direction. The text notes larger fluctuation for this forward-moving particle count when singing without a mask, with statistically significant mask-related differences: z = -2.803, p = 0.005, n = 10.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_25</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUSTAINED PHONATION OR SINGING">
      <data key="d0">SUSTAINED PHONATION OR SINGING</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A respiratory vocalization activity involving prolonged voice use, including sustained phonation and singing. The text reports that this activity can generate substantially more aerosol particles than breathing, with aerosol production enhanced by approximately 3-fold to 300-fold.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CHOIR AND AUDIENCE">
      <data key="d0">CHOIR AND AUDIENCE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The choir and audience are the exposed occupant groups for whom spacing is critical because aerosol distribution around singing emitters can influence potential airborne exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOCAL AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION AROUND THE EMITTER">
      <data key="d0">LOCAL AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION AROUND THE EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The spatial distribution of aerosol particles near the singer or speaker. The text emphasizes that particle count or concentration alone is insufficient because local aerosol distribution is critical for defining distances between singers and between the choir and audience.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPELLED CONCENTRATED AEROSOL CLOUD">
      <data key="d0">EXPELLED CONCENTRATED AEROSOL CLOUD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A near-field aerosol plume expelled during singing or speaking. It is described as highly concentrated and capable of reaching distances up to 1.3 m when generated by professional singers.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK-MODIFIED AEROSOL CLOUD">
      <data key="d0">MASK-MODIFIED AEROSOL CLOUD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The altered airflow and aerosol distribution produced when face masks decelerate and deflect the primarily expelled aerosol cloud, in addition to any filtering effect.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_27</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXPELLED AEROSOL PARTICLES AND DROPLETS">
      <data key="d0">EXPELLED AEROSOL PARTICLES AND DROPLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne particle carriers associated with droplet infection risk; the text discusses aerosols and droplets emitted during breathing, speaking, and coughing, including smaller aerosol particles in the 0.3–10.0 diameter range.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SIDE LEAKAGE AIRFLOW AROUND MASK CHEEKS">
      <data key="d0">SIDE LEAKAGE AIRFLOW AROUND MASK CHEEKS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Unfiltered airflow pathway at the sides of a face mask near the cheeks, through which a large portion of expelled particles may escape instead of passing through the mask material.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_29</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ENVIRONMENTAL AIR FLOW">
      <data key="d0">ENVIRONMENTAL AIR FLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">The surrounding air movement in the environment that small aerosol particles can hover in and follow after escaping through mask leakages.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MASK SIDE LEAKAGE AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">MASK SIDE LEAKAGE AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">An air escape route at the sides of the face mask near the cheeks, allowing smaller aerosol particles to bypass mask filtration.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_30</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE TRANSMISSION OF SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE TRANSMISSION OF SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne transmission of SARS-CoV-2 is the implied exposure pathway studied in relation to respiratory droplets, exhaled aerosols, face-mask obstruction, and respirator leakage. No specific hospital room, HVAC unit, pressure regime, or ACH rate is provided.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_31,ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED AEROSOL DISTRIBUTIONS AROUND THE WEARER">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED AEROSOL DISTRIBUTIONS AROUND THE WEARER</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Exhaled aerosol distributions around the wearer describe the spatial spread of aerosols emitted while wearing a face mask, including possible aerosol escape through gaps.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_31,ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_55,ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_56</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FACEMASK LEAKAGE">
      <data key="d0">FACEMASK LEAKAGE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Facemask leakage refers to airflow and aerosol escape through gaps around a face covering, altering the intended filtration and containment pattern.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.69</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="KN95 AND N95 RESPIRATOR LEAKAGE">
      <data key="d0">KN95 AND N95 RESPIRATOR LEAKAGE</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">KN95 and N95 respirator leakage describes airflow or aerosol escape through respirator faceseal gaps or other leakage routes, as reported in studies using CFD, infrared imaging, schlieren visualization, and infection-dynamics modeling.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SNEEZING AEROSOL PLUME">
      <data key="d0">SNEEZING AEROSOL PLUME</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A sneezing aerosol plume is the transient distribution pattern of droplets and aerosols expelled during sneezing, mentioned through experimental visualization studies assessing mask and face-shield efficacy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.58</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_31</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLOSED ROOM WITHOUT EFFECTIVE VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">CLOSED ROOM WITHOUT EFFECTIVE VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">An enclosed indoor space where ineffective ventilation allows exhaled aerosol particles to remain suspended and accumulate, potentially reaching a critical concentration if an infected person is present.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOW OR INEFFECTIVE AIR EXCHANGE">
      <data key="d0">LOW OR INEFFECTIVE AIR EXCHANGE</data>
      <data key="d1">ACH_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">A qualitative low ventilation or air-change condition; no numerical ACH is provided, but the text indicates that insufficient ventilation promotes aerosol accumulation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EXHALED AEROSOL PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">EXHALED AEROSOL PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Potentially infectious aerosol particles emitted by an infected person during activities such as singing; these particles can accumulate indoors and disperse according to ventilation, mask use, and thermal airflow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTED EMITTING OCCUPANT">
      <data key="d0">INFECTED EMITTING OCCUPANT</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">A single infected person or singer emitting aerosols into the indoor environment; even one such occupant can raise aerosol concentration in a poorly ventilated closed room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEAR-FIELD UPWARD AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION AROUND SINGER HEAD">
      <data key="d0">NEAR-FIELD UPWARD AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION AROUND SINGER HEAD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Aerosol distribution observed when a surgical mask is worn: reduced primary momentum and deflected expulsion keep particles mainly in the near-field above and around the singer’s head, with a median spread of about 0.5 m in all directions and a tendency to move upward.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FORWARD FAR-FIELD AEROSOL CLOUD DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d0">FORWARD FAR-FIELD AEROSOL CLOUD DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Aerosol distribution observed during singing without a mask: particles form a cloud spreading in front of the singer over substantially greater distances.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UPWARD THERMAL CONVECTION AIR PATH">
      <data key="d0">UPWARD THERMAL CONVECTION AIR PATH</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">An upward airflow caused by the emitting person’s higher body temperature relative to the surrounding environment, moving nearby aerosol particles toward higher regions around and above the head.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_32</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LARGE MEETING ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">LARGE MEETING ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Large indoor assembly spaces described as critical settings for infectious scenarios. They are commonly equipped with air conditioning and ventilation systems, and their ceiling-based air extraction can interact with upward aerosol transport.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONCERT HALLS">
      <data key="d0">CONCERT HALLS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Large occupied performance spaces identified as critical in infectious scenarios. Their ventilation configuration, especially ceiling-located outlets, can influence the upward movement and removal of expelled aerosols.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR CONDITIONING AND VENTILATION SYSTEMS">
      <data key="d0">AIR CONDITIONING AND VENTILATION SYSTEMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">Mechanical air-handling systems commonly installed in large meeting rooms and concert halls. In the passage, these systems remove used air and shape aerosol transport through ceiling-located ventilation outlets.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CEILING VENTILATION OUTLETS">
      <data key="d0">CEILING VENTILATION OUTLETS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation outlets commonly placed at the ceiling to remove used indoor air. Their ceiling location supports an upward extraction pathway for air containing elevated CO2 and expelled aerosols.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THERMAL UPWARD DRIFT OF EXPELLED AEROSOL">
      <data key="d0">THERMAL UPWARD DRIFT OF EXPELLED AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Thermally driven upward movement of aerosol caused by the generally higher temperature of the emitting person compared with the surrounding environment. This upward drift becomes important in large ventilated rooms where infectious aerosol transport is a concern.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VERTICAL UPWARD FLOW OF EXPELLED AEROSOL">
      <data key="d0">VERTICAL UPWARD FLOW OF EXPELLED AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A vertical upward air and aerosol movement pattern generated or reinforced by ceiling-based ventilation outlets that remove used air. This pattern affects the transport and possible removal of expelled aerosols in large indoor spaces.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CO2 IN USED AIR">
      <data key="d0">CO2 IN USED AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">Carbon dioxide is mentioned as being present at high concentration in used indoor air. In this passage it functions as an indicator of used or exhaled air being removed by the ventilation system, rather than as an explicitly described experimental tracer.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.64</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_33</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="E-CIGARETTE VAPOR AEROSOL CLOUD">
      <data key="d0">E-CIGARETTE VAPOR AEROSOL CLOUD</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">A visible tracer aerosol generated from the basic liquid of e-cigarettes and used to visualize aerosol-cloud dispersion. Although it is an aerosol rather than a true gas, it functions as the tracer medium in the described measurements; its visible contour depends on particle illumination and camera sensor sensitivity.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="10 SINGERS">
      <data key="d0">10 SINGERS</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">The human subject group used in the measurements. The singers acted as aerosol-cloud emitters, but their individual expulsion-flow characteristics limited reproducibility of the observed aerosol dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNCONFINED FLOWS">
      <data key="d0">UNCONFINED FLOWS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">Unpredictable free-flow air movement affecting how the aerosol cloud spreads, dilutes, evaporates, and disappears from the visualized region. This pattern contributes to the restricted reproducibility of the measurements.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STUDY ROOM">
      <data key="d0">STUDY ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The indoor measurement space in which the aerosol-cloud visualization was performed. Particle-counting techniques are described as providing data only at specific points in this room, limiting their ability to capture full spatial and temporal aerosol-cloud dynamics.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.52</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_34</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="E-CIGARETTE VAPOR TRACER AEROSOL">
      <data key="d0">E-CIGARETTE VAPOR TRACER AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d1">TRACER_GAS</data>
      <data key="d2">Inhaled e-cigarette vapor used as a visible tracer medium to analyze aerosol escape and flow behavior during singing with a surgical mask.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNCONFINED SINGING EXPULSION FLOW">
      <data key="d0">UNCONFINED SINGING EXPULSION FLOW</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The variable and partly unforeseeable airflow and particle-expulsion pattern generated by individual singers during unconfined singing.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="UNFILTERED ENVIRONMENTAL STUDIO AIR">
      <data key="d0">UNFILTERED ENVIRONMENTAL STUDIO AIR</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Ambient air in the television studio setting that lacked a filtering system and contained dust particles, complicating interpretation of droplet measurements.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_35</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EFFECTIVE VENTILATION CONCEPT OR AUTOMATED VENTILATION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">EFFECTIVE VENTILATION CONCEPT OR AUTOMATED VENTILATION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">HVAC_UNIT</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation intervention identified as necessary to prevent emitted aerosols from persisting in indoor air. The text emphasizes that masks alone are insufficient unless ventilation removes or dilutes aerosols that remain in the environment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CLOSED ROOMS">
      <data key="d0">CLOSED ROOMS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Enclosed indoor rooms where aerosols can accumulate over time if ventilation is ineffective. Although the passage concerns singing rather than a hospital, this is the bounded indoor zone relevant to airborne exposure and ventilation control.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOLS STAYED IN THE SINGER'S NEAR-FIELD AROUND AND ABOVE THE HEAD">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOLS STAYED IN THE SINGER'S NEAR-FIELD AROUND AND ABOVE THE HEAD</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The observed aerosol distribution during masked singing. Aerosols escaped through mask leakages but remained close to the emitter and were displaced upward, which reduced direct forward spread toward other persons.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOL CLOUD SPREAD FAR IN FRONT OF THE SINGER WITH DISTANCES OF OVER 1 M">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOL CLOUD SPREAD FAR IN FRONT OF THE SINGER WITH DISTANCES OF OVER 1 M</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The observed aerosol distribution during singing without a mask. The aerosol cloud moved forward more than 1 meter from the singer, increasing the potential exposure zone for people in front of the emitter.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AEROSOLS REMAINED IN THE ENVIRONMENT OVER TIME">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOLS REMAINED IN THE ENVIRONMENT OVER TIME</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">A persistence pattern in which emitted aerosols remain suspended in the indoor environment after emission. The text states this becomes especially critical in closed rooms after a certain time period when effective ventilation is absent.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="REDUCED BALLISTIC DROPLET EMISSION DURING MASKED SINGING">
      <data key="d0">REDUCED BALLISTIC DROPLET EMISSION DURING MASKED SINGING</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d2">The second experiment found that the number of ballistic droplets detected in front of the singer largely decreased when the singer wore a surgical mask. The droplets were assumed to be retained by the mask and therefore prevented from spreading long distances forward.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.79</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="POTENTIALLY VIRUS-LADEN PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">POTENTIALLY VIRUS-LADEN PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Aerosol or droplet particles that may carry infectious virus and create airborne or droplet transmission risk for nearby singers or audience members.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OTHER SINGERS OR THE AUDIENCE">
      <data key="d0">OTHER SINGERS OR THE AUDIENCE</data>
      <data key="d1">OCCUPANCY_LOAD</data>
      <data key="d2">Susceptible occupants who may be exposed to emitted particles during singing. Their presence increases the consequence of long-distance aerosol or droplet spread in the indoor setting.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_36</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY AEROSOL AND DROPLET TRANSMISSION PATHWAY">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY AEROSOL AND DROPLET TRANSMISSION PATHWAY</data>
      <data key="d1">AIR_PATH</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne or droplet-mediated pathway discussed in the cited references as relevant to respiratory infectious disease transmission and SARS-CoV-2 spread.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48_chunk_37</data>
      <data key="d5">ffb605c7-88bd-433a-9478-a7261e327d48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SPEECH-RELATED OCCUPANT AEROSOL EMISSION">
