      <data key="d8">CO2</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">Higher occupancy increases indoor CO2 because occupants exhale carbon dioxide. This supports the use of CO2 monitoring as an indicator of occupancy-driven exhaled-air accumulation under a given ventilation condition. | Higher occupancy increases indoor CO2 because occupants exhale CO2 during respiration. The cited context links occupancy and CO2 monitoring as factors in assessing ventilation and aerosol infection risk.</data>
