      <data key="d7">LIFT</data>
      <data key="d8">NO FAN CASE DROPLET DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">The lift has a no-fan droplet dispersion pattern when mechanical ventilation is absent. This case shows the smallest dispersion and is described as the safest direct-contagion scenario among the three cases studied.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.94</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d14">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="LIFT" target="UPWARDS-BLOWING FAN RECIRCULATION PATTERN">
      <data key="d7">LIFT</data>
      <data key="d8">UPWARDS-BLOWING FAN RECIRCULATION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">The lift has an upward-fan recirculation pattern when the upwards-blowing fan operates, causing droplets to remain mainly near the emitter region while increasing dispersion compared with no fan.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.91</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d14">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="LIFT" target="DOWNWARDS BLOWING FAN FLOOR-IMPACT AND RECIRCULATION PATTERN">
      <data key="d7">LIFT</data>
      <data key="d8">DOWNWARDS BLOWING FAN FLOOR-IMPACT AND RECIRCULATION PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">The lift has a downward-fan floor-impact and recirculation pattern when the downward fan operates. Most droplets are removed from the airborne domain by floor impact, but some can recirculate toward the healthy passenger respiration volume.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.91</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d14">c3ec75c5-6024-45ba-a0b0-8dd0c746991b</data>
    </edge>
