      <data key="d8">CO2</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">Spectators increase indoor CO2 through respiration during theatre events. The study used CO2 monitoring to assess ventilation effectiveness under real occupancy conditions. | Spectator occupancy contributes exhaled CO2, which can be used as a proxy for respiratory aerosols and ventilation effectiveness. | Spectators are modeled as breathing occupants with virtual mouths, so their respiration is associated with CO2 generation, although the passage emphasizes spectator exposure measurement more than spectator emissions.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.88</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
