      <data key="d8">SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">Spectator occupancy can increase potential SARS-CoV-2 airborne-transmission risk when one or more spectators are infectious, which motivates ventilation monitoring and mitigation in theatre events.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.72</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="SPECTATORS" target="INFECTIOUS AEROSOL">
      <data key="d7">SPECTATORS</data>
      <data key="d8">INFECTIOUS AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">Spectators are the exposed occupancy population considered in the infection-risk assessment; the reported high-emitter conditions increased the proportion of spectators exceeding risk thresholds. This relationship captures the occupancy-linked risk increase rather than implying spectators generated the aerosol.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.58</data>
      <data key="d12">3</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
