      <data key="d7">MASS GATHERING OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d8">CO2</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">Large indoor occupancies increase exhaled metabolic CO2, which is why CO2 is used as a tracer for ventilation and indoor air quality assessment at mass gathering events.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.75</data>
      <data key="d12">3</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="MASS GATHERING OCCUPANCY" target="SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d7">MASS GATHERING OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d8">SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">Mass gathering occupancy increases the potential for shared exhaled aerosol exposure and therefore can increase SARS-CoV-2 airborne transmission risk if ventilation is insufficient. | Higher event occupancy increases the number of potential contacts and infectious sources, increasing SARS-CoV-2 transmission opportunities. The text notes that smaller event sizes can further reduce simulated infection numbers.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.8</data>
      <data key="d12">3</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206,0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </edge>
