      <data key="d7">VENUE-SPECIFIC AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION PATTERNS</data>
      <data key="d8">CO2</data>
      <data key="d9">PATTERN_MEASURED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">High-resolution CO2 monitoring is cited as an experimental approach for assessing ventilation effectiveness and indoor air quality, providing tracer-based evidence relevant to exhaled-air and aerosol dispersion conditions in occupied venues.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.62</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="INDOOR ROOM" target="INSTANTANEOUSLY AND UNIFORMLY DISTRIBUTED AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d7">INDOOR ROOM</data>
      <data key="d8">INSTANTANEOUSLY AND UNIFORMLY DISTRIBUTED AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">Analytical approaches such as Wells-Riley and dose-response models assume that aerosols in the room are instantaneously and uniformly distributed, leading to equal estimated infection risk across occupants.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_8</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
