      <data key="d7">EMITTER POSITIONS H5 E6 B9</data>
      <data key="d8">DISPLACEMENT VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">For displacement ventilation, source position influenced the risk distribution: the number of spectators above the acceptable risk threshold was unchanged for H5 but increased by 2.4 to 2.9 times for E6 and B9.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.82</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_15</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="HIGH EMITTER" target="AIRBORNE PATHOGEN AEROSOL">
      <data key="d7">HIGH EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d8">AIRBORNE PATHOGEN AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">The high-emitter occupant condition increases the emitted infectious aerosol burden, causing CFD-derived infection risk to rise by approximately 13 to 14 times compared with the passive-emitter condition.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.92</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_16</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="HIGH EMITTER" target="INFECTIOUS AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d7">HIGH EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d8">INFECTIOUS AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">The high-emitter condition increased infectious aerosol emissions enough to spread aerosol broadly across the balcony and substantially raise airborne infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.91</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_22</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="HIGH EMITTER" target="AIRBORNE INFECTIOUS AEROSOL">
      <data key="d7">HIGH EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d8">AIRBORNE INFECTIOUS AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">The high emitter contributes a larger infectious aerosol source strength than the silent passive emitter, increasing modeled exposure and infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.89</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="HIGH EMITTER" target="50% REDUCED AIR FLOW RATE">
      <data key="d7">HIGH EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d8">50% REDUCED AIRFLOW RATE</data>
      <data key="d9">ACH_AFFECTS</data>
      <data key="d10">The text highlights that the high-emission profile combined with reduced airflow produces substantially higher risk; under this combined condition, the actor case can exceed the audience B9 case.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.77</data>
      <data key="d12">3</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_24</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="HIGH EMITTER" target="SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d7">HIGH EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d8">SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">A high-emitting infected occupant increases the airborne SARS-CoV-2 source strength through elevated quanta or viral shedding, producing larger risk differences than uncertainty in the assumed shed-quanta dose distribution.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.88</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_44</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="HIGH EMITTER" target="INFECTIOUS QUANTA">
      <data key="d7">HIGH EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d8">INFECTIOUS QUANTA</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">The high-emitter scenario introduced a substantially larger infectious quanta source term of 265 quanta per hour, increasing modeled airborne infectious burden relative to the passive-emitter case.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.88</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_52</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENTILATED VENUES" target="DVV">
      <data key="d7">VENTILATED VENUES</data>
      <data key="d8">DVV</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">The venues were evaluated under the DVV air distribution pattern, with experimental, numerical, and analytical infection-risk estimates compared for different emitter positions and emission modes.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.86</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENTILATED VENUES" target="MVV">
      <data key="d7">VENTILATED VENUES</data>
      <data key="d8">MVV</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">The venues were evaluated under the MVV air distribution pattern, where the three infection-risk estimation approaches showed reasonable agreement.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.84</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENTILATED VENUES" target="NVV">
      <data key="d7">VENTILATED VENUES</data>
      <data key="d8">NVV</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">The venues were evaluated under the NVV air distribution pattern, which produced markedly higher infection-risk estimates at position A14 and weaker agreement among analytical, experimental, and CFD methods.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.88</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_17</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="FULL OCCUPANCY" target="WILD-TYPE SARS-COV-2 VIRUS VARIANT">
      <data key="d7">FULL OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d8">WILD-TYPE SARS-COV-2 VIRUS VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">Full occupancy defines the reference high-exposure condition for estimating COVID-19 secondary cases. The passage does not explicitly compare it with reduced occupancy, so the relationship reflects increased exposure opportunity inherent to the modeled full-occupancy baseline.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.58</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_18</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="FULL OCCUPANCY" target="SARS-COV-2 WILD-TYPE INFECTIOUS QUANTA">
      <data key="d7">FULL OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d8">SARS-COV-2 WILD-TYPE INFECTIOUS QUANTA</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">Full occupancy increases aggregate inhalation exposure because more occupants can inhale infectious quanta, and the global risk metric sums individual infection risks.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.78</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_19</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="FULL OCCUPANCY" target="SARS-COV-2 WILD-TYPE">
      <data key="d7">FULL OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d8">SARS-COV-2 WILD-TYPE</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">Full occupancy is part of the pre-pandemic baseline condition and increases the number of susceptible occupants potentially exposed to SARS-CoV-2 wild-type aerosols in the venue.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.67</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="FULL OCCUPANCY" target="OMICRON VARIANT">
      <data key="d7">FULL OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d8">OMICRON VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">Full occupancy increases the number of occupants potentially exposed to Omicron-containing aerosols in the venue scenarios.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.69</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_40</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="FULL OCCUPANCY" target="MAXIMUM NUMBER OF OCCUPANTS (N) PER VENUE">
      <data key="d7">FULL OCCUPANCY</data>
      <data key="d8">MAXIMUM NUMBER OF OCCUPANTS (N) PER VENUE</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">Full occupancy represents the higher occupant-load boundary condition and is associated with a larger number of occupants or absorbers than reduced checkerboard occupancy.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.76</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_53</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="SINGING OR SHOUTING EMITTER" target="WILD-TYPE SARS-COV-2 VIRUS VARIANT">
      <data key="d7">SINGING OR SHOUTING EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d8">WILD-TYPE SARS-COV-2 VIRUS VARIANT</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">The high-activity emitter condition increases modeled airborne SARS-CoV-2 transmission risk. The text reports that singing or shouting increased R_CFD by a factor of 14.4 to 27.0 compared with a silent, passive emitter.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.96</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_18</data>
