      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="OCCUPANTS" target="SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d7">OCCUPANTS</data>
      <data key="d8">SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">The presence and variability of occupants contribute to airborne quanta emissions used to estimate SARS-CoV-2 transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.72</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_57</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="OCCUPANTS" target="AIRBORNE PATHOGEN">
      <data key="d7">OCCUPANTS</data>
      <data key="d8">AIRBORNE PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">Occupants are central to exhaled droplet and airborne pathogen transmission because they can emit and inhale respiratory particles. Greater occupant presence increases potential source-receptor interactions.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.68</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_65</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="OCCUPANTS" target="SARS-COV-2 OR COVID-19 AIRBORNE TRANSMISSION CONTEXT">
      <data key="d7">OCCUPANTS</data>
      <data key="d8">SARS-COV-2 / COVID-19 AIRBORNE TRANSMISSION</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">For COVID-19-related airborne transmission modeling, occupants represent potential emitters and receivers of infectious respiratory particles; increased occupancy can therefore increase SARS-CoV-2 exposure opportunities in enclosed spaces.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.66</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_65</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="EMITTER" target="DROPLET AEROSOLS GENERATED BY OCCUPANTS">
      <data key="d7">EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d8">DROPLET AEROSOLS GENERATED BY OCCUPANTS</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">The emitter is the source occupant producing droplet aerosols that drive local airborne exposure and infection-risk variation.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.88</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="EMITTER" target="ABSORBER-SPECIFIC AEROSOL CONCENTRATIONS">
      <data key="d7">EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d8">ABSORBER-SPECIFIC AEROSOL CONCENTRATIONS</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">Aerosol concentrations at absorber positions depend strongly on their position relative to the emitting occupant.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.79</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="SEVEN ABSORBERS" target="ABSORBER-SPECIFIC AEROSOL CONCENTRATIONS">
      <data key="d7">SEVEN ABSORBERS</data>
      <data key="d8">ABSORBER-SPECIFIC AEROSOL CONCENTRATIONS</data>
      <data key="d9">PATTERN_MEASURED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The experimental approach used seven absorber positions to characterize local aerosol concentrations, but their random placement may not represent the full exposure range.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.74</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="ENTIRE AUDIENCE" target="ABSORBER-SPECIFIC AEROSOL CONCENTRATIONS">
      <data key="d7">ENTIRE AUDIENCE</data>
      <data key="d8">ABSORBER-SPECIFIC AEROSOL CONCENTRATIONS</data>
      <data key="d9">PATTERN_MEASURED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The CFD approach considered aerosol exposure across the entire audience, giving broader spatial representation than the seven experimental absorber locations.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.68</data>
      <data key="d12">3</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_41</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="STUDIED INDOOR VENUES" target="VENUE AIRFLOW AND CONCENTRATION DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d7">STUDIED INDOOR VENUES</data>
      <data key="d8">VENUE AIRFLOW AND CONCENTRATION DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">The studied venues contain airflow and airborne concentration distributions that determine local exposure and are central to the CFD-based risk assessment.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.86</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENUE AIRFLOW AND CONCENTRATION DISTRIBUTION" target="ATMOS MEASUREMENT COVERAGE">
      <data key="d7">VENUE AIRFLOW AND CONCENTRATION DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d8">ATMOS MEASUREMENT COVERAGE</data>
      <data key="d9">PATTERN_MEASURED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The airflow or concentration distribution was experimentally sampled only at selected positions by ATMoS, creating potential positional bias and motivating more absorbers and repeated measurements.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.72</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="EVENT OCCUPANCY AND INFECTIOUS-CONTACT LOAD" target="COVID-19 AIRBORNE INFECTIOUS AGENT">
      <data key="d7">EVENT OCCUPANCY AND INFECTIOUS-CONTACT LOAD</data>
      <data key="d8">COVID-19 AIRBORNE INFECTIOUS AGENT</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">Higher event-related contact load, especially from an infectious person with additional contacts during the infectious period, increases the estimated risk of COVID-19 airborne transmission and epidemic growth.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.84</data>
      <data key="d12">3</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_42</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="EVENT LOCATION" target="THERMAL-BOUNDARY-CONDITION-SENSITIVE AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d7">EVENT LOCATION</data>
      <data key="d8">THERMAL-BOUNDARY-CONDITION-SENSITIVE AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">The modeled event location may have airflow and concentration behavior sensitive to environmental and thermal boundary conditions.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.67</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="HIGH-RISK REGIONS" target="STEADY-STATE CONCENTRATION">
      <data key="d7">HIGH-RISK REGIONS</data>
      <data key="d8">STEADY-STATE CONCENTRATION</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">Most numerical experiments showed that high-risk regions reached values close to steady-state concentration within a few minutes.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.87</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="BACKGROUND REGIONS" target="UNSTEADY CONCENTRATION DEVELOPMENT">
      <data key="d7">BACKGROUND REGIONS</data>
      <data key="d8">UNSTEADY CONCENTRATION DEVELOPMENT</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">Background regions are identified as locations where an unsteady-event correction factor could improve approximations, especially in low-air-change cases.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.73</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="LOW AIR CHANGE RATE" target="UNSTEADY CONCENTRATION DEVELOPMENT">
      <data key="d7">LOW AIR CHANGE RATE</data>
      <data key="d8">UNSTEADY CONCENTRATION DEVELOPMENT</data>
      <data key="d9">ACH_AFFECTS</data>
      <data key="d10">The low air change rate in NVV caused slower concentration increases, making time-dependent or correction-factor treatment more relevant.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="REDUCED VENTILATION" target="UNSTEADY CONCENTRATION DEVELOPMENT">
      <data key="d7">REDUCED VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d8">UNSTEADY CONCENTRATION DEVELOPMENT</data>
      <data key="d9">ACH_AFFECTS</data>
      <data key="d10">Reduced ventilation is an event-specific condition that could alter concentration buildup and the validity of steady-state approximations, although it was disregarded in the modeled cases.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.68</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="PERFECTLY AIRBORNE AEROSOL" target="STEADY-STATE CONCENTRATION">
      <data key="d7">PERFECTLY AIRBORNE AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d8">STEADY-STATE CONCENTRATION</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">The steady-state concentration approximation describes the modeled distribution of the perfectly airborne aerosol under the assumed flow field.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.76</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="PERFECTLY AIRBORNE AEROSOL" target="UNSTEADY CONCENTRATION DEVELOPMENT">
      <data key="d7">PERFECTLY AIRBORNE AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d8">UNSTEADY CONCENTRATION DEVELOPMENT</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">Fully unsteady simulation would describe the time-dependent distribution of the perfectly airborne aerosol, though it was considered computationally expensive for large venues.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.7</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="PERFECTLY AIRBORNE AEROSOL" target="DEPOSITION-AND-EVAPORATION-FREE AEROSOL BEHAVIOR">
      <data key="d7">PERFECTLY AIRBORNE AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d8">DEPOSITION-AND-EVAPORATION-FREE AEROSOL BEHAVIOR</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">The CFD model assumes the aerosol remains perfectly airborne and omits evaporation and deposition effects.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.89</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="DENSE OCCUPANCY HEAT LOAD" target="THERMAL-BOUNDARY-CONDITION-SENSITIVE AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d7">DENSE OCCUPANCY HEAT LOAD</data>
      <data key="d8">THERMAL-BOUNDARY-CONDITION-SENSITIVE AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">Dense occupancy increases the relevance of heat-load reservoirs and thermal boundary conditions, which can influence airflow and concentration predictions.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.75</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="HALF-OPENED DOORS" target="EVENT LOCATION">
      <data key="d7">HALF-OPENED DOORS</data>
      <data key="d8">EVENT LOCATION</data>
      <data key="d9">CONNECTS_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">Half-opened doors are event-specific openings that can modify air paths connected to the event location, although they were not included in the model.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.58</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_43</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="RESTING AND BREATHING-ONLY OCCUPANT" target="SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d7">RESTING AND BREATHING-ONLY OCCUPANT</data>
      <data key="d8">SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">A resting, breathing-only occupant can act as a source term for SARS-CoV-2 quanta in airborne infection risk calculations. The cited scenario has a low but nonzero emission estimate of 0.01 quanta h−1, influencing predicted pathogen-related airborne transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.64</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_45</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="LI ET AL. UNIVERSITY-CAMPUS SARS-COV-2 EMITTER SCENARIO" target="SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d7">LI ET AL. UNIVERSITY-CAMPUS SARS-COV-2 EMITTER SCENARIO</data>
      <data key="d8">SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">The university-campus infected-emitter scenario represents an occupant source of airborne SARS-CoV-2 quanta, with estimated median emissions between 20 and 454 quanta h⁻¹.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.78</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_46</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="MIKSZEWSKI ET AL. ACTIVITY-DEPENDENT SARS-COV-2 EMITTER SPECTRUM" target="SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d7">MIKSZEWSKI ET AL. ACTIVITY-DEPENDENT SARS-COV-2 EMITTER SPECTRUM</data>
      <data key="d8">SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">The activity-dependent infected-emitter spectrum shows that occupant expiratory activity, activity level, and percentile assumptions can substantially increase or decrease airborne SARS-CoV-2 quanta emissions, spanning 0.0058 to 4300 quanta h⁻¹.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.92</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_46</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="SARS-COV-2 STANDING-AND-SPEAKING EMITTER" target="SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d7">SARS-COV-2 STANDING-AND-SPEAKING EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d8">SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">A standing-and-speaking infected occupant contributes airborne SARS-CoV-2 quanta, with reported emissions of 2.7 quanta h⁻¹ at the median and 250 quanta h⁻¹ at the 95th percentile.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.86</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_46</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="SARS-COV-2 RESTING-AND-ORAL-BREATHING EMITTER" target="SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d7">SARS-COV-2 RESTING-AND-ORAL-BREATHING EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d8">SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">A resting-and-oral-breathing infected occupant contributes airborne SARS-CoV-2 quanta at lower activity-associated levels than standing and speaking, with reported emissions of 0.55 quanta h⁻¹ at the median and 52 quanta h⁻¹ at the 95th percentile.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.65</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_46</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="OUTBREAK-ASSOCIATED HIGH-EMISSION SARS-COV-2 SOURCE CONDITIONS" target="SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d7">OUTBREAK-ASSOCIATED HIGH-EMISSION SARS-COV-2 SOURCE CONDITIONS</data>
      <data key="d8">SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">The referenced outbreak-associated source conditions correspond to elevated airborne SARS-CoV-2 quanta emissions, typically 15 to 970 quanta h⁻¹, indicating above-average emitting occupant scenarios relative to the standing-and-speaking distribution.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.88</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_46</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENUES WITH MV" target="MIXING VENTILATION">
      <data key="d7">VENUES WITH MV</data>
      <data key="d8">MV</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">Venues with MV are characterized by a mixing-ventilation distribution pattern. The text indicates that this setting can be assessed analytically but is highly sensitive to boundary conditions.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENUES WITH MV" target="DISPLACEMENT VENTILATION">
      <data key="d7">VENUES WITH DV</data>
      <data key="d8">DV</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">Venues with DV are characterized by a displacement-ventilation distribution pattern. This strategy produced the lowest overall infection risk and lowest number of secondary cases.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.95</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENUES WITH MV" target="NATURAL VENTILATION">
      <data key="d7">VENUES WITH NV</data>
      <data key="d8">NV</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">Venues with NV are characterized by a natural-ventilation distribution pattern. Exposure prediction is difficult because airflow depends on boundary conditions and room parameters.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.88</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENUES WITH MV" target="INFECTIOUS AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION">
      <data key="d7">VENUES WITH DV</data>
      <data key="d8">DIRECTIONAL AEROSOL DISTRIBUTION</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">DV venues exhibited directional aerosol distribution, allowing prediction of highly exposed positions and expected secondary cases per event.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.92</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENUES WITH MV" target="BOUNDARY-CONDITION-SENSITIVE ROOM AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d7">VENUES WITH MV</data>
      <data key="d8">BOUNDARY-CONDITION-SENSITIVE ROOM AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">MV venues are associated with airflow that is sensitive to boundary conditions and room parameters, limiting the reliability of exposure prediction. | NV venues are associated with boundary-condition-sensitive airflow, especially due to factors such as windows and other room parameters.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.86</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENUES WITH MV" target="AIR INLETS AND OUTLETS">
      <data key="d7">VENUES WITH MV</data>
      <data key="d8">AIR INLETS AND OUTLETS</data>
      <data key="d9">CONNECTS_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">Air inlets and outlets connect to MV venues and act as important airflow boundary conditions that shape room airflow and aerosol transport.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.76</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENUES WITH MV" target="WINDOWS">
      <data key="d7">VENUES WITH NV</data>
      <data key="d8">WINDOWS</data>
      <data key="d9">CONNECTS_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">Windows connect NV venues to outdoor air and influence natural airflow patterns, affecting aerosol movement and exposure prediction.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.78</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="UNVENTILATED AREAS" target="POOR AIR CIRCULATION">
      <data key="d7">UNVENTILATED AREAS</data>
      <data key="d8">POOR AIR CIRCULATION</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">Unventilated areas are associated with poor air circulation, allowing aerosols to accumulate and locally increase infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENUE-SPECIFIC HIGH-RISK SITES" target="POOR AIR CIRCULATION">
      <data key="d7">VENUE-SPECIFIC HIGH-RISK SITES</data>
      <data key="d8">POOR AIR CIRCULATION</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">Some venue-specific high-risk sites correspond to areas of poor air circulation, which experimental and numerical approaches are needed to identify.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.78</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENUE-SPECIFIC HIGH-RISK SITES" target="NEAR-FIELD OF THE EMITTER">
      <data key="d7">VENUE-SPECIFIC HIGH-RISK SITES</data>
      <data key="d8">NEAR FIELD OF THE EMITTER</data>
      <data key="d9">ADJACENT_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">High-risk sites were observed in the near field of the emitter for all three ventilation strategies, reflecting elevated exposure close to the source.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.83</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENUE-SPECIFIC HIGH-RISK SITES" target="HIGH-RISK POSITIONS BEYOND PHYSICAL DISTANCE GUIDELINES">
      <data key="d7">VENUE-SPECIFIC HIGH-RISK SITES</data>
      <data key="d8">HIGH-RISK POSITIONS BEYOND PHYSICAL DISTANCE GUIDELINES</data>
      <data key="d9">ADJACENT_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">High-risk sites also included positions well beyond physical-distance guideline ranges, showing that risk was not confined to the emitter near field.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.76</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="AIR INLETS AND OUTLETS" target="BOUNDARY-CONDITION-SENSITIVE ROOM AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d7">AIR INLETS AND OUTLETS</data>
      <data key="d8">BOUNDARY-CONDITION-SENSITIVE ROOM AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d9">CONNECTS_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">The arrangement and operation of air inlets and outlets contribute to boundary-condition-sensitive airflow in the venue.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.74</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="AIR INLETS AND OUTLETS" target="VENTILATION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d7">AIR INLETS AND OUTLETS</data>
      <data key="d8">VENTILATION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d9">CONNECTS_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">Air inlets and outlets are parts of the ventilation air path connected to the HVAC system. Their arrangement is one of the boundary conditions that shapes room airflow.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.76</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="WINDOWS" target="BOUNDARY-CONDITION-SENSITIVE ROOM AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d7">WINDOWS</data>
      <data key="d8">BOUNDARY-CONDITION-SENSITIVE ROOM AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d9">CONNECTS_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">Windows contribute to boundary-condition-sensitive airflow by altering natural air exchange and room airflow patterns.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.73</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_47</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="WINDOWS" target="ROOM AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d7">WINDOWS</data>
      <data key="d8">ROOM AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d9">CONNECTS_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">Windows can connect the indoor air volume with external airflow or leakage paths. The text lists windows among the room parameters that influence the room airflow.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.62</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="STAGE AREA" target="ROOM AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d7">STAGE AREA</data>
      <data key="d8">ROOM AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">The stage area is subject to the venue room airflow pattern. This matters because the text highlights the importance of connecting the stage area to ventilation and adjusting airflow to reduce transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.78</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="AUDIENCE AREA" target="ROOM AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d7">AUDIENCE AREA</data>
      <data key="d8">ROOM AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">The audience area has an airflow distribution pattern that determines how aerosols from the infectious emitter spread through the fully occupied audience.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.82</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="HIGHLY EXPOSED POSITIONS" target="ROOM AIRFLOW">
      <data key="d7">HIGHLY EXPOSED POSITIONS</data>
      <data key="d8">ROOM AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">Highly exposed positions are determined by local room airflow behavior. The text states that identifying such positions is difficult because airflow depends on boundary conditions and room parameters.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.83</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="CONNECTION OF THE STAGE AREA TO THE VENTILATION SYSTEM" target="STAGE AREA">
      <data key="d7">CONNECTION OF THE STAGE AREA TO THE VENTILATION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d8">STAGE AREA</data>
      <data key="d9">CONNECTS_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">This air path connects directly to the stage area, enabling the HVAC system to influence air exchange and aerosol removal in that occupied zone.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.94</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="CONNECTION OF THE STAGE AREA TO THE VENTILATION SYSTEM" target="VENTILATION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d7">CONNECTION OF THE STAGE AREA TO THE VENTILATION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d8">VENTILATION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d9">CONNECTS_TO</data>
      <data key="d10">This air path links the stage area to the venue ventilation system. The text explicitly states that this connection should be enforced for pandemic preparedness.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.94</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206_chunk_48</data>
      <data key="d14">2c371b3c-bdf6-4d57-aab2-55e74c106206</data>
    </edge>
