      <data key="d7">ROOM AIR FLOW</data>
      <data key="d8">CO2</data>
      <data key="d9">PATTERN_MEASURED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">CO2 functions as a modeled tracer gas whose trajectory follows the room air flow. Pre-calculations showed that CO2 movement was directly dependent on room air flow.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.82</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d14">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="ROOM AIRFLOW" target="INFECTIOUS AEROSOLS OF 0.5, 5, AND 10 ΜM">
      <data key="d7">ROOM AIR FLOW</data>
      <data key="d8">INFECTIOUS AEROSOLS OF 0.5, 5, AND 10 ΜM</data>
      <data key="d9">PATTERN_MEASURED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">The modeled aerosol trajectories indicate the airflow-driven transport pattern. Pre-calculations showed that aerosols with d ≤ 10 µm were directly dependent on room air flow from 0.05 m s−1 air velocity.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.78</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d_chunk_26</data>
      <data key="d14">0676edf9-1d10-4220-bdea-1b4729f9856d</data>
    </edge>
