      <data key="d7">CONTAGIOUS INDIVIDUAL</data>
      <data key="d8">SARS-COV-2 VIRUS</data>
      <data key="d9">OCCUPANCY_INCREASES</data>
      <data key="d10">The contagious occupant is the source of airborne SARS-CoV-2 introduced into the shared environment through respiratory emissions.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.87</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_69</data>
      <data key="d14">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="WARM MANIKINS" target="POSITIVELY BUOYANT PLUME">
      <data key="d7">WARM MANIKINS</data>
      <data key="d8">POSITIVELY BUOYANT PLUME</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">Warm manikins generate an upward buoyant plume because they are warmer than their environment, producing free-convection airflow near and above the body.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d14">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="POSITIVELY BUOYANT PLUME" target="DROPLET AEROSOL">
      <data key="d7">POSITIVELY BUOYANT PLUME</data>
      <data key="d8">DROPLET AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d9">ACH_AFFECTS</data>
      <data key="d10">The upward buoyant plume affects aerosol transport by carrying emitted droplets upward through thermal effects. This captures an airflow-driven effect on particle distribution, despite the absence of a more specific valid relation type.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.76</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d14">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENTILATION AIRFLOW" target="DROPLET AEROSOL">
      <data key="d7">VENTILATION AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d8">DROPLET AEROSOL</data>
      <data key="d9">ACH_AFFECTS</data>
      <data key="d10">Aerosol droplets are transported by the surrounding airflow and follow it almost perfectly, so the airflow pattern strongly affects aerosol dispersion.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.79</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d14">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENTILATION AIRFLOW" target="LARGER RESPIRATORY DROPS">
      <data key="d7">VENTILATION AIRFLOW</data>
      <data key="d8">LARGER RESPIRATORY DROPS</data>
      <data key="d9">ACH_AFFECTS</data>
      <data key="d10">Larger drops are less governed by the airflow than aerosols because inertia and sedimentation cause them to depart from the main flow and deposit.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.66</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_68</data>
      <data key="d14">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="CONFINED ENVIRONMENTS" target="BUOYANT PLUME">
      <data key="d7">CONFINED ENVIRONMENTS</data>
      <data key="d8">BUOYANT PLUME</data>
      <data key="d9">HAS_DISTRIBUTION_PATTERN</data>
      <data key="d10">Confined environments can exhibit buoyant plume behavior that transports aerosols upward, supporting the recommendation for upper-part extraction.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.85</data>
      <data key="d12">2</data>
      <data key="d13">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42_chunk_69</data>
      <data key="d14">6ce6bcdd-6339-49d0-abf2-8f8a9a51aa42</data>
